the destruction of millions of acres of tropical jungles each year by peasant farmers and others is a problem for the developed nations as well as the third world and requires economic and educational solutions, say scientists at a leading plant research institution
the missouri botanical garden, known for its man-made tropical atmosphere in the so-called ``climatron'' designed by buckminster fuller, is working to halt the decimation of the world's real tropical jungles
the outlook is pretty grim,'' said biologist peter h. raven, director of the garden. ``although tropical forests once covered at least 12 percent of the globe _ an area about twice the size of europe _ they have already been reduced to about half that.''
currently, the forests are being cleared or degraded at the rate of about 60 million acres a year. that's an area about half the size of california.''
raven said roughly half of all known plant and animal species on earth are found in the tropical forests. at the current rate of destruction, as many as 60,000 species of plants will be extinct by the year 2020
the plant-rich tropics supply man with a wealth of food crops, medicines and other useful products,'' said dr. enrique forero, director of research at the garden. ``but they are being destroyed rapidly.''
the chief culprits, forero said, are loggers and slash-and-burn peasant farmers. the loggers obviously need the trees to stay in business and the farmers often have to destroy the forests to feed themselves and their families
and the scientists say the situation can only get worse unless something is done to stop it
at present, over half the people in the world live in countries that are at least partly tropical, excluding china,'' forero said. ``nearly a third of these people are already living in extreme poverty and with current rates of growth, the human population of these countries will double in less than 30 years.''
how can you tell these starving people that you are going to save the very things they have to destroy in order to sustain their already meager existence,'' asked raven. ``education and political and economic stability are obviously the keys. that and understanding.''
which is why, raven said, the garden has committed itself to an all-out effort to explore, document and save the forests
with a staff of 70 researchers and technicians, including many who live permanently in the tropics, the garden makes up one of the world's largest active field research programs in tropical botany
the goals, the scientists said, are to collect the plant species before they become extinct and to teach the impoverished farmers how to live in the forest without destroying it
with the growing knowledge of genetics, they said, it is important that the genes, the biological blueprints, of the endangered species be saved
to lose this genetic capital through massive extinctions just as we are developing our capabilities to explore its potential would indeed be a tragedy,'' raven said. ``the developments in genetics make the specter of extinction even worse,'' raven said. ``for each species of plant or animal lost to extinction, you're losing the potential for another 20,000 to 30,000 variants in the future.''
many of the plants, scientists say, could almost certainly be developed into cheaper, easy-to-grow sources of highly nutritious food. others could be converted into abundant sources of new medicines
another important part of the garden's program is to lend technical assistance to and train scientists from developing tropical countries through cooperative agreements
unfortunately, only 6 percent of the scientists working on the problem live in the countries involved,'' raven said. ``we must change that. momentum to implement the innovative conservation and development strategies needed to deal with these urgent problems ultimately must come from the affected countries themselves,'' raven said
the backbone of the garden's research, the scientists said, is its herbarium, or plant collection. along with the new york botanical garden and the smithsonian institution, the missouri herbarium is one of the three largest in the united states and among the 12 largest in the world
started by garden founder henry shaw in the 1850s, the missouri herbarium now contains samples of more than 3.5 million species and is expected to expand to 4.5 million within the next decade
pointing to a large map showing the locations of the garden's researchers in central and south america and africa, raven said of the encroachment on the forests: ``it won't be stopped soon
but there are encouraging signs. what people have to learn is that conservation and development are really two sides of the same coin.''
producers and consumers have to learn that they have a common problem. it can all be done, but it won't be easy.''
an old generation is remembering the vietnam war and a new generation is curious, stirring a revival of the controversial era in books and movies. now comes a new publication, a slick magazine simply named vietnam, whose premiere issue went on sale today
our timing could not have been better because right now, look at all the vietnam movies that have come out,'' said publisher gregg r. oehler in a telephone interview from leesburg, va., where the magazine is published by empire press. ``look at all the major emphasis now on video, on books. it's vietnam. everyone now is talking about vietnam.''
oehler said 150,000 copies of the first issue were printed, including 50,000 for subscribers and 100,000 for newsstand sales across the united states and in 16 other countries. the magazine, a quarterly, sells for $2.95 a copy on newsstands and for $9.95 for the four issues by subscription
oehler said the response has been so overwhelming from wholesalers, subscribers and the media that the magazine will probably go to six issues a year in 1989. many of the subscribers are vietnam veterans, a large number of them in prison
i've gotten hundreds of letters from vietnam veterans in prison,'' said oehler. ``they're so happy to hear that a magazine is coming out.''
each issue will run 68 pages with a regular format of four feature stories and six departments including editorial, fighting forces, bases and installations, arsenal and book reviews
the initial issue includes an interview with gen. fred c. weyand, america's last military commander in vietnam, and a story on tan son nhut air base, the command center for america's forces in vietnam which was called the ``pentagon east.'' it also includes 32 pages of color photographs and maps. the cover shows two soldiers defending their post with a machine gun
in the editorial in the premiere issue, the editor, retired col. harry g. summers jr., explains the goal of the magazine:
thirty-eight years after american involvement in vietnam began, 15 years after the withdrawal of all u.s. military forces there, and 13 years after the fall of saigon, the war there truly remains an enigma. the goal we here at vietnam magazine have set for ourselves is to find the key to unlock that enigma.''
in an interview, summers said that in visits to colleges he has found great interest in vietnam among young people who want to know what really happened there. he said there seems to be a misunderstanding of the war especially among this generation, many of whom were not even born when american soldiers were pouring into vietnam in 1965
there is the perception that the united states was defeated by a guerrilla army,'' he said. ``that's not true. the american military withdrew from vietnam 2{ years before the fall of saigon. the north vietnamese did not defeat the american military when they seized saigon for a very simple reason: there was no american military there to defeat. one of our objectives is to refute some of the myths.''
summers, 56, is widely known and respected as an authority on military affairs. he served in both the korean and vietnam wars
he is a columnist for the los angeles times syndicate, a contributing editor for u.s.news &amp; world report, and the author of two books, including the widely acclaimed ``on strategy: a critical analysis of the vietnam war.''
the magazine's editorial review board includes gen. william c. westmoreland, former commander of u.s. forces in vietnam, and authors stanley karnow and al santoli, both of whom have written books on vietnam
asked if the presence of westmoreland and other former vietnam officers on the board will leave the impression that the magazine will give only the official view, one that was often discredited during the war, summers said:
we've tried to get the voices as diverse as possible. i don't think stanley karnow's an apologist for the war. i don't think i'm an apologist for the war. certainly my book was very critical of the war. and so was al santoli.''
ben midgette bends and removes spikes from railroad ties, and rod korthals blows smoke through a scale-model hog house
they are among 3,000 scientists, administrators and graduate assistants on staff at the university of illinois agricultural experiment station, which celebrated its 100th anniversary monday
but the center, one of 66 in the country, is about more than agriculture
i've yet to see one person ... who didn't think there were exciting things going on here,'' said station director donald holt. ``one thing is clear _ research is crucial to the future of american agriculture and our society in general.''
in one laboratory, midgette compared the strength of railroad ties made from different woods, looking for the longest-lasting material. an african oak was so hard that it caused a bolt to break in a machine that measures the force required to pull out a spike
it snapped and went straight up,'' said midgette, who figures this african oak will out-last conventional ties. ``we've got indentations in the ceiling.''
korthals pumped smoke into the clear plastic model of a hog house to demonstrate how the air moves through the building with various ventilation systems. he said it should help farmers select the most efficient design for their own swine buildings
the 320 research projects funded by the station last year involved subjects such as agricultural economics, veterinary medicine, home economics and food science
the center has a $25 million budget from state and federal appropriations, as well as gifts, grants and contracts, many from the private sector, holt said
it began in the morrow plots, site of the longest-running continuous corn experiment in the western hemisphere. the test plots were created in 1876, the year gen. george custer and 264 cavalrymen were killed at little bighorn
much of the station's research still is aimed directly at production agriculture. visitors on monday saw a rainfall simulator used to study the effects of soil erosion, experiments on the biological control of insects, and research into the possible use of wild soybeans to improve commercial varieties
they also saw work being done to create new human foods from soybeans, to study tree growth and to learn more about infant nutrition and child development
the murderous rampages that left five people dead at two belfast funerals last week have aroused fears that northern ireland is sliding into a new cycle of violence after several years of relative calm
in the past month, 15 people have died _ twice the 1987 monthly average. the dead include three irish republican army guerrillas gunned down in gibraltar on march 6 in the incident that touched off the latest mayhem in belfast
a firm grip will be required to halt the slide of the province toward still further bloodshed and anarchy,'' the news letter, a belfast newspaper, warned monday
there is no time to lose,'' said the belfast telegraph. ``if there is a political vacuum _ and there is _ the initiative will always seem to be with the paramilitaries.''
there won't be anarchy and there won't even be a return to the level of violence in the early 1970s when 700 people died in a year,'' paul bew, a political science professor at queen's university in belfast, said in an interview
but the graph is starting to go up, up, up,'' he said
with police talking of about 30 suspects in saturday's violence, roman catholic areas of belfast are bracing for a wave of arrests that could provoke further clashes
ever since the irish republican army's struggle to drive britain out of northern ireland climaxed with the death of 10 hunger striking prisoners in 1981, the province seemed to be lapsing into relative calm. the death toll was dropping steadily and there even were signs of economic rejuvenation
the ira, having narrowly failed to assassinate prime minister margaret thatcher with a bomb in 1984, was suffering repeated military and political setbacks. the anglo-irish agreement of november 1985, which gave dublin a say in the running of northern ireland, was bolstering catholic moderates against ira radicals
the killing of the three guerrillas, allegedly as they were plotting a car bombing in gibraltar, was portrayed by britain as a triumph for its anti-terrorism strategy
but the fact that the guerrillas were unarmed outraged many catholics as well as the irish government. that reaction in turn angered many protestants, who believed that the ira got what it deserved
as the three were being buried, protestant michael stone emerged from behind a tombstone lobbing grenades and firing into the mourners. three died and 68 were wounded
three days later, at the funeral of one of the cemetery victims, a car sped toward the cortege. the mourners, keyed up and fearful of another protestant attack, pounced on it
when they realized the occupants were two british soldiers, they dragged them out, beat them with iron bars and stripped them. the two men were then hauled away and shot dead by ira gunmen
the two episodes revealed the hatred that can still erupt from a protestant majority that regards itself as being under siege, and from a catholic minority for whom gibraltar proves there is no british justice in northern ireland
the incidents all but obscured four other deaths since gibraltar: a policeman, an ira man and two civilians _ a protestant woman and a catholic man
in the context of a conflict that has claimed 2,638 lives since 1969, those four would be regarded as par for ulster's grisly course. the funeral deaths, however, were graphically captured by tv cameras, and they stunned and disgusted irish and british citizens alike
scum of the earth,'' stormed the sun, a london daily. in dublin, the irish press lamented: ``this was the shocking face of ireland '88.''
many catholics reacted to saturday's killings with shock and disgust, making no attempt to excuse them as a response to the previous cemetery bloodbath. the irish news, a catholic daily, called it ``a satanic rejection of the christian faith.''
the initial reaction is shock that something so barbarous could happen,'' said dan keenan, spokesman for the social democratic and labor party, northern ireland's moderate, mainstream catholic party
marcus eliason, news editor in the london bureau of the associated press, has covered northern ireland for 3{ years
the united states has urged panama's military leader, gen. manuel antonio noriega, to leave the country and live in spain. the united state has encouraged other world leaders to give up power and go into exile. among them:
syngman rhee _ the south korean president went into exile in hawaii in may, 1960 following widespread political unrest and allegations that he had rigged the presidential election. he died in 1965
shah of iran _ shah mohammad reza pahlavi gave up power during the islamic revolution and flew to egypt in his private plane on jan. 15, 1979. he was allowed temporary refuge in the united states for medical treatment, but was not allowed to live in the united states permanently. he went to panama and then to egypt, where he died in 1980
anastasio somoza _ the nicaraguan president fled the country jan. 19, 1979 under pressure from the organization of american states and after the united states refused to support him. a sandinista-led coalition took power. somoza lived in paraguay and was assassinated on sept. 7, 1980
baby doc'' duvalier _ jean-claude duvalier and his family fled haiti on feb. 7, 1986 aboard a u.s. air force plane following months of unrest. his departure ended the political dynasty founded in 1957 by his father, francois ``papa doc'' duvalier. duvalier is in exile in france
ferdinand marcos _ fled the philippines with his family aboard a u.s. jet on feb. 26, 1986 in the face of mounting opposition by political foes and the military. marcos is in exile in hawaii
don hewitt, who marks his 40th anniversary with cbs news today, recalls that he landed his first job at the network after a friend suggested his experience at a newsphoto service might come in handy
i said, what does cbs want with picture experience? radio doesn't need any pictures. he said, `no _ television.' i said whata-vision?''
today, the 65-year-old outspoken creator and executive producer of ``60 minutes'' is looking beyond current television technology, foreseeing a time when networks are superfluous and television news is beamed directly into subscribers' homes
hewitt began his career as associate director and later producer of the network's first television newscast, ``douglas edwards with the news'' and later the ``cbs evening news'' with walter cronkite
he remembers covering the coronation of queen elizabeth ii with edward r. murrow and flying back to the united states aboard a chartered airliner editing the kinescope that viewers would see on the news _ no videotapes, no satellite transmissions
i didn't think there was ever going to be satellites, bounce signals off a star, are you crazy?,'' he said, laughing. but hewitt, who considered buying cbs news a few years ago, thinks it's feasible to one day broadcast news directly to homes. news services already are beaming footage to local television stations, so hewitt's idea is not so far-fetched
i think that the network news departments, they might not even work for a network 10 years from now,'' he said. ``there might not be any networks because it may be an outmoded delivery system
i'm not sure you don't have a large newsroom somewhere and you just have direct broadcast ... feeding news into people's homes, for a price same way they pay for a newspaper.''
he also foresees delivering newspapers into home printers by satellite
i think about it more than most people, as you can see. and i wonder how long the networks in their present form will be around,'' he said
some other samples of hewitt's opinions:
_``60 minutes'': ``i've always said all we do in this broadcast is shine lights on people in dark corners, and if people in dark corners are doing things they shouldn't be doing, all we did was turn the light on.''
_the importance of pictures on television: ``the accepted wisdom in television was always you put words to pictures. i don't believe that. you put pictures to words. you start with the words. the audio is always more important to me than the video.''
_televised presidential debates (hewitt produced the famous 1960 meeting of richard nixon and john f. kennedy): ``it's still a terrible format and we shouldn't be doing them. they should have real debates. ... the republican candidate and democratic candidate should head up a team of two or three debaters who are really good and can really cross-examine the other side and give them a hard time, and they ought to do it in front of a joint session of congress, and it will produce something other than this sterile show where what it is is a joint press conference, not really a debate.''
_this year's election: ``i don't think there's enough caffeine in america to keep the electorate awake during a dukakis-bush campaign.''
_politicians: ``i don't put politicians on the air if i can help it, because i instinctively don't believe them. i believe they're only interested in getting themselves elected, and they only say what they think will get themselves elected.''
_ratings: ``no matter what i think about ratings, and whether they're accurate and everything, i don't say anything because they've been awfully good to me.''
_the future: ``i know where i'll be in nine years. i'm going to be here. my contract isn't up until i'm 74. ironclad, nobody gets out. now the question is, will there be a cbs? i think so. some form. maybe not this form.''
the supreme court is considering whether abused children should have the right to sue public officials for failing to protect them from their parents
but the justices have decided to avoid another children's rights issue: whether public school students enjoy any constitutional protection against paddling or other corporal punishment by teachers and administrators
the court announced monday that it will tackle the parental abuse issue in the case of a wisconsin boy, joshua deshaney, who suffered serious and permanent brain damage from beatings by his father
the boy's suit accuses social workers and officials of gross negligence in ignoring evidence that he was being brutally victimized. a lower court threw out the suit
a high court ruling is not expected until 1989 on whether to revive the suit against the winnebago county, wis., department of social services and two of its employees
the agency was accused of violating the rights of joshua by failing to rescue him from his father's beatings, even though it allegedly had known about the abuse since 1983, when the child was 4 years old
joshua has been institutionalized since 1984, suffering from injuries that destroyed half his brain and left him profoundly retarded
the boy's father, randy deshaney, since has been convicted of child abuse and sentenced to two to four years in prison
deshaney's ex-wife, melody, sued the social services officials on grounds they violated the child's constitutional right not to be deprived of liberty without due process
mrs. deshaney was divorced from her husband and living in cheyenne, wyo., when she was informed her son had suffered serious brain damage. deshaney had custody of his son
the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals, in throwing out mrs. deshaney's suit, said the social welfare agency and its employees ``though blameworthy, did not cause joshua's injuries'' but ``merely failed to protect him from his bestial father.''
the appeals court also said welfare agencies should not be placed in the predicament of removing a child from home and facing suit by the parent or leaving the child there and risk being sued by the child
putting officials in that position ``is unlikely to improve the welfare of american families and is not grounded in constitutional text or principle,'' the appeals court said
in the paddling case, the court, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling in a new mexico case that ``at some degree of excessiveness or cruelty'' such punishment violates constitutional rights
another appeals court has rejected that view, clouding the picture
the high court in 1977 ruled that such disciplinary measures never can amount to the ``cruel and unusual punishment'' banned by the constitution's eighth amendment
the decision barred students from suing teachers and school administrators in federal court over alleged eighth amendment violations, but left them free to sue in state courts under state laws
in the 1977 decision, however, the court said it had not considered whether corporal punishment can violate ``substantive rights under the (14th amendment's) due process clause.''
the 10th u.s. circuit court of appeals last april cleared the way for a trial in teresa garcia's federal lawsuit against penasco, n.m., school officials over two paddlings she received in elementary school
the appeals court said the kind of punishment alleged in the lawsuit can sustain a federal lawsuit even if a lawsuit could have been filed in state court
in other developments, the court:
_agreed to consider killing a key provision of a law designed to promote competitive bidding on government contracts. at issue is the proper boundary between presidential and congressional power
_agreed to decide in a case from texas whether states may impose sales taxes on most books, newspapers and magazines while exempting religious publications
as a capital institution, leaking confidential information to the press has a rich heritage and long roots
those roots may be longer than one might think
the news leak, in fact, may stretch back to thomas jefferson, or at least his political allies
that possibility was made clear last week as the senate was reminded that the day marked the 188th anniversary _ march 18, 1800 _ of the issuing of the very first contempt of congress citation
thomas duane, editor of the philadelphia aurora, was cited for contempt for having failed to appear as ordered to explain how he had obtained the text of a controversial but secret senate bill and caused it to be published
the senate in that era still met in secret and all of its deliberations were held to be private, not public, matters
according to senate republican leader bob dole of kansas and senate historians, the secret bill was the product of the senate's federalist majority and concerned a bid to change the method of settling disputes over presidential electors
jefferson was vice president and leader of the democratic-republican party. his supporters feared a plot to deny him the presidency in the upcoming elections
so, dole said, ``jefferson's allies in the senate leaked a copy of the bill to william duane.''
offended federalists demanded an investigation of duane and his illicit sources,'' dole said
vice president jefferson, as the senate's presiding officer, was directed to read duane a list of prepared questions about who had given him the bill, he said
duane asked for additional time to seek counsel, a request jefferson quickly granted
that was the last the senate saw of william duane,'' dole recounted. ``when he failed to reappear, the senate issued a contempt citation in his name. duane hid out through the remainder of the congressional session.''
when the new congress convened the situation had changed. jefferson had won the white house and his party had captured majorities in both the senate and house
needless to say,'' said dole, ``the new senate majority had no intention of pursuing charges of contempt against william duane.''
the first congressional investigation of a news leak was quietly shelved
rep. peter rodino, d-n.j., sifted through 40 years of memories last week after announcing he will end his congressional career at the end of the year
rodino, the chairman of the house judiciary committee, presided over the hearings which, on july 24, 1974, resulted in a vote to impeach president richard m. nixon
within days nixon resigned his office
a decade later, on may 30, 1984, rodino was en route from the capital to his home in newark, n.j
rodino is such a frequent flier on that route that the airlines, as a matter of courtesy, customarily assigned him a seat in the second row of the aircraft so that he could board and depart easily and quickly
but on the day in question, chairman rodino got bumped to the rear of the plane
who had the clout to oust rodino from his accustomed seat?
former president richard nixon's the one
nixon also had a home in new jersey and was traveling with his secret service bodyguards. the entire group got the front-of-the-plane seats
the two men didn't talk
i didn't even see his face,'' rodino recalled. ``i saw the back of his head.''
as struggling democratic presidential hopeful richard gephardt was wooing workers at a giant steel mill here with his trade-and-populism message, one of them handed him a button that read: ``survival.''
the button referred to saving mclouth steel through employee ownership, but it also aptly summed up gephardt's political goal in michigan
without a win here, it could be all over for the missouri congressman. but he hopes workers like the ones he campaigned among monday will keep his bid alive
if we don't do well here, obviously we aren't going to be able to continue the race,'' gephardt said in lansing on march 10
brushing aside questions about his future if he loses, gephardt said over and over again monday, ``i'm going to do well in michigan.'' asked if he would run for re-election to his house seat if he loses saturday, he declared: ``i'm going to win.''
i imagine he does have to'' win, said frank kelley, michigan attorney general and chairman of gephardt's effort in the state
but he was quick to say winning might not mean coming in first. kelley said jesse jackson, who has strong black support in detroit and its suburbs, could be first. he said gephardt must beat massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, the front-runner in delegates
if gephardt beats dukakis, his campaign is revived,'' kelley said
but the polls do not support that prospect
a survey conducted march 15-17 for the detroit news gave dukakis and jackson the lead, with gephardt far behind. dukakis had 33 percent, and jackson 31 percent. gephardt had 10 percent, with the rest of the field trailing
gephardt said the polls do not tap the caucus-goers accurately, as the campaign expects only 100,000 to 150,000 democrats to attend, a small fraction of the party faithful
i think a lot of people will be surprised by how well he does here,'' said chick mahoney, owner of chick's rooster lounge south of detroit, where gephardt campaigned monday. ``but it's going to be tough.''
to turn the poll findings on their head, gephardt has a message with a great deal of appeal in this state still shuddering from the massive changes in the auto and steel industries facing foreign competition
he denunciation of foreign trade practices _ epitomized by his rhetoric and ad saying ``a $10,000 chrysler k-car costs $48,000 in south korea'' _ draws big applause from blue collar crowds. at the mclouth mill and at chick's on monday, that line drew big cheers
he's the only one to take a stand on trade, a strong one,'' said jim hindman outside the mclouth mill south of detroit
`some of the people here were out of work for 4{ years,'' added ray ridings. ``that's why we like gephardt.''
gephardt is short of time and money to get his message out. kelley said the campaign has promised to spend between $300,000 and $500,000 on ads in the state. one campaign aide who spoke on condition of anonymity said, ``as fast the money comes in, we spend it.''
a key to gephardt's victory is what the union leadership does in the state
the united auto workers have not endorsed anyone nationally, although their state affiliate in iowa played a major role in his victory in iowa
that means gephardt is trying to pick up support local by local and district by district. at the mclouth plant, he won the backing of district director harry lester. and frank baker, a united steel workers local 2659 official, said many members will follow the district leader's suggestion
that backing must be repeated over and over again across the state for gephardt to win, for this caucus is not a simple process
the voting does not take place in the usual precincts across the state but in 567 locations that may not be familiar to the voters. that puts a premium on organization, which has been the trademark of dukakis' effort this far
gephardt's hyundai ad, which worked so well in iowa and south dakota, has come in for criticism in this state where autos are the economy
gephardt brushed aside suggestions the ad is inaccurate in its claim that the $10,000 chrysler car would cost $48,000 in south korea. and he got some help in that from chrysler corp. chairman lee iacocca, with whom he met on monday in highland park
asked if the gephardt ad's figure was correct, iacocca said gephardt has the point correct, whatever the details
damn close to it. maybe it's only $35-40,000, but don't lose sight of it, it's still a big difference between $7,000 here for a comparable car,'' iacocca said to reporters outside the chrysler corp. headquarters
gephardt said he was responding to a story in monday's editions of the detroit free press saying a k-car would cost about $33,000 in korea and that none is sold there. and gephardt, in an interview with the detroit news, conceded that many of those taxes are levied in korea on domestic consumption
banning reporters and photographers from the west bank and the gaza strip could prove to be a public relations blunder for israel and might not be effective anyway, several media observers say
larry gross, a professor at the annenberg school of communications at the university of pennsylvania, said it would be ``bad policy'' for israel to impose more restrictions on reporters covering unrest in the occupied territories
it would be a public relations risk _ one i hope they don't take,'' gross said. he said israel could jeopardize its reputation as the only true democracy in the middle east, which u.s. officials cite in providing millions of dollars to the country each year
but the israelis are obviously watching the situation in south africa to determine if the advantages of restricting the press outweigh the disadvantages, he said
south africa's widely condemned white government has succeeded in dampening outside interest in that country's racial problems by banning coverage of any security activities, experts agree. the order went into effect in june 1986
but gross doubted israel would be able to ``keep the lid on'' coverage of the occupied territories in a way the south africans have virtually halted reporting in black areas
israel's domestic political opposition and a thriving domestic press could prevent a blackout on coverage of the territories, he said
local israeli army commanders already have authority to close areas in the occupied territories at random, and they have been doing so with increasing frequency. a parliamentary committee in jerusalem is studying whether to ban the media formally from the territories
yael dayan, a well-known israeli peace activist, said during a recent u.s. visit that tough restrictions on the press would likely fail, because israelis demand news and have an aggressive press corps
eric goldstein of the committee to protect journalists, a new york-based group that monitors conditions for journalists worldwide, said israel might be able to stave off intense scrutiny by banning cameras
but in the long run the greater public interest is served by allowing the press access,'' he said. the committee opposes restrictions on reporters
some americans have joined israeli government officials in complaining that reporters, particularly those working for foreign television networks, have helped incite rock-throwing palestinians in the territories
new york mayor edward koch has said a television ban would be justified, and former secretary of state henry a. kissinger reportedly told prominent american jews during a meeting that banning television cameras would be a good idea. kissinger says his remarks were distorted
jeff cohen of fairness and accuracy in reporting criticized a ``censorship lobby'' for supporting restrictions that, in the united states, would be considered an unacceptable violation of freedom of the press
it would be one more comparison with south africa, and it would hurt israel,'' he said. fair is a liberal new york group that examines the media
fred w. friendly, former president of cbs news and a professor at columbia university's school of journalism, said it would be wrong to ban reporters from the occupied territories
that can't be right _ that's what south africa did,'' he said
but friendly said television coverage, with its time constraints and powerful pictures, can fail to portray a story accurately. `what is also wrong is letting the picture run away with the story,'' he told the new york times
mortimer zuckerman, editor-in-chief of u.s. news &amp; world report, had the same complaint. ``television has polluted the public debate because it is inherently difficult for pictures to give context, history and meaning to events,'' he recently wrote
two chicago &amp; northwestern freight trains collided head-on monday, injuring eight workers, three of them seriously, police said
an eastbound train with four engines and about 130 cars collided with a westbound train consisting of a switch engine and a single car while both trains were going 20 mph to 30 mph, police said. officials were investigating the cause of the accident late monday
the collision occurred about noon in the southwest part of dixon, a town of 15,000 in north-central illinois, and the crash could be heard up to a mile away, police said
eight employees were on the trains at the time of the accident, and were taken to katherine shaw bethea hospital in dixon
steve wilkerson, 35, of rock falls; and charles holdren, 56 and robert fonder, 38, both of sterling, were listed in serious condition late monday, hospital officials said. the other five workers were treated and released
because senators like to see farmers smile, your next mercedes benz could cost an extra $1,800
if you don't get the connection, that's just the way congress works sometimes
the senate finance committee voted monday to grant farmers and some other taxpayers relief from the 15.1-cent-a-gallon tax on diesel fuel used for logging, farming, oil drilling, mining, fishing and other off-the-road business purposes
but since budget constraints require that every dollar of tax relief be offset by a dollar of tax increase on somebody else, the committee's bill would double the tax on fuel-guzzling cars _ mostly expensive imports whose miles-per-gallon don't meet federal standards
other sources of revenue for the diesel relief and a new ``taxpayer bill of rights'' include a few distilleries that dodge some of the $12.50-a-gallon tax on liquor by watering down products with a grape-based alcohol, and any number of people whose tax refunds could be grabbed to pay an overdue government loan
after all that, farmers may have to wait six months for their tax relief. there is some doubt congress can complete action on legislation before april 1, when off-the-road diesel users are to begin paying the tax. they would have to wait for a refund until they file their income-tax returns next year
i just don't want to go back home and explain to my farmers why we've set up this ridiculous bureaucratic nightmare,'' moaned sen. david boren, d-okla
sen. david pryor, d-ark., noted the senate is due to recess easter week. to go back home with no settlement of the farmers' problem, he said, ``would be like us walking through a field of scorpions barefooted.''
sen. john danforth, r-mo., said the committee should, in effect, ask the senate to ignore the budget problem so farmers can be relieved
farmers and other off-road diesel users were caught up in congress' efforts last year to reduce cheating on the fuel tax. the solution was to change the point of tax collection to the producer or wholesaler, and to require that those legally entitled to an exemption pay the tax and then apply for a refund when they file their income-tax returns the following year
the typical farmer would thus allow the government interest-free use of $320 of his money, some of it for up to a year
the panel's bill does nothing for another big group with a complaint: about 82,000 state, county and city government units that, starting jan. 1, are now having to pay the 9.1-cent gasoline tax and apply for a refund later
the finance committee package, still subject to action by the senate and house, would:
_allow diesel bought for off-road business use from wholesalers to escape the tax altogether. tax-exempt buyers from retailers would have to pay the tax and get a refund next year. this would cost the government $543 million through 1993
_create a ``taxpayer bill of rights,'' clamping down on perceived abuses by the internal revenue service. this would lose $517 million over five years
_extend through june 30, 1989, the expiring authority for the irs to withhold tax refunds from people who owe student loans, farm loans and other federal debts. this would raise about $400 million
_double the tax on new cars whose fuel efficiency does not meet federal standards, raising $375 million through 1993. in the current model year, the tax hits only expensive foreign cars, such as the $38,000 volvo 780, which gets 21.2 miles per gallon, and the $61,130 mercedes 560sl. their guzzler taxes would rise to $1,300 and $3,600, respectively
_limit use of a ``wine flavors credit'' under which some manufacturers of distilled spirits avoid a significant share of the $12.50-a-gallon liquor tax by mixing some products with a grape-based alcohol. this is expected to raise $360 million over five years
republican presidential candidate pat robertson, faced with bumping up against the federally-imposed campaign spending limit, revised some of his state spending figures downward in his newly filed campaign financial statement
the spending allocations for nine states showed lower cumulative expenditures in the report filed monday than the figures robertson reported a month earlier
robertson's staff did not return a phone call monday to answer questions about the revisions
in his report filed monday with the federal election commission, the former tv evangelist reported he had spent $19 million through feb. 29 against the spending cap of $23 million that applies to expenditures for the entire primary season
even with the downward revisions in some state spending figures, the total was still more than the $17.6 million in spending against the cap that he reported through the end of january
candidates who receive federal matching funds must agree to stay within the spending limit. the reports candidates filed monday show new financial activity for the month of february as well as cumulative totals
robertson's revisions were in figures reported for califonria, district of columbia, louisiana, michigan, north carolina, oklahoma, tennessee, texas, and virginia
the biggest was in texas where his previous report showed an allocation of $1.1 million, but the new report shows an allocation of $746,514 through february
robertson, who has spent more overall than any other candidate, also reported he borrowed another $1.9 million in february
he has taken out more than $9 million in loans since he began his campaign last year, and ended february with $8.4 million in debts and $7.4 million in cash on hand
financial reports filed by his rivals show that sen. bob dole also has narrowly outspent vice president george bush, as bush has built a huge lead over both robertson and dole in the gop race
democratic contender michael dukakis, the governor of massachussetts, continues to raise more money than his rivals, all of whom have resorted to borrowing
dukakis raised $2.9 million in february, including federal matching funds, compared with less than $2 million each by rep. richard gephardt of missouri, sen. paul simon of illinois, sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, and jesse jackson
gephardt borrowed and repaid $149,000, during february, simon borrowed $292,352, and jackson borrowed $500,000. gore did not take out loans in february, which is the month covered by the new financial statements. but his aides have said he borrowed $1 million before the march 8 super tuesday contests in 20 states, and $300,000 before the illinois primary march 15
dole's receipts for february were $2 million, giving him $8.8 million for the year, including federal matching funds based on contributions raised privately. bush raised $1.5 million during february, $8.7 for the year, his report shows
but despite raising and spending more money through february, dole failed to interrupt the bush push toward the august nominating convention in new orleans. bush has won 788 delegates so far to dole's 178, according to the associated press delegate count
robertson raised $5 million for the month, including his $1.9 million loan, which brought his total receipts this year to $18.3 million
for the month, he spent $3.1 million, to dole's $5.3 million and bush's $4 million
dole has spent $18 million against the spending camp, and bush $14.1 million
dole ended february with $836,445 in the bank and $716,107 in bills. bush had $6.7 million in cash on hand _ more than any other candidate in the race _ and had $251,225 in debts
among democrats, gephardt ended february with $1 million in debts and only about half that in available cash
simon was $825,199 in debt, and had $760,755 in cash on hand, the reports showed
jackson owed $845,857, and had $428,420 on hand
gore had $342,964 in the bank and $91,858 in debts. but that was before gore took out $1.3 million in loans during march, according to capaign aides. figures detailing those transactions will appear in the financial reports due next month
candidates who run up debts generally do so in the knowledge they will be receiving federal matching funds to help pay off the loans
dukakis had $2.9 million in cash on hand at the end of the month, and $569,344 in debts
dukakis was the democrat closest to the spending cap, at $11.4 million
the operator of the three mile island nuclear plant has taken the first step in a plan to dispose of 2.3 million gallons of contaminated water that is a legacy of the 1979 accident at the plant
gpu nuclear, operator of the plant near harrisburg, pa., said monday it is spending $800,000 for a system to boil away the water, even though that method has yet to be approved by the nuclear regulatory commission and public hearings are months away
we expect the nrc to approve the evaporation eventually, but it's possible that that wouldn't happen,'' gpu nuclear spokesman gordon tomb said monday in a telephone interview
tomb identified the contractor as pacific nuclear systems inc. of federal way, wash
nrc spokeswoman sue gagner said utilities commonly make major expenditures for equipment before the commission grants permission for its use
gpu nuclear said the nrc might not consider the plan until december and the utility wants to be ready when approval comes
but kay pickering, spokeswoman for three mile island alert, a citizens' group, said she was alarmed when gpu nuclear told the nrc at a meeting last week that the company had authorized the contractor to design, install and begin testing the evaporation system
this is very distressing to the individuals and organizations involved here,'' she said
most of the water is left over from the 1979 accident, while some has been used to decontaminate the plant. gpu nuclear said the average additional radiation exposure from the evaporation would be about the same as ``the exposure from one to two hours of natural background radiation in the harrisburg area.''
the $7 million process involves boiling the water into steam released from a 100-foot-high stack, and packaging impurities for shipment to a low-level radioactive waste dump. tomb said testing at the plant would not use radioactive water
thomas gerusky, a member of a citizens' advisory panel on the tmi cleanup and director of pennsylvania's bureau of radiation protection, said some area residents ``were concerned about any releases from tmi'' and favored leaving the water in storage tanks
he said the nrc has given its blessing to the evaporation plan, but the commissioners have withheld formal approval pending public hearings
disposal of the water is part of the $1 billion cleanup of three mile island 2. during the accident, uranium fuel was allowed to lose the vital coolant that covers it, causing material in the core to begin melting
gpu nuclear announced plans in december 1986 to place unit 2 in storage indefinitely. the nrc is expected to issue a report next month on whether the ``monitored storage'' plan poses any threat to the environment, michael masnik of the commission said monday
while there are no plans to restart tmi-2, its twin reactor was not harmed in the accident and resumed operating in october 1985
widespread publicity about a handful of sexual abuse cases involving day care centers may have caused parents to be more worried than necessary about the safety of their children, researchers say
a study released monday by the family research laboratory of the university of new hampshire estimated that substantially more children are abused at home than in day care settings: 8.9 per 10,000 children at home compared with 5.5 per 10,000 at day care
david finkelhor, who directed the study, said the results are ``a far cry'' from the impression many people have gotten because of news accounts about a few incidents of child abuse at day care centers
we do not think day care centers in general are high risk areas,'' said finkelhor
however, he emphasized that child abuse does occur at some day care centers and is particularly hard to ferret out because the perpetrators do not fit stereotypes
only 8 percent had prior arrest records, 50 percent were college graduates and 40 percent were women, he said
we just can't say there is a nice shortcut, a couple of easy rules to spot places that might be dangerous,'' he said
for example, finkelhor noted, the study found no signficant differences between the incidence of child abuse in centers with a high teacher-to-pupil ratio and in less adequately staffed centers
however, finkelhor and two other participants at a news conference underscored the importance of parents having ready access to day care center activity and making surprise visits to see what is going on
parents need to go the extra mile to become familiar with the day care center they choose,'' said david s. liederman, executive director of the child welfare league of america. ``they should drop in unannounced and if the center doesn't like it, they should consider whether that is the kind of place they want their children to be.''
liederman said he agreed with the study's findings and said day care centers generally ``are safe places for children.''
sue bredekamp, director of the national academy of early childhood programs for the national association for the education of young children, said the report was the ``most comprehensive, national study of child sexual abuse in day care to date.''
it is our hope that dr. finkelhor's findings ... will be as widely disseminated and as influential to policy makers as were reports of several infamous cases of abuse in the past,'' she said
the survey examined 270 cases of sexual abuse involving 1,639 children from 1983 to 1985 and made an in-depth study of a random sample of 43 cases. an estimated 1.5 million children were cared for in day care centers during that time
finkelhor said there is no evidence the incidence of child abuse in day care settings was higher during the past two years than during the 1983-85 period surveyed
the study was commissioned by the national center on child abuse and neglect, an agency of the department of health and human services, and released in conjunction with the children's hospital national medical center
the federal aviation administration has decided to add an additional air traffic coordinator on each shift at o'hare international airport, an faa spokesman said monday
the decision by william h. pollard, director of the faa's great lakes region, was made after a u.s. house subcommittee hearing friday on safety problems at the airport, said spokesman mort edelstein
beginning in the near future, edelstein said, the faa will assign two full-time air traffic coordinators both day and night at o'hare. until now, only one full-time coordinator has been in the o'hare tower per shift, he said
the coordinators help improve the performance of the tower's air traffic controllers
one of those who addressed the subcommittee hearing was james burnett, head of the national transportation safety board, who warned of what he called ``a disturbing number of near-collisions'' at the busy chicago airport
the five-member subcommittee hearing was held at the request of rep. richard j. durbin, d-ill
edelstein said he did not know the exact date when the additional coordinators would be assigned to o'hare
supporters of former television evangelist pat robertson will apparently control the state gop convention in reno next month as a result of weekend county conventions, party officials said
nevada republicans use a three-step system of caucuses and conventions to pick their national convention delegates. the process began with precinct caucuses last month, at which a straw poll was conducted
in the straw poll, vice president george bush led with 27 percent, followed by bob dole with 22 percent and robertson with 15 percent. but robertson supporters claimed victory by saying most of the 23 percent undecided voters in the poll actually were robertson supporters
the straw poll participants were not bound to presidential candidates, however
at the county conventions, held over this past weekend, delegates were elected to the state convention april 21-23, where in turn national convention delegates will be elected
the delegate breakdown for the state convention won't be known for several days. but the robertson forces dominated republican conventions in nevada's two biggest counties, clark and washoe. party leaders said it appeared robertson got more than half the 800 state delegates in those two counties alone
robertson also picked up some delegates at the gop's county conventions elsewhere in nevada, although his supporters showed less strength in the outlying areas, party officials said
state gop chairwoman sally vitkus-mckinney said monday that party newcomers _ which most robertson backers are _ are welcome. but she added there is frustration because nevada probably will wind up with its 20-member delegation to the national convention committed to somone who won't be the presidential nominee
robertson's state director, steve wark, said there's no way he would encourage the robertson delegates to switch to bush at the state convention level, even though their candidate is clearly far behind
robertson supporters are not about to roll over. they're making a statement and sticking to their commitment,'' he said. however, he said robertson supporters would be prepared to support bush at the national republican convention
robertson, after big losses on super tuesday, indicated he intends to remain in the race, but has virtually given up hope of getting the nomination. he has talked more at recent appearances about his role at the convention, his long-term influence on the party and a possible bid in 1992
the federal government ran up a $23.9 billion budget deficit in february, but the red ink is still running slightly behind last year's total, the treasury department reports
the deficit in february came after a rare surplus of $16.1 billion in january which had occurred because the social security benefits for that month were mailed early and counted in the december spending figures
for the first five months of the budget year, the government has run up a deficit of $89.7 billion, 4.9 percent lower than the red ink incurred in the same period a year ago
the reagan administration is projecting a deficit of $146.7 billion for the entire fiscal year, a drop of 2.4 percent from the $150.4 billion deficit in the 1987 budget year
but this projection is lower than estimates by the congressional budget office and many private forecasters who contend the administration is being too optimistic about the economic outlook
cbo is forecasting a $157 billion deficit, and some private economists are estimating an even higher $170 billion deficit for the budget year that ends on sept. 30
the deficit in 1987 dipped from a record $221.2 billion shortfall in 1986 because of an unexpected windfall in tax revenues caused by changes in the new tax law
some analysts think there could be a second, smaller windfall this year if people end up owing more on their taxes under the new tax law than they did under the old law, something which will not be known until after the april 15 tax filing deadline is passed
we may have another april surprise which could add an additional $10 billion to revenue for the year,'' said michael evans, head of a washington forecasting firm
evans said if the windfall does materialize, the deficit could decline to around $160 billion, but that would still be above the reagan administration's estimate
in february, government revenue totaled $60.4 billion while government spending totaled $84.3 billion. for the first five months of the year, revenues total $347 billion while the government spent $436.7 billion
the largest spending categories in february, as usual, were the military followed by social security and interest on the national debt
military spending totaled $23.1 billion last month and $116.6 billion for the fiscal year so far, up 5.3 percent from the same period a year ago
spending for social security totaled $17.9 billion last month and $86.6 billion for the past five months, up 5.1 percent from the same period in the 1987 fiscal year
the other programs in the department of health and human services, including medicare and medicaid, spent $12.9 billion in february and $63.4 billion so far this budget year, a 2.3 percent increase over 1987
interest on the $2.5 trillion national debt totaled $15 billion last month and $90.8 billion so far this fiscal year, an increase of 9.8 percent over the same period last year, the fastest increase of any of the major categories
for the entire 1988 budget year, interest on the national debt is projected to total $210 billion, amounting to one-fifth of total government spending
hay prices nationally have been averaging around 12 percent higher than a year ago, reflecting a smaller 1987 crop and some increase in demand
the agriculture department in january revised 1987 hay output downward to 149.1 million tons from last october's preliminary forecast of 153.7 million tons
a new report by the department's economic research service says that the u.s. hay area turned out to be about 500,000 acres larger than estimated in october but that the yield was reduced by 4 percent to 2.46 tons per acre
the 1987 hay crop was 6.4 million tons smaller than the record of 155.5 million tons produced in 1986
alfalfa and alfalfa mixture hay production turned out to be 84.6 million tons, down 7 million tons from 1986, and all other hay production of 64.6 million tons was 600,000 tons above the previous year's 64 million,'' the report said
acording to usda production figures for 1987, california was the leading all-hay state with more than 9 million tons, followed by: wisconsin, 8.88 million; minnesota, 7.8 million; south dakota, 7.09 million; and iowa, 6.93 million
last may 1 at the start of the 1987-88 hay crop season, the inventory on hand was estimated at 32.4 million tons, the most since 1980. adding the 1987 crop, that made a total hay supply of 181.5 million tons for the marketing year that runs through april 30, slightly less than the 1986-87 suppply of 182.2 million tons
the hay stockpile on dec. 1 was reported at 119.7 million tons, meaning that 61.8 million tons had been consumed during the seven months since may 1. in the same period a year earlier, hay consumption was 60.5 million tons, the report said
hay prices paid by farmers and ranchers averaged $64.60 per ton during the may-november period, up $4.74 per ton from a year earlier. in december and january of this year, prices averaged $63.75 per ton, up $7.65 from a year earlier
according to usda estimates, the value of hay production in 1987, based on market prices, was more than $9.1 billion, ranking the crop third among all u.s. farm commodities. only corn at $12.2 billion and soybeans, $10.4 billion, were valued higher
those value estimates, incidentally, are not sales receipts or marketings. the usda estimates are based upon total farm values, whether a commodity is sold or used by the producer
the agriculture department has sold mexico 30,000 metric tons of surplus non-fat dry milk for $1,260 per ton, about a third less than it cost american taxpayers
acting undersecretary richard w. goldberg said monday the surplus powdered milk was sold by the department's commodity credit corp. to conasupo, the mexican government's food purchasing authority
goldberg said the sale ``reflects the world market price for non-fat dry milk at the time the sale was negotiated'' with mexico. deliveries are scheduled through march 1989. in addition, the ccc provided mexico with a three-year credit arrangement at commercial rates of interest, he said
according to a recent ccc report, about 454 million pounds of non-fat dry milk were held in storage, with a value of more than $385 million, or about 85 cents per pound. there are approximately 2,205 pounds in a metric ton, which translates to a u.s. value of $1,874 per ton
the surplus was acquired by ccc through purchases of cheese, butter and non-fat dry milk to support the price of milk paid to dairy farmers
congress in 1985 farm law mandated the export sale of 150,000 tons of dairy products annually for the three fiscal years ending sept. 30, 1988. the latest deal with mexico boosted sales this year to 77,520 tons, goldberg said
exporters have sold china an additional 200,000 metric tons of u.s. wheat at subsidized prices, the agriculture department said
the sale, equal to 7.34 million bushels, was handled by continental grain co. and will be shipped in the 1988-89 wheat marketing year that will begin on june 1
melvin e. sims, general sales manager for the department's foreign agricultural service, said monday the sales were part of an authorized 1.2 million tons of wheat announced feb. 5 under the export enhancement program, or eep
although no selling prices or other details were announced, recent prices of wheat at farm points have averaged around $2.67 per bushel, indicating a u.s. farm value of about $20 million
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat
china bought more than 4 million tons of wheat under previous eep arrangements, which allow exporters to sell commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition and then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies
sims said the bonus averaged $24.45 per ton, or about 67 cents per bushel of wheat. the bonuses will be paid in the form of surplus commodities owned by the department's commodity credit corp
china has 260,000 tons remaining for use under the eep initiative announced on feb. 5, he said
the senate has removed a roadblock to a 30-year nuclear cooperation pact with japan, rejecting claims by opponents that the new agreement could add to the proliferation of nuclear weapons
the senate voted 53-50 monday evening to reject a resolution to disapprove the agreement, which provides for the sale of u.s. uranium and uranium enrichment equipment to japan over the next 30 years
it replaces a more restrictive cooperation arrangement which was to expire at the end of the century
as the matter stands, the agreement will take effect at the end of april, 90 legislative days after it was submitted to congress
under the rules governing consideration of the agreement, it could be rejected only if both the house and senate passed resolutions of disapproval and the president signed them
the most controversial element of the new agreement is a provision giving japan advance consent for 30 years to reprocess u.s.-controlled spent nuclear fuel and to use plutonium separated from that fuel without the case-by-case approval required by the present agreement
plutonium is the key ingredient in the production of nuclear weapons
since the process involves shipment of the nuclear material to reprocessing plants in france, opponents of the agreement contended it will loosen u.s. control on the movement of plutonium, open opportunities for terrorists and potentially lead to the proliferation of nuclear weapons
responding to these and other concerns, the senate foreign relations committee voted 15-3 at the end of last year to recommend that the agreement be renegotiated
the reagan administration and supporters of the agreement on the senate floor said that permitting it to take effect would continue u.s. influence over the japanese nuclear program while providing the united states with a major long-term sales market
but sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., chairman of the foreign relations panel, echoed many other senators in contending the agreement does not meet the non-proliferation standards of the atomic energy act
sen. john glenn, d-ohio, said the agreement does not meet legal requirements and gives no assurance of effective non-proliferation safeguards
glenn said the present law works well and that its case-by-case approval arrangements should not be scrapped
but some supporters of the agreement said opponents were motivated less by a genuine concern over nuclear proliferation than by anger at japanese trading practices
there is a certain amount of emotional japan bashing going on around here,'' said sen. james a. mcclure, r-idaho
contending that rejecting the agreement would hurt the united states _ which would lose hundreds of millions of dollars in uranium sales _ and not japan, mcclure added: ``actually it's u.s. bashing we're engaged in here. rejecting this agreement will hurt us and not the japanese.'' father</head>
old loves and old photographs gave a sentimental air to the deportation hearing of a welshman who says he should be allowed to stay in this country because he is the illegitimate son of an american soldier
the claims of roger hobbs, 43, were supported monday in federal immigration court by the kin of the late floyd alexander of cundy's harbor, maine
alexander, who died in 1970, was an american soldier stationed in england during world war ii
hobbs, a janitor, insists he is the product of a union between alexander and sara hobbs, of cardiff, wales
no one has found any legal documents to prove the relationship, but alexander's kin say that for many years he talked openly about his son ``buddy'' overseas
the immigration and naturalization service contends hobbs hasn't proved alexander was his father. it has also said hobbs has a criminal record, including attempting to steal a radiator from an abandoned railway car
after alexander returned from the war, he fathered seven children in this country and married three different women. about a dozen members of the alexander clan came from maine to stand by the man they believe is one of them
hobbs also was accompanied by his wife, anne, 37, and sons, richard, 17, ian, 15, and wayne, 12. as british citizens, they can apply for u.s. citizenship if hobbs wins his case, which is built on memories, family photos, birth and death certificates and letters
alexander's first wife, elsie van buren, 60, of lisbon falls, maine, told immigration judge billino d'ambrosio that alexander wished he could bring sara hobbs and her son to this country but never had the money
as soon as he met me he told me all about it,'' said mrs. van buren. ``he told me he lived with her _ and i know he was in love with her _ and he had a son by her.''
she said alexander's mother, allegra, often wrote to mrs. hobbs and sent clothing and gifts
during the hearing, hobbs sat with head bent at the back of the small courtroom. he wiped an occasional tear from his eyes. his burgundy corduroy jacket was emblazoned with the name of his adopted hometome, richmond, maine, and a large american flag patch was sewn over his heart
mrs. van buren said her first husband once told her he signed a sworn statement that roger hobbs was his son. the document hasn't been found. but she said the documentation of alexander's blood is in the face of roger hobbs
i swear by my life on it. (roger) looked more like my husband than my children,'' mrs. van buren said
hobbs said he first learned of his relationship with alexander in 1968 from his mother, who died 11 years later
in october 1984, hobbs came to this country on a tourist visa with his family. their visas expired in 1985 and hobbs has asserted his right to citizenship since
in 1986, federal rules were changed to give citizenship rights to foreign children fathered by american men outside marriage
hobbs' family can stay here until the case is settled. a hearing was continued to july 7. to correct spelling to `neapolitan,' sted `neopolitan'; subs last graf of 2nd item datelined alford, mass., to correct spelling to `audubon,' sted `audobon'</note>
mike nigro said he was changing the oil on his truck when he first heard someone coming down the street singing ``o sole mio.'' it was his mailman, dennis jordan
i thought the truck had fallen on me and the angels were singing to me,'' nigro said
jordan, a full-time postal worker and a part-time tenor, has brought music to the ears of his customers along his mail route
the 29-year-old letter carrier warms up his voice while on his route with some easy stuff such as neapolitan folk songs. he breaks into arias from ``the barber of seville'' after a good lunch
when i'm in the mood, i'll sing my lungs out,'' he said
jordan has taken formal voice lessons for 12 years and performed with project opera in northampton and other local groups
i don't usually sing opera while i'm working,'' he said recently. ``i'm afraid of using the wrong pitch.''
