married virgins, celebrity children and american women who marry saudis aren't listed in the yellow pages. so where do tv talk show hosts phil donahue, oprah winfrey and geraldo rivera find those people, anyway?
viewer mail is one way we get ideas for guests,'' lorri antosz benson, chief producer for ``donahue,'' said monday
to get the off-beat people that you want, you have to rely on the mails, because there are people out there who write in willing to tell you all about themselves,'' ms. benson said in a telephone interview from new york
the ``oprah winfrey'' show looks for entire audiences that fit a theme of the chicago-based show
its ad on daytime television last week asked, ``if you live with a slob, have ever lived with a slob or your parents were slobs, please contact the oprah winfrey show.''
we get 200 names and call back those with the best stories,'' said alice mcgee, winfrey's publicist. ``we did a show on twins and we had an audience full of twins.''
the ``geraldo'' show syndicated from new york since september recently asked for ideas from various sources
i sent him 10 ideas on who i'd like to see on the show and topics i wanted to see done,'' said joanie stat, chicago publicist for rivera's syndicated specials
talk shows also use many other methods. usually producers spot something in a newspaper or on television, then spend hours tracking down the right guests
we have extensive files: every magazine published, newspapers from the top 15 or 20 markets. we're always clipping things,'' miss mcgee said. ``sometimes the author or guest themselves suggest other people to have on the show.''
with donahue, ms. benson said, ``mostly it's word of mouth. you talk to people who give you names of other people, or you ask the audience if they know of anybody.''
finding the right guests for a show often has been tough detective work
we did a show on women who marry saudis, and go over there and find life is not so good,'' ms. benson said
we got that from the mails, but then it gets more difficult. we started talking to people, calling embassies. then i ran across a book about this subject, and the author had names of people, and they knew people.''  says</head>
a new air force report says an often-cited 1984 government study that was supposed to be ``reassuring'' for vietnam veterans exposed to agent orange was flawed
the revised study said while the chemical defoliant could not be ``confidently identified'' as the reason for a series of health problems among veterans who handled the chemical, it could not be ``exonerated'' either
the report, released monday by sens. john f. kerry, d-mass., and tom daschle, d-s.d., was hailed by veteran activists as a major breakthrough
for the first time the air force is saying in a major way that they cannot rule out dioxin as the cause of ill-health effects,'' said barry kasinitz, spokesman for vietnam veterans of america
air force officials said they have never categorically ruled out a link between agent orange and health problems
but critics say the 1984 study gave that impression when it said, ``in the full context, the baseline study results should be viewed as reassuring to the ranch handers and their families at this time.''
what they're doing is trying to reverse themselves without really saying so,'' said eric hamburg, an aide to kerry
laura petrou, a daschle aide, said, ``we have gotten a clear sense that the air force wants to work with us to get the truth out.''
the air force rejected the senators' contention that the 1984 ranch hand study was ``seriously'' flawed
i think that's an overstatement,'' said dr. william wolfe, chief of epidemiology at the u.s. air force school of aerospace medicine at brooks air force base in texas and the senior investigator in the agent orange probe
there are areas of that report that we have less confidence in the conclusions,'' wolfe said. but he said the bulk of the 1984 findings were upheld by the review
the key problem with the original study, wolfe said, was assumptions about exposure that failed to take work habits into consideration. government scientists now realize that certain workers were sloppier than others in handling agent orange, and therefore had a greater exposure that was not taken into account, he said
the studies are part of the government's 20-year investigation of agent orange and its impact on soldiers who handled the defoliant. operation ranch hand was the air force's code name for the aerial spraying
last year, a veterans administration study found increased deaths due to lung cancer and certain lymph cancers among vietnam veteran marines, providing what veterans' groups called the first clear scientific data implicating agent orange
kerry and daschle also said the 1984 study incorrectly concluded that all birth defects were limited to the skin
and the senators said the revised study indicated that the 1984 study erred by saying the only type of cancer found among the agent orange veterans was skin cancer
wolfe defended the original conclusion, saying, ``there is an increase in the skin cancer in the exposed group, but not in more serious forms of cancers.''
since the 1984 study, scientists have discovered a way to detect dioxin levels in blood even years after exposure. blood samples have been taken from 2,010 veterans who worked with agent orange and that analysis should be ready within two years, wolfe said
kerry and daschle, both vietnam war veterans, are pushing legislation to compensate veterans who suffer from certain conditions that may be tied to agent orange exposure
the american civil liberties union is hailing a federal appeals court's decision to rehear the case of a terminally ill woman who underwent a court-ordered caesarean section against her wishes and those of her doctors
aclu attorney lynn paltrow said monday the decision by the court of appeals for the district of columbia to grant a rehearing is significant because it vacates a ruling that allowed the ``sacrifice of a pregnant woman's life in the name of so-called fetal life.''
the eight-member court, acting on a petition from the aclu, agreed that the full court would rule on a case previously decided upon by a three-judge panel of the appeals court
the three appellate judges had refused to block a superior court order that the woman undergo a caesarean section. the order was issued after george washington university hospital sought a superior court ruling ``as to what it should do in terms of the fetus, whether to intervene (by caesarean section) and save its life.''
the three-judge appeals panel based its decision not to block the lower court's ruling on the belief that the woman's death was imminent and that the child had a better chance of surviving if delivered before her death
the 27-year-old woman, a leukemia patient identified as angela c., gave birth in june to a baby girl who died shortly after the ceasarean operation at the university hospital. the mother died two days later
the full appeals court, in a ruling issued thursday and made public monday, agreed to rehear the case and ordered the submission of briefs by march 28
the aclu said the three-judge panel's ruling needed rehearing because the panel ``made a number of grave mistakes'' and raised the question of ``may a court order a person to submit to potentially life-extinguishing surgery for the benefit of another person, much less for a fetus whose chances of survival are slim.''
interest rates on short-term treasury securities rose in the latest auction, with rates on three-months bills climbing to the highest level since late january
the treasury department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills monday at an average discount rate of 5.76 percent, up from 5.65 percent last week. another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.96 percent, up from 5.78 percent last week
the rates on three-month bills were the highest since jan. 28, when they averaged 5.85 percent. the rates on six-month bills were the highest since they sold for 6.03 percent on feb. 16
the new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 5.93 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,854.40 and 6.23 percent for a six-month bill selling for $9,698.70
in a separate report, the federal reserve said the average yield for one-year treasury bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages dropped to 6.63 percent last week from 6.72 percent the previous week
a former state trooper was found guilty monday of murder in the slaying of his trooper girlfriend, who was shot three times in the head after he took out a $350,000 life insurance policy on her
the dallas county jury deliberated more than three hours before finding joe duncan jr. guilty on the charges of capital murder for financial gain and capital murder of a law officer
elizabeth cobb, 31, had been a trooper less than seven months when she failed to respond to radio calls while on night patrol oct. 11, 1987. the next day, investigators found her body in her patrol car behind a rural church
duncan, who had said that he and miss cobb had discussed marriage, held his chin with both hands as the verdict was announced, while his family, seated two rows behind him, began to cry
circuit judge j.c. norton denied a defense motion to delay the sentencing phase of the trial, which will begin tuesday. the jury can recommend either life in prison without parole for duncan, 33, or death in the state's electric chair. the final decision between those two options will be up to the judge
duncan initially told investigators that he did not know miss cobb's whereabouts the night of her disappearance
several days later, he changed his story, saying that he was scheduled to meet her at the church the night she was killed but that when he arrived she was dead. he was then arrested and charged with murder
during closing arguments earlier monday, defense attorney henry pitts said duncan was guilty only of poor judgment for failing to report her death and not telling investigators that he had seen her body the night she died. duncan had told authorities he had been afraid to report her death after finding the body
insurance agents testified that duncan and miss cobb each purchased $350,000 life insurance policies that named each other as beneficiaries
dallas county district attorney jim sullivan told the jurors that duncan was deeply in debt and plotted to collect from miss cobb's insurance policy
but pitts said investigators failed to fully examine possible links between the slaying and the arrest in florida of a man driving a vehicle similar to a car spotted in the area where miss cobb's body was found
here is the text of the state department reaction monday night to panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega's offer to resign before that country's 1989 presidential elections
we believe the offer is little more than one, a ploy to attempt to legitimize the illegal solis palma regime by calling for negotiations between it and opposition groups and two, an effort on the part of noriega to maintain direct or indirect control of the panamanian defense forces
noriega is the problem, and his preoccupation with remaining on the scene despite overwhelming domestic opposition will only ensure continued economic and political instability there. we stand by our previous view that noriega should go, and the sooner the better for panama
end of state department text
eds: note a0461, panama 8th ld, which makes an important correction. the elections referred to are scheduled for may 1989, not may 1988
