he did not elaborate, but asked the organization to study this issue from all sides
how come iran, which claims to support the palestinian issue and the uprising, is helping jews to migrate to israel.''
he provided no figures on the migration. iran has already denied the charge
mayor frank fasi has proposed legislation to stop foreign investors from purchasing some kinds of property in hawaii, saying the measure would put an end to skyrocketing housing and real estate costs
the mayor on monday sent a bill to the state legislature that would ban the sale of residential, agricultural or preservation land to non-americans. the bill does not cover commercial, resort and industrial properties
the mayor's move comes as the state attempts to deal with a recent wave of foreign investment that has caused property values to jump in some areas. the investment has been spurred by the fall of the dollar's value against the japanese yen
what has triggered my action is the japanese buyer with his cheap dollars,'' fasi told the professional women's network on monday. ``they have been buying homes in several areas of oahu, forcing values to unprecedented levels.''
fasi said he does not consider his move protectionist
i believe in free and open trade between most countries,'' fasi said. ``but i also believe in fairness, and what i see happening here is not fair to americans.''
a spokesman for state senate president richard wong said fasi's bill was under review and may be included in the legislative agenda
the city council is considering a number of bills to curb japanese investment and ease the property tax burden on oahu homeowners
two blacks were killed, seven injured and 39 arrested during a nationwide protest strike that brought the most extensive violence this year, police reported today
dozens of buses, delivery vans and private cars were stoned or firebombed on monday, the 28th anniversary of the sharpeville massacre, and in many cases security forces used tear gas, rubber bullets, birdshot and dogs to disperse rioters, police headquarters said
police said the two deaths and five of the injuries resulted from attacks by blacks on blacks. two blacks were injured by police
several of those arrested were trying to prevent children from going to school and workers from going to work, police said
the protest strike was organized by anti-apartheid activists in defiance of emergency regulations barring calls for such actions. hundreds of thousands of black workers and students stayed away from jobs and classes, both to mark the anniversary of the 1960 police shootings of 69 blacks in sharpeville and to protest the recent bannings of black opposition groups
the department of education and training said class boycotts were reported at 694 of the black schools under its control, 9 percent of the total
the star of johannesburg, the country's largest daily newspaper, said protest strikes would continue ``as long as grievances are not directly addressed.''
instead of tension being relieved through the extension of rights and the removal of restrictions, each new round of protests is met with further clamps which inevitably lead to fresh protests.''
five students from johannesburg's university of the witwatersrand went to local police headquarters today with a bunch of roses for rosemary hunter, the president of the student council who was detained under state-of-emergency regulations monday
the students said a police lieutenant refused to accept the bouquet and told them: ``this is a police station, not a hospital.''
ms. hunter, a law student, was taken from her parents' home at dawn monday
police have not commented on the detention
