astronomers say a vague prediction by the 16th-century astrologer nostradamus has caused unfounded fear that an alignment of planets will trigger an earthquake that will destroy los angeles in may
there is no alignment of planets in may, and even if there were, it wouldn't have anything to do with earthquakes,'' edwin krupp, director of griffith observatory, said monday
but rumors of an impending earthquake, spurred by writings of the french astrologer and the movie ``the man who saw tomorrow,'' which is being sold on videocassette, prompted more than 100 fearful people to call the observatory in recent weeks, krupp said
we an tell by the phone calls that many people are getting needlessly afraid of the possibility of an earthquake,'' he said, calling the quake predictions ``bunk.''
astronomer john mosley, the observatory's program supervisor, wrote recently: ``there are 11,000 earthquakes each year in the los angeles area strong enough to be recorded. there may be a significant earthquake in may 1988, here or elsewhere ... but if there is, it will have nothing to do with the planets' positions.''
mosley said followers of nostradamus, who lived from 1503 to 1566, have claimed he predicted such events as the russian revolution, the assassinations of john and robert kennedy and the japanese attack on pearl harbor
but nostradamus' predictions, written in rhyme, ``are exceptionally vague, and in general it is only after the fact that a link can be made between his rhymed prediction and an historical event,'' mosley said
he said ``the man who saw tomorrow'' claimed nostradamus wrote that an alignment of saturn, jupiter, mercury, venus and mars will cause a major earthquake in may in los angeles
the prophecy is quoted incorrectly in the movie,'' mosley said. ``nostradamus predicts a severe hailstorm, not an earthquake. ... there is no clue that tells us where this hailstorm will occur.''
mosley said: ``the last time the planets were supposed to align and trigger mass destruction in los angeles was in 1982, the year of the `jupiter effect,''' a book that claims the planets' tidal influence causes quakes
untold millions did not die in 1982 and there's no reason to think that anything will happen in 1988,'' he said. even if the planets were aligned, ``their gravitational effect would be completely negligible ... and they would have no effect on our planet's weather, tides or earthquakes,'' mosley added. with details on continued strike today. picks up 4th graf, `in washington ...'</note>
strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega offered to resign before the may 1989 presidential election if opponents agree to talks with his regime, but the opposition and the united states rejected the offer
the general has to go immediately _ not eventually,'' said aurelio barria, head of the national civic crusade, an opposition umbrella group. ``there will be no dialogue with him.''
barria said the general strike, which shut down over 90 percent of this nation's commerce on monday, would be even more complete today
indeed, most stores in the downtown area remained shuttered today
i say this to noriega: phooey,'' said one downtown panama city merchant guarding his closed dry goods shop
in washington, the state department also dismissed noriega's resignation offer as ``little more than ... a ploy'' to keep noriega's cronies in power and the general in control of the armed forces
noreiga should go, and the sooner the better for panama,'' said state department spokeswoman anita stockman
after noriega was indicted on u.s. drug charges, the reagan administration dried up the flow of money to panama, which uses the u.s. dollar as its currency, in an effort to force him out, and the economy is near collapse
noriega's offer to resign, announced monday night in a national broadcast by civilian chief of state manuel solis palma, was conditioned on a national dialogue with the opposition. but opposition leader guillermo cochez of the christian democratic party said the proposed dialogue involved a hand-picked 33-member panel that would have 22 pro-noriega members
this is not a dialogue,'' said cochez. ``it's just cynicism.''
noriega, the chief of panama's 15,000-member defense forces and the power behind the civilian government, left the presidential palace after solis palma's speech and hailed his proposal as a panamanian solution, rather than one imposed by the united states. ``i have no reason to talk to the united states,'' noriega told reporters. ``i talk to panamanians.''
in his speech, solis palma said noriega had given his word ``as an officer and a gentleman'' to step down before elections scheduled for may 1989
solis palma, elevated to chief of state when noriega ousted president eric arturo delvalle on feb. 26, said he would accept the general's resignation only after the dialogue
opposition leaders derided the proposal
he said, `here i have a little piece of candy, and if you all behave, i'll give it to you, okay?,' said businessman pierre leignadier, a crusade member. leignadier called the idea an insult to the panamanian people
crusade leaders said they expected even stronger support today for the general strike despite noriega's offer
on monday, the strike almost totally shut down the capital of this nation of 2.5 million and, according to the crusade, outlying cities and towns as well
the paralyzation is total in industry, finance and commerce,'' said business leader carlos gonzalez de la lastra
about half of government employees _ who were warned they would be suspended if they went on strike _ failed to show up for work, he said
the strike was called after the government decreed a state of emergency last week allowing authorities to suspend constitutional rights
solis palma said on monday the reagan administration ``says they want a country without drug traffickers,'' but that continued u.s. control of the panama canal was the real motive behind the attack on noriega
delvalle tried to fire noriega on feb. 25, after two u.s. drug trafficking indictments against noriega were handed up in florida
after noriega orchestrated delvalle's ouster on feb. 26, the united states froze panama's international bank accounts, leaving the government and many private businesses without cash to pay employees
retirees were told monday they will not be paid this week. the dockworkers union official, gustavo gonzalez, said solis palma told union leaders in a meeting at the presidential palace sunday the country had no more money
after the government was unable to give full paychecks to employees last week, several national police members tried and failed to stage a military coup, and thousands of anti-noriega rioters took the streets
one man hit by an army shotgun blast during last week's violence died monday of his wounds, becoming the first death in the latest wave of unrest
also monday, the panamanian defense forces announced a shakeup, kicking out 17 officers connected with the coup attempt and promoting 98 loyal officers
wedding guests looked on in horror as a suspected getaway car being chased by police ran down a bridesmaid, dragged her across the street and smashed into the church where the wedding had just taken place
marilyn york, 18, of little rock, was helping to decorate the bride and bridgroom's car monday when she was hit and killed, police said
she had been a bridesmaid in the wedding of 21-year-old valarie dodson and 20-year-old larry charles minutes before at hoover united methodist church
police were chasing a sports car which had been reported stolen last week when the car was driven onto a parking lot and hit the parked car onto which the wedding party had painted the words ``just married.''
the speeding car then ran over ms. york, crossed the street and hit a corner of the church
the driver of the car ran a short distance and was caught and arrested
we were decorating the car and spraying it when we heard a loud noise,'' said viola dodson, the bride's mother. ``we had our backs turned and when we looked around, we saw him coming at us real fast.''
the bride's mother said she started pushing people out of the way and managed to get out of the path of the car herself
ms. york, a friend of the bride, ``got caught between his car and my car and he drug her body across the street and slammed into the wall,'' mrs. dodson said
the police said the firebird was reported to have been used as a getaway car in a shoplifting at a little rock store sunday and was seen by a police officer less than a mile from the wedding scene monday. the officer tried to stop the car but the driver sped away
the company that distributed a cylinder of gas that exploded and killed three at a research laboratory here last week began recalling hundreds of similar cylinders nationwide, state officials said
liquid carbonics industries inc., a chicago-based gas distributor, is recalling cylinders containing the gas silane following the blast at the gollob analytical services plant here thursday, said richard fulton, a spokesman for the state department of environmental protection
a spokeswoman for the company in chicago said it was investigating the origin of the cylinder that exploded but declined to confirm the recall or comment further
the explosion was triggered by a silane cylinder that was contaminated with nitrous oxide, a highly unstable mixture, fulton said
the blast killed three people, seriously injured a liquid carbonics employee and forced the evacuation of 1,500 people living near the plant
fulton said liquid carbonics on monday removed cylinders of silane from its harrison, n.j. storage facility. phone calls to liquid carbonics in harrison were unanswered
elsewhere, about 1,000 workers were kept from their jobs monday in california after canisters containing potentially explosive chemicals were discovered at semiconductor facilities there
chemical inspectors eventually concluded that four canisters at advanced micro devices inc. in santa clara and teledyne semiconductor in mountain view were harmless, and work was scheduled to resume today
another 150 cylinders stored at a liquid carbonics plant in san carlos where they are manufactured were expected to be examined tuesday, officials said. company officials feared the canisters might have come from the same batch as the one that blew up
at a gould inc. semiconductor plant in pocatello, idaho, another possibly contaminated silane cylinder bought from liquid carbonics was emptied sunday after employees and residents of a nearby nursing home were evacuated, said a spokesman at gould's headquarters in chicago
new jersey officials said monday another potentially dangerous cylinder of silane that prompted officials to evacuate residents friday night continued to burn at the gollob plant
two other potentially hazardous canisters at the site were removed sunday. fulton said about 200 non-hazardous cylinders of gas remained at the site
state officials have not conducted an inventory of the gutted gollob building and were trying to decide whether to let the flaming cylinder burn itself out, fulton said
evacuees were allowed to return to their homes sunday and businesses near the gollob plant were allowed to reopen monday
a group of residents in this western pacific island chain have started a drive to have palau declared a commonwealth of the united states, citing a need for u.s. law enforcement agencies
the palau america association wrote to president reagan and lawmakers monday, informing them of a petition drive aimed at placing a constitutional amendment on palau's november election ballot
palau, the last pacific territory still under u.s. trusteeship since world war ii, has entered into a compact of free association with the united states. that measure is still awaiting implementation in congress
this movement is born out of a belated realization by many palauans that the future well-being of palau and a majority of its people will not be protected under a compact of free association without the presence of u.s. federal law enforcement agencies,'' said a letter from francisco t. uludong, who is working on the petition drive
volunteers need signatures of 25 percent of the electorate, about 2,000 people
the soviet government announced today that three soviet soldiers have been taken prisoner by eritrean separatists and another is missing in ethiopia
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov told reporters at a news briefing that 13 soviet military advisers were captured in ethiopia last week by forces fighting to establish an eritrean state separate from the government of addis ababa
recently the so-called people's front for the liberation of eritrea has intensified combat operations,'' gerasimov said
he said nine of the soviets captured had returned to their command posts, three had been identified by their captors as prisoners of war and one remained missing
the spokesman said the soldiers were serving as military advisers in ethiopia, which has strong political ties to the soviet union
gerasimov had no other details of the incident or the conditions in which the soviet captives are being held
eritrea, a former italian colony on the red sea, was administered by britain from world war ii until 1952 when it was federated with ethiopia under a united nations resolution. ethiopia incorporated it as a province in 1962, sparking a rebellion which seeks independence. the</note>
the united states can have ``great certainty'' that it will spot any soviet attempts to cheat on the treaty eliminating medium-range atomic missiles from europe, the senate intelligence committee unanimously concluded today
the testimony came as the senate foreign relations committee began working on the final details of the pact after two months of testimony on the treaty signed dec. 8 by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
the foreign relations committee is reviewing the pact. senate democratic leaders say they expect the treaty will be approved by the full chamber next month
leaders of both parties have predicted the final tally will show 88 to 90 votes for the treaty, far more than the 67 needed for ratification
as part of the senate review, the intelligence committee looked at american ability to monitor soviet compliance through a variety of means including on-site ground inspection and satellites
the intelligence community will be able to monitor the drawdown and elimination of declared soviet missile launchers and associated equipment with great certainty,'' said the report, which was unanimously approved by the committee
but sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the intelligence committee, told the foreign relations committee that more money needs to be spent to be sure of finding soviet attempts to cheat on a separate treaty making deep cuts in long-range atomic weapons. that prospective treaty is now being worked on by american and soviet negotiators
the interests of the united states are served by effective, verifiable limitations on nuclear weapons,'' said boren. ``indeed, such limitations must continue to be pursued vigorously long after the issue of ratification of the (medium-range missile) treaty has been been resolved.''
sen. william cohen, r-maine, vice chairman of the intelligence committee, warned the foreign relations panel that ``no verification and monitoring regime can be absolutely perfect.''
despite the expected outcome, the pact has come under fire from both democrats and conservative republicans
democrats, led by sen. joseph biden, d-del., are considering attaching a legal condition to the treaty which provides that the interpretation given by administration officials during treaty hearings is binding on future administrations
democratic officials were working late monday to agree on some type of language, but no final proposal had been approved, according to congressional sources speaking on condition of anonymity
the proposal arises from the ongoing dispute between the reagan administration and congressional democrats over reagan's assertion that he has the legal right unilaterally to change the u.s. interpretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty
that change would allow some tests of reagan's star wars anti-missile defense system, but congressional democrats have argued that any alteration in how a treaty is interpreted should first be approved by the senate
the white house told congressional democrats last week it opposed the democratic-backed effort to attach a condition to the treaty because the condition would require the executive branch to adhere to every statement made by administration officials during the hearings, ``no matter how trivial.''
the conservative opposition is led by sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., ranking republican on the foreign relations committee
helms has claimed that the administration made ``misrepresentations'' about the effect of the treaty, a charge that was flatly denied by secretary of state george p. shultz
shultz, who was both the first and last administration witness to testify to the foreign relations panel, said the treaty ``stands on its merits'' and ``should not be made a vehicle for statements on other issues.''
shultz and other administration officials have consistently urged the senate to avoid so-called ``killer amendments'' that could force a reopening of negotiations with the soviet union
administration officials have also argued that rejection of the treaty would be a deep blow to u.s. prestige and power in the 16-member nato alliance
one condition which will be opposed is being offered by sen. dennis deconcini, d-ariz
the amendment will require reagan to ``reaffirm to the soviet union the importance americans place on human rights and fundamental freedoms in the achievement of lasting peace among nations.'' ending</head>
a pro-iranian shiite moslem cleric called today for extremists to kidnap more americans because, he claimed, the united states was responsible for the problems in the middle east
america is the cause of all our calamities,'' sheik subhi tufaili was quoted as saying in a published interview. ``the moslems should chase america's symbols everywhere.''
tufaili, a senior leader of the iranian-backed hezbollah, or party of god, was quoted as urging his followers to ``hold (hostage) all the american regime.''
meanwhile, lebanon's highest ranking shiite cleric, sheik mohammed mehdi shamseddine, said he believed that the kidnapping of foreigners for political motives ``has reached its end.''
we are inclined to believe that this course of political action has reached an end,'' shamseddine told the lebanese news agency, an arabic-language newsletter. he did not elaborate
shamseddine said he has never approved of kidnappings
his remark reflects differences within lebanon's shiite community over the abduction of foreigners
tufaili made his remarks in an interview published by the hezbollah-financed weekly magazine al-wihda al-islamiah, or islamic unity
hezbollah, made up of shiites loyal to iran's ayatollah ruhollah khomeini, is believed to be an umbrella organization for underground groups holding most of the nine americans missing in lebanon
tufaili also charged that the united nations interim force in lebanon was an ``umbrella for many of america's and the west's spies.''
the nine-nation 5,800-strong unifil has been deployed in south lebanon since march 19, 1978
u.s. marine lt. col. william r. higgins, chief of the 76-member observer group-lebanon attached to unifil, was kidnapped near the southern lebanese port city of tyre on feb. 17
the pro-iranian organization of the oppressed on earth, believed to be a hezbollah-affiliated group, claimed higgins' abduction and claimed he was a spy. u.s. and unifil officials denied the charge
in addition to the nine americans, 13 foreigners are missing after being kidnapped in lebanon. they are four frenchmen, three britons, one west german, one italian, one irishman, one indian and two unidentified foreign men
terry anderson, 40, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, is the longest-held foreign hostage in lebanon. he was kidnapped march 16, 1985
