a protestant who allegedly killed three roman catholics in a gun and grenade attack at an irish republican army funeral last week will be charged with six counts of murder, police said today
michael stone, 33, has been in custody since last wednesday when mourners grabbed and beat him as he fled the funeral in milltown, firing and hurling grenades
police gave no immediate details of the three other murder charges against stone. but police sources have said stone was also suspected of being connected with other killings of catholics in recent years
meanwhile, the catholic ghettos of west belfast braced for a wave of arrests in the hunt for the killers of two british soldiers at an ira funeral saturday. a crowd, some of whom apparently feared another protestant attack, beat and stripped the soldiers who were then shot dead by ira gunmen
police sources said up to 30 people may be arrested
earlier today, british troops discoverd and detonated a homemade bomb outside an apartment building on the outskirts of west belfast
and police reported finding two rifles, grenades and a pistol in londonderry's catholic shantallow district, the fourth cache found in the city this week
in londonderry, police sought the men who killed policeman clive graham at a londonderry police checkpoint monday. graham was the 12th victim in two weeks of tension and sectarian violence in northern ireland
police chief supt. david turkington said ``someone must have seen'' the gunmen who held a family hostage, fired on graham from a row house and escaped in a hijacked car
britain's two tv networks, the british broadcasting corp. and independent television news, said monday they have refused police demands to hand over untransmitted film of last wednesday's funeral rampage on grounds this would endanger their crews in the future
this policy is to protect our film crews, to protect the lives of our staff,'' said a bbc spokeswoman, who declined to be identified
addressing the house of commons in london on monday, northern ireland secretary tom king said, ``a massive murder investigation is under way in which all possible resources are involved to identify all those responsible.''
he also announced an immediate review of a policy of not policing ira funerals
police introduced the no-policing policy at last wednesday's funeral for the three ira guerrillas killed in gibraltar under pressure from catholic leaders who feared clashes between police and mourners
the latest wave of tension and violence began march 6, when british commandos shot and killed three unarmed ira guerrillas in gibraltar while they were allegedly planning a bombing attack in the british colony
