residents of the northeast dug out winter overcoats and ski jackets as unseasonable cold gripped the region today, three days into spring
temperatures were generally below freezing, with readings in the teens and single digits over much of the great lakes region and northern atlantic coast. subzero readings were reported at a few locations in maine, new york and pennsylvania
somebody left the door open on the north side of the house,'' said bob thomas, a forecaster for the national weather service in albany, n.y. ``we're getting a strong cold wind right out of hudson's bay.''
spring has been in disguise since it began sunday; the 21-degree high in albany on monday was about 20 degrees below normal
some of the early blooming flowers may be negatively affected. some of the crocuses may not fare too well,'' said george good, a horticulturalist in ithaca, n.y
however, many flowers may not have poked their shoots out of the ground yet, good said. ``for the most part there hasn't been enough warm weather yet to really get things started.''
ten northeastern cities reported records this morning, including allentown, pa., where the 15 degree low tied the record set in 1965; mansfield, ohio, where the 14-degree mark shaved a degree off the 1965 record; and syracuse, n.y., where the 5 degrees cut three degrees off a record set in 1959
a reading of 7 degrees shortly after midnight set a record in binghamton, n.y. the old record low for the date was 8 degrees in 1965
bradford, pa., was the coldest place in the nation at 2 a.m. est, at zero degrees, and it was 18 degrees at 5:30 a.m. in new york city. ohio residents looked out on a lake erie that was still mostly ice-covered
however, a warming trend was expected to put winter to flight this afternoon and wednesday, with temperatures rising into the 40s and 50s in the mid-atlantic region
steve smith, a weather specialist for environment canada at churchill, manitoba, on the shores of hudson's bay, disavowed responsibility for the cold
smith said a high-pressure system was driving the cold air from the north. ``that's why you're getting our weather. so you really can't blame us,'' he said
they call us the polar bear capital of the world. while you're getting our weather, we've got a south wind that's pushing our temperatures above normal,'' smith said
in churchill, the high monday was 10 degrees, seven degrees above normal. the low was minus 15. tehran. picks up 4th graf, `shipping executives ...' subs grafs 7-8, bgng, `the escalation ...,' with 2 grafs to update with today's missile attack. picks up 9th graf, `the havglimt ...'</note>
an iranian gunboat and helicopter attacked a norwegian-operated tanker carrying volatile chemicals through the persian gulf at dawn today. a greek supertanker later was reported set ablaze in another iranian raid
two crewmen were killed and four wounded in the first attack, on the 38,534-ton havglimt, flying the singapore flag, shipping executives reported
iraq fired a missile at tehran today and mounted air raids on seven other cities, the iraqi news agency reported. the missile was the 45th aimed at the iranian capital since the iran-iraq ``war of cities'' resumed march 13
shipping executives said an unidentified u.s. warship patrolling the gulf picked up 10 seamen, who were floating in a raft after abandoning the greek supertanker, the 357,130-ton stavros g.l
the executives said the other 19 greek crewmen stayed on board to fight the flames. a salvage tugboat soon joined the effort
there were no casualties aboard the greek vessel, which was attacked about 1 p.m. only a few miles south of where the havglimt was hit in a dawn attack
the attacks were the seventh and eighth by iran on neutral shipping since friday. they came as 51 crewmen remained missing and were presumed dead after an iraqi raid on two tankers near iran's kharg island oil terminal. earlier reports had said 54 crewmen were missing
the escalation of the ``tanker war'' came as iran and iraq were locked in a series of missile duels and air raids on each other's major cities. the two nations have been at war for 7{ years
today's missile attack on tehran was the 106th such attack since feb. 29
about 65 iranian missiles have slammed into baghdad in that time. also monday, iran launched an artillery and rocket attack on basra, inflicting heavy casualties, iraq said
the havglimt tanker, carrying ammonia and operated by the oslo-based havtor co., was hit at dawn about 12 miles northwest of dubai, said the gulf-based shipping executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the dead crewmen were identified as singapore nationals, and the ship's norwegian captain was among the wounded. other members of the 26-man, multinational crew were mainly treated for inhalation of ammonia vapors, according to the executives. four needed hospitalization
the fire in the engine room of the stricken tanker was brought under control by salvage tugboats, but the flames later reignited in the crew's quarters, the executives said
the british destroyer hms exeter, on patrol in the area, dispatched a helicopter to help rescue the crew, many of whom had fainted from fumes leaking from blasted cargo holds, the shipping sources said
a navy medical team wore gas masks as they were lowered from the helicopter onto the tanker to help airlift the seamen
the bodies of the dead and the injured crew members were lowered onto a salvage tugboat, which took them to a hospital at the united arab emirates port of dubai, the sources said
the shipping executive said at least one gunboat raided the vessel with machine-gun fire and rocket-propelled grenades. forty minutes later, a helicopter fired rockets at the tanker
they went for the accommodation quarters. there were plenty, plenty of hits all over,'' said associated press photographer greg english, who flew over the stricken tanker in a helicopter
iraq resumed attacks on iranian oil shipping lanes on march 8, after a lull in attacks in the persian gulf for about a month
on monday, iranian gunboats attacked and set ablaze the 10,168-ton spanish refrigerator ship iberian reefer and the 61,762-ton liberian-registered fumi with rocket grenades. no casualties were reported on board either ship
at least 51 crewmen remained missing from iraq's saturday attack near iran's kharg island oil terminal. the attack destroyed two iranian-owned ships, the 253,837-ton sanandaj and the 316,379-ton avaj
the norwegian shipping association reported today that the number of missing was ``imprecise,'' but the latest figure was 51
earlier, norwegian officials had said 54 crewmen, mostly iranians and asians, were presumed dead. a swedish engineer also was among the missing
the shipping association said it had no independent confirmation of the deaths and was working on the basis of gulf sources
both ships were owned by the iran's national iranian tanker co., but the sanandaj crew was hired by a norwegian firm, viking engineering, and another norwegian company, scanact, had part interest in the avaj
the maritime insurance firm, lloyd's of london, said 37 ships had been damaged in attacks by both iraq and iran this year
delegates to the american jewish congress convention voiced concern today about the role of religious groups in politics but tabled a resolution urging churches and synagogues to refrain from active roles in political campaigns
the proposed resolution, which will be redrafted, had suggested it was ``inherently dangerous'' for religious groups to identify with one candidate or one political party. it reaffirmed the right of all people, including clergy, to seek political office
the resolution is expected to be taken up at a later national meeting of the group, but leaders did not indicate whether it would be during the 1988 presidential campaign
discussion centered on whether delegates should take a strong stand against practices by two religious leaders now running for president, pat robertson and rev. jesse jackson
the tabled resolution said ``certain recent practices of both these candidates are troubling issues,'' citing robertson's use of church-owned buses to bring supporters to caucuses and jackson's effort during the super tuesday primaries to collect contributions in churches
in their nearly unanimous decision to redraft the resolution, delegates said it could be counterproductive and also should not refer to any individual
on monday night, an ajc leader urged that a new world zionist meeting be convened in jerusalem in the 1990s to unify jews everywhere with israelis and to heal the division over how to achieve peace with the arabs
we are indeed one people, sharing one destiny, no matter where we live,'' executive director henry siegman told delegates at the 70th anniversary convention
siegman reiterated the ajc's support for a u.s. plan calling for talks on palestinian autonomy in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, followed by an international peace conference including israel and its arab neighbors. he also spoke out against israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir's condemnation of jews who object to his opposition to the plan
the jewish people everywhere, and not only those who vote in support of a particular israeli party, have a right to speak up when they believe certain policies profoundly violate a legacy that belongs to the jewish people collectively, even if finally only the citizens of israel will vote and make those decisions on which their security depends,'' siegman said
one moment, deandra anrig was peacefully flying her kite. the next, she too was soaring through the air, courtesy of a passing plane which snagged the kite string
i'm very sore _ and i was very scared,'' said the 8-year-old dublin, calif., youngster after spending monday at home on an air mattress, surrounded by ice packs. ``i want to go kite flying again, but where there are no airplanes.''
on sunday, deandra and her father, brad, were flying the kite at shoreline park, using strong 200-pound test line. suddenly, a plane taking a patient to nearby stanford university hospital snagged the kite and jerked her off the ground
she flew about 200 feet, about 10 feet off the ground, until she let go to avoid hitting a tree. she was bumped and bruised, but otherwise uninjured
pilot jake uranga, of reno, nev., and his passenger also were uninjured and the plane landed safely at palo alto airport nearby
the plane suffered $10,000 in damage and the park has banned kite flying until an investigation is complete
she said it was just a big jerk that lifted her into the air,'' said deandra's mother, debby. ``it carried her right over my husband's head. all he saw was a shadow going over his head
i'm just thankful she let go.''
the head of the public health service said today he is pleased with new guidelines prohibiting discrimination against federal employees with the aids virus
we worked very closely with the office of personnel managment in developing them,'' said dr. robert windom, the no. 2 official of the department of health and human services and head of the health service
the regulations are reasonable and reflect phs concerns,'' windom said
he and other health service officials will brief personnel officers from about 30 federal agencies on the guidelines on thursday
the rules, which will allow federal supervisors to take disciplinary action against employees who refuse to work with colleagues carrying the virus, were distributed to federal agencies this week
the federal government, as an enlightened and compassionate employer concerned with the health and welfare of its employees, has an obligation to show the way in addressing the realities of the aids epidemic,'' constance horner, the director of the office of personnel management, said in a memo accompanying the guidelines
the guidelines instruct federal agencies to treat aids-infected employees ``in the same manner as employees who suffer from other serious illnesses.'' they also say there is ``no medical basis for employees refusing to work with such fellow employees or agency clients
if an employee's threat or refusal to work with an aids-infected co-worker disrupts office functions, managers are told to ``consider appropriate corrective or disciplinary action against the threatening or disruptive employees.''
horner said agencies should grant leave to aids-infected employees ``in the same manner as they would for other emloyees with medical conditions.'' aids-infected employees may continue their life insurance, but cannot increase their coverage after they become seriously ill, the guidelines state
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. indictment</head>
a federal judge ruled today that gen. manuel antonio noriega's attorney can formally protest the legality of racketeering and drug trafficking charges, even though the panmanian strongman has not appeared in court to answer the indictment
u.s. district judge william m. hoeveler granted permission for noriega's attorney, neal sonnett, to file a ``limited appearance'' on behalf of the embattled strongman
this limited appearance would be solely for the purpose of attacking the legality and sufficiency of the indictment,'' said sonnett, among a battery of miami attorneys retained by noriega
the decision came over vehement objections from assistant u.s. attorney richard gregorie, who said that noriega's attorney could not make any arguments until noriega responds legally to the u.s. indictment by making an appearance
gregorie noted that noriega had not surrendered nor made any court appearance to answer charges in the sealed indictment returned by a federal grand jury in miami feb. 4, which named noriega and 15 other people
gregorie and sonnett were involved in a heated exchange during the hearing in hoeveler's courtroom
i represent general noriega,'' sonnett told the judge
the government objects. he has no client to represent!'' responded gregorie
i have a client and mr. gregorie knows that i have a client,'' sonnett shot back, to which gregorie responded, ``then bring him here!''
hoeveler agreed to let sonnett file by friday a memorandum of law setting forth his position. he gave gregorie until the following friday to respond
you may file your motion; then we'll decide whether you can argue it,'' hoeveler told sonnett
only one of the 16 defendants named in the indictment, brian alden davidow, was at today's hearing
davidow, 26, the only person to surrender in the case thus far and be arraigned, has pleaded innocent to the racketeering conspiracy count and other charges in the indictment. he is free on $500,000 bond after his family posted 10 percent of that amount with the court
hoeveler delayed setting a trial date after davidow made a formal waiver of his right to a speedy trial
most of the other defendants named in the indictment were in either panama or colombia, gregorie said
anglican bishops, including an envoy sent by the archbishop of canterbury, today pledged support for archbishop desmond tutu in his confrontation with the government
tutu, the first black to lead the anglican church in southern africa, has angered president p.w. botha by declaring that he and other church leaders will carry on the work of anti-apartheid groups which last month were banned from operating
nineteen bishops, after an emergency meeting with tutu, issued a statement warning that the government ``is driving this beloved country closer to civil war.''
we offer archbishop tutu our loyalty and support,'' the bishops said. ``we shall not allow the government to isolate him.''
tutu, who declared that the government would ``bite the dust,'' said it was important that botha and other white south africans ``know that i am not just spouting forth things that come into my head.''
these are responsible people,'' said tutu, gesturing to the bishops. ``they would have knocked me down if they believed that what i am saying is inconsistent with the gospel.''
botha met with tutu, the winner of the 1984 nobel peace prize, last week and suggested that the archbishop had aligned himself with the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement
referring to this, the bishops said they ``take grave offense at the cavalier way'' in which botha treated tutu
among those attending today's meeting was bishop keith sutton of lichfield, england, who was sent as representative of the archbishop of canterbury, robert runcie
runcie is spiritual leader of the 70-million-member worldwide anglican communion
he is a christian leader,'' sutton said of tutu. ``his objections to apartheid grow directly out of his pastoral work.''
at a news conference monday, tutu dared botha to take action against him
if they try to restrict me or ban me, they are just wasting their time, because i will not obey their orders,'' tutu said. ``they will have to put me in jail.''
i can't keep looking over my shoulder to see if god has got the approval or disapproval of the government,'' he added
three weeks ago, tutu and 24 other church leaders were arrested and briefly detained after they tried to march to parliament in cape town with a petition protesting the latest crackdown on opposition
last month, the government banned 17 other organizations from participating in any activity not approved by the government
since then tutu and other church representatives have taken up the struggle against apartheid, which by law and custom establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs
south africa's 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. pvs, ``i'm not</note>
president reagan said today he still hopes panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega will relinquish power and leave the country
but reagan would not say whether he expects noriega to do that
asked by reporters if he would be satisfied should noriega step down but not leave his central american country, reagan said, ``we feel noriega should leave panama.''
reagan, questioned as he arrived at the capitol for talks on the possibility of resuming u.s. aid to the contra rebels in nicaragua, was asked if he expected noriega to agree to leave his nation
i'm not making any predictions,'' the president replied
at the state department, spokesman charles redman said that the panamanian people clearly have not been deceived by noriega's conditional offer to step down by may 1989
redman said panamanians regard the offer as a ``ploy to buy time,'' a view shared by the united states
the message from panamanians is clear. for the good of panama, noriega should leave,'' redman said
his presence is the root cause of continued political and economic instability,'' redman added. ``the ongoing general strike is only the most recent demonstration of the overwhelming opposition from all segments of panamanian society to noriega's continued rule.''
on monday, shortly after panama's chief of state, manuel solis palma, told panamanians of noriega's offer, state department press officer anita stockman said, ``we stand by our previous view that noriega should go, and the sooner the better for panama.''
solis palma said noriega had given his word ``as an officer and a gentleman'' to step down before panamanian elections scheduled for may 1989 if his conditions _ which include talks with opposition leaders _ are met
william g. walker, deputy assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs, said noriega's offer ``totally ignores the reality of the situation.''
almost everyone in panama wants him out tomorrow and wants him out of the country,'' said walker, who was in panama last week to discusss terms under which noriega might step down
a state department statement released by stockman said:
we believe the offer is little more than one, a ploy to attempt to legitimize the illegal solis palma regime by calling for negotiations between it and opposition groups and two, an effort on the part of noriega to maintain direct or indirect control of the panamanian defense forces.''
noriega is under indictment on federal drug charges in florida. the united states has dried up the flow of money to panama, which uses the u.s. dollar as its currency, in the effort to force him out, and the economy is near collapse
noriega is the problem, and his preoccupation with remaining on the scene despite overwhelming domestic opposition will only insure continued economic and political instability there,'' the state department said
noriega put down a coup attempt by dissident officers last week and rejected a u.s. plan for him to leave panama and live in spain
solis palma replaced eric arturo delvalle, who was dismissed by the legislature after he tried to fire noriega. delvalle, who is hiding in panama, is still recognized by the united states as panama's president
cuban dissident ricardo bofill's home in havana has been surrounded by people protesting his activities on behalf of human rights, and he appears to be under house arrest, a newspaper said today
bofill, president of the pro human rights committee of cuba, was forced back into his house when he tried to leave, said jerry scott, press attache of the u.s. interests section in havana, told the spanish-language edition of the miami herald on monday
the mobs have been organized by the (cuban) government,'' said hilda felipe, a delegate of the cuban committee who does not live in cuba. ``they have followed him, insulted him on the bus and the mobs in front of his home have thrown rocks at him.''
a diplomatic source who asked not to be identified told el nuevo herald that the cuban government wanted to destroy bofill's image and put him in prison before a scheduled united nations human rights commission visit to cuba
since last week granma, the official newspaper of cuba's communist party, has published a series of articles criticizing bofill
ms. felipe said she had been assured by contacts in cuba that the protest against bofill was not supported by the community at large but backed solely by the government
the u.s. interests section in havana operates out of the swiss embassy because the united states and cuba don't have diplomatic relations
the government said tuesday that 12 men _ including an opposition party leader _ have been arrested in a plot to overthrow the government of president samuel doe
seven coup plotters were still at large, including an army captain and two sergeants, said information minister emmanuel bowier
among those arrested in the plot, which was uncovered march 16, were gabriel kpolleh, leader of the opposition liberia unification party, bowier said. four of those arrested were soldiers
arms, ammunition and military uniforms were found in a monrovia neighborhood, he added
doe has been the target of several assassination and coup attempts. an abortive nov. 12, 1985 coup attempt, which came after elections that opposition leaders said were rigged, left more than 600 people dead
police on tuesday said they authenticated a statement from a left-wing terrorist group claiming responsiblity for a weekend bar bombing that injured 13 people, including four u.s. servicemen and two britons
the statement sent by the revolutionary popular solidarity organization to the left-wing daily eleftherotypia is similar to one the group sent five years ago claiming responsibility for an abortive attack against the saudi arabian envoy in greece, a police spokesman said
the four non-commissioned u.s. officers who were injured in saturday's bomb attack at the seaside bar in the suburb of glyfada all serve at nearby hellenikon u.s. air force base
the group's statement said it would continue its attacks ``against the north american imperialists'' until the four u.s. military bases in greece are shut down
parliament on tuesday approved a government plan to raise the speed limit on the nation's highways from 62 mph to 74 mph
the vote ended several years of debate by environmentalists, pro-auto lobbying groups and the government, which conceded the old speed limit was widely ignored
the decision, scheduled to go into effect may 1, marked the demise of a measure that followed the 1973 arab oil embargo against the netherlands
the new speed limit of 120 kilometers per hour had been vigorously opposed by vocal environmentalist groups, which said it would further damage the fragile environment in this crowded nation of 14.6 million people. the groups, backed by left-wing political parties, faced a powerful lobby of road builders, garage owners and other car-related interests
the old speed limit of 100 kilometers per hour remains in force along the highway in the densely populated urban crescent stretching from rotterdam via the hague and amsterdam to utrecht in the central netherlands
the last two years have been the warmest in this country in more than three decades, the national oceanic and atmospheric administration reported tuesday
both 1986 and 1987 recorded average temperatures for the year of 54.0 degres fahrenheit over the 48 contiguous states, the agency said
these were the warmest years since 1953, which averaged 54.7 to tie with 1934 for the warmest year in this century
by contrast, records going back to 1895 show the normal annual average temperature for the 48 states is 52.5 degrees. the coldest year was 1917, which averaged 50.7
tom karl of the national climatic data center in asheville, n.c., said the combination of the position of the jet stream upper air currents and the high pressure center located over bermuda were contributing factors in the recent warm years
the more basic thing is why they were in those positions, and that's more difficult to answer,'' karl said
the concern everyone has in the back of their mind is if it's part of the greenhouse gas effect'' that has been reported on, he said
the greenhouse effect is a prediction of computer models, which say increasing amounts of carbon dioxide and other gases in the atmosphere could act much like the glass in a greenhouse, trapping heat and raising the temperature of the earth
it's not clear yet,'' if that is a factor in the warmth of 1986 and 1987, ``but it bears watching,'' karl said
until 1986 the average temperature of the united states had been running at or slightly below normal in the 1980s, karl said, even though worldwide temperatures seemed to be on the increase
in 1986, he said, the spring was particularly warm across the country. the winter of 1986-87 and the spring of 1987 also were unusually warm, particularly in the north-central region
the offer of asylum to gen. manuel antonio noriega of panama maintains a spanish tradition of opening its doors to latin americans seeking a place of exile
the hospitality stems from historic and cultural ties with latin america that transcend spanish party politics. but the spain that is prepared to offer asylum to noriega is far different from the country that took in ousted cuban dictator fulgencio batista in 1959
during the 36-year rule of gen. francisco franco, spain became a haven for batista, colombian ruler gustavo rojas pinilla, ousted argentine leader juan d. peron, toppled dominican president juan bosch and venezuelan strongman marcos perez jimenez
rojas pinilla arrived in 1957 after a stopover in bermuda, batista spent time in madeira and lisbon before settling in madrid and peron wandered from paraguay to panama to venezuela after his 1955 ouster before arriving in seville in 1960
both perez jimenez, ousted in 1958, and bosch, a democratically elected president toppled in 1963, lived in the united states before coming to spain
franco's conditions for receiving all were simple: maintain a low profile and don't meddle in spanish or foreign politics
in the case of noriega, prime minister felipe gonzalez says spanish policy is to accept requests when asylum could help maintain or restore democracy in a specific country
as conditions for accepting noriega, spain requires that he himself ask for asylum, that the united states agree not to seek his extradition on drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges filed against him in u.s. federal courts, and that washington honor the 1977 treaty under which control of the panama canal will revert to panama in 2000
noriega has refused to leave panama. but he has said he is willing to step down as military leader prior to the 1989 presidential elections in panama
santiago varela diaz, a gonzalez spokesman, said since spain's transition to democratic government in 1977, the type of political exile in spain has changed considerably
since then, spain has taken in many chileans, argentines and uruguayans fleeing from military dictatorships,'' he said. ``the case of panama and noriega is separate, but it is a concrete example of our willingness to serve as a support for a democratic solution to a problem.''
during the waning years of the franco regime in the early 1970s, not all the latin american exiles in spain were rightist dictators
former economics minister manuel ulloa of peru came to spain after the army ousted president fernando belaunde terry in 1968. belaunde went to the united states
christian democratic leader andres zaldivar of chile moved to madrid after gen. agusto pinochet overthrew president salvador allende in 1973
most of the latin american leaders exiled in spain have lived in the opulent suburbs north of madrid
batista died in madrid of a heart attack in 1973. perez jimenez, 74, still lives in a palatial residence in la moraleja
until his return to argentina after an 18-year exile, peron held court at his 17th of october estate in puerta de hierro
franco laid down the law to peron four years after his arrival when the argentine general tried an unsuccessful return to buenos aires in 1964 and threatened him with explusion if he kept up his politicking
but by 1970 peron was again receiving a steady stream of visitors and plotting his return to argentina where he was elected president in 1973. he died a year later
his widow, maria estela martinez de peron, who succeeded her husband as the first woman head of state in the western hemisphere, lives in quiet exile in madrid after her overthrow by the military in 1976 and five years of house arrest in southern argentina
two federal parole examiners recommended today that anti-castro militant orlando bosch be released from prison may 16 after completing a three-month sentence for violating his parole
bosch, convicted in the united states of conspiring to bomb foreign freighters and firing a recoilless rifle in 1968 at a polish freighter docked in miami, served four years of his 10-year federal prison sentence
he has acknowledged violating parole when he fled to south america in 1974. he served 11 years in venezuelan jails until his final acquittal on charges of bombing a cuban jetliner in which 73 died in 1976
the recommended sentence, which includes time bosch has spent in jail since returning to the united states, must be approved by the u.s. parole commission. the panel is expected to decide within three weeks
but after serving his three-month sentence, the 61-year-old bosch will likely be taken into custody by the u.s. immigration and naturalization service, said bosch's attorney, george yoss. the ins has targeted bosch for exclusion hearings and possible deportation
bosch entered the united states illegally last month after his release from a venezuelan prison. since mid-february, he has been detained at the metropolitan correctional center in south dade
bosch hugged his family after learning the examiners' recommendation, said his daughter, myriam bosch. ``we're very satisfied with the recommendation,'' she said. ``we think it's very fair.''
yoss said bosch probably would not appeal the recommended sentence for his 1974 parole violation. ``it's something dr. bosch, the family and we can all live with,'' yoss said
several prominent cuban-americans, including jorge mas canosa, head of the cuban american national foundation, testified today before the parole examiners in a hearing closed to the public because it is an administrative procedure, federal officials said
mas canosa said bosch should be released because he has learned his lesson and would now work peacefully for the overthrow of cuban president fidel castro
general electric is recalling about 45,000 ge and rca brand electric surge suppressors which could present a shock hazard, the consumer product safety commission said tuesday
known as electronic protection center surge suppressors, the units were sold nationally between october 1986 and december 1987, officials said
no injuries have been reported, but officials said a defect in some of the units could allow their metal housings and the metal housings of any connected appliances to become electrified, creating the potential for a shock
involved are ge surge suppressor models epc-6s, epc-6ms, epc-4ns and epc-cpu as well as rca models sk416 and skf416
the items sold for $40 to $60. they resemble a gray power strip with four or six electrical outlets. each has an on-off switch, a power indicator light, resettable circuit breaker and 6-foot cord. the product was designed to prevent damage from sudden electrical power surges to such equipment as personal computers, stereos, televisions and other appliances
owners of the units should disconnect them from the outlet, without touching the metal housing, and mail them to general electric co., attn: epc recall, p.o. box 8203, beaverton, ore., 97076. the units will be replaced and postage costs reimbursed
anyone needing more information may contact ge at 1-800-626-2000 or the safety commission at 1-800-638-2772
democrat albert gore jr. stood in front of one of the most powerful computers ever built and for half an hour spoke with the kind of emotion not often seen in the 1988 presidential race
he complained of the reagan administration's ``starvation of super-computing,'' and described his vision _ a nationwide fiber-optic network connecting such machines for research and business, a public works project as important as the building of interstate highways a generation ago
when he was done, a television reporter's first question made gore's face sag. what, the newsman wanted to know, did the tennessee senator think of the latest polls that showed him trailing in the presidential race
gore managed a chuckle and, after a pause, gave the answer he had repeated three times before in three other cities that day: polls are sometimes wrong
but gore had come to the campus of the university of illinois in champaign, one day before illinois' important democratic presidential primary last week, to talk super-computers _ the kind that perform millions of calculations in an instant, and whose usefulness is more widely assumed than understood
gore's performance, and the staging and timing of the event, illustrate the incongruity that sometimes surfaces as he takes his campaign to the north
he uses newly adopted slogans about ``working men and women,'' and of bringing the democratic party ``back to the grass roots'' _ populism that proved successful in the south
yet gore often seems more inspired when the discussion turns to deeply technical issues of the sort that may not evoke much response from those working men and women he seeks
super-computing will be the engine of the information age,'' gore said
he and his audience were crowded into an antiseptic, white-floored and glass-walled room with a cray super-computer the size of two or three coca-cola machines and about as red. with him were his wife and his father
what we have seen in the last several years is the emergence of an entirely new field of scientific inquiry _ computational science,'' gore said. ``it's time we move forward to create a national infrastructure that enables us to take advantage of that computational science.''
gore, 39, was educated at harvard, showing an intellectual curiosity that led him to enroll in both the divinity and law schools, finishing neither
in 12 years as a member of the house and senate, he immersed himself in issues such as medical technology, organ transplants and arms control
he gained the reputation of an arms-control specialist who enjoys detail. on his campaign plane he talks with excitement of ``unmistakeable signs,'' in warsaw pact troop placements of recent weeks, that the soviets' ``basic posture is undergoing re-evaluation.''
but his claimed expertise can be a two-edged sword. rival michael dukakis charged gore ``got taken to the cleaners'' when he led democratic negotiations with the reagan administration over arms control and star wars
there's also the possible problem of bogging down his audience _ in what is, after all, a political battle _ with detail on technical subjects
for example, there was his campaign statement last week reacting to reports that ozone _ a protective layer of atmosphere shielding out harmful rays _ was disappearing faster than thought
gore called for an immediate ban on ``non-essential uses of chlorofluorocarbons (cfcs)'' as propellants in aerosol sprays. beyond that, he outlined five other steps, including ``an immediate $1 per pound assessment of the most harmful cfcs, rising to $5,'' and having the president ``personally call on the leaders of japan and europe to ratify the montreal protocol, and to put the issue on the june summit.'' no explanation of that protocol, or much else, was given
still, in person and in the campaign statement, gore did take care to make broader points. the computers are keys to increased competitiveness, he said. and ozone depletion raises the threat of skin cancer
the candidate who loves to talk technical detail became, in the campaign press release, ``an environmental paul revere.'' adding to, but deleting last 5 grafs pvs, reagan's meeting, to trim.</note>
president reagan today issued a plea to house republicans to help him revive his stalled policy of aid to the nicaraguan contra rebels, but said democrats will be to blame if the rebels go out of existence
the president, in a one-hour meeting with house republicans on capitol hill and later with a group of state and county gop officials, called on gop members to unite behind a new effort to push some kind of help for the rebels through congress
u.s. aid to the rebels expired feb. 29
we are determined to get continued assistance to the resistance, and if we stick together, this time we'll make it,'' the president told the closed meeting of lawmakers on capitol hill, according to a text of his remarks provided by the white house
alluding, however, to democratic efforts to thwart any military aid for the rebels, reagan added, ``those who led the fight against our package of assistance to the democratic resistance cannot escape responsibility'' if the rebel forces wither
reagan, in response to a reporter's question, declined to say precisely what kind of aid package he was supporting
in a separate session with the local gop officials, reagan again pointed the finger of blame at house democrats
the house leadership, who played hardball to win the vote to cut off aid, now says it won't accept responsibility for the destruction of the freedom fighters. but if the freedom fighters are extinguished and communist rule is consolidated in nicaragua, the american people will be the ones to decide who is responsible,'' reagan said
the white house has encouraged a bipartisan group of contra supporters in the senate who are proposing a one-year, $48 million ``humanitarian'' aid package that also would give the cia the right to deliver previously stockpiled weapons, and the president the right to get a quick vote in congress on sending new military aid under certain conditions
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters after reagan's capitol hill visit that the administration has not yet aligned itself with any specific bill, but would like to have a package introduced soon and a vote prior to congress' departure next week for an easter recess
we'd like to have a vote before then,'' fitzwater said
on capitol hill, house gop leader robert michel said the administration ``will surely be supporting, or at least encouraging, the kind of movement we are seeing in the senate.''
michel, r-ill., said last week's incursion across the honduran border by sandinista troops was creating political pressure on some of the moderate democrats whose votes have been crucial to the outcome of the closely divided issue in the past. ``that doesn't do anything but help our side,'' michel said
adding to that pressure, said rep. trent lott, r-miss., is the instability in other areas of central america, including panama and el salvador. ``the whole region is still in an unstable condition,'' he said. some moderate democrats last week ``were quite pale in their appearance when they realized there was this incursion'' into honduras
we think there is some potential there to get a few more votes than we have had in the past,'' said lott, the chief house gop vote counter
before the meeting, reagan told reporters he hopes the cease-fire talks between the sandinista government and the rebels will be successful, but said he would not withhold pressure for new contra aid to await the outcome of the talks
i hope they can achieve something there'' in the talks, he said. asked if he would hold up a new request for rebel aid while the talks are in progress, reagan replied, ``we haven't given that any consideration.''
before reagan arrived, michel said an aid package should be developed during the cease-fire talks
we want to be prepared in the event negotiations break down, so there's always a fallback position,'' michel said. ``we ought to be very wary... take a more worst-case scenario.''
house democrats said any action on further aid should await the outcome of those negotiations
what we need to watch very carefully is the peace talks,'' house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said on monday. ``i hope both sides will be very forthcoming.''
the sandinista government and u.s.-backed rebels on monday opened three days of talks at the border town of sapoa by exchanging cease-fire proposals and agreeing to a truce during the negotiations
asked about prospects for a $48 million contra aid proposal being drawn up by senate backers of the rebels, wright objected to provisions that allow the cia to continue delivering previously stockpiled weapons and that would guarantee a future vote in congress on new military aid
if they would agree to humanitarian aid without military aid, that could be done very swiftly,'' wright said. ``we would be ready to meet (with republicans) at any time.''
senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., in a toughly worded senate floor speech, said the administration's policies have produced few positive results
the united states, after all of this _ not to mention several hundred million dollars _ has achieved virtually nothing positive in central america,'' byrd said. ``we have no right to ask americans to risk their sons and daughters when there are other solutions we have not even tried.''
the soviet union has invited a vatican delegation to help celebrate the 1,000th anniversary of christianity in the region, but pope john paul ii won't be a member of it, a vatican official said tuesday
cardinal johannes willebrands made the disclosure at a news conference at which he presented the pope's letter on the millennium of christianity in kievan rus', the ancient name of the ukraine. the celebrations are scheduled for june
the letter stressed europe's christian roots and said christian unity is essential to peace in europe and the world
willebrands, president of the vatican's secretariat for christian unity, said a representative of the russian orthodox church patriarch made the invitation orally to two officials of his agency march 18 in moscow
he said john paul, as head of the roman catholic church, was invited to send a delegation to celebrations in moscow being organized by the russian orthodox church
when an official written invitation is received, the pontiff will name the delegation for the trip to moscow, which is expected to last about 10 days, the dutch-born cardinal said
john paul often has expressed interest in visiting the soviet union. willebrands said the pope had not received a personal invitation to the celebration and had no plans to attend, but that does not rule out a posssible future visit
he said it would not be ``opportune'' for the pope to attend the observance because ``he cannot make his pastoral visit, which is destined primarily for catholics, during celebrations organized by another church.''
the pope has said he would visit the soviet union if he was allowed to visit roman catholics throughout the country, including the ukraine, lithuania, latvia, byelorussia and kazakhstan
three years ago, he disclosed that soviet authorities had refused permission for him to visit lithuania, a catholic stronghold
in his 39-page letter to bishops around the world, john paul urged the faithful to join in prayer to mark the baptism in 988 of prince vladimir on the banks of the dnieper in kiev
the whole catholic church turns its gaze to that event and shares spiritually in the joy of the heirs to that baptism,'' he said
john paul praised christians in the region, who he said have sometimes experienced ``persecution and martyrdom'' in those 1,000 years
in particular, we join with all the heirs of this baptism, whatever their religious confession, nationality or dwelling place, with all our orthodox and catholic brothers and sisters,'' the letter said
in a special way, we join with all the beloved sons and daughters of the russian, ukrainian and byelorussian nations. to those who live in their homeland, as also to those who dwell in america, western europe and other parts of the world.''
the millennium is ``in a special way the feast'' of the russian orthodox church, which ``remains united to the catholic church with very close links,'' the pope wrote
at this solemn moment in history the catholic community ... sends to her 1,000-year-old sister church, through the bishop of rome, the kiss of peace as a manifestation of an ardent desire for that perfect communion.''
in a plea for christian unity, john paul said the christian roots of europe present ``a particularly pressing challenge to the unity of christians. ... the desire for unity and peace, the desire that barriers should be broken down and opposition removed . .. is becoming an impelling sign of our times.''
true peace can only exist on the basis of a process of unification in which each people is able to choose, in freedom and truth, the path of its own development.''
the american space program will be crippled and u.s. leadership threatened if congress fails to approve the $11.5 billion requested by nasa, space agency officials said today
james c. fletcher, nasa administrator, said that fiscal 1989, which begins in october, ``is a crucial year for nasa. it will make or break the civil space program.''
he said the $11.5-billion budget requested by the national aeronautics and space administration is a ``bare bones'' request, with most of the money going to maintaining programs already underway
the entire future of the u.s. civil space program rides at risk in this budget,'' said fletcher
he said that the money would be applied to three basic elements:
_building up the flight rate for the space shuttle once missions resume in august. there are two space flights set for this year, he said, seven in 1989 and 10 in 1990
_building up hardware development for the space station, which he said is essential for american leadership in space
_continuing the space science programs in astronomy and planetary research, developing advanced rocket engines for the shuttle and financing the pathfinder program, which would develop new technology for possible missions to mars
fletcher made the comments as leadoff witness before the senate subcommittee on science, technology and space, which is beginning to consider the fiscal 1989 nasa budget
a hanford nuclear reservation plutonium processing plant was shut down and two technicians were suspended in the wake of an incident involving the improper transfer of chemicals, a westinghouse hanford spokesman said today
operations at the plutonium-uranium extraction plant, or purex, were suspended over the weekend as a precautionary measure, said spokesman rudy cortez
the temporary suspension resulted from an incident friday in which a valve was left open and a batch of the wrong chemical solution was transferred to a tank, cortez said
as a consequence, the certifications of two nuclear process operators were suspended for failing to follow operating procedures, he said. the event was declared to be an infraction of a ``criticality prevention specification.''
a ``criticality'' is an uncontrolled nuclear chain reaction resulting in a rapid buildup of radiation and heat. it is caused by such factors as the amount, shape, density and enrichment of plutonium or uranium and the manner in which they are stored
there was no danger of a criticality incident and no danger of a radioactiuve release to the environment, cortez said. it has not been determined how long operations will be suspended, he said
the purex plant was closed for a time in october 1986 because of safety concerns over plutonium handling and possible accidents. westinghouse hanford officials who took over operation of the plants in july 1987 promised to make safety a top priority
the chemical transfer incidents were the latest in a series of safety-related ones at the purex facility, which dissolves fuel rods to remove plutonium and uranium for reprocessing
the cause of contamination of two crane operators at the facility march 14 is still under investigation. radioactive contamination was found in one crane operator's home and another contamination was found on another operator as he prepared to leave the plant. both men were decontaminated and returned to work the next day. optimistic</head>
orders to u.s. factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods fell 1.8 percent in february, but analysts said the second consecutive monthly decline had not shaken their belief that manufacturing will be a bright spot in the economy this year
the commerce department report tuesday said that orders for durable goods _ items expected to last three or more years _ totaled a seasonally adjusted $111.4 billion in february, following an identical 1.8 percent january decline
it was the first time since the spring of 1986 that durable goods orders have fallen for two consecutive months
the february decline surprised economists, but they maintained that manufacturing companies were still enjoying boom times because the weaker dollar has boosted export demand
the fundamentals continue to look positive for manufacturing,'' said allen sinai, chief economist of the boston co. ``what we have is a two-month hesitation after some big increases.''
manufacturing is expected to be a major source of strength this year as businesses step up production to meet rising export demand and american companies increase orders for capital equipment to expand their production capabilities
the reagan administration is forecasting that almost half of all economic growth in 1988 will come from rising export demand
still, analysts said the back-to-back declines did show that businesses were cutting back on orders in the early part of 1988 in an effort to get control of bulging inventories. inventories swelled at the end of 1987 while consumer demand fell
economists once had feared this combina4hn could be enough to topple the country into a recession. but brighter statistics this year, including continue declines in the unemployment rate in february, have eased those concerns
cynthiaxlatta, an economist with data resources ik#-, noted that while new orders fell in february, the toas no immediate response from the rebels, who have been supported by the united states since the start of their fight in late 1981
negotiators for both sides were optimistic after the first day of cease-fire talks monday, the first held since december
also monday, nicaragua withdrew its soldiers from the honduran border and declared an end to fighting with contra rebels while the talks are held in sapoa. the honduran military reported sandinista soldiers had retreated
the importance of today was that we listened for the first time at the highest level their (contras') proposal, gen. humberto ortega, nicaragua's defense minister, told journalists in sapoa on monday
alfredo cesar, a negotiator for the u.s.-backed rebels, called the first round a ``step ahead'' and said they discussed a wide range of issues
neither side seeks a military victory over the other,'' cesar said
monday's session was held under tight security at the customs post in this town beside the border with costa rica, along the bank of lake nicaragua
at stake in the talks, scheduled to resume today, is an end to the bloodshed that has claimed an estimated 50,000 dead and wounded and shattered the country's economy
the sandinista proposal to stop the fighting calls for an ``immediate and definitive cease-fire,'' ortega said. he did not elaborate
the contra plan calls for a 30-day truce, political amnesty, press freedom and continued talks to work out a lasting cease-fire, cesar said
frank arana, a rebel spokesman, said the talks went beyond the bounds earlier established by the sandinistas and included political issues and ``concepts of democracy.''
we spoke about everything,'' he said
the goal of the sandinistas is to work out a viable cease-fire in accordance with the regional peace plan signed last august by the presidents of the five central american nations. they had said the talks would cover only the mechanics of how the contras would lay down their arms
the rebels said the talks should include discussion of democratic reforms, also covered in the regional peace plan
we came here with an open agenda,'' adolfo calero, a contra leader, told journalists at the border post. ``and that includes democratization including amnesty. we insisted on speaking about all the problems facing nicaragua.''
negotiations opened after ortega, brother of president daniel ortega, said the sandinistas were suspending military operations for the duration of the talks and called on the contras to do the same
sandinista spokesman manuel espinoza told reporters the ``reciprocation of the contras'' in agreeing to suspend hostilities and ``the fact that this meeting is taking place are the first positive steps'' toward a permanent cease-fire
president ortega on monday signed a document that dealt with a number of internal problems. the statement called on all political parties to refrain from violence, a position targeted at the government supporters who have attacked the opposition
it also calls for the media to respect the government, a reference to the opposition newspaper la prensa, and the sandinistas promised to release more than a dozen recently jailed labor leaders and review cases of imprisoned opposition politiciaans
the sandinistas' willingness to comply with the peace plan was cited by u.s. congressional members as a reason for rejecting president reagan's calls for additional military and nonlethal aid to the rebels. the peace plan also calls for internal dialogue with the political opposition
southern methodist university is considering a tougher sexual harassment policy that could result in the demotion or firing of faculty members found to be romantically involved with students
under the proposal, if a student files a complaint, the faculty member would appear before a committee, which would evaluate evidence and decide punishment
the faculty have been the prime movers for this policy,'' leon bennett, vice president for legal affairs, said monday. ``we're not trying to create a hostile environment, we're trying to prevent one.''
civil libertarians say such a policy might infringe on a person's constitutional right of free association. other critics question whether a university can, or should, regulate relationships between adults
smu, like most universities, prohibits faculty and staff from making sexual advances and seeking sexual favors in exchange for favorable treatment
officials at smu say they have received 10 sexual harassment complaints in the last five years, everett winters, director of smu's office of affirmative action, said. although some professors have been reprimanded, none have been dismissed, demoted or taken to court
lindley doran, director of the human resources women's center, said the harassment policy was proposed by the center and the universitiy's commission on status of women. the faculty senate approved it in the spring of 1987
she said the proposal is now with the administration, which is investigating what legal sanctions can be used. the faculty senate would then review the proposal. with its approval, it will go to the trustees
ms. doran said she thinks the proposal will be university policy by the end of the semester
bystanders looked on but no one intervened while a man was stabbed to death on a crowded downtown sidewalk, police said
there were people standing around the incident and watching it go down,'' police detective larry martinez said of monday's 10:30 a.m. attack
it's non-involvement,'' he said. ``it's like a disease. these people have to live with themselves. i just wish they had a bigger conscience. it would be easier on us.''
it was the second such murder to occur in front of crowds near the busy intersection of seventh and spring streets in four months. on nov. 17, roberto lopez, 23, was knifed to death shortly after 5:30 p.m. in what was believed to be a drug-related case
the 32-year-old man killed monday was knifed several times in what martinez said was also possibly drug-related. his identity still wasn't known tuesday and police said they had no suspects in the case
investigators believe the man staggered a short distance after he was stabbed. an off-duty officer working nearby on a movie production was alerted about the incident and contacted paramedics and police. visit</head>
six months after pope john paul ii's second u.s. visit, roman catholic leaders in three of the nine cities where he stopped still have bills to pay
the archdiocese of san francisco owes as much as $2 million, and the nearby diocese of monterey still has at least $1 million to repay, church officials say. in phoenix, ariz., the church has yet to pay nearly $165,000 for renting a stadium
church officials say the debts are paid for the pope's stops in miami, columbia, s.c., new orleans, san antonio, texas, los angeles and detroit
we knew we would have some deficit, but we didn't think it would be of this magnitude,'' said bruce egnew, director of finance for the archdiocese of san francisco. he said the church has raised $2 million since the visit, but still owes at least $1.5 million
the rev. miles riley, chief publicist for the archdiocese, put the total at $2 million
the monterey diocese has a debt of $1.1 million, said spokesman ted elisee
to help retire the debt, the san francisco archdiocese plans to sell pieces of the elaborate $500,000, six-tiered stage used for the mass at candlestick park. there are also plans for collections in the churches, receptions and direct appeals to the community, said egnew
it's always harder to raise money after the event,'' said riley. ``not a little bit harder, a lot harder.''
on the plus side, riley said last week, he had just received a letter from a man who had been inspired to return to the church after a 20-year absence. he enclosed a check for $500, riley said
elisee said the monterey diocese spent $2 million and still owed $1 million to $1.1 million. the diocese plans an appeal to its 45 parishes, which have 145,000 members, and the church has been selling memorial magazines at $5 each and videotapes for $25
in some cities, church officials dipped into reserve funds and other accounts to cover the difference between costs and fund-raising efforts. that amounted to $400,000 in miami, $200,000 in new orleans and $1.3 million in detroit, officials in those cities said
in san antonio, the church came out a bit ahead, raising $2.4 million but spending 2.32 million, said the rev. larry steubben, chairman of the texas papal visit committee
it was just last week that the diocese of phoenix was billed for $164,765 for the use of arizona state university's sun devil stadium. church officials had said in january that they faced a deficit, but did not say how much
last week, the rev. john mcmahon, head of the diocese's papal-visit committee, declined to comment on the debt. ``we just got the bill from asu and we want to see where we are,'' he said last week
three-year-old ashley hopkins never heard a sound until the beep of a computer intruded on her silence. she cried
i shouldn't be happy to see ash's tears, but i am,'' said her mother, janie hopkins, who cried some herself. ``that means it's working.''
the englewood girl is believed to be the youngest person to get a cochlear implant
thomas j. balkany implanted the $17,000 electronic hearing aid during an operation at porter memorial hospital. the 22-channel device stimulates the hearing nerve. the implant, considered experimental in children, bypasses damaged inner-ear cells by stimulating a tiny portion of the nerve fibers in the cochlea
doctors say ashley eventually will be able to hear her own voice. the device also will help her pick up intonation patterns of people she is talking to and should improve her lip-reading
without this, she has no hope of talking properly,'' hopkins said. ``she wants to be in the hearing world with everyone else.''
an implant patient must wear a nickel-size microphone on his ear. the microphone is linked to a battery pack that modulates the microphone's electrical signal, which ultimately stimulates the hearing nerve
bernice dinner, ashley's audiologist, said the noise transmitted to the cochlea is nothing like sounds in the hearing world; it is a monotone, like a bee's buzzing
she's going to learn that sensation is sound,'' dinner said. ``she doesn't know that yet. she doesn't have a label for it.''
the first time dinner activated the electronic device by computer, the little girl shrugged a shoulder. the second time, she rolled her eyes
the first two times were more like a brushing sensation, a tickling in her inner ear,'' dinner said
the third time, dinner calibrated the electronic signal higher so it was loud and painful. ashley cried
a brochure about aids intended for sexually active adults was mistakenly distributed to teen-agers, an aids program director said
we're sorry it happened,'' said edward darstein, executive director of the western new york aids program. ``but we've done a lot of good work over the past five years, and we hope this won't wreck our record.''
state sen. walter j. floss was not satisfied, and said monday he complained to the governor and state health commissioner
floss said he directed his staff to investigate whether state funds were used to print the brochures. darstein said his organization receives about 90 percent of its $198,000 budget from the state but private donations funded the brochures
darstein said the brochures were handed out march 9 by a volunteer who spoke at pavilion central school and a second place and left the wrong brochures at the school
the brochure rates the risk of acquired immune deficiency syndrome infection from various forms of sexual activity, both homosexual and heterosexual
a man who allegedly sought romance rather than religion has been barred by a judge from attending a church
judge anne dranginis issued a temporary restraining order monday prohibiting john steinmann, 78, of middlebury from attending the first congregational church of washington
we believe his motives to worship are not consistent with promoting the worship of god, but for the purpose of forming relationships, particularly with women,'' said the rev. richard sears, pastor of the chruch
the judge's order also prohibits steinmann from harassing or contacting church members without their permission
according to court documents, steinmann, member of a middlebury church, began attending services in rural washington in an attempt to maintain a relationship with his former wife
the couple has since divorced, the woman moved and steinmann used the church to meet other women, church officials said
church officials filed for the court orders monday, a day after steinmann was arrested for the third time on charges of criminal trespassing at the church
virginia steinway of morris, testified steinmann once sidled up to her in a pew, grabbed her arm and made lewd and revolting remarks to her during a hymn. ``i was extremely panicked,'' she said
steinmann, who represented himself in court, maintained his actions were consistent with the church's policy of christian fellowship
moslem nations were united tuesday behind the palestinian rebellion in israeli-occupied lands, but iran and iraq traded insults and there was no islamic accord on the 7{-year-old persian gulf war
foreign ministers of the 46-member organization of the islamic conference issued a statement condemning ``oppressive and criminal measures by the (israeli) authorities against our brothers.''
tariq aziz, iraq's foreign minister, claimed iran was aiding the emigration of iranian jews to israel, according to a text of his remarks
in the statement about the rebellion, which began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, the ministers said: ``all moslems in the world are proud of this uprising.''
that echoed a speech by king hussein of jordan at the opening of the conference monday, in which he said the ``blood of martyrs'' was being shed in the territories. more than 100 arabs have been killed since the violence began
the ministers declared: ``members of the organization are concerned to support palestinians financially, politically and morally and also to back their sole legitimate representative, the plo.''
no indication was given of what form aid would take, or whether there would be financial assistance, and the statement did not elaborate
tajer masri, jordan's foreign minister, told reporters: ``we can only provide support in a political manner, to pressure the world's nations to get them to pressure israel and reveal the meaning of the uprising. i don't remember seeing any request for financial support.''
farouk kaddoumi, the palestine liberation organization's equivalent of a foreign minister, said the statement was valuable to the plo and especially ``for the people inside the territories.''
about u.s. plans to close the plo's u.n. observer mission in new york under terms of an anti-terrorist law, kaddoumi said:
we will keep the office open until american police come and seal it off. then we will go to the united nations (headquarters) and live there.''
aziz, the iraqi foreign minister, said the alleged help given iranian jews to move to israel was ``a violation of the rules'' of the organization of islamic conference.''
how come iran, which claims to support the palestinian issue and the uprising, is helping jews to migrate to israel?'' there was no elaboration in a text of his prepared remarks made available to the associated press
he gave no figures on the number of alleged emigrants. the iranian envoy, mohammed ali taskhiri, denied the claim and accused iraq of being ``zionist.''
the point is sensitive in the arab and moslem world because many nations do not recognize israel's right to exist and oppose the emigration of jews to the country. 10th graf: ``i never...</note>
testimony ended today on the first of three impeachment charges against gov. evan mecham, but a move for a quick vote on whether to oust mecham from office was withdrawn in the face of vehement opposition
it would be our everlasting disgrace if we do not consider all of the evidence from both sides in such a historic and important case,'' said republican sen. jon hays
after testimony ended on the first impeachment count, a charge that mecham tried to thwart an investigation into a death threat, democratic state sen. carolyn walker proposed that the senate consider voting on that charge alone
the senate had earlier agreed to hear evidence on all three charges before voting on any one. conviction on the first count alone would have ended the trial early with the first term republican removed from office
i would think if governor mecham is exonerated he would be extremely happy to know he has one less article to face,'' she said. ``and if he is convicted, we should not go on and spend untold dollars of taxpayers money.''
in a heated debate, the motion won support from democrats but was opposed by republicans, and walker finally withdrew it. a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate would have been required to change the trial rules
the prosecution then said it was ready to begin presenting evidence on the second charge against mecham _ alleged that he misused $80,000 from a state fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
the last witness on the obstruction of justice count was mecham's lawyer, fred craft, who this morning seized the opportunity to give a lengthy speech in praise of mecham's political philsophy. he called mecham an ``uncommon politician'' who sought no personal aggrandizement and wanted only to improve the quality of life in arizona
the speech brought an objection from prosecutor paul eckstein and craft was instructed to stick to answering questions
craft, in an abrupt role change, became a witness monday and said mecham ``didn't know that he was obstructing anything'' when he told the state's top lawman he would not cooperate with the attorney general's investigation of the alleged death threat
craft was subpoenaed at the request of the democratic minority leader, sen. alan stephens. craft was a mecham insider when the threat against a witness before a grand jury investigating mecham was reported to the governor on nov. 13
i never heard `felony.' i never heard `death threat' and i certainly never heard `tampering with a grand jury witness,''' craft said monday. ``i never heard those words, which would have been an alarm to me.''
later, in his cross-examination, eckstein asked craft whether he had ever advised the embattled governor to resign
we had these meetings and no one could see a political escape route for the governor,'' craft said. ``no one was offering the governor any other political option than to go down with the ship.''
thefirst charge alleged that mecham tried to thwart the investigation of the alleged death threat against former top mecham aide donna carlson by mecham confidant lee watkins. at the time, ms. carlson was about to testify before the state grand jury about mecham's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan
the next article charges mecham with misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. the third impeachment article accuses him of concealing the $350,000 campaign loan
craft and co-defense counsel jerris leonard said they opposed taking an early vote. ``we ought to hear all the evidence on all three articles and then let them vote,'' leonard said
in his testimony, craft echoed mecham in contending the governor was not fully informed that the situation involved a felony and the possible tampering of a grand jury witness
nobody said the house is burning down, we've got a crisis,'' craft said. ``i didn't know that a crime had been committed.''
however, sen. john mawhinney, a republican, noted that then-chief of staff richard burke testified that he considered the matter to be serious and that he assumed the department of public safety was investigating
what is mystifying is how two people can sit in the same meeting'' and come away with different impressions, mawhinney said
a two-thirds vote of the senate is required to convict mecham, the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona
mecham also faces an april 21 criminal trial on charges of concealing the $350,000 campaign loan, and a may 17 recall election
the inimitable emanuel ungaro has toned down his sexy, exaggerated look, but he had enough opulent fabrics in his tuesday winter ready-to-wear show to please the fans of his show-off styles
laroche, by contrast, preferred the ultra simple lines, in short skirts and tailored pants
ungaro, along with christian lacroix and some others, remains in the ``feminine-fancy'' school of designing, despite this season's trend to somewhat simpler, more practical styles
in one variation on the tent dress, he puts bright flowered and flowing silk or light wool tunics over narrow skirts. but ungaro also sneaked in a print chemise dress from the 1950s, knotted and draped baggily in back
rose, salmon and dusky shades of blue and green or brighter tones all turned up in ungaro's vast color palette. crazy over fabrics, he mixed them with somewhat less abandon this time around
paisley, brown or camel colored short coats were often paired with outfits that had lean knee-revealing skirts in polished leather: a flashy, fascinating new look here
ungaro still likes big bertha or flounced collars using them on lots of ensembles. he can't forget leg o'mutton sleeves, ruffles and bows, either
as usual, velvet was used richly in ungaro's suits _ as a single-lapelled collar, a wide jacket-hem border, or overall in dressy suits in shades of claret, deep purple or black
another success in opulence was to pair a velvet-piped paisley long and fitted jacket with a teeny draped black jersey cashmere skirt
even pants looked dressy, with their little velvet or irridescent taffeta vests and fitted jackets, plus flowered blouses. bows on derrieres or the hips of draped pants gilded the lily a bit
ungaro's body-hugging draped cocktail numbers were less risque than last season, nearly hitting the knee instead of grazing the upper thigh
ungaro's less expensive line called ``solo donna,'' shown last week, had much of the same allure, but looked much more comfortable. his ribbed spencers with flowered sheaths or his checked skirts with windowpane plaid reefers could even be worn to the office without raising eyebrows
at guy laroche, meanwhile, the trend to short skirts continued, but the collection looked more sane than sexy. designed by guy douvier, the clothes had a certain played-down attraction
soft wool coats were ample and short, with caped and huge squared-off collars. these were worn over tailored trouser suits and dresses in browns, tans or striking jewel colors
bright belted tunics with dark skirts or straight tunics with elaborate wool embroidery in swirly ribbon patterns were also items for the safe dresser
the diagonal plaid belted suits in frank yellow, green or red make a peppy change
late-day flocked velvet or cloque silk suits were easily fitted, and dance dresses with shirred tops and puffy taffeta skirts also came down the runway. the shocking pink or black flounced taffeta gowns, short in front, long in back, are no shockers, but are gala enough to wear without looking like a wallflower
hermes, usually known for expensive hand-finished leather bags and scarves, is making a bigger effort to steer customers to the ready-to-wear racks
designed by eric bergere, the line remained firmly in the classic sportswear vein. as the redingote sweeps paris, hermes had the last word in its brown or red models topped with jumpers' netted bowler hats
but fitted suits with oval skirts and plaid spencers or a-line jackets over slim gray flannel hats looked just as appealing for a country weekend or informal moments in town
even if the clothes don't set trends, they will never look out of place, especially with those incomparable silk scarves
authorities have granted polish mormons permission to build their first chapel in this communist country, a church missionary said tuesday
the only other soviet bloc country in which there are mormon chapels is east germany, where there are about 5,000 members of the church of jesus christ of latter-day saints
although polish authorities registered the mormon church as an official religious organization in 1977, only recently were there enough polish mormons to warrant building a chapel, said elder juliusz fussek
fussek, 66, a u.s. citizen of polish descent, was sent to poland to do missionary work by the church headquarters in salt lake city. he is a retired printer
there are only about 100 mormons in this overwhelmingly roman catholic country, but fussek said he saw ``great prospects'' for the church's development ``because people are interested in religion here.''
you need members first before building a chapel ... because there is no point having a chapel and it standing empty,'' said fussek
we are very pleased with the cooperation and help we have received from the government,'' he said
at the end of last year, polish mormons applied for permission to build a chapel and cultural-educational center in warsaw's western wola district, fussek said
the local council for wola approved the project at a meeting last week and forwarded its decision to the warsaw city president for formal approval, he said
fussek said the chapel, expected to open in 1989 or 1990, would be paid for by donations from polish mormons and the church headquarters in salt lake city. he did not have any estimate of the cost
fussek said there were about 300-400 mormons, mostly of german descent, in the country before world war ii. the mormon chapel did not reopen after the war because most of its members fled the country when the communists took power
more than 35 religious denominations are active in poland today. ninety percent of poland's 37 million people are baptized catholics
czechoslovak and soviet ground troops tuesday started week-long war games in northwestern bohemia to be watched by foreign observers, according to an official report
the march 22-28 exercise involves 17,400 soviet and czechoslovak troops, the ctk news agency reported
under an 1986 accord reached at the stockholm conference on confidence and security-building measures and disarmament, large exercises held by the warsaw pact and nato require advance notification and inspection by foreign observers
czechoslovak first deputy chief of staff lt. gen. jiri brychta said 43 observers from 22 countries, including the united states, west germany and britain, will watch the maneuvers
brychta was quoted as saying the maneuvers are the third to be watched by western military officers in czechoslovakia, while czechoslovak observers last year saw eight exercises staged by north atlantic treaty organization members. detail, edit for transition. picks up 15th graf pvs ``frank arana,.... '' edits thereafter to trim.</note>
the sandinista government and contra rebels today announced proposals for an extended cease-fire that would include amnesty and steps toward a lasting peace
the leftist government's proposal, outlined in a statement to journalists on the second day of peace talks at this post on the costa rican border, calls for a 30-day truce with the rebels intended for them to lay down their arms and ``rejoin nicaraguan society.''
it also provides for the release of a political prisoner for each rebel accepting amnesty. deputy foreign minister victory hugo tinoco told reporters there are 3,300 prisoners the government considers eligible for release under the program
the contra proposal calls for a 45-day truce starting on good friday, april 1, in which rebel fighters would move into cesae-fire zones still to be determined
it said the government should grant ``total and unconditional amnesty'' as soon as the truce takes effect, allowing anyone who left nicaragua for political reasons to ``rejoin the political, economic and social process without any conditions.''
the rebels also want to join a national dialogue between the sandinistas and their internal political opponents while the cease-fire lasts. the government also would allow rebel leaders to participate in national reconciliation talks
at the moment in which a cease-fire is signed, whether it be for 30, 60 or 90 days, according to what the counterrevolution wants, at that moment the leadership of the nicaraguan resistance will be able to rejoin civic and political life and even participate in the national dialogue that seeks a reconciliation of all nicaraguans,'' tinoco said
both proposals call for international monitoring of the cease-fire
the two sides agreed monday to a cease-fire during the three days of talks, the first ever held on nicaraguan territory in more than 6 years of war and the first direct talks without a mediator
rebel and government negotiators for both sides were optimistic after the first round of peace talks monday, the first held since december
also monday, nicaragua withdrew its soldiers from the honduran border. the honduran military reported sandinista soldiers had retreated
the importance of today was that we listened for the first time at the highest level their (contras') proposal, gen. humberto ortega, nicaragua's defense minister, said monday
alfredo cesar, a negotiator for the u.s.-backed rebels, called the first round a ``step ahead'' and said the delegations discussed a wide range of issues. ``neither side seeks a military victory over the other,'' he said
at stake in the talks is an end to the bloodshed that has claimed an estimated 50,000 dead and wounded and shattered the country's economy
frank arana, a rebel spokesman, said the talks went beyond the bounds earlier established by the sandinistas and included political issues and ``concepts of democracy.''
we spoke about everything,'' he said
the goal of the sandinistas is to work out a viable cease-fire in accordance with the regional peace plan signed last august by the presidents of the five central american nations. they had said the talks would cover only the mechanics of how the contras would lay down their arms
the rebels said the talks should include discussion of democratic reforms, also covered in the regional peace plan
we came here with an open agenda,'' adolfo calero, a contra leader, told reporters. ``and that includes democratization including amnesty. we insisted on speaking about all the problems facing nicaragua.''
president daniel ortega on monday signed a document that dealt with a number of internal problems. the statement called on all political parties to refrain from violence, a position targeted at the government supporters who have attacked the opposition
it also calls for the media to respect the government, a reference to the opposition newspaper la prensa, and the sandinistas promised to release more than a dozen recently jailed labor leaders and review cases of imprisoned opposition politiciaans
the sandinistas' willingness to comply with the peace plan was cited by u.s. congressional members as a reason for rejecting president reagan's calls for additional military and nonlethal aid to the rebels. the peace plan also calls for internal dialogue with the political opposition. riegle's name</note>
richard gephardt said today fellow democrat michael dukakis has undergone a ``battlefield conversion'' on the trade issue to try to win votes in michigan. vice president george bush lent his support to president reagan's veto of a civil rights bill, saying he's ``not going to start differing with the president now.''
democratic contenders albert gore jr. and paul simon flew back to washington to cast their votes for an override. gore criticized bush's loyalty to reagan ``even when the proposals are ... dumb.''
gephardt was angered by dukakis' change-of-mind on trade legislation and he accused the massachusetts governor of a flip-flop to improve his chances in saturday's caucuses in michigan, where 138 delegates are at stake
now we're getting some battlefield conversions on trade. ... the acid test on trade is the gephardt amendment,'' the missouri congressman told senior citizens in madison heights, mich
last night, gephardt told reporters, ``on the central issue in this campaign, mike dukakis is trying to have it both ways.''
dukakis on monday endorsed a trade bill put forward by michigan sen. donald riegle, which gephardt said was very similar to his measure. the massachusetts governor has opposed gephardt's bill. riegle endorsed dukakis monday as did michigan congressmen dale kildee and bob traxler
this is no change in my position,'' dukakis responded at his own news conference
michigan did not have the spotlight to itself as candidates from both parties are stumping in connecticut, with its primary a week from today, and wisconsin, a week later
dukakis was making a foray into neighboring connecticut today, where he appeared well-positioned to add to his string of wins on his new england home turf. campaign sources said dukakis will receive a sought-after endorsement on wednesday from new jersey sen. bill bradley, who has been mentioned as a possible dark-horse democratic nominee if the convention is deadlocked
gore, still searching for a northern breakthrough after establishing his candidacy in the south, met today with pennsylvania gov. robert casey, who said afterward he still hasn't decided whether to endorse a candidate before the state's april 26 primary. on monday, the tennessee senator met with new york gov. mario cuomo, who said some nice things about him but didn't endorse him
although connecticut is one of bush's home states _ his father represented it in the u.s. senate, and his mother and brother still live in the state _ the vice president said he was taking nothing for granted there
i don't want to be beaten in this state,'' he said as he campaigned in bloomfield on monday. in connecticut, reporters asked bush whether he backed president reagan's veto of a sweeping civil rights bill
i'm not going to start differing with the president now,'' he replied
later bush told black supporters in washington that he supports the idea that institutions receiving federal money should comply with civil rights laws. but he said the civil rights measure, passed overwhelmingly by both the house and the senate, was flawed
the legislation ... is imperfect and the imperfections should be corrected,'' he said. up until monday, bush had not said directly whether he supported the veto
i'm not going to start doing now what i haven't been doing for seven years, finding differences with the president, for whom i have great respect,'' he said
the measure would forbid the distribution of federal funds to entire institutions, state and local government agencies and many corporations if any part of them practices discrimination. the administration supports a plan that would grant religious schools and organizations as well as corporations more exemptions from civil rights laws
bush said he believed the president should have line-item veto powers so he could ``take some of the extremes'' out of bills like the one in question
earlier monday, new jersey gov. thomas kean endorsed bush, and new jersey's 21 county gop chairmen followed suit. new jersey's primary is june 7
bush's republican opponent, down-but-not-out bob dole, was in wisconsin, where he again challenged the vice president to a debate. but bush has rebuffed dole's calls for a faceoff, saying it is time to turn the attention to differences with the democrats
gephardt was campaigning in the must-win state of michigan, wooing workers at a steel mill and making appearances with chrysler corp. chief lee iacocca at his side. iacocca says he likes gephardt's trade stance, but isn't formally supporting him
gephardt's says his trade views _ raising the threat of sanctions if foreign barriers don't come down _ are getting a good reception in the industrial state of michigan
the people in michigan are interested in someone who is really going to stand up on the trade issue,'' he said in highland park
jesse jackson made a visit to colorado, which holds democratic caucuses on april 4, and met monday with ex-candidate gary hart
jackson said hart was going to advise his campaign on policy matters. hart said, however, that he wasn't formally endorsing jackson. that, he said, would be ``old-fashioned.''
hart abandoned his democratic bid earlier this month, 10 months after quitting the first time over reports about his relationship with a miami model
jackson was campaigning in michigan today
simon's campaign on monday was talking up his plans for a big media buy in wisconsin. simon won his home-state primary in illinois last week without buying any television ads. he has said he hopes for a ``respectable'' showing in michigan, although he can't spend much money in the state. 4 p.m. est, with a vote unlikely before 5 p.m. at the earliest. should stand. ^by jill lawrence</note>
the senate voted 73-24 today to override president reagan's veto of a bill reversing a supreme court decision that narrowed the scope of laws to prevent federally funded discrimination against women, minorities, the elderly and the handicapped
the civil rights restoration act went directly to the house, where leaders also said they had the votes to override the veto. majority leader thomas foley, d-wash., said the house would vote tonight
we expect a vote to override,'' house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said monday. the house passed the bill 315-98 and republican head-counters said only a dozen members at most were expected to move into the president's corner
the senate vote was more than the two-thirds majority needed to override a presidential veto. the bill initially passed 75-14. to become law over a president's veto, the legislation must be approved by a two-thirds vote of both chambers
the house and senate votes capped a four-year struggle to overturn the 1984 supreme court decision
the senate vote came after several senators, including acting republican leader alan simpson of wyoming, condemned what they called a misinformation campaign launched by conservative opponents of the bill. simpson, who voted to sustain the veto, nonetheless said he was concerned about erroneous claims that it would create ``massive new rights.''
some opponents have claimed the bill would require churches to hire active homosexual drug addicts with aids to counsel children. proponents of the bill say it offers no protection for homosexuals or drug or alcohol addicts
even as the senate prepared to vote, reagan urged congress to sustain his veto
i ask every senator and representative to rise above the pressures of an election year, to make a stand for religious liberty by sustaining my veto of this dangerous bill,'' reagan said in a speech to local republican officials from around the country
the truth is, this legislation isn't a civil rights bill,'' the president said. ``it's a power grab by washington, designed to take control away from states, localities, communities, parents and the private sector and give it to federal bureaucrats and judges
one dollar in federal aid _ direct or indirect _ would bring entire organizations under federal control, from charitable social organizations to churches and synagogues.''
house republican leader bob michel, r-ill., said reagan discussed the reasons for his veto today in a meeting with house republicans and outlined the alternative he proposed last week
it's rather too bad that that alternative did not get to us earlier on than the time it was presented,'' michel said
the reagan alternative would enable more institutions to escape regulation on religious grounds and limit most corporate compliance requirements to specific plants or facilities receiving federal aid
the court ruled that an organization or governmental body getting federal support must comply with anti-discrimination rules only for the program receiving the federal aid, not for the entire organization. the bill would cut off aid for the whole organization if discrimination against minorities, women, the elderly or the disabled was practiced by any part of the organization
obviously there's a very organized and promoted campaign'' against the bill, said senate majority leader robert byrd said. ``apparently the white house let the word out, as we began getting hundreds of calls (that) all said the same thing.''
i think a lot of misinformation has been spread,'' byrd added. ``there's a great deal of misinformation, distortion of truth and fact.''
the civil rights restoration act passed both chambers earlier this year by lopsided margins far greater than the two-thirds majority needed to override a presidential veto
vice president george bush on monday said he would support the reagan veto, saying the legislation ``is imperfect and the imperfections should be corrected.''
supporters of the legislation say it restores civil rights laws to the way they were interpreted before the court challenge mounted by tiny grove city (pa.) college
congress had tried since the supreme court decision to pass a corrective measure but became enmeshed in various controversies involving regulation and abortion. the final bill had broad bipartisan support and many republicans asked the president not to veto it
an eleventh-hour push by the conservative moral majority group resulted in thousands of phone calls, letters and telegrams urging lawmakers to uphold the veto
the liberal people for the american way responded monday with newspaper ads saying ``the far right could defeat civil rights'' unless people call their representatives and ``tell them your tax money must not pay for discrimination.''
the restoration act says entire institutions and government agencies must not discriminate if any program or activity within them receives federal aid. entire corporations are covered if they provide a public service such as health care or if the aid goes to the business as a whole, as in the chrysler bailout
farmers receiving crop subsidies, people using food stamps and other individuals receiving federal assistance would not be subject to regulation. an institution's refusal to perform or pay for abortions would not be considered discriminatory
the supreme court decision applied specifically to title ix of the 1972 education amendments barring sex discrimination in federally funded education programs. it was interpreted also to cover the 1964 civil rights act barring racial discrimination in federally-assisted programs; the 1973 rehabilitation act barring discrimination against the handicapped in any program or activity receiving federal aid; and the 1975 age discrimination act barring employment discrimination against older people. contra truce proposals. </note>
u.s. troops here on an emergency training exercise have no plans to pull out despite nicaragua's withdrawal of soldiers from the honduran border, an american military spokesman said today
right now the plans are to make it a 10- to 14-day exercises,'' said maj. gary hovatter, public relations director for the u.s. military in honduras. ``we have not received any directive as to when to begin redeployment.''
he said training exercises between honduran and american soldiers would continue today at four sites, but few details were available
hovatter also said five or six of the 10 soldiers injured in a helicopter crash during an exercise could be released to light duty
on monday, he said they ``are in some pain and discomfort, but they are handling it very well.''
hovatter said the helicopter, a uh-1 huey, was flying from southern san lorenzo to eastern jamastran when it hit bad weather and was forced to divert to juticalpa, 35 miles north of the nicaraguan border. it crashed about six miles south of juticalpa in a pine-covered valley, he said
nicaragua announced monday its troops had withdrawn from the border, and the honduran military reported sandinista soldiers had retreated. nicaragua's sandinista government and contra leaders also agreed to a cease-fire during three days of peace talks which will end wednesday at sapoa on nicaragua's southern border with costa rica
today, the sandinista government proposed a 30-day cease-fire and amnesty for rebels. the contras proposed a 45-day truce during which rebels would move into cease-fire zones
col. manuel suarez benevides, the honduran armed forces spokesman, said monday the 3,200 u.s. troops that rushed to honduras after a reported incursion by 2,000 sandinista troops won't be needed much longer
it'll be a very short time. we're talking days only,'' he said in an interview
also today, a u.n. fact-finding team requested by nicaragua was to leave for that country to investigate the border violence, the united nations announced in a statement. it said observations will be limited to the nicaragua side, since no permission was received from honduras to go there
meanwhile, nicaraguan and contra officials were optimistic after the first round of truce talks held in nicaragua on monday. the talks resume today
the worst (fighting) is over and there is peace now in the border region,'' col. reynald andino flores, commander of the honduran army's 101st infantry brigade, said monday by telephone from his headquarters in southern honduras. ``we are remaining on a state of alert to be ready for anything that may happen,'' he added, and soldiers are ``constantly patrolling the area.''
flores and other officers, some of whom insisted on anonymity for security reasons, said on monday the sandinistas penetrated an area of about 20 square miles inside olancho province while chasing the u.s.-supported contra rebels in a two-week offensive to evict the contras from nicaragua
about 200 border incidents have been reported in olancho since the contras began fighting the leftist sandinista government in 1981
president daniel ortega and the nicaraguan government have denied sandinista soldiers crossed the border
the contras maintain camps in an area called bocay, which includes territory on both sides of the border. nicaragua claims the camps, which the contras use to store supplies and to stage raids inside nicaragua, are in nicaraguan land, but the rebels say they are in honduras
the sandinistas and the contras agreed to a three-day truce on monday, the first of three days of their latest round of peace talks
at sapoa, nicaragua, a town on the costa rican border, representatives of the sandinista government and contras began their first direct talks on nicaraguan soil. the purpose is to work out a cease-fire as required by the peace plan that five central american presidents signed last aug. 7
after monday's closed session, gen. humberto ortega, nicaragua's defense minister, said: ``the importance of today was that we listened for the first time at the highest level their (contras') proposal,'' he told journalists
alfredo cesar, one of the rebel negotiators, said the contra plan calls for a 30-day truce, political amnesty and continued talks to work out a lasting cease-fire. ``neither side seeks a military victory over the other,'' cesar said. he called the first round a ``step ahead.'' secretary</note>
the chairman of the u.s. civil rights commission today gave an ``uncivil rights award'' to the mayor of newark, n.j., for allegedly pressuring rep. peter rodino into retirement
yielding to minority constituents, rodino, who is white and a democrat, announced march 14 he would not seek a 21st term in congress. minorities, who make up the bulk of rodino's district, have clamored for several years for a minority representative
at a news conference, civil rights commission chairman clarence pendleton, who is black, said he was awarding an ``uncivil rights award'' to newark mayor sharpe james, who is also black and who, according to pendleton, worked ``with several other newark politicians'' and ``pressured ... rodino to retire from congress.''
the notion that peter rodino doesn't represent the people in the 10th district is absurd,'' pendleton said. ``they have elected him to congress 20 times, and continue to support his leading role on civil rights issues. no matter. the newark power brokers have decided that he is not `their' representative _ he's just the wrong color.''
pam goldstein, a spokeswoman for james, said the mayor had not been told of the ``award.'' but ms. goldstein said she doubted james' would be bothered by criticism from pendleton, whose own civil rights record she termed a ``joke.''
i would say it's an endorsement for what the mayor's doing in this city,'' ms. goldstein said
rodino's press secretary, larry spinelli, said he would have no immediate comment on the matter
cbs' plan to liven up its schedule with a rash of new half-hour comedies was a ratings failure in its first week. abc, meanwhile, put the critically praised comedy ``the wonder years'' into the nielsen top 10
nbc won the week handily. cbs finished slightly ahead of abc for the week, but continued to lag in season-to-date ratings and seems destined to finish in last place for the first time
for the week ending march 20, nbc had an average, prime-time rating of 15.8. cbs had a 12.9 and abc 12.6. with four weeks left in the season, nbc leads with a 16.3, abc is second with a 13.9 and cbs third with 13.6
the good news for cbs was that ``cbs evening news'' was still in first place with an average rating of 11.6 and a 22 share. abc's ``world news tonight'' was second with 10.8 and 20, and ``nbc nightly news'' third with 9.7 and 18
of the new cbs comedies, only ``eisenhower &amp; lutz,'' which premiered with double episodes on monday, fared very well. the first episode ranked 41st. the second was 31st with a rating of 14.2 and a 22 share
the rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with television sets. the share is a percentage of sets in use
the two new comedies and one returning comedy cbs added on tuesday night were steamrollered by abc's normally strong lineup, including ``the wonder years,'' a sweet-natured nostalgia comedy set in the late 1960s. it replaced ``growing pains,'' which moved to wednesday night where it continues to be a top-10 show
the top 10 for last week were: ``the cosby show'' nbc, ``a different world'' nbc, ``golden girls'' nbc, ``60 minutes'' cbs, ``who's the boss?'' abc, ``cheers'' nbc, ``the wonder years'' abc, ``night court'' nbc, ``murder, she wrote'' cbs and ``growing pains'' abc. half of the top 10 shows were repeats, as the networks began to conserve new episodes for the may sweeps
on tuesday night, cbs' ``coming of age,'' starring paul dooley as an acerbic former airline pilot struggling to adjust to a sunny retirement village, was 59th out of 77 shows. ``my sister sam'' was 75th
sam'' had originally done well in the ratings and was brought back from hiatus to fill in for ``the dictator,'' a new comedy that was delayed by the writers guild strike
trial and error,'' a hispanic ``odd couple,'' was 76th with a rating of only 6.5 and an 11 share. the critically praised ``frank's place'' was moved from monday to tuesday where the rest of the lineup dragged it down to 65th
nbc did well with its regular lineup and a couple of remakes of hit movies. a new tv version of ``inherit the wind,'' this one starring jason robards and kirk douglas, ranked 14th. tied for 15th place was ``in the heat of the night,'' starring carroll o'connor and howard rollins in the pilot of the series getting a spring tryout
the bottom-rated shows of the week were: ``the thorns,'' ``a place at the table,'' ``probe,'' ``west 57th,'' ``the disney sunday movie,'' ``ohara,'' ``hotel,'' ``my sister sam,'' ``trial and error'' and ``buck james.''
here is a summary of developments monday and today involving honduras, nicaragua and the united states:
nicaragua on monday withdrew its soldiers from the border but the frontier remained tense, with honduran patrols on the lookout for any booby traps left behind by the sandinistas
president jose azcona hoyo said the 3,200 u.s. troops sent to honduras last week, after the nicaraguan army was accused of sending 2,000 men across the border in pursuit of contras, may not be needed much longer
however, the u.s. troops were to begin a new set of joint maneuvers with the honduran army today. on monday, a u.s. army transport helicopter crashed while participating in a military exercise and 10 soldiers were injured. other helicopters evacuated the soldiers for medical treatment
the sandinista government, in its second day of peace talks with contra rebels, today proposed a 30-day truce, and the u.s.-backed contras said a cease-fire should last 45 days. the nicaraguan government proposal calls for the rebels to lay down their arms, while the contras said rebels should move into cease-fire zones during the truce. on monday, the two sides agreed to a battlefield truce during the three days of the peace talks
president reagan today met with house republicans in a bid to renew interest in his stalled aid package for the contras. the proposed aid package would offer a one-year, $48 million infusion of humanitarian aid, as well as continued authority for the cia to deliver weapons remaining in rebel inventories, estimated at as much as $2.5 million. ``the youngest child xxx</note>
police today found six children reported missing when the eldest child, a 13-year-old girl, drove out of a parking lot while their foster parents were inside a hospital
the children had been left in the van monday while the couple kept a doctor's appointment in san diego, san diego police lt. bill brown said today. a witness saw the teen-ager drive the van out of the parking lot, brown said
everybody's safe. everybody's in good health,'' said police sgt. ron brown
investigators from the child abuse unit were going to talk with the children, said police spokesman bill robinson
a determination will be made if the parents were ``remiss'' in their actions, and where the children should be placed, robinson said. it is unlikely that any action will be taken against the teen-ager, he said
police sgt. roy stamper said the girl had driven to a friend's home in encinitas, a seaside community about 20 miles north of san diego, and the younger children spent the night in the van outside the house
the mother of the friend heard a news report about the missing van and called sheriff's deputies
the children's names were not released
the youngest child, an 8-month-old baby, was described as ``medically fragile,'' sgt. dan luth said. he did not know details of the baby's condition
two of the children are age 12. the others are 4 years and 19 months
police alerted authorities in san diego county to watch for a yellow, california-registered 1978 chevrolet van with red, black and orange stripes. the license number was entered into a national computer network of stolen cars
it was not known if the children had any money, luth said
as far as we know, the foster parents took all the kids to kaiser hospital where the father had to see doctor,'' brown said. ``apparently the children wanted to stay in the van, found the key, and drove off.''
he said it was at first assumed the driver would take the children to her biological parents' house in vista, but she did not
the cost of mailing a first-class letter will jump from 22 cents to a quarter on april 3, the u.s. postal service announced today
the hike is part of an overall increase in postage rates, replacing charges that have been in effect since feb. 17, 1985
the biggest increase will affect so-called ``junk'' mail, with rates for third-class advertising increasing nearly 25 percent
magazines and newspapers will pay about 18 percent more, while postage charges for individual consumers will climb nearly 15 percent
the government tuesday shut down the new nation, a combative, church-backed anti-apartheid newspaper, making it the first victim of a campaign to stifle militant publications
the government ``has killed the messenger instead of listening to the message.'' said peter soal, a parliament member for the liberal progessive federal party
home affairs minister stoffel botha, who has state-of-emergency powers to censor publications singlehandedly, said in a special decree that further issues of the black-oriented weekly newspaper are ``totally prohibited'' through june 10
another cabinet minister, stoffel van der merwe, said the new nation was closed because it advocated violent overthrow of the government and supported communism
it is absolutely astonishing that a publication issued under the name of a christian organization should act in this way,'' he said
the closure came a day after the 2-year-old newspaper, published by the southern african catholic bishops conference, lost a court appeal seeking to postpone government action while it challenged the censorship regulations
the new nation technically could resume publication after three months, but botha could close it again if its contents in the ensuing issues dissatisfied him
bishop reginald orsmond, chairman of the newspapers' publishing board, said the 22-member staff would be retained during the suspension. he declined to predict would would happen to the paper if the suspension was extended
orsmond accused the government of ``suppressing the voice of the people.''
authorities have banned four of the new nation's editions and seized two. police have raided the paper's offices, and it was the first of six publications warned by botha that they could be closed or forced to obey an in-house censor if they continued to publish material he found objectionable
anglican archbishop desmond tutu, whose stepped-up political activities in recent weeks have angered the government, described the new nation's closure as ``quite scandalous.''
only a government that is scared or already totalitarian, or very close to totalitarian, behaves in the kind of way that ours does,'' tutu said
with a circulation of about 60,000, the new nation is the largest newspaper in south africa to devote virtually its entire content, including sports and entertainment pages, to politically related developments
one regular feature was a learning section, ``to bridge the deficiencies of apartheid education.'' in simple language, it told readers about black activists not covered in school courses and explained how to apply for a job, feed a baby nutritiously, treat an injured riot victim or protect oneself from tear gas
the newspaper's editor, zwelakhe sisulu, has been detained without charge for 16 months. he joined the new nation after a year as a neiman fellow at harvard university
sisulu's father, walter, former secretary-general of the now-outlawed african national congress, is serving a life prison term along with anc leader nelson mandela for treason and sabotage
state-of-emergency regulations give botha nearly unlimited powers to deal with newspapers he feels might contribute to unrest. under the regulations, he does not have to give reasons for his actions
the new nation lost an initial court challenge of the regulations and intends to pursue its case in an appellate court. but on monday, a supreme court rejected the newspaper's bid to prevent closure during the appeal process
the last edition of the new nation, on march 17, said the government was ``bent on destroying what little freedom of expression is left in a country where the majority are voteless.''
because the new nation dared to act as their voice, it has now been damned to silence,'' the paper said
the issue also carried a quotation from president p.w. botha on the front page: ``i believe in a free press and in free news media.''
christian bale, the 14-year-old star of ``empire of the sun,'' told reporters at a gala opening of the film here that he had one complaint
i don't like watching myself,'' said bale, who plays a boy growing up in shanghai during the japanese invasion of the chinese city in world war ii in the adaptation of the novel by j.g. ballard
director steven spielberg, who also attended the gala premier along with queen elizabeth ii monday, said 4,000 boys were interviewed for the part, ``but he (bale) was meant to be the star of this movie. i could not believe my luck when i found him.''
bale, who is from bournemouth on england's south coast, flies to tokyo friday for the last leg of a six-week promotional tour
singer linda ronstadt called san francisco chronicle columnist herb caen a ``creep'' for publishing the address of her new home here, the newspaper reported tuesday
ronstadt, 41, recently bought the house for $2.55 million in the city's ritzy pacific heights neighborhood. although she hasn't moved in, she is thinking about selling it
there's too much publicity about it, and it's not a good idea to live there,'' said ronstadt, who is on a national tour. ``it's kind of a security risk.''
according to the newspaper, after caen published the address, ronstadt said it made her ``not like the house, and it made me not like the neighborhood, and it made me not like the city, and it made me not like to live there. that's the end of it.''
don hewitt, who marks his 40th anniversary with cbs news tuesday, recalls landing his first job at the network after a friend suggested his experience at a newsphoto service might come in handy
i said, what does cbs want with picture experience? radio doesn't need any pictures. he said, `no _ television.' i said whata-vision?''
today, the 65-year-old outspoken creator and executive producer of ``60 minutes'' is looking beyond current television technology, foreseeing a time when networks are superfluous and television news is beamed directly into subscribers' homes
i think that the network news departments, they might not even work for a network 10 years from now,'' said hewitt, who produced the the network's first television newscast, ``douglas edwards with the news,'' and later the ``cbs evening news'' with walter cronkite
there might not be any networks because it may be an outmoded delivery system.''
garrison keillor says he's glad he's finally getting a chance to work on a humphrey political campaign
the humorist, author and former minnesotan took to the stage here monday night to raise money for minnesota attorney general hubert humphrey iii, a democrat who is challenging u.s. sen. dave durenberger, r-minn, for his seat this year. humphrey is the son of the late sen. hubert h. humphrey jr
at a private fund-raiser after his performance, keillor said he had worked in several political campaigns but regretted never having worked for the late senator and vice president
to me it feels right ... just to be able to work for a humphrey campaign after all these years,'' he said
humphrey returned the compliment, saying ``i see in garrison's lighthearted, satirical humor a real sense of understanding of where people really are.''
doug flutie will be changing diapers as well as learning the offensive patterns of the new england patriots
the former heisman trophy winner's wife, laurie, gave birth to the couple's first child monday night. alexa dawn flutie was born at 9:45 p.m. at leonard morse hospital. she weighed 7 pounds, 13 ounces
i'm thrilled to death,'' said flutie, 25
when i think now how people live and die with their football teams every sunday, and how quarterbacks worry about their jobs after throwing an interception, well this, a new-born baby, really puts everything in perspective,'' flutie said
president francois mitterrand said tuesday he will seek a second term, ending months of speculation on whether the 71-year-old socialist would enter the presidential race
appearing on the nationwide evening newscast of the state-owned antenne 2, mitterrand was asked if he would run. he answered with a single word, ``oui'' _ ``yes.''
he said he decided to run because he thinks disunity threatened ``to tear the social fabric'' of the nation
prosecutors on tuesday opened an investigation into fraud, influence peddling and financial scandals allegedly involving the brother of former president chun doo-hwan
the prosecutor general's office said at least 10 officials have been questioned in an investigation of whether chun kyung-hwan, a younger brother of the former president, embezzled funds of the saemaul undong development group
top saemaul officials are suspected of diverting private and government subsidies to profit-oriented projects, land speculation and other illegal activities
the former president left office feb. 25 at the end of a seven-year term. he left tuesday on a private visit to the united states, where he will meet president reagan on wednesday
president roh tae-woo, who succeeded chun, has pledged to eradicate abuses of power and corruption under previous governments. in a recent move to reduce the ex-president's power, roh removed some chun supporters from their posts
some political observers say the roh government opened the investigation to disscredit the former president and improve the current government's image
there have been allegations of corruption by the saemaul group since the former president seized power with military backing in 1980 and installed his brother as saemaul head
the younger chun resigned in 1987 after being linked to gangsters
prosecutor kang won-il said government officials also were being investigated to see if they had assisted or protected corruption
my investigation team will unearth all malpractices and make public the results of the probe,'' kang told reporters
dong-a ilbo, an influential seoul newspaper, said the younger chun was responsible for a sharp drop in cattle prices in 1983 when he forced government officials to import cattle from the united states
saemaul was formed in 1971 to improve rural and urban living standards, but critics contend the country's authoritarian governments have used the movement to promote government influence
the party for peace and democracy controlled by opposition leader kim dae-jung charged that roh also aided saemaul officials when he was a government minister in 1982
the opposition party demanded that roh and other family members of the former president be investigated
when asked the key question by a television reporter, mitterrand paused dramatically, clearly savoring the moment before delivering his one-word answer and awaiting the reaction
in follow-up questions, he said he had watched the campaign, and feared opposing candidates were bringing on france disputes that threatened to damage the country. ``we need social peace,'' he said
with just four weeks remaining until the first round of voting, mitterrand said his decision was arrived at after mature reflection
the president's plans had been the subject of speculation for months. sometimes he had indicated he preferred to retire. other times he hinted he would run out of a sense of duty
individual pickets have a right to carry signs within 500 feet of foreign embassies in the nation's capital but police may disperse groups of three or more protesters there, the supreme court ruled tuesday
by a vote of 8-0, the justices upheld the district of columbia's ban on groups demonstrating within 500 feet of embassies if police have reason to believe the protesters pose a threat to ``the security or peace of the embassy.''
but by a separate 5-3 vote, the court said the city's anti-picketing prohibition that prevents even one or two people from carrying signs within 500 feet of the embassies violates free-speech protections
justice sandra day o'connor, in her opinion for the court, said a blanket ban on signs that might be offensive to foreign diplomats goes too far
it may serve an interest in protecting the dignity of foreign missions, but it is not narrowly tailored,'' she said. ``a less restrictive alternative is readily available.''
for example, she said, it would be constitutional to ban picketing that is designed to intimidate, coerce, threaten or harass a foreign official
that type of ban has been adopted by congress for all areas of the nation with the exception of the district of columbia
officials of the district of columbia government have said they are considering adopting a law based on the congressional model
tuesday's ruling allows district police to continue to enforce a ban on demonstrations near embassies when at least three people take part and police fear there will be disruptions
o'connor said police must ``reasonably believe that a threat to the security or peace of the embassy is present.''
banning such gatherings ``does not prohibit peaceful congregations,'' she said. the ban ``is limited to groups posing a security threat.''
o'connor rejected arguments that such a ban gives police too much discretion to break up demonstrations
she said the test for deciding whether a demonstration is illegal ``is whether normal embassy activities have been or are about to be disrupted.''
the ruling partially overturned a 1986 decision by the u.s. circuit court of appeals in washington upholding all aspects of the district of columbia's ban on protests near embassies
that ruling was written by former judge robert h. bork, who recently retired from the appeals court. bork was president reagan's first choice to fill a supreme court vacancy last year but was rejected by the senate in a bitter fight
tuesday's decision is believed to be the first time the high court gave full review to an opinion written by bork. his backers during the senate confirmation fight emphasized that he had never been reversed by the high court
the appeals court ruling that bork wrote in the embassy case said free-speech interests of the demonstrators were outweighed by the need to protect foreign emissaries
the 500-foot restrictions were challenged by michael boos, j. michael waller and bridget brooker, members of the young conservative alliance of america
they wanted to carry signs in front of the soviet embassy saying ``release sakharov,'' referring to soviet dissident andrei sakharov, who was allowed in 1986 to return to moscow, ending his internal exile in the city of gorky
the demonstrators also planned to picket the nicaraguan embassy with placards saying ``stop the killing'' in opposition to the sandinista government there
the conservatives also said they were not receiving equal treatment with opponents of the south african government who have demonsrated near that nation's embassy in washington
many of those protesting south african racial policy have been arrested and then freed without being prosecuted
joining o'connor in both phases of tuesday's ruling were justices william j. brennan, thurgood marshall, john paul stevens and antonin scalia
dissenting and voting to uphold the ban on individual picketing were chief justice william h. rehnquist and justices byron r. white and harry a. blackmun
justice anthony m. kennedy did not take part in the decision
in other action, the court:
_unanimously ruled in a case from michigan that states are barred from regulating the way interstate natural gas companies issue securities to finance their operations
_heard arguments in a case from illinois on whether the so-called miranda warnings police give criminal suspects are adequate to insure their right to legal help. a decision is expected to be announced by july
kansas democrats decided tuesday to allow local delegates pledged to the presidential runners-up in saturday's caucuses to vote at district conventions after all
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis won the kansas contest with 278 of the 764 local delegates elected and jesse jackson finished second with 235
however, there was confusion over the local delegates pledged to tennessee sen. albert gore jr. and missouri rep. richard gephardt and those who were uncommitted
under state rules, local delegates who supported a candidate who didn't reach a 15 percent threshold would be non-entities at the district conventions april 23
the state decided monday that those local delegates would be unable to vote at the district conventions and would be ignored in computing national delegates from the districts
but after conferring with the democratic national committee's compliance commission, which interprets the national rules for electing delegates to the national convention, the state party decided tuesday that all local delegates will be allowed to vote
thus, the delegates pledged to gore, gephardt and uncommitted could possibly form larger blocs that could secure national delegates
an initial calculation by the associated press based on candidates' strength at the local level showed that dukakis won 16 national delegates, jackson 14, gore five and uncommitted four
but when peculiarities in the kansas rules are applied, gore and uncommitted lack enough statewide strength to claim additional delegates. the ap recalculation and state party count give dukakis 18 delegates, jackson 16, gore three and two uncommitted.    reaction should be monitored, not necessary lead to trouble. subs lead to correct by deleting `city.'</note>
colors,'' a movie about street gangs starring sean penn and robert duvall, could prompt more street warfare, some officials complain
the violence was certainly graphic, but no more graphic than on the streets,'' city attorney james hahn said monday, a day after a private screening for the film, which uses real gang members as extras and real gang names
it portrayed the dead end of getting involved in gangs,'' hahn said. ``it was a pretty depressing movie from that standpoint.''
gang violence has claimed more than 50 lives in los angeles county this year
the orion pictures movie is scheduled for release april 15, and anti-gang specialists fear violence could erupt at theaters if rival gang members go to see it
it could create some problems,'' hahn said. ``it's the kind of thing we need to be concerned about and careful. we're just going to wait and see and monitor the situation.''
sheriff's sgt. wes mcbride, president of the california gang investigators association, said ``colors'' glorified gangs at times
i'd be surprised if we don't have some people die because of this movie,'' he said
a warning advising suspects that they may remain silent and are entitled to an attorney is not adequate to protect their rights under the constitution, the supreme court was told on tuesday
donald honchell, a cook county, ill., public defender appealing the 1983 murder conviction of a gang member, said the ``miranda warning'' does protect a person from self-incrimination under the fifth amendment
but he argued that, once a suspect is indicted, the warning alone is not enough to protect the sixth amendment guarantee of legal help
the supreme court is using the illinois case to decide whether the warnings that police have been required to give since 1966 are adequate to advise suspects of their right to legal aid
it ruled in ``miranda vs. arizona'' that people accused of crimes must be informed of their rights to remain silent, to have a lawyer, to have counsel present during questioning and to receive free legal assistance if needed
honchell contended that even if a defendant has waived his rights under miranda, he has an automatic right to a lawyer as soon as he is indicted and may not be asked from that point on to submit to interrogation
there is a shield around the accused through which the police cannot get a waiver,'' honchell said. ``at no time after the indictment should the police be allowed to go to the defendant, seek a waiver and begin to question.''
however, a prosecutor said authorities would be unfairly limited if they cannot interrogate a defendant who is read his rights and then agrees to speak without a lawyer present
jack donatelli, an assistant cook county prosecutor, also said the warning is perfectly understandable to defendants
they have a common-sense meaning that enables defendants to understand they have both a right to counsel and that things could go against them if they don't have a lawyer with them when they're in custody and questioned,'' donatelli said
honchell said police coerced his client, tyrone patterson, 22, of evanston, ill., into making incriminating statements by telling him he had been indicted. but donatelli said patterson understood his rights and agreed to be questioned anyway
patterson, a member of the vice lords street gang, is serving a 24-year sentence at the pontiac correction center for his conviction in the aug. 21, 1983 beating death of rival black mobsters gang member james ``pudge'' jackson
according to court briefs, he was arrested on a misdemeanor charge following a gang fight, received a ``miranda warning'' and signed a statement waiving his right to counsel
two days later, after initially refusing to discuss jackson's death, patterson was told he had been indicted, signed a second miranda waiver and agreed to answer questions, the briefs said
hoosier taxpayers with a grudge can walk into union station next month, pay a dollar and try to plunge an internal revenue service manager into the chilly waters of a charity dunking booth
the dunking booth is part of ``tax bash,'' scheduled april 11-15 at the downtown train station. proceeds from the event will benefit the muscular dystrophy association
during the evening hours, dry irs employees will be on hand to answer tax questions while their managers are taking the plunge. h&amp;r block inc. representatives will be available to prepare tax returns, with a portion of the fee going to the mda, and the u.s. postal service will operate a special tax return drop-off box
we're billing it as one-stop shopping for taxes,'' carolyn stumpf, irs public affairs officer, said tuesday
she said it didn't take any arm-twisting to get the irs involved in the fund-raiser
we thought that it's about time we show that we have a sense of humor, and the fact that we can help another group of individuals _ besides the tax-paying public _ so much the better,'' she said
the hot debate between mayoral and council candidates in parker is whether to use a 12-acre sodded area for polo or soccer
this is the horsiest county in the united states. we have more horses per person in our community than they do in kentucky,'' said dean salisbury, 66, mayor of this town of 700 about 15 miles southeast of denver
voters will decide april 5 whether to retain salisbury, the town's first and only mayor, or replace him with one of two challengers: ann waterman, 43, or mark lewis, 36
seven people are running for the four open seats on the town council, including three of the incumbents and four challengers
salisbury, who has won ribbons as a carriage and sulky race driver, takes credit for starting a regional park from 150 acres dedicated to the town by developers, then cultivating about 12 acres into a low-cost ``utility field'' for soccer or softball
but he also hopes the grassy field can be used to host an annual polo match to lure thousands of spectators to parker as part of a drive for economic development
the challengers say such schemes indicate salisbury is a better promoter than mayor and claim he has ignored the town's mundane recreational needs
for years, gayle e. culberson has been teaching kids at karval high school how to make ethanol in a class on energy conservation
but when the industrial arts teacher got a letter from the federal bureau of alcohol, tobacco and firearms saying his school would have to pay $500 a year because it was a fuel alcohol producer, he became a little upset
so culberson did what ever civics teacher recommends: he wrote his senator
culberson wrote sen. william armstrong that the school could not afford the tax and could lose its permit to produce fuel alcohol. his class makes a few quarts a year, he said
without the permit, he said, students in this eastern plains community would miss an important lesson
at a time when it seems important to reduce foreign oil imports, reduce pollution in our states, when education is struggling to better itself with diminishing budgets, why was there a tax of this nature levied on fuel alcohol plants and educational facilities in particular?'' culberson asked armstrong
armstrong has responded by drafting an amendment that would exempt from the tax producers who make less than 10,000 gallons of fuel alcohol per year
this is a classic case of the bureaucracy gone berserk,'' armstrong said
gen. manuel antonio noriega's opponents scorned what they called a cynical offer to negotiate his resignation and kept panama shut down tuesday with a general strike intended to force him out
an estimated 90 percent of offices and industries were shut by the strike, which appeared to be gaining support on its second day. most shops and stores were closed, public transportation was halted and many government employees did not go to work
panama is out of cash because of pressure from the united states to force the ouster of noriega, who is the real power in panama as commander of its 15,000 soldiers and police. the u.s. dollar is the national currency and the supply has been cut off
most government workers were paid only $75 of their midmonth wages last week and the $33 million end-of-the-month payroll for the 130,000 public employees problably won't be met. pension checks due wednesday have been delayed, at least until march 28
hunger is spreading among workers as well as the poor, unemployed and elderly. many washerwomen, cleaning women, maids and cooks have lost their jobs because there is no money with which to pay them
manuel solis palma, the civilian noriega chose to run the government, said on television monday night the general would resign in exchange for ``a national dialogue'' to reconcile differences with opponents of the regime. he prefaced the offer with a diatribe against the united states
the implication was that noriega, under federal court indictment in florida on narcotics and money laundering charges, would stay in panama and might retain power behind the scenes
calling the offer a ``noble gesture,'' solis palma said noriega pledged ``as an officer and a gentleman'' to resign before presidential elections scheduled for may 1989
solis palma, who has the title ``minister in charge of the presidency,'' said he would not accept noriega's resignation unless ``all of the political forces in the country'' join ``a national dialogue.''
noriega put solis palma in office feb. 26, after president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire the general and the legislature dismissed delvalle instead
delvalle, still recognized by the united states, is hiding in panama. his dismissal began a run on panama's banks and they were closed the next week
pressure from washington has included freezing virtually all panamanian funds in the united states, including revenue from the panama canal
reagan administration spokesmen rejected the noriega proposal. last week, noriega turned down a u.s. plan for him to leave panama and live in spain
the general said his plan was a ``panamanian solution'' to the crisis
i have no reason to talk to the united states,'' he told reporters after solis palma's speech. ``i talk to panamanians.''
guillermo cochez, vice president of the christian democratic party, said the proposed discussion would occur in a panel of 33 members, 22 of them supporting noriega
this is not a dialogue,'' he said ``it's just cynicism.''
aurelio barria said: ``the general has to go _ immediately, not eventually
barria is a leader of the national civic crusade, a coalition of 200 business, professional, labor and political groups that called the general strike. it was organized last june to lead the campaign against noriega
solis palma spoke on television for 30 minutes, devoting all but the last five minutes to castigating the united states. he accused washington of ``economic aggression'' in ``an undeclared state of war.''
he claimed the united states wants to renege on the 1977 treaties under which the panama canal will be turned over to this country at midnight dec. 31, 1999
the canal, guarded by about 10,000 u.s. troops, has been operating normally despite the crisis. the united states sent 300 more soldiers monday, most of them security personnel
because of increasing hunger, the rev. francisco verar said his roman catholic church in the poor san miguelito suburb is feeding more families every day
if we had not done this there would have been chaos, even cases of death,'' he said. ``we have people who have gone five, six days without food.''
longshoremen, on strike for more than a week, voted overwhelmingly tuesday to stay out but accepted part payment of back wages despite fears of compromising their position
there are mothers and fathers who have to feed their children,'' said luis asprilla, a union leader
in some parts of panama city, workers formed vigilante groups to guard stores and other places of employment. looting occurred during street protests against noriega last week. ^eds: for release at 6 p.m. est, time set by source</head>
a bladder cancer treatment that avoids surgery has shown promising results in a preliminary study, a scientist said tuesday
twenty-one of 36 patients who have completed the drug-and-radiation therapy were found free of disease for three to 21 months, said george prout, professor of surgery at harvard medical school
three others showed partial remission, while treatment failed outright for nine patients. the other three were not evaluable, he told science writers at a seminar sponsored by the american cancer society
the study focused on patients whose cancers had invaded the bladder muscle, a condition usually treated by surgically removing the bladder, prout said
if the bladder is removed, the patient must wear a bag to collect urine for the rest of his life. it also essentially ends sexual activity
the experimental treatment attacks liver cancer with radiation to the pelvis, plus treatment with a mix of the drugs methotrexate, velban and cis-platinum
nearly 300,000 people have become sick and 11 have died in shanghai's 2-month-old hepatpresses soon will be turning out new editions of highly popular works by mikhail bulgakov, author of ``the master and margarita,'' and boris pasternak, who won the 1958 nobel literature prize for his novel ``doctor zhivago.'' it has not yet been published in book form in his homeland
the newspapers did not say whether foreign literature was included among the books to be made available. foreign writers such as jack london, ernest hemingway and emile zola are very popular in the soviet union, and some have been available for years
no details were given on the pricing system to be used for books published by their authors
this is not going to be a cheap venture for the author,'' pravda warned. ``depending on the number of copies and the volume, such a publication will cost roughly 2,000 rubles and more.''
that sum, the equivalent of $3,340, represents nearly a year's pay for the average industrial worker
the author in return will receive 20 percent of the sales income, pravda said
the program has not yet been put into the form of law, pravda noted, but already state publishing houses have many applications from authors who want to pay to see their works in print
by offering an alternative to creation of publishing cooperatives, the state publishing committee retains a monopoly on what gets into print
on a related subject, the newspaper soviet culture disclosed tuesday that glavlit, the state body which for decades has been responsible for censorship, is conducting a review of 6,000 books held in ``special detention'' storehouses
most of the fiction and non-fiction titles were banned during the 29-year dictatorship of josef v. stalin and removed from library shelves and book kiosks because their authors were deemed to have espoused politically hazardous ideas
the vast majority of those books were works whose authors were subjected to repression during the years of stalin's personality cult,'' vladimir a. solodin, a member of the review committee, told soviet culture. ``the others had other `faults,' for example, forewords written by such repressed politicians, quotes from their works or their photographs.''
among the blacklisted books were 180 that contained references to nikolai i. bukharin and 70 that mentioned alexei i. rykov, two prominent political figures from the early years of the soviet government executed by stalin but recently rehabilitated by gorbachev
glavlit, or the chief directorate for the protection of state secrets in publishing, was created in 1922 to ensure freedom of the soviet press from ideological impurity. it has served since as the chief censorship agency, and would have banned the blacklisted books in the first place
a glavlit committee went through 4,000 of the ba readers, but said the review was helping to resolve the deficit in good literature
the 500 books left in special detention are mostly ``profoundly instigatory literature and nationalistic writings,'' that could be used for ill purposes if allowed into general distribution, solodin said
the decision to keep them under wraps is not final, and the glavlit committee will take another look at them once the initial screening is completed, solodin said
a suspected mail thief who changed his identity was traced to a navy warship in the persian gulf and was arrested when the ship came home, investigators said
postal inspector j.a. mcdonald obtained a warrant for the arrest of luke lee mccall on july 10, 1986, on a charge that he took a letter containing a $620 insurance check from someone else's post office box
mccall, who otherwise had a clean record, began using the name of andre darnell robinson in order to avoid trial, said stan hills, a deputy marshal in jacksonville. he said mccall returned to chicago and enlisted in the navy
after several months in the persian gulf on the uss okinawa, mccall was arrested monday in norfolk, va., when the vessel docked
with no prior record, mccall probably wouldn't have received the maximum penalty _ five years in prison and a $250,000 fine _ had he gone to trial in 1986, hill said
mccall, 28, was ordered held on $75,000 bond following his appearance monday before a u.s. magistrate in virginia
mccall is scheduled to be arraigned april 4 in jacksonville on the federal mail charge, said assistant u.s. attorney teresa wright. he also faces additional charges stemming from the use of a false identity, she said
mccall had obtained a copy of andre robinson's birth certificate and was using his social security number, officials said. robinson, who lives in jacksonville, was not involved in the scheme
under his assumed name, mccall married a woman in san diego and bought a car with a loan from the navy credit union there, hills said
reyner banham, an influential writer on architecture and the arts, has died of cancer at the age of 66
the burly professor returned to london after more than 10 years in the united states after developing cancer last year. he died saturday in london, his family said
most recently, banham taught art history at the university of california for seven years
he was educated in norwich, and at the beginning of world war ii, he began working at the bristol aeroplane co. after the war, he studied art history at london university's courtauld institute while writing about contemporary architecture for the architectural review
in 1959, he joined the staff of the review full-time, but five years later, left for a teaching post at bartlett university college in london, where in 1969 he became professor of the history of architecture
after enthusiastic u.s. reaction to his 1960 book, ``theory and design in the first machine age,'' he moved to the united states in 1966 to teach at the university of buffalo in new york. he moved to california in 1980
he wrote two other widely studied books, ``the new brutalism'' in 1966 and ``architecture of the well-tempered environment'' in 1969
banham is survived by his wife, mary, a son and a daughter
the chairman of the u.s. civil rights commission announced tuesday that he was bestowing an ``uncivil rights award'' on the mayor of newark, n.j., for pressuring rep. peter rodino, d-n.j., to retire because he is white
chairman clarence pendleton, who is black, said that rodino receives the ``victim of uncivil rights award'' for the way in which he was treated by ``newark power brokers'' who have decided that ``he is not their representative _ he's just the wrong color.''
at a news conference where he criticized the civil rights restoration act and the resignation under pressure of gallaudet university president elisabeth zinser, pendleton said he was instituting his own personal ``uncivil rights award'' program in an effort to highlight ``the absurdities committed in the name of civil rights.''
pendleton's first recipient was newark mayor sharpe james, who is black. james has said the courts carved out rodino's 10th congressional district more than 12 years ago to elect a minority congressman, and that ``it's time to get that done.'' pendleton said james worked ``with several other newark politicians'' in pressuring rodino to retire
rodino announced march 14 that he would not seek a 21st term in congress. minorities, who make up the bulk of rodino's district, have clamored for several years for a minority representative
rodino has been pressured to retire so that a proper _ read this black _ representative can be elected,'' said pendleton. ``the notion that peter rodino doesn't represent the people in the 10th district is absurd. they have elected him to congress 20 times, and continue to support his leading role on civil rights issues.''
james declined to respond to the criticism from pendleton, said pam goldstein, a spokeswoman for the mayor. ``i will not dignify his comments with a response,'' she quoted james as saying
rodino also declined comment, said spokesman larry spinelli
pendleton said he would bestow his new awards ``as often as they are properly earned _ perhaps once a month. if the civil rights restoration act passes today over the president's veto, i suppose i will have more than enough material.''
pendleton said the civil rights restoration act represents ``an unwarranted invasion ... by big brother.''
the statute forbids distribution of federal funds to entire institutions, state and local government agencies and many corporations if any part of them practices discrimination. it was spurred by a 1984 supreme court ruling that civil rights laws applied only to a specific program or activity receiving federal aid
the head of the civil rights panel also said that one of his candidates for a ``victim of uncivil rights'' award had been zinser, who was named the first woman president in the 124-year history of gallaudet university for the deaf, only to resign following protests over the fact that she was not deaf
patrick steptoe, the doctor who delivered the world's first test-tube baby in 1978 and helped pioneer a technique that revolutionized infertilty treatment, has died of cancer. he was 74
steptoe, a gynecologist and obstetrician who pioneered the in vitro fertilization technique with physiologist robert edwards, died monday night at chaucer hospital in canterbury
on tuesday, he was to have been decorated by queen elizabeth ii as a commander of the british empire, an honor one step below a knighthood, for services to his country
an expert in infertility, steptoe also was to have received the british medical association's gold medal, one of the profession's highest awards, at its annual meeting in july
mr. steptoe made an invaluable contribution to medicine and raised the honor and dignity of the profession,'' the association said. british surgeons use the designation ``mr.'' instead of ``dr.''
the test-tube baby technique gave hope to millions of childless couples and spawned a range of fertility treatments for both men and women
more than 1,000 test-tube babies have been born as a result of treatment at bourn hall clinic, near cambridge, run by steptoe and edwards, and thousands of others have born elsewhere in the world
it is a very great loss to bourn hall and to me personally,'' edwards said. ``in the last three years, he was working under considerable difficulties but carried on
he wished to do service to his patients for as long as possible.''
truck driver john brown, father of louise joy brown, the world's first test-tube baby, said he and his wife, lesley, ``are forever in his debt.''
there is no way we, or any other couples mr. steptoe helped, can possibly repay him for what he has given them,'' brown said
louise was born on july 25, 1978, in oldham, england. four years later, the browns had a second test-tube baby, natalie jane
the birth of louise brown, the first human conceived outside the womb, was hailed as a medical breakthrough on the order of the first heart transplant. but some people were horrified, seeing it as the dawn of a ``brave new world'' of baby farms and genetic engineering
i am not a wizard or a frankenstein,'' steptoe once said
all i want to do is help women whose child-producing mechanism is slightly faulty.''
under the in vitro fertilization technique, which actually involves no test tubes, eggs are removed from the prospective mother and fertilized with the intended father's sperm in a glass dish. the resulting embryo is then implanted in the mother's womb
it took 10 years for edwards and steptoe to develop the technique
working at cambridge university, edwards worked out the procedure for fertilizing eggs in a laboratory dish, and steptoe adapted a technique known as laparoscopy, a way of seeing and operating inside the abdomen by inserting a tube with a fiber optic light
originally intended for women who were unable to conceive because of blocked fallopian tubes, in vitro fertilization has given rise to such procedures as embryo freezing, egg and sperm donation, embryo transfer and surrogate motherhood
steptoe, who was born on june 9, 1913, qualified as a doctor in 1939 and immediately went into world war ii service as a royal navy surgeon. he was a prisoner of war in italy from 1941 to 1943, and was discharged with the rank of surgeon lieutenant commander in 1946
he worked as an obstetrician in state hospitals, moving in 1951 to oldham, a northern england city where in the fall of 1967 he teamed up with edwards
in 1984, a furor erupted over allegations that they had experimented on embryos, although the scientists later insisted they had only observed embryos
the same year, the team proposed implanting embryos into animals to determine whether some conditions favorable to fertility exist in the animal's uterus but not in a woman's. the idea eventually was dropped
but steptoe said he and edwards never thought their work was in any way unethical. ``we are not creating life,'' he said. ``we have merely done what many people try to do in all kinds of medicine _ to help nature.''
steptoe said the greatest contribution of their work would likely be in early embryo research into genetic diseases
he is survived by his wife, sheena, and a son and daughter. funeral arrangements were incomplete
a car salesman didn't think he'd be stepping on any paws when he put a pair of seven-foot lion statues on the roof of his auto dealership and advertised ``the car institute.''
but a roar of sorts erupted from the art institute of chicago, which has lions guarding its entrance
i didn't think people would be confused,'' said joe levy jr., the car dealer, who said tuesday he had agreed to a compromise. ``i don't know how much of their traffic we've been getting. i think there's room for both of us.''
the art institute contended ads for the ``car institute'' violated a museum trademark
we agreed to discontinue the `car institute,''' levy said. ``but they've agreed to let us keep the lions'' on the building in evanston
robert mars, the art institute's vice president for administrative affairs, said the advertising was the real problem. to allow levy to capitalize on the institution's image might allow others to do the same, and in an offensive way, mars said
i think it maybe sends a signal out to people who all-too-frequently try to use images from our collection that aren't terribly appropriate,'' he said
mars said a mistake was made long ago when the museum did not protect its copyright of the painting ``american gothic'' by grant wood. ``now we can no longer say anything about how'' parodies use the stern-faces farm couple, mars said
levy said he got the call from the museum attorney about a month ago. last week he had his fiberglass lions painted the colors of nearby northwestern university ``to help clear up the confusion.'' one is now white, the other purple
we hope they don't object,'' he said
mars said the lions, even in purple and white, can stay
four palestinians who had sought political asylum in sweden were ordered expelled tuesday for undisclosed security reasons, a government official said
the order came after prime minister ingvar carlsson's government met in a special session to consider their appeal against a ruling by police and immigration authorities that they leave the country, said erik lempert, a senior official of the labor ministry
a fifth palestinian was granted a resident's visa for humanitarian reasons, despite objections by the national security police, lempert said
he said the government normally granted asylum to stateless palestinians arriving from lebanon since the 1982 israeli invasion of that country, but police objections ``weighed heavier'' in these cases
one of the four was married to a swedish woman expecting their child in april
lempert declined to specify the suspicions against the palestinians. lawyers representing them were ordered not to comment, but the attorneys were quoted by the national news agency tt as saying they would appeal. pvs, earlier on</note>
republican presidential hopeful bob dole campaigned in wisconsin on tuesday rather than return to washington for the senate override vote of president reagan's veto of civil rights legislation, saying ``i wasn't needed.''
dole indicated both opposition and support for reagan's veto of the civil rights bill in a confusing series of statements
on a radio call-in show, dole said he would vote to override the veto if he were in washington. but he added, ``if it were the deciding vote, i would side with the president.''
he later elaborated, saying the only reason he would vote to sustain reagan's veto would be to ``give (the white house) a chance to rework the bill.'' in a speech to milwaukee businessmen, dole said, ``that bill is not nearly as bad as advertised.''
in washington, his spokeswoman also issued a double-edged statement. dale tate said dole, republican leader in the senate, ``opposes the president on this issue'' and would like to reverse the supreme court ruling that prompted the legislation. but she said, ``if his vote were needed to sustain the veto, he would.''
in principle he opposes the president,'' she said
the democratic-controlled senate had more than enough votes to provide the two-thirds majority needed to override reagan's veto, with or without dole, who was campaigning in wisconsin in advance of the state's april 5 republican presidential primary
vice president george bush, the faraway front-runner for the gop nomination, announced on monday that he supported reagan's veto. ``i'm not going to start differing with the president after 7 1@2 years into the vice presidency,'' he said
dole was criticized by bush earlier in the campaign for failing to take a clear-cut position on key issues such as tax increases and arms control
and a variety of statements by dole and allies left a confused impression on the hotly debated civil rights bill
sen. alan simpson, the gop senate whip, said he had been authorized to say on the senate floor that ``were he (dole) present and voting, he would vote to sustain the president's veto.''
dole himself issued a statement for the record which did not say how he would vote
i have always supported legislation to overturn grove city to restore the broad civil rights coverage that existed prior to that case,'' he said
at the same time, i recognize that (the grove city bill) is not a perfect bill. i am not fully satisfied with it... but the fact remains that the administration and its congressional allies had the opportunity to offer amendments and they were voted down.''
the legislation stems from a 1984 supreme court ruling that says that an organization receiving federal aid must follow anti-discrimination rules only for the program that receives the aid, and not for the entire organization or institution
the legislation would erase that distinction and require that an entire organization follow the rules. dole was absent when the senate passed the bill in january. reagan vetoed the bill, saying it was too broad and infringed on the activities of religious groups, small buisnesses and others
civil rights groups have strongly suppored the bill and favor overriding reagan's veto.  total number of hemophilia cases to 615 sted 566.</note>
here are the latest statistics on acquired immune deficiency syndrome in the united states, as reported this week by the national centers for disease control:
total cases reported since june 1981: 57,024
cases, year to date: 6,670
total deaths: 31,836, or 56 percent of all cases
homosexual or bisexual males: 35,954, or 63 percent
intravenous drug abusers: 10,031, or 18 percent
homosexual male and drug abusers: 4,186, or 7 percent
heterosexual cases: 2,254, or 4 percent
transfusion or blood cases: 1,481, or 3 percent
hemophilia patients: 615, or 1 percent
undetermined transmission cause: 1,805, or 3 percent
childhood cases (under age 13): 908, or 2 percent
cases among whites: 33,966, or 60 percent
cases among blacks: 14,568, or 26 percent
cases among hispanics: 7,979, or 14 percent
cases among other: 511, or 1 percent

(note: these statistics are through march 21 and have been rounded by the cdc to the nearest whole percent. cumulative totals are for aids cases reported since june 1981, and include 75 cases subsequently found to have occurred prior to that date. the ``other'' classsification under age and race includes asians, american indians and native alaskans
the pentagon announced a series of high-level moves involving army generals on tuesday, saying the president had selected successors for two retiring officers
maj. gen. edwin s. leland jr. has been nominated by reagan for promotion to lieutenant general and assignment as chief of staff of the u.s. european command
assuming he is confirmed by the senate, leland, 48, will replace lt. gen. howard g. crowell jr., who is retiring. leland, a native of washington, d.c., now commands the 1st armored division, u.s. army europe
the president also nominated lt. gen. thurman d. rodgers for assignment as commander of the army information systems command, the pentagon continued. he would replace lt. gen. emmett paige jr., 57, has held the post since july 1984 and is retiring on aug. 1 after more than 40 years' service
rodgers, 53, a native of cookeville, tenn., now is director for information systems on the staff of the army secretary
maj. gen. bruce r. harris would be promoted to lieutenant general and to replace rodgers in the staff position. harris, 53, a native of sullivan county, ind., now commands the army signal center and signal school at fort gordon, ga
the soviet union on tuesday increased official pressure on armenia and azerbaijan to halt ethnic unrest that has left at least 32 people dead
the tass news agency said the presidium of the supreme soviet of the russian federation, the nation's largest republic, and equivalent bodies in the ukraine, byelorussia, georgia and uzbekistan called on the national parliament to take firm action to end the tension
the moves came amid increasingly negative coverage in the official press of armenian demands to annex the predominantly armenian nagorno-karabakh region, which is part of neighboring azerbaijan and the reported arrest of a leading armenian nationalist
tamara grigoryants, wife of armenian-born dissident sergei grigoryants, said in an interview that paryur arikyan was arrested tuesday evening by three policemen in central moscow after meeting with a western journalist
she said arikyan was accused of crossing the street illegally, and that he informed her of his arrest by calling from a pay telephone as the policemen stood by. arikyan said saturday he had traveled clandestinely to moscow after his passport was confiscated in armenia
the government newspaper izvestia on tuesday criticized armenian activists who it said gathered almost 4,000 people for a meeting in yerevan on march 19 to devise strategy to press their demands
on monday the communist party newspaper pravda charged the armenians' campaign has a ``clear anti-socialist spirit.''
ethnic rioting broke out in sumgait, a azerbaijani city, after armenians began protesting last month for annexation of nagorno-karabakh. officials say 32 people were killed, but armenian activists say the death toll was much higher and that most of the dead were armenians killed by azerbaijanis
the russian federation expressed ``concern and alarm'' over the ethnic unrest and asked the presidium of the national supreme soviet, the country's nominal parliament, to ``adopt resolute measures aimed at ... uniting in all ways the soviet peoples.''
the soviet constitution says little about the rights of autonomous regions such as nagorno-karabakh, but says the territory of a republic such as azerbaijan or armenia may not be changed without its consent. that means azerbaijan would have to approve the annexation of nagorno-karabakh to armenia
under soviet law, each of the country's 15 republics is ostensibly sovereign. but the appeals from the five soviet republics about nagorno-karabakh seemed designed to serve as a reason for the national government in moscow to act on the simmering territorial dispute
the policy-making central committee of the communist party rejected the demand for annexation on feb. 20, but soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev promised on feb. 26 that the issue would be considered when the central committee holds another meeting to discuss national disputes
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov told a regular news briefing that protests continued in armenia on sunday and monday. a nationalist source said armenians would gather again in their capital of yerevan on saturday to decide whether to call a general strike
gerasimov said the situation in azerbaijan and armenia still is too tense to allow foreign journalists to travel there
a curfew is still in effect in sumgait, although the situation there is regarded as absolutely normal,'' gerasimov said. ``in armenia i wouldn't call it normal because there are demonstrations going on and that's not normal.''
arikyan told the associated press on monday that 7,000 people had gathered in yerevan to protest the pravda article published earlier that day criticizing the movement to annex nagorno-karabakh
at a tuesday news conference in moscow before his reported arrest, arikyan, 38, a former political prisoner, read what he said was the text of a telegram from armenian journalist y. arakyelan to pravda editor viktor g. afanasyev
according to arikyan, the correspondent said the article was an ``editor's article expressing the will of the communist party central committee,'' rather than the views of those whose names were attached to it
arikyan, chairman of an armenian nationalist group called alliance for national determination, said the pravda article was an indication that authorities will not agree to unite nagorno-karabakh with armenia, despite appeals from local communist party and government officials
arikyan once headed an underground armenian nationalist group called the national unification party, and was jailed for 17 years beginning in 1969 for his political activities
he said armenian activists in yerevan claim 78 people were killed in sumgait. but, he said, ``i think a worse tragedy than sumgait awaits us.''
communist china's chief representative in hong kong was quoted tuesday as praising modern capitalism as a ``great creation of human civilization.''
xu jiatun's comments appeared in the pro-beijing wen wei po newspaper, which ran the text of an interview he gave with a chinese magazine, and appeared aimed at boosting confidence in hong kong after 1997, when china takes over the capitalist territory
we have some comrades who always fear capitalism, but in fact they don't understand that the modern capitalist system is a great creation of human civilization,'' said xu, who as head of the xinhua news agency branch is china's chief representative in hong kong
the xinhua official was quoted as saying china ``should systematically absorb the beneficial experience and knowledge from modern capitalism,'' which he praised for guaranteeing an enivronment of free competition, allowing production forces to develop, and creating a good legal system
in the past, we believed capitalism would quickly die out,'' xu was quoted as saying. ``looking from today's perspective, modern capitalism has a lot of room to develop.''
china's communist party last year reaffirmed its commitment to opening up the country and pushing market-oriented reforms to stimulate the economy
xu's comments not only indicated strong support for reform but also appeared designed to allay fears about what will happen to this bastion of capitalism after china takes over in 1997
much of hong kong's well-educated middle class are seeking to move overseas before the territory reverts to chinese rule, even though beijing has promised the territory can retain its capitalist economic system and enjoy ``a high degree of autonomy.''
but many of hong kong's 5.7 million people are refugees from political campaigns in communist china and remain pessimistic. xu acknowledged they have ``a kind of distrust of the communist party, which is completely understandable.''
he said residents will be allowed to criticize the communist party and socialism after 1997, but will be asked to ``love china and love hong kong.''
this is what we call `one country, two systems,''' xu was quoted as saying. ``this will benefit china's cooperation with every circle of people in hong kong, especially the middle class.''
the house voted 401-1 tuesday to continue and expand a program to encourage private companies to develop drugs for combatting rare diseases
the bill, which was sent to the senate, extends the so-called ``orphan drug'' program through fiscal 1990. it would also expand the program, which is overseen by the food and drug administration, to include special devices and foods needed to help people with unusual maladies
under the program, companies are given tax credits and seven-year exclusive marketing rights if they develop products for rare diseases. without incentives, the companies would not pursue development of those products because the small number of beneficiaries would not make it profitable, according to supporters of the legislation
the revised statute, while expanding the program, would triple its cost in the next few years. the current annual authorization of $4 million would grow to $14 million in fiscal 1990
the reagan administration has said it has no objection to the legislation
rep. henry waxman, d-calif., chairman of the health subcommittee of the house committee on energy and commerce, had also sought to include a provision to limit profits on orphan drugs. however, the restrictions were opposed by the pharmaceutical industry and waxman dropped them rather than face possible stalling tactics when the bill reached the senate
the only dissenting vote was cast by rep. philip crane, r-ill
a court on tuesday fined toshiba machine co. $15,750 for illegally selling sensitive technology to the soviet union, and ordered suspended sentences for two former toshiba machine executives
tokyo district court judge toshio yonezawa found that toshiba machine's actions ``seriously damaged the economic activities, foreign relations and trade policies of our nation, which is trying to protect free trade and international cooperation.''
between 1982 and 1984, toshiba machine, a subsidiary of toshiba corp., japan's second-largest electronics maker, sold $17 million in sophisticated milling machines to the soviet union, part of them allegedly through norway's state-owned kongsberg vaapenfabrikk. u.s. officials alleged the machines helped moscow build propellers that make submarines quieter and harder to detect
since the statute of limitations on that action had expired, however, the current case involved charges that parts and software were sold later in violation of foreign trade and exchange laws based on the regulations of the western allies' coordinating committee for exports to communist nations
the defense argued that the machine parts and software could have been produced by the soviet union and there had been no violation worthy of serious legal consideration
but yonezawa said, ``the violation cannot be dismissed as trivial, since it involved misleading explanations made by toshiba machine officials to the ministry of international trade and industry and the destruction of related papers after the incident was uncovered.''
yonezawa added that toshiba machine's actions ``fed distrust of the japanese government and industry in the united states.''
he held that the sale occurred ``with the approval of the company's president and under the direction of the corporation's top executives.''
hiroaki tanimura, former deputy senior project manager of the company's first engineering department, was sentenced to one year in prison, with the sentenced suspended for three years
ryuzo hayashi, a former manager in toshiba machine's material supply division, was sentenced to 10 months in prison, also suspended for three years
following the decision, joichi aoi, president of toshiba corp., told reporters, ``the toshiba group has been taking the utmost efforts to assure that no such incident will recur, and there will be no change in this policy in the future.''
earlier, in the milling machine case, the japanese government banned toshiba machine from exporting to any communist nations for one year
a bill authorizing $3.5 million in transitional expenses for president reagan's successor and $1 million for reagan to move to retirement in california next january was approved tuesday by the house government operations committee
the democratic-controlled committee rejected a republican move to increase the expense allowance for the outgoing president to $1.5 million from $1 million, the level in effect since 1976, to offset the effects of inflation
the proposed boost was opposed by rep. jack brooks, d-texas, the panel's chairman, who said the budget squeeze requires congress to ``make some hard choices'' on spending cuts
the panel approved raising the president-elect's allowance for transitional expenses to $3.5 million from $2 million, the level in effect for the past 12 years. it also rejected, 24-9, a move by rep. robert s. walker, r-pa., to forbid the president-elect from accepting private donations to supplement federal transitional funds
the $1 million for reagan's initial retirement expenses, if approved by the house and senate, would cover his moving expenses from the white house to california and the costs of establishing an office for six months, until funds for former presidents become available under a separate law
the military services had no problem meeting their recruiting goals last last year, but there were ``some adverse signs'' for the future in lower re-enlistment results, the pentagon said tuesday
releasing its latest quarterly report, the defense department said the army, navy, air force and marine corps signed up 66,300 recruits during the first quarter of fiscal 1988, which ended dec. 31
that compares with a combined goal of 65,400, and all four services met or exceeded their individual quarterly objectives, the pentagon said
moreover, the percentage of first-time enlistees with a high school diploma actually increased slightly _ from 92 percent during the period in fiscal 1987 to 93 percent in fiscal 1988
retention (re-enlistment) results for the first quarter of fiscal 1988 were also satisfactory, but with some adverse signs,'' grant s. green jr., assistant defense secretary for manpower, said in a statement
first-term re-enlistment rates trailed comparable fiscal 1987 statistics for three of the four services. and while overall career retention rates showed some improvement over fiscal 1987, retention among second-term and career navy petty officers continued to decline after falling short of objectives last year.''
the pentagon pays particular attention to the percentage of men and women willing to re-enlist after completing their initial obligation, viewing it as a measure not only of military readiness and experience in the force but also job satisfaction
according to the latest report, 46 percent of military personnel eligible to re-enlist for the first time during the period did so _ down from 49 percent during the comparable period in fiscal 1987
some of the individual service declines, however, were much more precipitous. for example, the air force's first term re-enlistment rate dropped from 74 percent to 62 percent over the year
the marine corps' rate dropped from 24 percent to 18 percent, and the navy's rate fell from 56 percent to 51 percent. the army managed to buck the trend with a small increase, from 40 percent in fiscal 1987 to 43 percent this fiscal year
green noted that various re-enlistment bonus programs had been suspended for 65 days during the period awaiting congressional action
but most retention measures have fallen several percentage points below their 1983-84 peaks, and this trend has been particularly noticeable among personnel in higher-technology skills that are in particular demand in the private sector,'' he added
meanwhile, dan howard, the pentagon's chief spokesman, restated the administration's strong opposition to a cut in the 4.3 percent pay raise proposed for military personnel in fiscal 1989, which begins oct. 1
the 4.3 percent hike exceeds the 2 percent proposed for civilian government workers and some congressional leaders are now arguing military and civilian workers should be treated the same
the comparability studies ... show an 11 percent gap between military and civilian pay,'' howard said. ``the 4.3 percent pay raise is fully justified unless we want to return to the situation that we saw in the past where the disparity was so great that good people couldn't afford to stay in the military.'' suggests^ ^eds: subs 2nd graf bgng ``the trends'' to explain why woodchucks used in study.</head>
extracts of a tropical plant appeared to reduce levels of hepatitis virus and liver cancer rates in woodchucks, a hopeful sign for the world's 200 million human virus-carriers at risk for the cancer, a scientist said tuesday
the trends emerged in analysis of data on about 60 animals that had become infected with the woodchuck version of the hepatitis b virus, said baruch blumberg of the fox chase cancer center in philadelphia. woodchucks are used in hepatitis research because the virus they carry so closely resembles the human hepatitis b virus
blumberg stressed that the results are only suggestive, and a prelude to a formal study of the plant extract's effects
even if it doesn't get rid of the virus altogether, it may still be useful,'' he said after speaking to science writers at a seminar sponsored by the american cancer society
that is because the virus now can lie dormant for decades after infection, and if the extract can extend that period, it may essentially block the progression to liver cancer until after a person has died of something else, he said
infection with hepatitis virus b has long been linked to later development of cancer originating in the liver, as opposed to cancer that starts elsewhere in the body and spreads to the liver
studies in taiwan have found that male carriers of the virus run more than 200 times the risk of developing liver cancer than non-carriers, giving them a 40 percent chance of dying from the disease, blumberg said
the cancer is particularly common in asia and sub-saharan africa, he said. in the united states, the cancer society expects about 6,000 new cancers of the liver this year
the best way to deal with the problem is vaccination at birth for people at risk of the disease, blumberg said. such a vaccine is not recommended for the american population generally because the overall risk is so low, he said
china and taiwan have programs for vaccinating newborn children, he said. his institution has established a vaccine program in philadelphia directed at newborn children of carrier mothers and others in their household. he said he hopes other such programs will be established
but the world already has about 200 million carriers of the virus, and more will be added every day until vaccination programs become fully effective, he said
the plant, called phyllanthus ammarus, grows in india and throughout the tropical world, blumberg said. it can be grown in the united states, he said
the extract of the plant appears to fight the virus by blocking a substance called dna polymerase that the virus needs to reproduce itself, he said
when the extract was injected into the bellies of woodchucks infected for a month, evidence of the virus disappeared, he said. those infected longer showed decreases in the amount of virus in their blood
treated animals also developed significantly fewer liver cancers than others, blumberg said
limited studies in animals suggest the extract does not cause significant side effects, he said. scientists are trying to isolate the portion of the extract that fights the virus, he said
raymond koff, a liver disease specialist and professor of medicine at boston university, said the work should be followed up with more study. ``innovative, exciting stuff has to be looked at,'' he said in a telephone interview
a gas distribution company has warned customers nationwide that cylinders of silane gas may have been contaminated the same way as one that exploded, killing three people, officials said tuesday
liquid carbonic industries corp. of chicago issued the warning monday that the cylinders of silane may have been contaminated with an unstable oxidizer, said dewey erzinger, the company's director of public relations
erzinger said he could not estimate the number liquid carbonic customers across the country, but said most are in the electronics industry. the company manufactures industrial and medical gases, such as silane, which is widely used to coat silicon wafers
erzinger said company officials are investigating the origin of the cylinder that exploded thursday at the gollob analytical services plant, killing three people and seriously injuring a fourth
the state department of environmental protection has tentatively traced the cylinder _ believed to contain a volatile mixture of nitrous oxide and silane _ through three states before it reached berkeley heights
the exact cause of the blast remains unknown, say officials with the dep and liquid carbonics
in its note to its customers, liquid carbonic said the explosion may have been caused by some kind of oxidizer being drawn back into the cylinder
if your process utilizes silane gas product in conjunction with oxidizers, such as nitrous oxide or oxygen, you are urged to make certain that oxidizers cannot be drawn back into your silane gas container,'' the notice said
meanwhile tuesday, liquid carbonic completed removal of 300 cylinders of silane from its harrison plant, erzinger said. he said the company may conduct similar removals at other plants around the country
on monday, nearly 1,000 workers were held off their jobs on the san francisco peninsula after canisters containing potentially explosive chemicals were discovered at semiconductor facilities there
chemical inspectors eventually concluded that the four canisters at advanced micro devices inc. in santa clara and teledyne semiconductor in mountain view were harmless
a similar precautionary evacuation took place sunday in pocatello, idaho, when officials of the gould inc.'s semiconductor plant examined silane cylinders belonging to liquid carbonic
one of the men killed in thursday's blast, dennis feeney, was a regional manager for liquid carbonic at the company's harrison facility. the two others killed were gollob employees
a liquid carbonic deliveryman, james diemer, lost a leg and suffered shrapnel wounds. he was in fair condition tuesday in the plastic surgery ward of bellevue hospital center in manhattan
sen. albert gore jr. got the meeting he'd sought with new york gov. mario cuomo on monday, but he got no endorsement for his presidential bid despite complimentary words from the governor
he's very bright,'' cuomo said of gore. ``he's very deep in his knowledge of government. ... he has a particular kind of appeal that's especially attractive to the democratic party at this moment.''
but cuomo said he and lt. gov. stan lundine are not ready to publicly back a candidate. he said of gore, ``it was nice of him to come by.'' but he added that during their private meeting at the state capitol, ``sen. gore said nothing that i haven't heard him say before.''
gore had tried to arrange a meeting with cuomo early last month in albany but couldn't. cuomo said gore had asked to stop at the capitol again monday as part of a campaign trip through new york in advance of the state's april 19 primary. gore also campaigned in connecticut monday
of course, i asked for his support and we talked about his desire to play the most constructive role possible in helping the country and helping the democratic party win a victory in november,'' gore said. the tennessee senator said they also discussed problems new york and other states are wrestling with such as housing, the homeless and aids
gore rose to third place in the battle for nominating delegates by winning five southern states in the super tuesday primaries on march 8
cuomo said the democratic race between front-runners michael dukakis, jesse jackson and gore has created a ``confused picture politically.''
we're _ stan lundine and i _ now accelerating the process of trying to determine how best to be useful to the democratic party,'' cuomo said. ``maybe we'll go beyond that and endorse somebody. we'll know within a couple of weeks.''
the fact that cuomo has yet to endorse any democratic candidate, coupled with his refusal to rule out accepting a draft for the nomination if there should be a deadlocked national convention, has kept alive the speculation that he might be angling for the nomination. howver, cuomo says he is not a candidate for president this year
later gore, in a quick swing through connecticut, predicted he would do well in the state's democratic presidential primary next tuesday despite massachusetts gov. michael dukakis' strong regional appeal here
i'm extremely optimistic that we're going to do very well here, in spite of the fact that it's in the backyard of one of my opponents,'' gore said during a brief stop at an office building construction site outside of hartford
we're going to surprise some people here,'' gore said
gore expressed hope that connecticut gov. william a. o'neill would make an endorsement soon, rather than remaining uncommitted until the democratic convention in atlanta in july
i'd love to have the governor's endorsement and i've asked him for his support,'' gore said. ``but i certainly understand why he wants to take a close look at the race and think about it some more.''
gore praised o'neill lavishly, calling him ``a tremendous leader'' who's done ``an outstanding job as governor.''
president reagan refused monday to discuss a possible pardon for former white house aide oliver north, and a presidential spokesman said north's lawyer had not contacted the administration about the matter
in response to a reporter's question at the end of a ceremony to sign an afghanistan day proclamation, reagan replied, ``not going to discuss that now.''
separately, presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater repeated the administration's oft-stated position that ``there's been no discussions of pardons.''
he also said that the administration has not been contacted by north's attorney, brendan sullivan, who has been saying publicly that testimony may be sought from the highest officials of government
the president will cooperate but we'll just have to wait and see what the format takes,'' fitzwater said
north was indicted last week by a federal grand jury on charges he conspired to divert iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels
earlier sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, said reagan should pardon north. he said north had been guilty of misleading congress but did not intend to break the law
i continually ask the question, where's the venality, where's the corruption, where's the criminal intent?'' hatch said on ``cbs this morning.'' ``i don't think anybody who watched oliver north believes that he intended to break the law or that he intended to be a criminal.''
asked if north had misled congress, hatch said, ``that's true. but keep in mind oliver north saw his buddies get killed in lebanon. he found the terrorists who had killed them through leaks. ... he was the fellow who helped plan the the grenada invasion. he was the fellow who captured the achille lauro terrorists through leaks.''
you go on right down the line. ... i think that he was a hero then, he's a hero today and i think we ought to get this behind us and i think a pardon would be the appropriate way to do that,'' hatch said
however, rep. thomas s. foley, d-wash., who also served on the committees that investigated the iran-contra affair, said the courts should decide the guilt or innocence of north and former national security adviser john m. poindexter, who also was indicted
for the president to pre-emptively pardon them in advance i think would send a terrible signal to the country about the even-handedness and objectivity of our legal system. remember they are all assumed innocent,'' foley said on the cbs program. says</head>
federal parole officials recommended tuesday that an anti-castro militant convicted of conspiring to bomb foreign freighters should be released after serving a three-month prison sentence for violating parole, his lawyer said
the suggested sentence, which includes time orlando bosch has spent in jail since returning to the united states, must be approved by the u.s. parole commission. the panel is expected to decide within three weeks
parole examiners made the recommendation recommended after a closed hearing tuesday, bosch's attorney, george yoss said
bosch, 61, convicted of conspiring to bomb foreign freighters and of firing a recoilless rifle in 1968 at a polish freighter docked in miami, served four years of a 10-year federal prison sentence
he has acknowledged violating his parole when he traveled to south america in 1974. he served 11 years in venezuelan jails until his acquittal on charges of bombing a cuban jetliner in which 73 died in 1976
but after serving his three-month sentence by may 16, bosch probably will be taken into custody by the u.s. immigration and naturalization service, said yoss. the ins has targeted bosch for possible deportation
bosch entered the united states illegally last month after his release from a venezuelan prison. since mid-february, he has been detained at the metropolitan correctional center in south dade
several prominent cuban-americans, including jorge mas canosa, head of the cuban american national foundation, testified before the parole examiners in a hearing closed to the public because it was an administrative procedure
mas canosa said after the hearing that bosch should be released because he had learned his lesson and now would work peacefully for the overthrow of cuban president fidel castro
it is a crime to keep this man behind bars,'' mas canosa said
dr. alberto hernandez, bosch's physician, said he testified that bosch suffered from stomach, heart and prostate problems. bosch's illnesses would be aggravated by a prison sentence, he said
ted kline, who prosecuted bosch in 1974, said he testified that bosch could be released safely
tom kowalski, the parole commission's atlanta regional administrator, said the decision would be forwarded to regional commissioner george mckenzie rast, who will make a recommendation to the full, four-member parole commission in washington
two men have been given a chance to avoid federal prison terms for their role in a racially motivated fight that resulted in the death of a mexican-american farm worker five years ago
walter pringle, 35, who faced a maximum 15-year federal prison term, was sentenced monday to 33 months in prison and assessed $4,450 in fines, costs and restitution. federal judge g. kendall sharp said pringle would not have to go to prison if he can pay the money by sept. 1
pringle was found guilty in january of violating the civil rights of joseph ozuna, 26, by beating him unconscious near seville, a town of about 650 residents 60 miles north of here
sharp also sentenced mark miller, 25, to 12 months in prison. sharp said he would suspend that sentence if miller could pay $1,500 in fines and restitution by sept. 1. miller had pleaded guilty to conspiracy and testified for the government in the january trial
both he and miller said later they would raise the money for the fines and stay out of prison
a federal jury acquitted pringle's ex-girlfriend, paula hires smith, 29, of violating the civil rights of gilberto garza, 17, by shooting him to death in the same fight
the 1983 case triggered controversy when pringle received a six-month jail sentence, a $15 fine and five years probation after pleading no contest to aggravated assault and battery, and ms. smith was given 10 years probation for her no-contest plea to manslaughter
outrage over what were considered to be light sentences in the state circuit court criminal case led to a federal investigation and the january trial on civil rights charges in u.s. district court in orlando
according to the federal indictment and information from miller, pringle and ms. smith pursued cousins ozuna and garza into the countryside. while pringle was beating up ozuna, ms. smith shot garza in the face with a rifle
i have been handing down sentences for 10 years, and i think without doubt this is the most difficult case i ever had in terms of meting out a sentence,'' sharp told pringle
but, the judge said, ``i am convinced that you will never do anything like this again.''
pringle had contended that drinking got him into fights, and the judge agreed, adding that only pringle knows whether he is really prejudiced against mexican-americans
three children and their mother died tuesday morning when the children set fire to their house while playing with matches, authorities said
the deaths follow a rash of similar fires here in recent months
kevin reardon, who heads a program aimed at preventing children from starting fires, said 11 children have been killed in the last four months in fires they started
fire battalion chief david zwayer identified the victims of tuesday's fire as patty compton, 36, and three of her children: joshua, 1, jennifer, 4, and cassandra, 5. all were dead at the scene, officials said
a fourth child, tanya compton, 7, and a woman identified as a family friend, dorleen wilson, 32, escaped the fire, zwayer said
police said the children were lighting matches and set fire to a couch. according to witnesses, ms. compton went outside, but returned to the house in an attempt to save her children
you (could) hear them crying and calling for their mom, and then their mom went into the house,'' said witness lakisha glasco, 12
on sunday, four children ages 10 and younger were killed when fire struck their home. a fifth child survived and was in poor condition tuesday in children's hospital
fire officials said they believe that fire also was caused by a child playing with matches
more coast guard installations would be forced to close next year if congress fails to increase the agency's budget by $300 million, the head of the coast guard said tuesday
these are not intended as threats or scare stories; these are the real choices that we face,'' adm. paul a. yost jr., commandant of the coast guard, told a house subcommittee
yost said the reagan administration's proposed fiscal 1989 funding level of $2.98 billion would not enable the coast guard to reopen any of the nearly 30 stations and offices closed in february because of a $103 million shortfall in the current budget
but yost said the administration's proposal would allow the remaining stations to stay open. in addition, it would restore to full levels drug patrols, which were reduced by 55 percent last month, and routine search and rescue patrols, which were eliminated
if congress approved a budget with only modest increases from 1988, the agency would have a $171 million shortfall next year that would trigger a more serious round of station closings, yost said
i can't even come up with a list of coast guard (facilities) that could be closed,'' he said
rep. earl hutto, d-fla., chairman of the house merchant marine and fisheries subcommittee on the coast guard and navigation, embraced the administration's budget proposal as ``the minimum necessary for the coast guard to continue to function in the manner expected of it by the congress and the american public.''
hutto and yost said while the 1989 budget request is a big jump from current spending levels, it really would just be bringing the coast guard up to past levels
when adjusted for inflation, the budget request for the next fiscal year is about the same as the 1983 spending levels. however, the coast guard since has increased its drug interdiction activities substantially
the congressional general accounting office found that from 1980 to 1987, the proportion of coast guard operating expenses devoted to drug operations more than tripled _ from 7 percent to 22 percent
meanwhile, the percentage devoted to more traditional coast guard duties, such as search and rescue patrols and marine safety, has been sliced from 60 percent to 51 percent, the gao said
last week, yost unveiled an administration plan to transer $60 million from other transportation department accounts to the coast guard to immediately upgrade patrol levels to last year's levels
foreigners would be barred from working as crew members aboard u.s. aircraft and ships during strikes against the carriers, under legislation approved, 302-114, by the house on tuesday
the restrictions would apply only to american-owned planes or ships that are entering or leaving the united states
supporters of the legislation said the measure would protect the rights of striking american workers by preventing companies from hiring foreigners to replace them
aliens should not be allowed to hurt american employees by working in their jobs as strike-breakers,'' said rep. marge roukema, r-n.j., the measure's sponsor
opponents said the bill would hurt carriers by forcing them to release foreign employees in the event of a labor walkout, and would invite retaliation by other countries
it is easy to be against foreign nationals,'' said rep. steve bartlett, r-texas
the legislation was written in response to a 1986 strike against trans world airlines inc. by its flight attendants in which the workers accused twa of using foreigners to serve on trans-atlantic flights
the bill was sent to the senate
newly issued guidelines for dealing with federal employees infected with the aids virus are in line with the general anti-discrimination recommendations of the government's health department
we worked very closely with the office of personnel managment in developing them,'' dr. robert windom said tuesday. ``the regulations are reasonable and reflect phs concerns.''
windom, no. 2 official of the department of health and human services, heads the seven-agency public health service that includes the centers for disease control, food and drug administration and national institutes of health
windom will review the guidelines thursday with personnel officers from about 30 major federal agencies
the federal government, as an enlightened and compassionate employer concerned with the health and welfare of its employees, has an obligation to show the way in addressing the realities of the aids epidemic,'' constance horner, director of the office of personnel management, said in a memo accompanying the guidelines' initial distribution this week
quoting from cdc statements on aids in the workplace, the personnel office memo says, ``the kind of nonsexual person-to-person contact that generally occurs among workers and clients or consumers in the workplace does not pose a risk for transmission of aids.''
the guidelines instruct federal agencies to treat aids-infected employees ``in the same manner as employees who suffer from other serious illnesses'' and say there is ``no medical basis for employees refusing to work with such fellow employees or agency clients
fellow employes who disrupt agency functions by refusing to work with an aids-infected person could be subject to ``appropriate corrective or disciplinary action'' under the guidelines
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections
for a few fleeting weeks, free enterprise thrived in brooklyn
that was back in the good old days, about two months ago, when a thrifty commuter entering the greenpoint avenue subway station in the morning could buy a $1 subway ride for 50 cents
the bargain was offered by three crafty entrepreneurs, who discovered the key to a padlocked gate next to a turnstile. they unlocked the gate, put the padlock on the turnstile and went into competition with the new york city transit authority
from about 5 a.m. to 7 a.m. weekdays, the subway station was turned into a bargain basement, according to an account in tuesday's new york newsday
and then the police found out
as of 2-15 fare for rider will be 55 cents per person,'' read a flyer handed to riders shortly after the police crackdown. ``and no pennies will not be accepted no more. ... people we had run in with transit police so that why we raise it. we couldn't afford of getting busted.''
the flyer ended on a promotional note: ``catch that fare special.''
it became amusing,'' observed transit police sgt. tom sullivan, still slightly astonished by this flowering of the entrepreneurial spirit. ``because we arrested them, they increased the fare.''
the police had been notified by an irate token clerk, who arrived with a uniformed police officer each morning at 7 a.m. to find her competitors fully engaged in business
the token booth was staffed only at rush hour. the rest of the day, patrons without tokens had to go to the main station entrance two blocks away; those with tokens could go through the cage-like turnstile _ until the discounters arrived
at first, the men scattered when the token clerk arrived. but after a while, sullivan said, ``they were being so brazen that they would just retreat to the stairwell and wait for the uniformed cop to leave.''
then they'd return to business, in full sight of the token clerk, whose business dwindled. about 100 riders a day were taking advantage of the reduced fare, plunking their money into a bucket beside the swinging gate
this really infuriated the railroad clerk,'' said sullivan
her complaints eventually led to undercover operations that resulted in the first arrests on jan. 29. and the second arrests on feb. 1. each time, the men were issued desk appearance tickets and released. and each time, they went right back to work
on feb. 16, the police raised the stakes against paul franklin, 35, kenneth norris, 36, and willie brown, 22. this time they went to jail on charges including disorderly conduct, petty larceny, criminal tampering and other crimes
so far, franklin, who, like brown, lived in an apartment near the station, has pleaded guilty to disorderly conduct and served eight days in jail. norris, who lived in a homeless shelter, has pleaded guilty to petty larceny and been sentenced to 70 hours of community service _ including washing subway stations
even as we made the arrests, we had one guy in handcuffs and people were still walking up to him and trying to hand him money,'' sullivan said. ``they were pretty slick in their operation. they thought they had all ends covered.'' differences</head>
commerce secretary c. william verity opened a new round of japanese trade negotiations on tuesday with an appeal for fast resolution of the differences separating the two sides
the negotiations involve u.s. demands that japan allow american and other foreign construction companies to compete for an estimated $60 billion in public works projects planned in japan over the next decade
verity announced that the american team would be headed by deputy u.s. trade representative michael b. smith, who is taking over from j. michael farren, a deputy commerce undersecretary who is leaving the department because he was passed over for promotion
i trust that everyone in this room shares my feeling that these negotiations on construction have gone on for too long already and that the time has come to bring them to a close,'' verity said in opening remarks
last week, president reagan's cabinet-level economic policy council set a two-week deadline for resolving the construction dispute. if the issue is not settled by the deadline, administration officials have indicated they will recommend that the president bring a trade complaint against japan, a process which could lead to u.s. trade retaliation against japan
the japanese have offered to allow u.s. companies access to seven public works projects. u.s. negotiators have contended in the past that this offer was too small and omitted sophisticated engineering jobs
but verity, in his remarks, indicated a willingness to consider the japanese proposal as a starting point
the japanese side has suggested that contracts worth $30 billion in seven major projects could be opened to bidding by our firms,'' he said. ``very well, then, we simply ask that you open them, and that, over time, you add additional projects until the japanese construction market is open.''
verity called on the japanese to open up ``the broadest spectrum of contract work'' to u.s. bidding
earthmoving and runway construction are not enough,'' he said
democrat richard gephardt charged tuesday that michael dukakis' support for tough trade legislation is just ``a political ploy'' that will end after the michigan caucuses are over
dukakis, the massachusetts governor, said his position on trade has been consistent, and his staff released quotations from last year indicating his support for major provisions of a senate trade bill
who is for a tough trade policy? who is going to be for a tough trade policy after michigan?'' gephardt asked in a telephone interview tuesday. ``the answer is, dick gephardt is and will be. mike dukakis hasn't been, isn't and won't be.''
when he is on the east and west coast, he wants to talk about free trade. when he's in michigan, he doesn't,'' gephardt said
gephardt's tough trade legislation, now in a conference committee on capitol hill, has been the capstone of the missouri congressman's platform
monday night, dukakis endorsed trade legislation sponsored by michigan sen. donald riegle, who in turn endorsed dukakis. gephardt quickly accused dukakis of having a ``battlefield conversion'' on trade, saying the riegle bill was the senate version of the gephardt legislation
dukakis and jesse jackson are tied for the lead in the polls on saturday's michigan caucuses, with gephardt a distant third. dukakis aides say that may be the reason for gephardt's attacks
on tuesday, gephardt stepped up the attack, questioning the sincerity of dukakis' support for such legislation
i think he remains against it. i think it is a political ploy,'' gephardt said. ``by what he has done, he is trying to have it both ways. ... now that he is in michigan and we are five days out from the caucuses, he wants to fool the people of michigan.''
dukakis said in michigan late monday that his position hasn't changed
he has been a strong opponent of the gephardt bill from the begining, but has always been an advocate of leveling the (trade) playing field,'' said dukakis spokesman leslie dach
dukakis' staff on tuesday pointed to quotes from the massachusetts governor last year in favor of the senate bill
on july 11, 1987, dukakis said, ``i think the trade bill which the senate approved yesterday says if there is a consistent pattern of unfair trade practices ... there i think we have to do something.''
i feel a lot better about the senate bill'' than the gephardt trade legislation, dukakis said on aug. 4, 1987
gephardt said dukakis ``has said in the past you don't need new legislation. ... he has been profoundly negative about everything i have said about trade.''
the congressman, too, provided quotes from dukakis last year _ quotes he said back up his charge of a flip-flop
the president today has all the authority he needs to do something about those unfair trade practices. we do not need more laws or more amendments,'' dukakis said at the aug. 8 debate at drake university, according to gephardt aides
in debates in dallas and atlanta, dukakis told gephardt, ``you want a law. dick, i want to act.''
and earlier this year in lansing, mich., gephardt aides said, dukakis said ``we do not need more legislation.''
the gephardt amemdment and the riegle bill do differ, but both try to strengthen potential retaliation against u.s. trading partners for unfair practices. in general, the riegle bill would target specific industries in foreign countries which engage in unfair practices. the gephardt amendment would trigger retaliation against another country for running a big surplus with this country in part through unfair practices
dukakis has always felt the president has had the authority to act. the riegle amendment ... gives the president a better way to get there, but he can pretty much get there on his own now,'' dukakis spokesman dach said
thousands of poor people are lining up for help at churches and soup kitchens as the country sinks deeper into political and economic crisis
it is a good thing people have such a good heart at times like this,'' israel gonzalez said monday as he cooked a big pot of rice over an open fire outside san jose church in san miguelito, a poor neighborhood on the outskirts of town
the poor have been hit hardest by a campaign to oust strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega that has crippled businesses, closed banks and dried up the supply of cash. noriega is chief of panama's 15,000-member defense forces and the power behind the civilian government
while a general strike paralyzed panama city on monday, scores of volunteers like gonzalez were working at soup kitchens run by caritas, a roman catholic community organization
the rev. francisco verar said his parish at san jose church is a made up ``mostly of people who are underemployed.''
they include ``women who wash and iron or work as maids and now cannot find a job, construction workers who have not worked since the crisis started or laborers who work in whatever they can find,'' he said
although food and money are scarce for almost everyone, help has been streaming in, the rev. laureano duran, director of caritas, said as he watched dozens of volunteers pick up bags of donated food
we have to help those who are worse off than we are,'' said a housewife who brought a sack of groceries
duran said caritas believes more than 6,000 families in the archdiocese are without money or food
gonzalez, the owner of a small neighborhood grocery store, said he has been cooking broth for several days for the thousands of people who have lined up at the san jose soup kitchen
my wife and i are working here now every day,'' he said. ``no one is buying anything anyway, so i am not needed at the store.''
as gonzalez cooked, wiping the sweat off his forehead, cirila flores and her six children waited for a hot meal
i live alone but i have always managed to get food for my children washing clothes and ironing,'' she said. ``now there are no jobs because no one has money. i have never been through a situation like this before.''
verar said the san jose kitchen has been feeding chicken and rice and vitamins to the needy
we are cooking at least 300 pounds of rice every day,'' he said. ``we think we will have some beans and lentil soup tomorrow.''
san jose also has a malnutrition clinic staffed by volunteer doctors and nurses
they starve to give food to their children,'' dr. carlos lizarraga said, pointing to a woman he said had not eaten since friday so she could feed her six children
my husband works in construction and he has not been paid,'' explained alicia flores, 26. ``i do not work and we are about to go out on the street and beg. it's all noriega's fault. we don't even have bananas to eat.''
the city council has approved an ordinance requiring guests checking into the city's 11 hotels and motels to show identification
the measure was proposed in january following the discovery of the bodies of two women in different hotel rooms. the deaths, one attributed to strangulation and the other to drowning, were not related, authorities said
mayor francis x. flaherty was expected to sign the ordinance in a couple of days, said mayoral spokeswoman anne turner. it would go into effect 20 days later, she said
councilman lincoln d. chafee, the only one of the seven council members to vote against the ordinance monday night, called the measure ``loose and vague'' and cautioned the council against ``stampeding to enact a bad bill.''
the ordinance was amended to say that information from a hotel registrant will be used only for emergencies or during criminal investigations. the american civil liberties union had complained that the original version violated the rights of individuals
the guest who pays for a hotel room would be required to show a driver's license, major credit card, state identification card, military identification card, passport, vehicle registration or vehicle title documents
councilman c. kenneth wild jr., who proposed the ordinance in january, said it would help police investigate cases such as those of the two women. identification would not be required of people other than the person signing for the room
neither woman had paid for the room where she was found dead. in the drowning, two people were charged with leaving the scene of a death, but no one has been arrested in the strangulation, police said
u.s. troops sent here for emergency training exercises will stay on to complete the maneuvers, a u.s. military spokesman said tuesday, although honduras says its border crisis with nicaragua is over
right now the plans are to make it a 10- to 14-day exercises. we have not received any directive as to when to begin redeployment,'' said u.s. spokesman maj. gary hovatter in a telephone interview
he said exercises were taking place tuesday at four sites
president reagan ordered 3,200 american troops to honduras last week at the request of president jose azcona hoyo, who had accused sandinista soldiers from neighboring nicaragua of penetrating honduran territory in pursuit of u.s.-supported contra rebels
president daniel ortega of nicaragua denied his troops were in honduras. last week honduran jets twice bombed nicaraguan positions to force them to leave. no casualties were reported
honduran foreign minister carlos lopez contreras told the associated press in an interview tuesday the border tension ``has virtually disappeared'' after both the sandinistas and the contras suspended hostilities and began truce talks
the three days of negotiations began monday in the small southern nicaraguan town of sapoa, near the costa rican border. the talks aim mainly at reaching a cease-fire so that both sides can strike a permanent peace accord in their 7-year-old war
the dispatch of the u.s. troops bolstered the american military presence in honduras to about 6,000 servicemen. the reagan administration billed it as both a show of support for azcona and a warning to the sandinistas against further actions in the border region
as the sandinistas pulled out of the bocay region, where the incursion took place, azcona said the additional u.s. troops would not be needed much longer
hovatter said, however, that the troops will complete their training first. the united states has been carrying out joint exercises with the honduran military periodically for five years as part of the reagan administration's policy of isolating the sandinistas
ten american soldiers were injured monday when their uh-1 huey helicopter crashed during an exercise near the southern honduran town of juticalpa, apparently as a result of mechanical failure
hovatter said five or six of the injured soldiers would be released for light duty
the nixon white house kept heavy pressure on federal reserve board chairman arthur burns to do its bidding but gently turned aside complaints from one fed critic, then-california governor ronald reagan, documents made public on tuesday show
among 400,000 pages of white house records released by the national archives is a sept. 17, 1973 letter from reagan to nixon complaining about the impact of a fed decision on california mortgage loans
the documents also included many internal white house memoranda suggesting that white house aides devoted considerable effort to encourage burns, appointed by nixon in 1970, to stimulate the economy prior to nixon's 1972 re-election campaign
critics claim the easy-money policy pursued by burns in the early 1970s did keep the economy humming through 1972, but set the stage for sharply rising interest rates and inflation in the following year, triggering a recession
in his letter to nixon, reagan contended that the fed and the federal home loan bank board were drying up the availability of mortgage money in california
they were doing this by easing restrictions that had kept interest rates which banks could pay on savings accounts below those offered by savings and loan associations, reagan said
the result, he wrote, ``has been a flow of funds from savings and loans to banks.''
since savings and loans are the ``major supplier of funds for home building in california,'' the result of the action threatened ``irreparable damage'' to his state's home-building industry, gov. reagan charged
present events have occurred which places the home-building industry in the state of california in a potentially grave situation,'' reagan wrote
the reagan letter was shunted back and forth among several aides, with tod r. hullin, an assistant to domestic policy adviser john ehrlichman, recommending that it be given ``special attention.''
although white house assistant kenneth dam wrote a draft of a white house response, the final job of answering reagan was given to george p. shultz, then nixon's treasury secretary and now reagan's secretary of state
shultz told his future boss that while the nixon administration ``shares your concern,'' a return to the former limitations on interests paid by banks would not solve the problem of california savings and loans
we have been limited in our ability to maintain the availablity of home mortgage credit,'' shultz said
then, he added: ``inflation is our most important domestic problem and this administration firmly believes that the nation is best served in the longer term by our vigorous efforts to curb inflation.''
the documents released on tuesday were a second installment of nixon white house material made public by the archives. an earlier 730,000 papers from the white house central files unit, containing many personal documents kept by nixon and his top lieutenants, was made public in december 1986
the newly released documents seemed likely to fuel longstanding speculation by critics that burns deliberately manipulated monetary policy to help re-elect nixon _ an allegation the late central bank chairman repeatedly denied
in any event, the documents show a pattern of close white house involvement with the fed on monetary issues during burns' tenure, including frequent meetings among burns and top white house officials
at one point, the white house even arranged an ``appreciation'' luncheon for burns in late 1971 to which 58 leaders from the financial community were invited
although the first 20 minutes of the late fed chairman's speech to the group ``was somewhat professorial,'' burns at the end of his speech ``was very optimistic. from this point of view, the lunch was a success,'' former white house aide peter flanigan said in a confidential memo to nixon
noting that financial writers were then brought into the luncheon to speak to burns, the memo continued: ``while arthur is no (then treasury secretary) john connally in terms of stimulating a response, the exercise was clearly a plus.''
in an august 20, 1970 memo to nixon, his then chief economic adviser, paul mccracken, praised burns for ``effective leadership'' at the fed in easing monetary policy and proposed that the money supply be permitted to grow even more rapidly
we urge this in no sense of trying to `take over' monetary policy, but merely as those who will be held accountable for the economy's performance during this period,'' mccracken wrote to nixon
the relationship between administration officials and the federal reserve system has always been a somewhat uneasy one,'' mccracken added. ``but it is the president who will be held politically accountable for the economic results of federal reserve policy.''
burns himself wrote a confidential note to nixon on march 9, 1970, pointing out how the nation's money supply had grown since he had been named fed chief five weeks earliers
let me add that the (fed) board's liberalizing action took place only on february 10 _ the first meeting of the federal open market committee over which i presided,'' burns wrote to nixon. the committee is the fed's chief policy-making unit. police probe</head>
a television evangelist who resigned as pastor of the orange county church he started is the target of a police investigation and lawsuits claiming he owes tens of thousands of dollars
richard hogue, who came here from oklahoma one year ago after facing financial difficulties in that state, said in a television interview tuesday he resigned as pastor of metrochurch sunday to concentrate on paying his debts
i'm just having to knuckle down and go back to work and take my time and try to work myself back out of this debt,'' hogue said in a telephone interview with station koco in oklahoma city
hogue was interviewed from miami, where he said he is ``looking to put together a major opportunity which could mean i could maybe be out of debt very soon.''
hogue frequently appeared on ``richard hogue weekdays'' on the ptl network formerly run by defrocked minister jim bakker and his wife tammy. he also occasionally hosted a show on trinity broadcasting network called ``praise the lord.''
trinity discontinued using hogue as a host three weeks ago
the red lights went off when we learned his board has resigned,'' tbn attorney norman juggert said
former metrochurch members june and david muehlberger of palm springs filed suit in orange county superior court on dec. 16, 1987, against metrochurch and hogue, alleging he repaid just $2,000 of a $126,000 they loaned him to buy pews
irvine police said monday they are investigating allegations of embezzlement as a result of the muehlbergers' complaint
we don't know if it's a civil problem or a criminal problem,'' sgt. scott cabe said. ``it just popped up in the last two or three days.''
in 1985, hogue resigned from his church in oklahoma, where he was a well-known pastor and tv personality
the los angeles times reported tuesday that hogue's former oklahoma attorneys are seeking $18,426 they claim he owes for legal services
we've been trying to catch the guy for two years,'' david livingston, attorney for the oklahoma law firm of mosburg, sears, kunzman and bollinger, was quoted as saying
the times also reported that an oklahoma couple sued hogue and alleged he failed to repay $142,000 on a $160,000 note for a 157-acre horse ranch. the newspaper also reported that hogue's oklahoma house was foreclosed for a $228,000 debt he owed gmac mortgage corp. of iowa
separately, hogue's assistant, mike maggard, said monday ``it appears that pastor hogue and (his wife) marilyn may be separating.''
joe chagra, a former lawyer who spent nearly six years in prison for plotting the assassination of a federal judge, says it feels good to be free of prison and free of drugs
chagra, 41, was released on parole friday from a federal prison in stafford, ariz
for all the sadness and the pain that you go through, walking out of that gate has to be the all-time high in life,'' he told the el paso times. ``i can't really tell you how good i feel.''
chagra pleaded guilty in 1982 of conspiring to kill u.s. district judge john h. wood jr., who had been scheduled to preside over the drug trial of joe's older brother, jimmy
wood, known as ``maximum john'' because of his tough sentencing of drug dealers, was murdered outside his san antonio home in 1979
jimmy chagra, who along with joe was accused of hiring charles harrelson to kill wood, was acquitted on a murder conspiracy charge and is imprisoned on a drug conviction. harrelson was sentenced to two life terms
joe chagra blamed his problems on a heavy cocaine habit and the influence of his two older brothers, jimmy and lee
now we know what a seductive drug cocaine is,'' said chagra, who said he is a convert to health foods and exercise. ``i'm sorry that (drug use) happened. it did. i can't change it. ... i don't anticipate any more problems in my life.''
lee chagra, the eldest brother, gained notoriety by successfully defending alleged drug dealers. he was gunned down in his office in december 1978
both lee and jimmy chagra lived flamboyantly, gambling huge amounts of money and using drugs. jimmy chagra once paid off a las vegas casino debt of more than $900,000 in cash, and he lost a $580,000 golf match
joe chagra, who has been disbarred, returned to el paso friday but declined to discuss what he plans to do
the only thing i won't do is make any hasty decisions,'' he said
lyn nofziger tried unsuccessfully to make then-interior secretary walter hickel an emissary to protesting students after hickel's famous protest letter to president nixon in 1970, according to newly released white house documents
nofziger, a long-time political aide to president reagan who was convicted of illegal lobbying last month, was working in the white house congressional relations office at the time
a memorandum from nofziger to h.r. haldemann, nixon's chief of staff, turned up in the latest batch of nixon white house files opened by the national archives on tuesday
hickel wrote nixon on may 6, 1970, after the invasion of cambodia by u.s. forces in vietnam had set off a storm of protest on the nation's campuses. he said that attacks on the protesters by vice president spiro t. agnew were creating an impression of a lack of concern for ``the attitude of a great mass of americans _ our young people.''
the letter, whose prompt appearance in newspapers dismayed the white house, said nixon should, among other things, talk with members of the cabinet from time to time. hickel was quoted in news accounts as saying he had had only two personal meetings with nixon since becoming secretary more than a year before
nofziger's memo, dated may 8, 1970, said: ``whether we like it or not, wally hickel is the kids' new hero. suggest we use him. suggest he meet with the president saturday and then send him out to talk to the kids
why not have the president meet with a group of kids tomorrow at mid-morning to take some of the steam out of the demonstration and give us some favorable publicity?''
the nofziger memo was directed, apparently by haldemann's office, to dwight chapin, nixon's appointments secretary. chapin seems to have sent it back to ken cole, haldemann's assistant, with the handwritten notation: ``ken cole _ good idea? _ c''
after that appeared the one word, unattributed: ``no.''
nixon did meet with protesting students, on his own without staff preparation, at 5 a.m. at the lincoln memorial. that meeting garnered much publicity, most of it in a tone of astonishment
hickel and nixon defended each other in public appearances immediately after that, but hickel did not get to see nixon and the president fired him on november 25 _ in a personal meeting
hickel was traveling tuesday and could not be reached, said his office in anchorage, alaska. nofziger had left for the day and also could not be reached, according to his washington office
a pennsylvania man who received political asylum in the soviet union says the socialist life suits him just fine
we have found this country to be free, with all freedoms you find in america. you may also attend the church of your choice. people also speak freely,'' theodore branch said in a letter from moscow to george sharrer of erie
branch, 43, and his wife, cheryle hoffman branch, 40, left the united states with a tour group in november. on jan. 19, soviet foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov announced that the branches had been granted political asylum and would be given jobs and an apartment
in the ussr there is no unemployment and no homeless people. also, medical care is free. this is also true in most cases for visitors. each employee receives one month's paid vacation each year,'' branch wrote in a letter sharrer said he received saturday
the branches lost their jobs at a florida radio station when it went off the air in 1986, and were unable to collect back pay of $6,500 which was awarded by a court
sharrer, an erie metropolitan transit authority driver for 11 years, said he talked with branch when the man rode home from his job as a janitor at an erie department store
i never heard anything from him about ideology,'' he told the erie daily times. ``he got disgusted with not being able to find a job. he kept saying he couldn't make ends meet with a minimum-wage job.''
the two sometimes ate together on the bus during a scheduled layover at the millcreek mall, sharrer said
one day, he told me he had been in washington and that he'd been approached by someone in the soviet embassy. he said he was offered a job working at a radio station. he said he was going to go over and see if he liked the job. he asked me for my address and said he'd write me and tell me how it was going,'' sharrer said
sharrer, a member of the naval reserve, gave a copy of branch's letter to his commanding officer and notified the fbi
i'm afraid to write him back because of my security clearance'' as a computer operator, sharrer said
president francois mitterrand ended months of speculation on tuesday by announcing that he will seek a second term
opinion polls have put the 71-year-old socialist in the lead for the two-stage election, beginning april 24, although he was not formally in the race
on tuesday, mitterrand appeared on the nationwide evening newscast of state-owned antenne 2 television. when asked if he would run, mitterrand paused dramatically, clearly relishing the moment, and answered with a single word: ``oui.'' yes
in reply to follow-up questions, the president said he decided to run because he thinks disunity threatened ``to tear the social fabric'' of france
i saw a risk that the country might fall again into the quarrels and divisions that have hampered it so often. i want france to be united ... not be taken in hand by the spirit of intolerance, by parties who want everything, by clans, by cliques,'' he said
as soon as mitterrand declared, michel rocard, until now the socialist party's only candidate, withdrew from the race and gave the president his full support
mitterrand's plans had been the subject of intense speculation. on some occassions he had indicated that he would preferred to retire and at other times hinted he would run because of a sense of duty
in the end, with four weeks remaining before voters go to the polls, duty called
the main conservative candidates, premier jacques chirac and former premier raymond barre, had criticized mitterrand for being coy and cutting short the democratic debate
mitterrand justified his silence by saying that with the premier campaigning it was up to the president to look after the nation's affairs in a non-partisan way
the conservatives hope to end what the french call ``cohabitation,'' created when the conservatives ousted the socialists from control of the national assembly in march 1986, but were left with a socialist president with two years to go in his term
the president is chief of state and has major duties in defense and foreign affairs. he appoints a prime minister who must be backed by a majority of the national assembly. the premier then names his cabinet and runs the government
mitterrand said tuesday that after watching the campaign, he feared opposing candidates were bringing on france disputes that threatened to damage the country
we need social peace,'' he said. ``someone has to face up to this, and i shall do it.''
chirac heads the neo-gaullist rally for the republic and barre the center-right union for french democracy
in a statement issued by chirac's campaign committee, the premier said: ``the stakes are now clear. there is on one side the socialist party which wants to retake power to lead a socialist policy and its candidate casts aspersion on all the others.''
there was no immediate reaction from barre
national polls consistently placed mitterrand ahead of barre and chirac in a campaign that has been more a contest of styles than policies
a handful of minor-party contenders, including andre lejoinie of the once-powerful communists, are expected to draw a combined total of 5 percent of the vote or less. jean-marie le pen of the extreme-right national front could get about 10 percent of the vote
a poll published in the journal du dimanche newspaper sunday indicated 55 percent of the 1,813 people polled were satisfied with mitterrand. forty-eight percent were satisfied with chirac as premier
another recent poll, however, indicated 30 percent of those queried were undecided
mitterrand told the tv audience tuesday night that he would pursue the programs and policies of the last seven years
i have maintained the confidence of the french people,'' he said
he suggested that if he won, he might dissolve the national assembly and call for new parliamentary elections
the first round of the elections is to be held april 24 with a run-off between the top two candidates scheduled for may 8
the tennessee valley authority, bidding to recover from the 1985 shutdown of its entire nuclear power system, won permission from the government on tuesday to restart the sequoyah unit 2 reactor near chattanooga, tenn
the 5-0 vote by the nuclear regulatory commission clears the way for the sequoyah plant to become the first of five licensed tva reactors to resume production of power. the approval was conditioned, however, on tva resolving a last-minute problem involving temperature detectors in the plant's pressurizer system
the unanimous vote also provided a clear indication that the nrc is not seriously concerned _ at least from a safety standpoint _ about allegations involving the tva's nuclear chief, steven a. white
in a case referred to the justice department last year, nrc investigators questioned white's veracity when he certified in writing that another tva nuclear plant, watts bar, met federal quality assurance standards. white has denied any wrongdoing
nrc chairman lando zech said the commissioners had reviewed the case, still pending at the justice department, and ``we have concluded ... that there is no presently known regulatory reason to preclude authorization to restart'' sequoyah unit 2
there is nothing unusual about the commission's consideration of a restart while investigations are ongoing,'' zech added
on capitol hill, tva chairman marvin runyon told the house public works subcommittee on investigations that ``tremendous progress is being made in our nuclear recovery efforts ... led by steve white.''
tva is about ready to turn its nuclear corner,'' said runyon
runyon said the tva hopes to have a second sequoyah reactor, unit 1, ready for restart within six months
the sequoyah facilities and three reactors at the browns ferry plant, near athens, ala., were closed in 1985 for safety improvements. after a management shakeup, construction of four other reactors was slowed down and plans for nine others were canceled. the tva still was left with $15 billion in long-term debts for the nuclear program
runyon said the first of the browns ferry plants should be ready for restart sometime next year
we're not going to rush this process,'' said runyon. ``we're proceeding deliberately, and we're putting public safety above all else. no one reactor will be restarted unless we are conpletely confident, and the nrc is fully satisfied, that it can be operated safely and efficiently for a good, long time.''
a blaze ignited in a kitchen and swept through more than 2,000 buildings in a northern burmese city, killing 113 people and leaving 20,000 homeless, government radio reported tuesday
in a separate development, insurgents attacked a famous hilltop pagoda and killed five pilgrims and a government soldier, the state radio said tuesday
the radio said the fire sunday afternoon burned two primary schools as it engulfed 2,096 buildings within two hours in lashio, a city of 200,000 in the northern shan states
efforts to communicate via telephone or telex with the associated press office in burma early wednesday to obtain more details were unsuccessful. it is often difficult to get phone or telex connections to the country
the report said most of the victims were trapped by the fire, which began in the kitchen of a chinese resident, chao wai lin
in addition to the dead, 64 people suffered serious burns, the radio said. the casualty toll was the largest ever reported in a fire in burma
more than 3,000 families lost their homes and damages were estimated at about $10 million, the radio said
lashio, 450 miles northeast of rangoon, is the largest city and business center in the northern shan states and the seat of the northeast military command
in the pagoda attack, the radio said insurgents of the karen national union attacked the kyaiktiyo pagoda in mon state monday with mortars, and then looted pagoda donation boxes and shops, robbed pilgrims and set fire to 13 shops and a fire station
it said 16 pilgrims and eight government soldiers were wounded before the rebels were driven off in a four-hour firefight
the pagoda, 120 miles northeast of rangoon, attracts large numbers of pilgrims from all over the country, especially between december and march each year
the karens are among several ethnic minorities in burma fighting the central government for greater autonomy
the nuclear regulatory commission on tuesday conditionally authorized a restart of the rancho seco nuclear power plant near sacramento, calif., after a 27-month shutdown which triggered a management shakeup and hundreds of plant modifications
the commission, in a 5-0 vote, stipulated that one remaining equipment problem _ excessive vibration in emergency diesel generators _ must be resolved to the satisfaction of the nrc's staff before the restart can begin
even if the generator problem is handled swiftly, rancho seco still faces an uncertain future. area voters are scheduled to decide on the day of the california primary, june 7, whether the 913-megawatt facility should be closed permanently
the reactor is the sole nuclear plant owned by the sacramento municipal utility district, but it represents about 55 percent of the utility's generating capacity and is directly responsible for 1,000 jobs and $75 million in wages. indirectly, as many as 3,000 jobs and $150 million in wages are affected
the plant, which has long history of problems, was shut down in december 1985 because of a power loss in its control system, leading to severe overcooling of the reactor. the nrc subsequently required major overhauls of the equipment, as well as deep changes in management and operator training programs
carl andognini, smud's chief nuclear officer, and ann taylor, a board member of the utility, told the commission the plant is ready for restart, except for the diesel problem, and pledged that safety would always remain the paramount concern in future operations
taylor said ``there's tremendous support for the plant, out there in the community.''
but ed smeloff, another board member, said he thought rancho seco should be closed permanently, even though ``i do believe it can be operated safely.''
smeloff said he thought the dangers were economic, arguing that the utility is too small to support an expensive nuclear plant with an uncertain potential for future production. ``rancho seco represents a $200 million per year risk,'' he said. ``we are not a large enough utility to support that kind of risk.''
one of the questions facing the voters is whether the plant should remain open provided it meets certain production goals. nrc chairman lando zech chided the smud board for wording the issue that way, saying ``you should have emphasized safety on the ballot. it gives the commission some concern about the judgment of the board.'' expenses</head>
a group of about 300 west coast citizens arrived in the nation's capital tuesday, hoping to persuade congress to spend more on domestic programs and less on the military
the group, including residents from washington, oregon and california, arrived five hours behind schedule because of mechanical troubles, but remained enthusiastic about its mission
this train is bound for congress,'' the residents sang upon their arrival at union station near the capitol. ``get this country back on track, get this deficit off our back.''
the group, part of the ``citizens' train'' which began a cross-country journey on saturday, was greeted by several lawmakers from the northwest
sen. mark o. hatfield, r-ore., told the group that lawmakers recently had been discussing the emergency deployment of u.s. troops to honduras but ``today they have been discussing you, an emergency deployment of citizens to washington.''
a leaflet from the group calls on the president and congress to establish a citizens' budget ``based on the ideals of the u.s. constitution and the bill of rights. further, we call upon the president and the congress to address the critical issue of the unprecedented national deficit with a keen regard for the well-being of all americans.''
the group planned to lobby congress on wednesday and thursday and attend several briefings and receptions with members of the west coast congressional delegations
almost a billion dollars must be allocated to the space station next year or america will have to abandon plans to build the orbiting platform, nasa administrator james c. fletcher said tuesday
a substantial cut in the space station budget, added to delays caused by cuts in earlier years, will make it useless for the national aeronautics and space administration to continue efforts to build the station, he said
this is year is crucial,'' fletcher told the senate subcommittee on science, technology and space. ``otherwise, we've got to just forget it and start over at a later date.''
but senators attending the hearing warned fletcher that would be extremely difficult to get nasa its entire requested budget in a year when federal dollars are tight because of deficit-cutting efforts. seeral pressed him on how much of a reduction could be tolerated in the space station program, but fletcher said the requested budget was the ``rock bottom'' that nasa needs
fletcher said a severe cut in the station budget last year caused a full year's delay, and another cut in fiscal year 1989, which begins oct. 1, would make it ``a waste of the taxpayers dollars'' to continue the underfunded program
nasa's 1989 budget calls for a total of $967.4 million for the space station. plans call for the station to be assembled in orbit and for crews to start living in the orbiting laboratory in the middle of the next decade
the station funds are part of a $11.5 billion appropriation request by nasa that would include money for space shuttle missions, advanced shuttle rockets, aeronautical research and a study of the technology that will be needed one day to send astronauts back to the moon and possibly to mars
the budget request, which was approved by president reagan, is a 24 pecent increase over nasa's current spending blueprint
fletcher said that unless congress passes the entire space budget, there is no way for the u.s. to maintain world leadership in space
the entire future of the civil space program rides at risk on this budget,'' he said. ``this is a crucial year ... it will make or break the civil space program.''
fletcher said the budget is the final boost needed for nasa's recovery from the 1986 challenger disaster, in which a space shuttle was destroyed and seven astronauts killed. the shuttle fleet has been grounded since while the space agency corrected flawed equipment that caused the accident
nasa tentatively plans to resume shuttle flights in august. two are planned for this year, seven in 1989 and 10 in 1990
without this increase, nasa will be in serious trouble,'' fletcher said. ``a major cut would be equivalent to the challenger disaster itself.'' haughey, sted houghey.</note>
a scholar abused research privileges at the library of congress and national archives to steal and try to sell letters signed by abraham lincoln, winston churchill and other historic figures, a prosecutor said tuesday
charles merrill mount also defaced some letters between lincoln and civil war generals to remove government markings that would have alerted a rare documents dealer to the fact they were stolen, assistant u.s. attorney martin murphy said in his opening statement at mount's trial
but mount's attorney, charles mcginty, argued mount had legally collected the documents and shoddy record-keeping led the library of congress and national archives to believe the letters were part of their collections
mcginty said the government would offer no evidence showing mount stole the documents, a point murphy conceded
mount, 59, a washington-based author of several artists' biographies, tearfully denied the allegations, but predicted he would be convicted
mount told reporters outside court that associates in ireland, including prime minister charles haughey, had seen the documents when mount lived in ireland during the 1960s. but mount said a government freeze on his assets prevented him from bringing witnesses to the united states to testify on his behalf
without witnesses, i'm going to be convicted,'' he said
mount is charged with two counts of interstate transportation of stolen property and faces up to 10 years in prison and a $10,000 fine if convicted. his trial is expected to last three weeks
mount was arrested in august when he tried to sell a 158-page collection of civil war documents to goodspeed's book store for $64,600. a month earlier, the store paid mount $20,000 for 23 letters signed by 19th-century painter james mcneill whistler, a churchill letter and one by henry james
the whistler letters, brought to boston in a plastic bag, were stolen from the library of congress last july, murphy told the jury
the civil war collection disappeared from the national archives within a week before mount's aug. 5 letter to goodspeed's offering to sell the documents, murphy said. mount spent the last five days of july viewing the collection, murphy said
mcginty asked the jury to note testimony about keeping records at the library of congress and national archives and how government records were stored before the archives opened in the 1930s
he said thousands of historic records were lost and stolen after the civil war because they were kept in basements, attics, and even the white house garage
records at the institutions show they should have possession of numerous documents that actually are in private collections, mcginty said
the government's top health officer said tuesday that hospitals have engaged in a kind of medical arms race that assures neither quality care nor good value for the dollar
sometimes you can save money and also improve care, like concentrating certain procedures in hospitals that specialize in them,'' said health and human services secretary otis r. bowen. ``this not only leads to better results for the patient, it also allows us to benefit from economies of scale.''
bowen's remarks to a conference of the health care quality alliance followed a report by the 28-member coalition that cautioned against emphasizing cost control to the point that the ``quality of care _ and quality of life _ are adversely affected.''
the health secretary acknowledged that the government is concerned about rising costs in the medicare and medicaid programs, but said, ``we won't accomplish anything if we sacrifice quality for lower costs.''
one reason today's health care is so expensive is that the financing of that care is little more than a collection of disincentives to practice cost-effective medicine,'' he said
bowen contended that ``hospitals, in order to attract doctors and their patients, have bought and often duplicated the latest in medical hardware in a kind of medical arms race.''
another reason for concern, he said, is that government tax policies which do not tax employer-paid health insurance coverage like some other fringe benefits ``have encouraged employers and unions to bargain for ever-greater first-dollar coverage in health insurance plans.''
compounding this folly,'' bowen continued, ``most insurance plans cover expensive high-tech procedures and slight preventive services. and all of this has made patients and their families all but oblivious to costs, since they pay so little out of pocket.''
turning to medicare, he said creation of the program 23 years ago ``created a powerful incentive for the health care industry to develop the technology to treat the chronic, degenerative diseases that afflict the aging.''
bowen said he was not suggesting those procedures are bad. ``on the contrary,'' he said, ``they have improved the quality of life for americans of all ages.''
still to be decided is how much is too much. ... how much heroic medical care and how many procedures to keep a dying patient alive are desirable for the patient, the family and, not least of all, for society at large? when is such care merely prolonging the act of dying rather than contributing to longer life, or at least some type of quality to it?''
bowen, a physician whose first wife died of cancer and whose mother recently died in a nursing home, said: ``sometimes our high-tech capability lures us into pursuing expensive answers when less costly ones are available. our veneration of technology has become a cultural blindspot that sometimes keeps us from pursuing practical solutions to our problems.''
the theme of the conference was ``balancing health care costs, quality, and access: the challenge for the next administration.''
the alliance membership includes the american medical association, the alzheimer's disease and related disorders association, the arthritis foundation, the american cancer society, the american academy of pediatrics and the national council on the aging. east, but no firm decision; picks up at pvs 3rd grasf, ``state department.''</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz will probably travel to the middle east within two weeks if israel agrees to further discussions on his regional peace plan, an israeli diplomat said tuesday
asher naim, the information minister at the israeli embassy, said he expects israel's cabinet will vote to keep alive the shultz peace initiative when the issue is debated
apparently, secretary shultz will be in the middle east ... in two weeks time again,'' he told reporters at the national press club
israel will not reject the u.s. peace proposals, naim said, ``and if the government indeed decides a neutral way _ that means you continue negotiations _ then probably secretary shultz will go to the middle east.''
state department spokesman charles redman said tuesday that shultz had not yet decided to return to the mideast, where he conducted a diplomatic shuttle last month
another state department official, who spoke only on condition he not be named, said shultz probably would make his decision by the end of this week after being briefed by presidential envoy philip habib about his tour of four arab capitals. habib visited jordan, egypt, and saudi arabia this week, and is due back by thursday following a stop in morocco
habib will bring with him reactions from the arab leaders to shultz's plan, which calls for israeli-arab talks to begin may 1 on palestinian self-rule, and for the next phase to start by dec. 1 to determine the future of the israeli-occupied territories. so far, syria is the only party to have rejected the plan
shultz's plans also may be shaped by his talks this week in washington with soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze about the u.s. peace plan, which envisions international sponsorship for the arab-israeli negotiations, the official said. a group of u.s. and soviet negotiators were scheduled to discuss the mideast on wednesday, he said
naim, addressing reporters at the national press club, said shultz would be coming back to the region because the israeli government will not reject his plan, despite internal divisions. ``they won't vote `no.' they'll probably decide to continue negotiating about the plan,'' he said
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, who visited washington last week, rejects the international auspices proposed by shultz for the talks. his rival, foreign minister shimon peres, has accepted the plan
president reagan, in an unusually blunt statement, warned shamir against rejecting the plan and said the united states would not change its proposals to suit shamir's reservations
but naim hinted at one possible avenue for continued negotiations with israel over the shultz plan. ``there are some suggestions to cushion israel's fears about an international conference,'' he said
naim was referring to proposed guarantees by the united states that an international conference would not have any power to impose solutions on israel. other u.s. officials have suggested these guarantees would be included in a memorandum of understanding between israel and the united states
redman said the united states also might promise israel that the guarantees would be binding on future administrations
we really have the sense that if we can get this thing moving, that there really is no difficulty in having it move right across the boundaries of one administraiton to another,'' he said
congress on tuesday overrode president reagan's veto of a sweeping civil rights bill, restoring broad anti-discrimination protections that were sharply restricted by the supreme court
the senate voted 73-24 for the override, and the house followed suit 292-133. both votes exceeded the two-thirds margin needed to hand reagan a stinging defeat
congressional support for a $4.4 billion atom smasher is dwindling rapidly because of budget constraints and irritation with the site-selection process, house members said tuesday
although seven states remain in the running for the superconducting super collider, lawmakers say the huge project is in jeopardy
some even advocate that it be scrapped at once
now that all but seven states have been eliminated from the ssc site-selection process, the remaining states should help put an end to the process,'' said rep. don ritter, r-pa. ``it's time to face up to the facts.''
testifying before the house science, space and technology committee, ritter said a financial commitment to the high-energy physics project would endanger funds for scientific research in other fields
ritter, whose home state did not seek the project, said the house budget committee recognized the conflict by appropriating $100 million for the collider in fiscal 1989 rather than the $363 million president reagan requested
congressional delegations from the states picked as finalists said tuesday they are forming a task force to seek support for ssc funding
my fear is we will end up with a site to build the ssc and no funds for construction,'' said rep. carl pursell, r-mich
rep. sherwood boehlert, r-n.y., said that with the demand for budget cuts and the current feelings of lawmakers whose states were bypassed, ``it will be well-nigh impossible to pay for this thing.''
the collider would be a 53-mile, underground ring of magnets capable of whipping proton beams into each other with 20 times the force of the world's most powerful existing accelerator
scientists hope to learn more about the nature of matter from studying the subatomic particles created by the proton collisions
the project is expected to bring thousands of construction jobs, permanent employment for as many as 3,000 people and an annual budget of $270 million to the host state
an independent panel appointed by the department of energy reviewed 35 bids from 25 states before picking seven finalists: illinois, texas, arizona, colorado, michigan, north carolina and tennessee
energy secretary john herrington said he would announce a tentative choice for the site in november and confirm the selection in january 1989
but the science committee's chairman, rep. robert roe, d-n.j., told doe undersecretary joseph selgado at the hearing that ``a question of credibility is arising'' about the selection process
he said said several lawmakers have complained that the department failed to use the criteria it had established previously when the seven finalists were chosen
democratic sen. albert gore jr. told students at a campaign stop tuesday that combating illegal drugs would take precedence in foreign policy if he is elected president
gore told a crowded gathering at traverse city high school that he would use the military to stop the flow of drugs into the united states
he said the nation's drug problem reflected ``a spiritual crisis ... an absence of hope.''
we have to have the courage to say there's nothing more important in our foreign policy than stopping'' illegal drugs, gore told the students. ``i'll change that and put the war on drugs at the top of our foreign policy agenda.''
he commented while campaigning in michigan, where polls show him trailing badly just four days before the state's democratic presidential caucuses
earlier in the day, gore canceled a speech at the university of wisconsin in madison to return to washington to cast a vote to override president reagan's veto of a civil rights bill
he also stopped in harrisburg, pa., where he met with gov. robert p. casey, who is neutral in the presidential race, and received the endorsement of state legislative leaders
gore said he was ``a little bit'' surprised at vice president george bush's decision to go along with reagan's civil rights veto
he added, ``when push comes to shove the vice president never disagrees with president reagan. i don't remember a time in eight years when he has been willing to express any disagreement with the president
he really has not carved out an identity of his own in this election,'' gore said
in harrisburg, he called pennsylvania ``an excellent opportunity for a gore victory.'' in michigan, he said he expected to ``do significantly better than expected.''
gore is running far behind in polls in michigan, and he is competing in the state without campaigning intensively. his campaign has been airing radio commercials featuring an endorsement by singer johnny cash, but has not aired television ads
he is running television commercials in wisconsin, a state where he figures to have a greater opportunity to demonstrate broad appeal outside his native south. gore is scheduled to speak to the state legislature in madison, wisc., on wednesday
in traverse city, gore spoke to an overflow crowd of about 700 students at an event held after school had ended for the day. the auditorium was filled with hand-lettered posters, such as one saying, ``al's your pal.''
with him was the state house speaker gary owen, a gore backer, and the mayor of traverse city, bryan crough, who also endorsed him
gore's comments on drugs were in response to questions from students. he pointed to the alleged involvement in massive drug smuggling by panama strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega. he has repeatedly accused the reagan administration of having continued support for noriega even after it had evidence of drug involvement
early senate ratification of the agreement banning medium-range nuclear weapons worldwide hit a potentially major roadblock tuesday with the reopening of a long-festering constitutional feud between congress and the white house over the interpretation of treaties
several members of the senate foreign relations committee expressed dismay at the development. they said it could delay ratification of the new intermediate-range nuclear forces or inf treaty until after the planned summit meeting later this spring between president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
on another front, however, the senate intelligence committee reported unanimously that soviet compliance with the new treaty can be monitored with ``great certainty.''
but the panel made clear that detecting soviet efforts to cheat on a future pact making sharp cuts in long-range strategic arms would strain u.s. intelligence capabilites
the treaty interpretation controversy was raised in testimony before the foreign relations panel by sen. sam nunn, d-ga., chairman of the senate armed services committee
nunn said a recent letter from white house counsel arthur b. culvahouse jr. effectively undercut previous assurances from secretary of state george p. shultz that administration testimony on the new pact is ``authoritative.''
the dispute stems from the reagan administration's unilateral re-interpretation last year of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty with the soviet union in order to permit the deployment of a ``star wars'' missile defense system
the new culvahouse letter undercuts the shultz assurance, nunn told the committee, by asserting that some administration responses may be less authoritative than others
culvahouse suggested that the testimony of a secretary of state may be more authoritative than that of other administration witnesses or responses in writing to questions by members of congress, nunn said
culvahouse has since issued a second letter asserting that his original remarks were not inconsistent with the shultz statement. but nunn said he finds that unacceptable
it doesn't solve my problem,'' nunn said. ``it simply asserts there is no conflict. you can assert anything ... it puts the shultz statement in the trash can, saying that certain testimony is not to be taken seriously.''
he said the culvahouse assertion casts doubt on the authority of several administration interpretations on a list of ambiguities in treaty language. that might have to be resolved point by point in a time consuming process on the senate floor, he said
nunn said he believes the controversy must be resolved by the full senate and that another letter, even one from the president, would not be acceptable
sen. alan cranston, d-calif., said, ``this is the major stumbling block and could create grave perils if we don't resolve it.'' he predicted that the issue could result in a serious partisan split inside the committee and in the senate
it would be tragic if this treaty was destroyed because we had a procedural dispute with the president,'' said sen. brock adams, d-wash
the intelligence committee report was presented to the senate foreign relations committee as that panel prepared to consider a series of amendments to the medium-range missile pact, the final phase of a two-month process of intense examination
the treaty was signed by reagan and gorbachev on dec. 8. it eliminates nuclear-armed missiles with a range of between 300 miles and 3,400 miles in europe and elsewhere and provides the most intrusive verification system in arms control history
sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., the foreign relations chairman, said earlier he hoped the panel could complete its work by the end of the week, sending the treaty to the senate floor for a vote expected sometime in april. vote tallies in both parties predict ratification by far more than the required two-thirds or 67 votes
the intelligence committee conducted its own review of treaty provisions, concentrating on the u.s. capability to monitor soviet compliance with a variety of information-collecting techniques, including the use of spy satellites and on-site inspection
the intelligence community will be able to monitor the drawdown and elimination of declared soviet missile launchers and associated equipment with great certainty,'' the panel said in its final report
but sen. david boren, d-okla., the intelligence panel's chairman, said that effective verification of a future pact cutting strategic intercontinental arms by up to 50 percent would require a significant and expensive bolstering of u.s. intelligence capabilities
the committee recommended ``investing more in programs that would be most helpful in verifying a start treaty, in preventing technological surprise and in supporting u.s. policy and operations in crises,'' boren said
speaking for the committee, boren said that because a strategic arms reduction or start treaty would not involve a ban on an entire class of weapons but would rather impose limits on total numbers of weapons that will make ``the detection of cheating far more difficult.''
the intelligence committee said also that the extensive on-site inspection requirements of a strategic arms treaty _ with soviet inspectors given access to some of the most sensitive u.s. military facilities _ could have a significant impact on u.s. intelligence operations
it said that while it has overall confidence in the ability of the u.s. to detect soviet cheating on the inf treaty, ``soviet compliance with some of the treaty's provisions will be difficult to verify.''
the panel noted, for example, that a controversy between the central intelligence agency and the defense intelligence afency over the number of ss-20 missiles in the soviet arsenal remains unresolved, with the dia estimating a larger number
but it said the treaty's ban on flight testing will ultimately limit the utility of any covert ss-20 force. salvadoran party</head>
the united states should establish stronger ties with the rightest party that won convincing victories in municipal and legislative elections in el salvador, a congressman who monitored the weekend elections said tuesday
sunday's elections, which had a 70 percent voter turnout despite threats of violence by leftist guerrillas, proved that the republican nationalist alliance will be a major force in el salvador, said rep. john g. rowland, r-conn. the party, known by its spanish acronym arena, won a majority of the elections over the moderate christian democrat party of president jose napoleon duarte
we really need to concentrate on working with the arena political party,'' rowland told reporters at a news briefing
we need to get more involved. we have invested there millions and millions of dollars in foreign aid. it's the only country that's had any democratic reform of significance over the last few years. it would be a shame to see the whole thing fall apart,'' he said
rowland pointed to arena's strong electoral support across a wide cross-section of salvadoran society and efforts by the party to moderate its views. and he noted the low profile taken by former army maj. robert d'aubuisson, the party's controversial founder who has been accused of links to salvadoran death squads
my impression is that arena is not as nearly as right ... as we had originally suspected. there's tremendous support among the people,'' rowland said. ``there are some bad apples, of course, within their party, but our information suggests that maybe they're not the crazies that you might suspect.''
rowland was one of six house members who monitored the elections
our observations concluded that it was a fair and open election,'' he said
a jury tuesday recommended a former state trooper be sentenced to life in prison without parole for murdering his trooper girlfriend, the first woman state trooper in the nation slain while on duty
circuit judge j.c. norton will not be bound by the jury's recommendation when he sentences joe duncan, who was accused of killing elizabeth cobb to collect $350,000 in life insurance
no date for sentencing was set immediately
ten members of the dallas county jury voted for life imprisonment without parole, while two voted that duncan should die in the electric chair. the jury convicted duncan of capital murder monday night after about three hours of deliberation
in a sentencing hearing tuesday, duncan's daughter pleaded that his life be spared. ``he was _ he is _ the best father you could have,'' 14-year-old tanya duncan said
duncan, 33, was convicted of shooting miss cobb, 31, in the head at close range oct. 11. her body was found the next day behind the wheel of her patrol car, which was parked behind a rural church
at the time, the fbi described miss cobb as the first female state trooper in the nation slain while on duty
prosecutors charged that duncan killed miss cobb for a $250,000 life insurance policy that paid an extra $100,000 if she died in the line of duty. the slaying occurred 10 days after the policy went into effect on the rookie trooper, with duncan as beneficiary
defense attorney henry pitts said the trial's most decisive factor was evidence showing duncan gave investigators conflicting accounts before his arrest
jurors saw a videotape that showed duncan denying he knew anything about miss cobb's death, and a second tape in which he told investigators he found the slain trooper's body shortly after she was killed. duncan said he didn't tell anyone of finding her body for fear he would be accused of the crime
forty wild welsh ponies were shot dead and left to rot on this great salt lake island because the rancher who rents the island said he could not afford to capture and move them
the carcasses were discovered saturday by a private pilot on a recreational flight, said antelope state park superintendent mitch larsson, who had gone to the island monday, concerned the animals may have died from disease
the uninhabited island was leased to rancher dallen ward last fall, and ward killed the horses to make way for sheep he plans to move from his home in almo, idaho, said weber county sheriff's lt. archie smith
ward said monday that the horses were over-grazing the island, and the cost of moving them was prohibitive
we looked at every avenue possible and economically i couldn't do it,'' he said, explaining he would have had to hire a crew to round up the horses and rent a barge to move them
he also said he could find no buyers for the animals
ward said he shot the animals himself, but he refused to discuss details
bruce dibb, an attorney for the owner of the island, steven richards sr., said the horses were introduced about 30 years ago with commercial recreation in mind. however, the enterprise never got off the ground and the horses became wild
dibb said his client removed about 100 horses by barge last year, but the others eluded capture
the shootings probably did not violate utah law, said john fox, a special deputy for the utah humane society. ``unless it can be proved the horses suffered or didn't pass out right away, it is legal,'' he said
however, fox said ward may have violated the law by not burying the horses within 48 hours, a misdemeanor
smith said he planned to speak to weber county attorney reed richards to determine whether charges should be filed
the ponies appeared to have been dead for about two weeks, said utah veterinarian michael marshall, who accompanied larsson to the island monday
there is no real danger from the carcasses other than maybe a bird pecking on them, then flying across to the mainland with that material,'' marshall said. ``but i don't see any way to bury them. you would have to airlift a backhoe over there to do it.''
north carolina's attorney general is preparing to ask the u.s. supreme court to uphold a state law requiring professional fund-raisers for charities to tell potential donors how the money will be used
the nation's highest court is scheduled to hear arguments wednesday on north carolina's petition to reverse lower-court rulings, which struck down the 1985 law as a violation of the first amendment's freedom of speech guarantee
both sides agree that the outcome of the case could have a nationwide impact on the professional fund-raising industry, which attorney general lacy thornburg called a ``multi-multimillion-dollar business,'' and on smaller charities that lack personnel to raise money
it's really a question of survival,'' said errol copilevitz, a kansas city attorney representing the national federation of the blind of north carolina inc. and the optimist club of north raleigh, n.c., which filed a lawsuit in 1985 challenging the law
about 75 charities have filed a friend-of-the-court brief opposing the statute. many are represented by independent sector, an umbrella group including such organizations as the american red cross and the american cancer society, copilevitz said tuesday
thornburg said maine, connecticut, indiana and west virginia had filed briefs in support of north carolina's law
the most controversial provision requires professional fund-raisers to tell people they solicit what portion of the money will be spent on the charitable cause and how much will be used to cover expenses
the purpose of the law is to promote honesty through disclosure ... in very much the same way that banks and other institutions are required to tell, for example, what their interest rate is going to be,'' thornburg said at a news conference
a study of fund-raising campaigns conducted in north carolina by professionals on behalf of charities between 1980 and 1984 showed that, on average, only 13 percent of gross receipts were returned to the charities, he said
the law presumes that whenever a professional group retains 35 percent or more of the gross receipts, it has reaped an excess profit, thornburg said
the solicitations licensing branch of the state department of human resources is empowered to increase the charity's share if it finds excessive profit for the fund-raisers
if allowed to stand, the law would bolster public confidence in charities, thornburg said. ``we feel that if a donor knows in advance what portion of the funds are going back to the charity, then they will much more freely give.''
but wayne shevlin, president of the raleigh chapter of the national federation of the blind of north carolina inc., disagreed
if the first thing you have to say is how much is going for expenses, most people ... are going to hang up before you've had a chance to go through the spiel,'' shevlin said
the law might drive out of business many small- and medium-sized charities, he said
copilevitz said most potential donors who want information on how the money will be spent ask for it. many states _ including north carolina _ require professional and amateur fund-raising groups to provide such details on request, he said
most states regulate fund solicitation, he said, but north carolina's law goes far beyond any other
u.s. district judge earl britt struck down the measure as unconstitutional on may 14, 1986, a finding upheld by the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals in richmond, va., on april 23, 1987. economy average to 28.2 mpg sted 28 mpg.</note>
federal fuel-economy standards will cause thousands of traffic deaths next year by discouraging the use of safer, larger cars, two researchers said tuesday as the government reported a slight increase in auto fuel efficiency last year
fuel economy regulation inevitably leads to smaller, lighter cars that are inherently less safe than the cars that would be produced without a binding fuel-economy constraint,'' said a study by robert w. crandall of the brookings institution in washington and john d. graham of the harvard school of public health in boston
they estimated the standards would cause 2,200 to 3,900 traffic deaths next year
also tuesday, the transportation department told congress that passenger cars sold in the united states got 28.2 miles per gallon last year overall, up 0.2 miles per gallon from the previous year
transportation secretary jim burnley said americans tended to buy slightly heavier, higher performance cars last year than in prior years, and imports showed a shift way from subcompacts to compacts, increasing their market share by 8 percentage points
among the big three automakers, chrysler corp. had the most fuel efficient cars fleetwide in 1987, at 27.6 mpg, down from 27.8 mpg in 1986
ford motor co. had a fuel-economy of 26.8 mpg, unchanged from the previous year, and general motors corp.'s was 26.4 mpg, up from 26.2 mpg the previous year
weighted by sales, imports had an fuel economy of 31 mpg, down from 31.7 mpg the previous year
domestic cars averaged 26.7 mpg, up from 26.6 mpg the year before
burnley used the report to reiterate his support for elimination of the fuel-economy requirement, saying it placed u.s. manufacturers at a disadvantage against their foreign competition
the greatest contribution we can make to keeping jobs in the united states and to making the domestic auto industry competitive on a worldwide basis is to repeal the (fuel economy) rules,'' burnley said. ``thousands of american jobs are threatened because of an anachronistic law that is doing substantial harm to our economy and our trade balance.''
the corporate average fuel economy standards _ cafe for short _ from 1978 sought to encourage more fuel efficient cars and thereby reduce petroleum use at a time of shortages and soaring prices
the required fuel economy this year is 26 mpg of gasoline. manufacturers that fail to meet the standards are liable to fines
using mathematical models, crandall and graham estimated the cafe standards had reduced the weight of cars by 500 pounds, to 3,100 pounds, despite sharp declines in oil prices after 1981 that in an unregulated market would be expected to encourage manufacture of larger cars
that decline in weight ``caused by cafe is associated with a 14 to 27 percent increase in occupant fatality risk,'' the study said. they applied that range to existing traffic fatality figures to make their estimate of the number of additional deaths likely in 1989
the estimate took into account such factors as the tendency of occupants of smaller cars, compared with those of larger cars, to buckle their safety belts, the study said
the study also said the cafe standards, by raising the cost of desirable high-performance cars, have encouraged people to drive their cars longer, extending ``the useful life of older, less safe and higher-pollution cars.''
rep. bob carr, d-mich., said at a news conference marking the study's release he hopes the conclusions will help win support for legislation he introduced last year to abolish the cafe standards
congress is not the place to design auto models,'' carr said, acknowledging the bill's chances of passage this year are slim
the study by crandall and graham is scheduled for publication next year in the journal of law and economics
the study was released by the competitive enterprise institute, a public-issues group espousng free-market principles. crandall and graham said they did the study without funds from the institute. middle east. picks up 6th graf pvs, `former u.s...'.</note>
the justice department sued tuesday to force the palestine liberation organization to close its mission to the united nations, and the plo envoy defiantly responded that he could live on the street as a refugee
the government sought a federal court order barring the plo; zehdi labib terzi, head of the plo's observer mission; and five other plo officials or employees from continuing to operate the mission or any plo office in manhattan or at any other location
the action is required under the 1987 anti-terrorism act, which found the plo and its affiliates were a terrorist organization responsible for numerous violent incidents, including the murder of an american citizen during the hijacking of the cruise ship achille lauro in 1985
terzi said he would have no comment on the plo's possible legal response until he reads the complaint
the only asset we have in this country is the building we live in,'' he told reporters. ``maybe they want me to live on the street, but this would not be the first time the palestinians become refugees.''
he called efforts to freeze plo funds ``financial terrorism to strangle us.''
earlier tuesday, he had said, ``if they force me to leave, i will have to move to the united nations'' on international territory, out of reach of u.s. marshals. in 1973, plo chief yasser arafat spent a night at the united nations because he could not stay on u.s. territory
in amman, jordan, plo foreign affairs spokesman farouk kaddoumi said tuesday before the suit was filed,:``we will keep the office open until the american police seal it off. then we will go to the united nations and live there
this will become a continuous headache to the u.s. administration,'' said kaddoumi
former u.s. attorney general ramsey clark, the plo's legal counsel, was not available for comment, his office said tuesday. clark did not immediately return messages left at the office
clark has said, however, that he would seek to have the federal complaint dismissed on grounds that u.s. courts lack jurisdiction in the matter involving an international treaty, in this instance between the united states and the united nations
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar said he would have to wait until the u.n. general assembly adopts a resolution wednesday before commenting on possible legal action
the 159-member general assembly is to vote on a resolution supporting the plo's right to operate and deploring u.s. moves to shut the mission. the draft of the resolution calls on the secretary-general to take measures to allow the plo to carry out its official functions as a u.n. invitee
in a separate action last september, the state department ordered the closing of the plo's information office in washington. that was before congress passed the anti-terrorism act, which president reagan signed on dec. 22. the law took effect monday
under the law, congress determined that ``the plo and its affiliates are a terrorist organization and a threat to the interests of the united states, its allies and to international law and should not benefit from operating in the united states.''
earlier this month, secretary of state george shultz called the act ``one of the dumber things that the congress has done lately.''
a lawsuit filed tuesday alleges that an underground prison facility for women in lexington, ky., was designed specifically to house political activists and that inmates are subjected to inhumane treatment
civil liberties groups filed the suit in u.s. district court here against nine federal officials, including attorney general edwin meese iii. it seeks the immediate transfer of the inmates from the high-security facility to the general population of a federal women's prison
the lexington control unit opened in november 1986, now houses five inmates and contains 16 basement cells constructed beneath the federal prison at lexington. the u.s. bureau of prisons said last october it will phase out the unit, the only high-security unit for women in the federal prison system
the primary purpose for the creation of the unit was to confine prisoners whose political associations and affiliations were determined to pose a security threat,'' said the suit, alleging violation of the women's constitutional rights. ``all the women in the unit are suffering psychological and physical harm as a direct consequence of their isolated confinement in this underground segregation unit.''
a new medium- and high-security facility for women will be opened in june in marianna, fla., and the phaseout in lexington will be completed shortly thereafter, said bureau of prisons spokeswoman kathryn morse. she declined to comment on the suit
the ``small basement facility'' has ``virtually no natural light'' and is illuminated 24 hours a day by fluorescent lights, said the suit, prepared by the national prison project of the american civil liberties union and other attorneys
the women, the suit said, are monitored continuously by staff and video cameras, have no opportunity to participate in any of the activities available to the general prison population and are subjected to random strip searches
we believe the women's lives are in danger,'' said susan waysdorf, a spokeswoman for civil libertarians supporting the suit. ``they're beginning to experience signs of behavior modification, general disorientation, vision problems, loss of appetite, sleeplessnes.''
among the inmates are silvia baraldini, convicted of racketeering and conspiracy in aiding a $1.6 million brink's armored car heist in nyack, n.y., that left a guard and two police officers dead. another inmate at lexington is susan rosenberg, linked by law enforcement officers to the same bungled brink's robbery
baraldini, serving a 43-year term, was transferred to lexington after refusing to be interviewed by an fbi agent, the suit said
rosenberg, serving a 58-year term for possession of weapons and explosives in connection with a 1985 police raid in new jersey, was told that she would be confined to the unit until she changes her political beliefs, the suit alleges
when civil liberties groups began to expose lexington as a ``political prison, federal officials hurriedly brought in two other women serving long sentences,'' a coalition of prominent civil libertarians said in a statement about the lexington unit
one of the women brought in later, sylvia brown, serving a 27-year term for violating probation and escaping from a federal prison, was told that her release from the unit would depend on her lack of interaction with the political activists, the suit added
president reagan harshly criticized the process of gerrymandering on tuesday, complaining that republicans are getting short-shrift treatment in the redrawing of congressional boundary lines.
i promise you this: as far as the president of the united states is concerned, he's not going to be sitting around his garden sniffing roses in 1988,'' reagan told a group of republican elected officials
i'm going to be out on the campaign trail, telling the american people the truth about how the electoral process has been twisted and distorted,'' he said
reagan noted that reapportionment is scheduled in 1991, and said that ``having republicans in state and local offices is the only hope we have of getting a fair deal. and that's what we're asking for -  an end to the anti-democratic and un-american practice of gerrymandering congressional districts.''
gerrymandering is the political process by which congressional district lines are redrawn in such a fashion as to benefit the party in power, whether democratic or republican
reagan said there were 367 congressional races contested by both major political parties in 1984. in these contests, the president said, republicans won half a million votes more than democrats, but the democrats won 31 more seats
in his remarks, reagan said that ``gerrymandering has become a national scandal. the democratic-controlled state legislatures have so rigged the electoral process that the will of the people cannot be heard. they vote republican but elect democrats.''
the president maintained that ``the congressional map is a horror show of grotesque, contorted shapes. district lines jump back and forth over mountain ranges, cross large bodies of water, send out little tentacles to absorb special communities and ensure safe seats.''
reagan said that while republican party chairman frank fahrenkopf has challenged democratic gerrymandering in courts, ``ultimately, it's in the state legislatures that the battle for fairness must be won. and that's why republicans are going to have to campaign with all our heart and soul for republican state legislative candidates.''
reagan has steadfastly refused to take sides in the competition for the republican party nomination to succeed him, but has indicated he will campaign actively for the nominee
in his talk tuesday, the president signaled that he would hit the campaign trail for an array of other causes, including his plan to speak out against the practice of gerrymandering. says agreement expected wednesday. picks up 4th graf pvs, victor hugo ...</note>
nicaragua's defense minister, gen. humberto ortega, said at the end of a second day of peace talks between sandinista and contra rebel negotiators that he expected a ``concrete agreement'' on wednesday
he declined to elaborate, telling a news conference, ``obviously we aren't able to go into details.''
earlier tuesday both sides said they had exchanged proposals, which agree on major points, for an extended cease-fire accompanied by amnesty and release of political prisoners
contra leader adolfo calero told reporters, ``we worked hard during the day. we clarified (points that coincide) and we are working on differences.''
it was a fruitful day and tomorrow could be even better.''
calero described the second round of talks as ``direct and frank.''
the two sides began three days of meetings monday at this town on the costa rican border, trying to end a civil war that president daniel ortega says has cost 26,500 lives since 1981. both sides suspended battlefield action during the talks
the sandinista delegation proposed a 30-day truce that could be extended to three months, during which the u.s.-supported contras would lay down their weapons and join a ``national reconciliation dialogue.''
victor hugo tinoco, the deputy foreign minister, announced the proposal at a news conference. for every rebel who stops fighting, he said, the leftist government will free one of the 3,300 political prisoners it considers eligible for release
most prisoners are former members of the national guard, as the army was called under the late president anastasio somoza, whom the sandinista revolution overthrew in july 1979
contrary to previous sandinista demands, tinoco said rebels who put down their arms would be free from prosecution without applying for amnesty and could take party in nicaraguan political life
they would be permitted to operate uncensored newspapers, magazines and radio stations, but television would remain a government monopoly
contra proposals, as outlined to reporters by spokesman bosco matamoros, call for a 45-day truce beginning on good friday, april 1. rebel fighters would move to cease-fire zones and a permanent truce would be negotiated by sandinista and contra leaders
matamoros said the contras demand ``total and unconditional amnesty'' when the cease-fire begins, so anyone who had left nicaragua for political reasons could ``rejoin the political, economic and social process without any conditions.''
contra leaders also want to join a national dialogue between the sandinistas and their internal political opponents
an agreement signed monday night by president ortega, the defense minister's brother, and leaders of eight opposition political parties has a significant effect on that contra demand
it says the parties pledge to discuss ``internal political issues exclusively with the government'' and the ``government will discuss exclusively with rebel groups'' all matters involving a cease-fire
according to matamoros, other contra demands include immediate, total amnesty, freedom for all political prisoners and an end to mandatory military service
tinoco said: ``at the moment at which a cease-fire is signed, whether it be for 30, 60 or 90 days, according to what the counterrevolution wants, at that moment the leadership of the nicaraguan resistance (contras) will be able to rejoin civic and political life and even participate in the national dialogue that seeks a reconciliation of all nicaraguans.''
both sides propose international monitoring of the cease-fire. the sandinistas would have a 15-member international commission including representatives of the united nations, organization of american states, contadora and its support group
contadora is made up of mexico, venezuela, colombia and panama, and began trying to negotiate peace in central america several years ago. the support group is argentina, brazil, uruguay and peru
the battlefield truce appeared on tuesday to be holding. it was the first agreed suspension of fighting since truce for christmas and new year's during which some fighting was reported
alfredo cesar, a former sandinista who leads the contra delegation, called the exchange of proposals ``a step ahead.'' on monday night, he told reporters: ``neither side seeks a military victory over the other.''
both cease-fire and reconciliation talks are required under the peace plan signed aug. 7 by the five central american presidents. it also calls for greater democracy in the region and an end to both foreign aid to insurgents and the use of one country's territory for attacks on another
cardinal miguel obando y bravo, nicaragua's roman catholic primate, is attending the talks as one of two observers
he acted as mediator in four previous cease-fire conferences in which the sides did not meet face-to-face. they were held outside nicaragua and ended without agreement
the other observer is joao baena soarez, general secretary of the organization of american states
the battle for first place in the michigan caucuses will heat up the airwaves thursday as jesse jackson goes on television with an ad featuring bill cosby and michael dukakis counters with a radio ad featuring detroit mayor coleman young
jackson's campaign is spending about $90,000 in the last 48 hours before the saturday voting across the state, said spokeswoman pam smith
one of the major parts of the $70,000 television buy will be an ad featuring an endorsment by cosby, the popular television star. the ad was run first before the iowa caucuses and was run across the south before super tuesday
smith said the jackson television buy will be divided equally between detroit television and other markets across michigan. the $20,000 radio buy will be spread across the state she said
dukakis' campaign, which has already been on the air in michigan, will start running an ad featuring the endorsement of the massachusetts governor by young, detroit's longtime mayor. bob boorstein, a dukakis aide, said the radio ad will air on radio stations around the metropolitan area through saturday
dukakis has been running a biographical television ad for the last week in michigan. boorstein said the campaign added an ad emphasizing dukakis' executive experience _ contrasting that to the legislative experience of his rivals. dropouts</head>
north carolina should encourage students to finish high school by denying driver's licenses to people under the age of 18 who drop out, the lieutenant governor said tuesday
lt. gov. bob jordan, a democrat who plans to run against republican gov. jim martin in the nov. 8 general election, held a series of news conferences across the state to introduce a package aimed at reducing the state's dropout rate
jordan is expected to win the democratic nomination in the may 3 primary. martin has no opposition
a similar bill failed during the 1987 legislative session, but jordan said he was confident he could steer the measure through the democrat-dominated general assembly
jordan said martin had made no proposals to reduce the dropout rate although during his term nearly 100,000 youngsters _ one student in four _ have left school without a diploma
martin told reporters jordan's proposal was reasonable and interesting but said he did not know whether it would work
jordan said that if elected he would set a goal of halving the rate by 1992
the driver's license provision would give young people an incentive to remain in school, jordan said. under the proposed law, dropouts would have to wait until their 18th birthday to get a license, while those still in school could take the license test at age 16
the state of north carolina should do what a lot of parents do,'' he said. ``when their kids don't study or don't do well in school, they take away some privileges. some parents take away their car keys.''
jordan's package also includes hiring more guidance counselors and additional technical training
a cold front off the northern pacific coast on tuesday stirred up strong wind, while the central plains and southern third of the nation enjoyed unseasonable warmth
winds of 20 to 40 mph were common along the washington state coast, where a storm warning was in effect for coastal waters. a gale warning was posted for the oregon coast
a low pressure system over eastern south dakota produced strong northerly wind across western south dakota and the central high plains with speeds of 25 to 40 mph. a gust of 49 mph was clocked late tuesday morning at rapid city, s.d
strong southerly wind at 20 to 35 mph reached from central texas across eastern kansas and western and northern missouri into southeastern iowa and northern illinois
rain fell in western washington and oregon, with snow in the mountains expected to amount to 6 to 10 inches in the cascades
precipitation elsewhere was very light and spotty. clear to partly cloudy skies prevailed in the north and east
unseasonably warm weather extended across the southern third of the country and the central plains, with midday temperatures mostly in the 70s and low 80s
after some record cold temperatures for the date in the northeast on tuesday morning, a warming trend began in the afternoon and was expected to continue through wednesday. midday temperatures climbed into the upper 20s and 30s from the great lakes region to the northern atlantic coast
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est tuesday ranged from 23 degrees at saranac lake, n.y.; caribou, maine; and limestone, maine, to 88 degrees at palm springs, calif. the early-morning low was 15 degrees below zero at saranac lake, n.y
the national weather forecast for wednesday called for rain showers, with snow showers in the mountains, from the pacific northwest across the northern rockies. snow was predicted in parts of minnesota, scattered showers and thunderstorms in northeast texas across missouri into michigan, and scattered showers and rain from the lower great lakes through new england
high temperatures in the 30s and 40s were forecast across most of the northern tier of states, in the 70s and 80s across the southern third of the country, 90s in the southwest deserts, and in the 50s and 60s across most of the rest of the nation
danas, an influential weekly newspaper in zagreb, on tuesday called for pope john paul ii to visit communist yugoslavia
it said in an editorial, ``in slovenia there is not a single serious reason against a papal visit.... if there are reasons elsewhere against the pope's trip, then these should be dealt with in a public discussion.''
if john paul should come to yugoslavia, he probably would visit only slovenia and croatia, the two northern republics that are predominantly roman catholic, according to danas
at the annual meeting last week of the slovenian socialist alliance, a communist-led organization, alliance secretary-general joze smole said it was time to do ``everying possible'' to arrange a papal visit
danas noted allegations that croatian authorities were opposed to a papal visit and said the decision could not be made by one republic alone
it is expected that if the pope visits croatia, he would honor the late cardinal aloisius stepinac, who was convicted of collaborating with nazi troops in world war ii. the cardinal died under house arrest in his native village and his body was buried in the zagreb cathedral
danas said there have been 11 visits to the vatican in the past year by yugoslav state representatives, compared to one by a ranking catholic leader _ cardinal agostino casaroli's visit to djakovo, croatia, in 1985 to mark a st. method's anniversary
smole said yugoslavia ``should at least honor the principle of reciprocity in its relations with the holy see.''
government officials have said a papal visit could take place when agreement is reached on all conditions
there was speculation that such a visit was discussed when premier branko mikulic had a 30-minute audience with the pontiff on jan.30
danas said the clergy of the orthodox church and atheists probably ``would not gladly see the pope in yugoslavia, but the opposition does not come from these quarters alone
the situation in yugoslavia is so complex that a papal visit, unless it gained a kind of (national) consensus, would indeed become a motive for political showdowns.''
press conditions in haiti improved after the duvalier dictatorship fell, but a restrictive code and government intimidation still cause concern, the inter-american press association said tuesday
an iapa delegation said that after president jean-claude duvalier fled to exile in france in 1986, ending 29 years of harsh rule by the duvalier family, radio stations and newspapers flourished
local newspapers resumed political commentary. bans were lifted on newspapers published abroad by exiles. radio stations _ the main source of news in a country where illiteracy approaches 80 percent _ rehired staff members who had been deported or hounded into exile
when jean-claude duvalier fled haiti in february 1986, the media, like haitians in general, assumed that they had democracy and acted accordingly,'' harold hoyte, managing director of the barbados nation, told the iapa
haitian publishers, radio and tv station directors, opposition leaders and officials all agree that there was, in fact, almost total freedom,'' said hoyte, who traveled to haiti on march 17-18 and spoke with newly elected president leslie manigat and many others
the sense of journalistic freedom changed when the provisional government, a military-led junta, issued a press code in july 1986. it required journalists to have university degrees, declare news sources, and be accredited annually
haitian reporters told the delegation the code raised concern. they also expressed concern about recent communiques from the information ministry and armed forces cautioning the news media about publishing or broadcasting reports from abroad that might be perceived as negative to the image of haiti or its leaders
managers of newspapers, radio and television stations were almost unanimous that there is now self-censorship of certain news, and an awareness that to offend the army is to risk new repression,'' hoyte said
he said manigat supports the press code and ``brushed aside the delegation's arguments that the best press law would be no press law at all.''
in general, hoyte said, ``the delegation was satisfied that conditions for the press in haiti are much better than those under the duvalier dictatorship, but also notes with concern the atmosphere of intimidation and mistrust, and the prospect of a new press law which will maintain some of the present limitations.''
three delegation members stopped off in port-au-prince last week before going on the dominican republic for the iapa meeting. the others besides hoyte were wilbur landrey, foreign editor of the st. petersburg (fla.) times and chairman of the iapa freedom of the press committee, and iapa president ignacio lozano, editor of la opinion in los angeles, calif. threats</head>
a prosecutor accused of fabricating death threats against herself during extradition proceedings for two sikhs charged with terrorism gave fbi agents a description used to make a sketch of a suspect, a lawyer for the sikhs said tuesday
the fbi showed the sketch to several new jersey sikhs during an investigation of the threats against special assistant u.s. attorney judy g. russell, and one was ordered to appear before a federal grand jury, said lawyer ronald kuby
kuby represents sukhminder singh. he and ranjit singh gill are accused of terrorism in india
a federal magistrate ruled in february that gill and singh could be extradited. the hearings were conducted amid tight security partly prompted by the threats to ms. russell and an anonymous letter sent to the magistrate, ronald j. hedges
in a hearing before hedges on monday, u.s. attorney samuel a. alito jr. said there was evidence that ms. russell may have manufactured the threats
laboratory tests found the same typewriter was used to address the envelopes and to fill out ms. russell's application to the justice department in 1983. the typewriter was found in her home along with three similar letters in envelopes, as well as materials apparently used to make the letters out of words cut from newspapers and magazines, the prosecutor said
ms. russell, who left the u.s. attorney's office before the hearings began but handled the case as a special assistant, is in a private hospital. her attorney, robert j. fettweis, has declined to comment
federal authorities have said they would request a new extradition hearing to avoid the appearance of impropriety, and were considering how much of the proceedings should be repeated
kuby said tuesday he wanted all pretrial arguments repeated before a new magistrate and possibly outside of new jersey
at monday's hearing, alito said the allegations about ms. russell have no bearing on the case's final outcome
during the investigation into the threats, kuby said, one of his clients, amarvir ``sonny'' singh, was ordered to appear before a newark grand jury investigating the threats
they didn't question him, they just viewed him'' to see if he matched the sketch, kuby said. amarvir singh was later told by investigators not to return for a lineup, kuby said
the lawyer said agents told sikhs they interviewed that the sketch was based on ms. russell's description of a man who shouted a threat at her in a shopping mall
first assistant u.s. attorney michael chertoff said he would not comment on the shouted threat because it was not on the public record. fbi spokesman michael mines said he would not comment on a continuing investigation
jagjit singh mangat, president of the new york-based sikh cultural society, said fbi agents apologized to those who were questioned about the alleged threats
the allegations ``damaged the sikh community quite a bit,'' mangat said. ``everybody is looking at us as a terrorist, but we are not.''
justice department officials outside of the u.s. attorney's office in newark are investigating the russell case, and have the power to pursue an indictment, chertoff said
here are tuesday's major developments in central america:
panama city _ gen. manuel antonio noriega's opponents scorned an offer to negotiate his resignation and kept panama shut down with a general strike intended to force him out. an estimated 90 percent of business and industry was closed, and many government employees stated home
sapoa, nicaragua _ negotiators for the sandinistas and contra rebels said they exchanged proposals that agree on major points and envisage an extended cease-fire, amnesty and release of political prisoners. they began three days of meetings monday at this town on the costa rican border. defense minister humberto ortega told reporters he expected a ``concrete agreement'' would be reached wednesday
washington _ president reagan sought to revive his stalled effort to aid the contras and said congressional democrats would be at fault if the rebel movement ceased to exist for lack of supplies. the last aid package ran out feb. 29
tegucigalpa, honduras _ a u.s. military spokesman said american soldiers, sent to honduras for emergency training after nicaraguan soldiers were accused of crossing the border last week to attack contras, will stay on to complete the maneuvers. ``right now the plans are to make it a 10- to 14-day exercise,'' maj. gary hovatter said
a judge on tuesday gave bishop college two months to come up with $200,000, but rejected a motion to take the struggling school out of protection of bankruptcy court
u.s. bankruptcy court trustee george mcelreath had sought to dismiss the school's chapter 11 reorganization petition. that would have left bishop vulnerable to lawsuits from its 400 creditors, who are owed more than $12.5 million
u.s. bankruptcy court judge robert mcguire, in denying mcelreath's motion, ordered the school to raise $50,000 every two weeks beginning april 5. if the school cannot prove it has the cash on hand within three days of each deadline, he will reconsider the motion to dismiss the chapter 11 petition
it's a good deal,'' said bishop attorney t. glover roberts. ``it's incentive for the school, especially the students, to do something.''
roberts said the school, which has failed to meet its payroll for two months, has operating expenses of $200,000 a month and would not have survived if the trustee's motion had been granted
bishop is in a deeper and deeper financial hole,'' roberts said
observers in the packed courtroom, mostly bishop students and faculty, applauded mcguire's ruling. afterward, many joined in singing the school's alma mater in the courthouse lobby
judith swift, attorney for bishop's largest creditor, its faculty-staff committee, praised the judge's ruling
clearly the debtor is in violation on matters of legal concern, but law is about equity, too,'' swift said. ``the equity here is the human concerns of the students and faculty.''
swift told the judge that 28 of the school's approximately 50 faculty and staff members had agreed to work without pay for the rest of the term if bishop was allowed to stay open
only two creditors joined mcelreath's motion to dismiss the chapter 11 protection
though he rejected the motion, the judge said mcelreath was right to carry out his duty as court-appointed trustee to point out bishop's violations of the bankruptcy filing. the most notable, the judge said, was the accrual of nearly $700,000 in new debt since the school filed for protection last may
school officials are hoping for aid from the u.s. department of education, which is expected to decide next week whether to renew $400,000 in funding for the school. that funding was lost last year when the southern association of colleges and schools failed to renew bishop's academic accreditation because of its financial problems
bishop's board of trustees voted earlier tuesday to allow conversion of the school's bankruptcy filing from chapter 11 to chapter 7 at the end of the spring semester in late may unless the school's dire financial situation changes
under chapter 7, bishop would close and its assets would be sold to pay creditors
school officials are also working to get back $150,000 from two churches that recently withdrew donations. the churches backed out after dallas businessman clifford sugerman reneged on a $300,000 pledge
sugerman had promised to match donations up to that amount
sugerman, whose chapter 13 bankruptcy petition filed in 1985 is still an open case, gave no reason for dropping the pledge and his sugarman foundation is now under investigation by the state attorney general's office
bishop college, affiliated with the national baptist churches, was founded as a college for blacks in 1861. it currently has about 300 students
foreign minister r.f. botha apologized on behalf of the government tuesday for a police search of the west german consul's home, but also criticized west germany's policies
police searched the home of erhard loeser, west germany's acting consul-general, on monday. they were looking for heinrich grosskopf, a 24-year-old white south african accused of a car-bombing last week that killed three people
officials claim grosskopf carried out that bombing and at least one other on orders from the outlawed african national congress, the predominantly black guerrilla group fighting to end domination by south africa's white minority
botha gave no reason why police decided to search loeser's home and coupled his apology with an attack on foreign minister hans-dietrich genscher of west germany for suggesting a boycott of south african products as a means of protesting the apartheid racial policy
he said the suggestion was ``callously irresponsible'' and a boycott would ``deprive people of their livelihood.''
the foreign minister also criticized genscher for questioning the fairness of legal proceedings for the ``sharpeville six,'' a group of blacks granted a one-month stay of execution last week. they were convicted of complicity in the mob killing of a black official
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which south africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. and 2 grafs after 22nd graf pvs, bgng: ``senate gop ...'' to update with moral majority comment.</note>
congress overrode president reagan's veto of a major civil rights bill tuesday, ending a four-year battle to restore broad protection for women, minorities, the elderly and the handicapped
a 73-24 vote in the senate, followed by a 292-133 tally in the house, handed reagan a severe political defeat and reversed a 1984 supreme court decision that sharply restricted the reach of four anti-discrimination statutes
the votes in both chambers exceeded the two-thirds majority needed to enact a law over a presidential veto. it was the ninth time congress had rejected a reagan veto
the white house pledged to enforce the new law, which reagan had called a federal ``power grab.''
we presented an alternative civil rights act which stated the president's strong views against discrimination in this country,'' a white house statement said. ``the congress chose to override the president's veto. we will work to implement the new law.''
people who voluntarily take federal funds have an obligation to treat everybody else fairly,'' said rep. barney frank, d-mass., summing up the rationale of lawmakers who have been pressing for the civil rights restoration act since the high court ruling
the moral majority, which had campaigned against the bill, said after the vote that the legislation would cause ``severe damage to the free exercise of religion'' and ``will put at risk our other guaranteed freedoms.''
the court said only specific programs or activities receiving federal aid had to comply with four major civil rights laws
the restoration act bars discrimination by institutions, government agencies and some corporations that receive any federal aid. that means if a college physics department, for example, receives federal assistance, the entire college would fall under the civil rights laws
reagan and his congressional allies argued for a less sweeping alternative, saying the act went far beyond simple restoration. they said it would curtail religious liberty and expand federal control over the private sector
it's a blank check to the bureaucrats and the litigators,'' said rep. james sensenbrenner, r-wis
but house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said in a statement that reagan's veto was ``wholly unnecessary and it provoked an unnecessary confrontation. the new law will not end illegal discrimination. but it does represent a step forward in making america truly a land of equal opportunity for all.''
supporters in the house erupted into cheers and applause when the two-thirds mark was reached. in the senate, the mood was more subdued
sen. edward kennedy, d-mass., chief senate sponsor of the bill, said the senate had demonstrated that ``this country does not want to retreat on protections of rights for the american people.''
the opposition leader, sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, said: ``sometimes you win some and sometimes you lose some. that's the nature of our process.''
ralph neas, executive director of the 185-group leadership conference on civil rights, called the votes ``a bipartisan reaffirmation of civil rights and a bipartisan repudiation of the civil rights extremism of the reagan-bush administration. it was a great victory for civil rights and for the nation.''
the u.s. chamber of commerce, however, said the bill ``does little to protect these basic rights'' and may end up ``imposing unncessary regulatory burdens'' on businesses, farmers and others
opponents contended the bill had little to do with civil rights and had much to do with what reagan on tuesday called ``a power grab by washington, designed to take control away from states, localities, communities, parents and the private sector and give it to federal bureaucrats and judges.''
reagan had proposed an alternative last week that would enable more institutions to escape regulation on religious grounds and limit most corporate compliance requirements to specific plants or facilities receiving federal aid
as they voted tuesday, many lawmakers, even some who voted to sustain reagan's veto, denounced a last-minute campaign against the restoration act by the conservative moral majority
they said they received hundreds of calls from people who said they had been told the bill would force them to hire homosexual ministers and teachers, give new privileges to drug addicts and intrude on their freedom to practice or contribute to their religions
rarely has the legislative process been subjected to such a campaign of misinformation and distortion,'' said sen. george mitchell, d-maine
senate gop leader bob dole of kansas and acting gop leader alan simpson of wyoming also criticized the campaign. simpson said he was concerned about erroneous claims that ``massive new rights'' would be created, while dole said in a statement that there were ``serious misconceptions about what this bill does.''
jerry c. nims, president of moral majority, said in a statement after the vote that the override is likely to be ``the major political issue for evangelicals in the 1988 elections.''
if enough people are not voted into office to change what's occurred, we will have entered the moral dark ages,'' nims said
dole, who was absent for the initial vote, was on the campaign trail tuesday for the gop presidential nomination and did not vote then either. on a radio call-in show in milwaukee, dole said he would vote to override the veto if he were in washington. but he added, ``if it were the deciding vote, i would side with the president.''
eight gop senators who initially voted for the bill switched tuesday and supported reagan. they were simpson, thad cochran of mississippi, paul trible of virginia, john warner of virginia, larry pressler of south dakota, charles grassley of iowa, john danforth of missouri and christopher bond of missouri
in addition, two senators who didn't vote last time _ sens. malcolm wallop of wyoming and james mcclure of idaho _ sided with the president
the supreme court ruling came in a challenge to federal regulation mounted by tiny grove city college in pennsylvania. in its attempts to reverse the decision, congress became enmeshed in controversies over abortion, religions and federal intrusion and was unable to pass a corrective measure until this year
the restoration act says entire institutions and government agencies must not discriminate if any program or activity within them receives federal aid. entire corporations are covered if they provide a public service such as health care or if the aid goes to the business as a whole, as in the chrysler corp. bailout
farmers receiving crop subsidies, people using food stamps and other individuals receiving federal assistance would not be subject to regulation. an institution's refusal to perform or pay for abortions would not be considered discrimination against women
the supreme court decision applied specifically to title ix of the 1972 education amendments barring sex discrimination in federally funded education programs. it was interpreted also to cover the 1964 civil rights act barring racial discrimination in federally assisted programs; the 1973 rehabilitation act barring discrimination against the handicapped in any program or activity receiving federal aid; and the 1975 age discrimination act barring employment discrimination against older people. update with dukakis endorsements</note>
democratic presidential contenders paul simon and albert gore jr. broke off campaigning tuesday long enough to return to their senate desks and vote to override president reagan's veto of a civil rights bill. republican contender bob dole stayed away and straddled the issue
with saturday's michigan caucuses looming as the next campaign test for the democrats, rep. richard gephardt attacked michael dukakis for a ``battlefield conversion'' on trade issues so important to the automotive industry. dukakis aides retorted that the massachusetts governor has long been in favor of trade legislation, just not gephardt's proposal
jesse jackson was in michigan, too, turning his anti-drug crusade into a slap at the reagan administration's central american policy. ``the no. 1 threat to your lives today is drugs,'' he told a high school audience in lansing. ``we're not threatened by 3 million sandinistas and if so, can't be saved from them by 15,000 contras.''
dukakis, at the massachusetts statehouse in boston, did change his stance on one issue, agreeing tuesday to support a ban on furloughs for first-degree murderers after public pressure stemming from the release of a murderer who raped a maryland woman
i try to listen, i try to learn,'' said dukakis, who previously had called the furlough program for murderers essential for maintaining order in the state's prisons
later, dukakis made a trip to connecticut to pick up endorsements from sen. christopher dodd and gov. william o'neill. o'neill predicted dukakis would do ``extremely well'' in next week's primary
sources said dukakis also would win the backing on wednesday of new jersey sen. bill bradley, whose name crops up consistently in speculation about a darkhorse emerging as the democratic nominee in a deadlocked convention
that would leave new york gov. mario cuomo alone among the prominent non-candidates who has yet to make an endorsement
an abc news poll suggested a matchup between dukakis and vice president george bush in the general election could be a close race. the network tuesday night its nationwide poll of 1,007 people gave dukakis 48 percent and bush 47 percent. the margin of error was 3.5 percent, abc said
bush was in washington during the day, and the only other gop hopeful, pat robertson, was cutting his staff to avoid exceeding a federal spending limit. aide connie snapp said the payroll has been cut from a maximum of 230 to about 100, and another 30 or 40 aides may be released later in the month
reagan's veto of the civil rights bill and the democratic-controlled congress' attempt to override dominated the political news during the day. the senate voted 75-24 to overturn the president's veto, more than the two-thirds majority needed. the house also voted to override, 292-133
simon, who is hoping to win the wisconsin primary on april 5, said he sponsored the legislation in 1984 when it was first introduced
this is something that ought to appeal to the basic good instincts of every member of the senate and the house,'' he said. he said the issue involved is, ``are we going to make real the dream of equality in the constitution?''
gore returned to washington from harrisburg, pa., after collecting endorsements from several legislative leaders. he also met with gov. robert casey, but came away without an endorsement
gore used the civil rights bill to attack bush, the prohibitive front-runner for the republican nomination. gore said bush, who announced monday that he supported reagan's veto of the measure, always sides with the president, ``even when the proposals are unfathomably dumb.''
when push comes to shove the vice president never disagrees with president reagan,'' he said, adding that bush didn't disagree with selling arms to iran for hostages or in keeping panama strongman manuel noriega on the cia payroll despite evidence of drug involvement
bush's top campaign spokesman, pete teeley, dismissed suggestions that bush would begin looking for an issue to disagree with reagan on, just to prove his independence
the fact is, six months ago everybody was writing that george bush had to disagree with the president in order to get the nomination. everyone now sees that that was a myth,'' the spokesman said
far, far behind in the republican presidential race, dole said he stayed in wisconsin rather than return for the senate vote because ``i wasn't needed.''
he said he was personally opposed to the president's veto. but asked on a milwaukee radio station call-in program, he said, ``but if it were the deciding vote, i would side with the president.''
dole, who was attacked by bush earlier in the campaign for not taking firm stands on issues such as arms control and tax increases, placed a formal statement in the senate record that did not take a precise stand
in part it said, ``i have always supported legislation to overturn grove city to restore the broad civil rights coverage that existed prior to that case. ... at the same time, i recognize that (the bill) is not a perfect bill. i am not fully satisfied with it... but the fact remains that the administration and its congressional allies had the opportunity to offer amendments and they were voted down.''
dole was absent when the bill passed the senate originally in january
the legislation stems from a 1984 supreme court ruling that says an organization receiving federal aid must follow anti-discrimination rules only for the program that receives the aid, and not for the entire organization or institution. the legislation would erase that distinction
gephardt's repeated jabs at dukakis centered on the trade issue that is central to his own campaign. the missouri congressman is the sponsor of legislation calling for retaliation against unfair trading practices. dukakis opposes the gephardt provision but declared a few days ago that he favors a different proposal backed by sen. don riegle _ the michigan senator who bestowed his endorsement on monday
we're getting some battlefield conversions,'' gephardt said. observers</head>
nicaragua told the security council tuesday the united states is plotting an invasion of that central american nation
honduras, meanwhile, rejected nicaragua's call for u.n. observers to visit the honduran-nicaraguan border, where there was fighting last week between soldiers of the leftist sandinista government and u.s.-backed contra rebels
nicaraguan envoy rita delia casco, said of the alleged u.s. plot:
the danger is not past. indeed, it is growing. america plans to provide a central american gulf of tonkin incident to serve as a pretext for direct invasion and escalation of intimidation and threats.''
the united states sent 3,200 soldiers to honduras last week at the request of the honduran president, who accused nicaraguan soldiers of penetrating honduran territory while chasing the rebels. president reagan said the u.s. move was to show support of honduras and as a warning to nicaragua
ms. casco, director of the foreign ministry's department of international organizations, said the situation ``points to the possibility of imminent imperialist military action on a broad scale.''
the gulf of tonkin incident occurred when washington said north vietnamese boats attacked two u.s. destroyers in that waterway on aug. 2, 1964. congress passed the gulf of tonkin resolution five days later and the united states began a military buildup in south vietnam that led to major american involvement in the vietnam war
a four-member u.n. team was leaving tuesday night to inspect the nicaraguan side of the border with honduras
u.n. spokesman francois giuliani told reporters that honduras turned down a u.n. offer to send observers to that country
honduran ambassador jorge ramon hernandez told the council a u.n. team was not necessary because the five central american presidents, in a regional peace plan signed last august, had set up an executive committee to verify compliance with the accord
hernandez said sandinista troops invaded honduras and his nation had the right to self-defense
our military response has been limited so far and the international assistance we are asking for basically has a deterrent nature,'' he said
honduran jets raided nicaraguan positions last week in the bocay region, which straddles the border between the two countries. no injuries were reported
on sunday honduran officials said the nicaraguans were withdrawing and the u.s. troops would leave the country soon. maj. gary hovatter, a u.s. military spokesman in honduras, said tuesday that the american troops were conducting training exercises that could last from 10 to 14 days
u.s. ambassador herbert s. okun, the deputy permanent representative at the u.n., told the council that nicaragua had launched a massive attack against the rebels, who have base camps in honduras
the sandinistas committed aggression against honduras,'' he said. ``it was not the other way around.''
okun said the sandinistas retreated into nicaragua without crushing the rebels because honduras reacted forcefully and the united states demonstrated its determination to help honduras
he said stability will return to central america only when nicaragua complies with the regional peace plan and gives up ``its self-appointed right to subvert neighboring democracies and to launch premeditated attacks.''
president francois mitterrand, who said tuesday he will seek re-election next month, has managed in one seven-year term to be both the least and most popular chief executive in the 30 years of the fifth republic
mitterrand, 71, led the leftist surge in may 1981 that ousted president valery giscard d'estaing and the center-right alliance that had controlled the national assembly for 23 years
the victory avenged socialist mitterrand's defeats in the presidential elections of 1965 by charles de gaulle and 1974 by giscard d'estaing
after five years, french voters turned against the socialists in the march 1986 parliamentary elections and returned control to the right _ creating what became known in france as ``cohabitation'' between a socialist president and a conservative premier
socialist policies had dragged mitterrand's popularity rating in public opinion polls as low as 27 percent, but under the unwanted marriage with the conservatives it soared again to a consistent 55 percent or more
the president pursued costly social programs after the socialists gained power, but then reversed course, instituting austerity measures
economic troubles brought his party to power, and caused its downfall five years later. after the socialist defeat, mitterrand eased into the role of elder statesman and held himself above the day-to-day battles of governing, commenting on issues only occasionally
he was born oct. 26, 1916, in jarnac in western france and attended universities in paris, earning degrees in law and letters. he was drafted into the army in 1938, and shot and captured during the german invasion in may 1940
mitterrand escaped from a prison camp in germany, returned to france and created a resistance network. his long feud with de gaulle began when mitterrand refused to unite his resistance group with de gaulle's
it was in the resistance days that he met danielle gouze, and they married in 1944, soon after france was liberated. he held several government posts, including interior and justice minister, during the chaotic postwar fourth republic
in the early 1970s he built the moribund socialist party into a major political force, but the union of the left he formed with the communists fell apart in 1977
not until the final days of the 1981 campaign did the two main leftist parties join forces again to defeat giscard and oust the conservatives
mitterrand shocked much of the west by bringing communists into his government, but the union lasted only three years. in 1984, the communists pulled out in a dispute over economic policy. climax</head> update with hearing in recess until wednesday. picks up 4th graf pvs, `even though...'. a longer version moved on financial wires.</note>
dissident stockholders dropped their opposition to texaco inc.'s financial reorganization plan tuesday as a federal judge opened a hearing on whether to implement the proposal
texaco, the nation's third-largest oil company, announced that 96 percent of the shares voted, 174 million of 181 million, backed the plan, which would allow the company to emerge from bankruptcy court protection
after receiving the vote results, u.s. bankruptcy court judge howard schwartzberg heard comments on the plan, but no one opposed it
later, he recessed the hearing until wednesday morning
even though the plan received more than the two-thirds vote needed from shareholders, the final decision on whether the plan was fair and equitable rested with schwartzberg
if schwartzberg confirms the plan, texaco could emerge from bankruptcy protection by mid-april, which would be a year after it sought protection from creditors under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code
texaco was the biggest company ever to seek refuge in the bankruptcy courts
shortly before the hearing, harvey miller, the bankruptcy lawyer representing texaco, announced that attorneys for dissident shareholders had dropped their opposition to the reorganization plan
those stockholders had objected to provisions that would free officers and advisers of texaco, pennzoil co., the former getty oil co., the sarah getty trust and the j. paul getty museum from all liability arising out of the court fight that resulted from a texaco-pennzoil battle over getty oil
texaco said it was forced into bankruptcy court by a requirement that it post a multibillion-dollar bond while appealing the $10.3 billion judgment held against it by pennzoil
a houston jury had awarded the judgment in november 1985 after finding texaco had interfered wrongly with pennzoil's agreement to acquire part of getty oil before texaco bought getty itself
in december, pennzoil agreed to accept $3 billion in cash from texaco to drop the judgment. the settlement was the keystone of the overall bankruptcy reorganization plan, which would require texaco to pay its other creditors an additional $2.5 billion
while some shareholders first opposed dropping liability for executives in the pennzoil matter, others were unhappy with anti-takeover provisions of texaco's charter and bylaws that they argued entrenched management and lessened accountability
the leader of the latter group was takeover specialist carl c. icahn, who controls 14.8 percent of texaco's common stock, making him the company's largest shareholder. despite his opposition to those provisions, however, he had said he would vote for the reorganization plan
icahn's involvement _ along with reported interest by fellow takeover artist t. boone pickens and others _ made texaco a prime target for takeover speculation in recent weeks
the company cleared another obstacle on friday when it announced it had reached a framework for resolving a dispute with the internal revenue service
in january, the irs said it was pursuing claims totaling as much as $6.5 billion against texaco. but friday texaco said it would put into escrow $1 billion over the next four years while negotiating the dispute after emerging from bankruptcy reorganization
demonstrators protesting against the state grand jury in the tawana brawley case met counter-demonstrators for the first time on tuesday, while at least two protesters scuffled with police
there were no arrests
roughly 100 marchers led by the rev. al sharpton and brawley family lawyer c. vernon mason gathered outside chanting, ``governor cuomo, haven't you heard? this is not johannesburg.'' that group was predominantly black
about 75 whites, who at first watched silently, began to shout back. ``get tawana to testify. we care too,'' some of them said
there was no scuffling between the two groups
miss brawley, a black 16-year-old, claims she was kidnapped and sexually assaulted by at least six white men during four days in november. mason and another attorney, alton maddox jr., have advised their client not to cooperate with investigators
sharpton's group had promised to disrupt grand jury proceedings in the case. about 50 people from new york city joined as many local residents tuesday morning for a march from the mid-hudson bridge
later, members of sharpton's group attempted to push through a line of police who stood shoulder to shoulder in front of the doors of a state armory, where the grand jury has been meeting. at least two protesters struggled with police and were taken into a van, but were released and allowed to return
if it comes necessary for arrests to be made, we'll make them,'' police chief stewart bowles said. ``i'd rather not.''
despite temperatures which hovered near 30 degrees, sharpton said his group would stay all night or even several days until the grand jury was disbanded. some 15 to 20 protesters remained at the scene at midevening
a spokesman for attorney general robert abrams would not say if the grand jury was meeting tuesday, but there was no sign of grand jury activity
gov. mario cuomo selected abrams to investigate and, if necessary, prosecute the case
at one time, sharpton, maddox and mason had insisted that abrams personally handle the case. they have since demanded a special prosecutor, but cuomo has refused
maddox says abrams has violated the law by disclosing certain facts about the grand jury, such as the instructions it received, its purpose for forming and its makup. he said state law requires that grand jury proceedings be secret
this story is from a report filed by richard pyle, a member of the pentagon media pool in the persian gulf
the u.s. navy is preparing to shepherd its 40th convoy through the persian gulf war zone and officers say alertness is as high as when the operation began eight months ago
they said, however, that a permanent high level of alertness takes a toll on the crew
the hardest part of the mission is that you have to stay ready 24 hours a day. there's no time, really, to let your guard down,'' said cmdr. paul rinn, 40, of the bronx, n.y
he commands this missile frigate, one of 16 navy ships serving in the escort and patrol squadron called the middle east force
rinn spoke with members of a pentagon news media pool tuesday on the bridge of his ship, one of the navy's newest perry-class frigates
soon afterward, officers in the combat information center were monitoring radio traffic about an iranian attack on a commercial vessel off dubai, 90 miles away
messages said the greek-flagged tanker stavros g.l. was attacked at 2:45 p.m. approximately 30 miles north of dubai and was on fire
the u.s. frigate jack williams, a sister ship to the roberts, went to the tanker's aid from about nine miles away. the williams rescued 14 crewmen in a lifeboat, according to lt. cmdr. mark van dyke, a navy spokesman
when the fire was under control, the tanker's skipper asked that the crew be returned to the ship, van dyke said
it was believed to be the third time a u.s. warship gave ``humanitarian assistance'' to a ship attacked by iranian gunboats in the gulf. the last was christmas day when the uss elrod rescued crewmen from a burning vessel in the southern gulf
iran has attacked seven neutral ships in the gulf since friday. iraq has raided a similar number of iranian owned or chartered tankers beginning earlier in march. iraq and iran have been at war since september 1980
the roberts, a 445-foot vessel launched two years ago, began its latest mission after a three-day resupply stop and the first liberty for the 209-man crew since arriving in the gulf nearly a month ago
soon after entering international waters tuesday, rinn ordered the crew to general quarters to ``clear the mind'' after the port call
they test-fired defensive gun systems as part of the effort to renew vigilance
on its last mission in the northern gulf, the $400 million warship had a series of ``close encounters'' with iraqi aircraft, the captain said
from 30 to 40 iraqi air missions came near his ship en route to attacks on iranian vessels, rinn said, including three mirage f-1s armed with exocet missiles that flew wing-to-wing 50 feet above the water
he said the jets came within five miles of the roberts, heading away and not demonstrating hostile intent
you can basically say we were a blink of an eye away from anything that could happen,'' rinn said
i'm never going to allow my ship to be shot at and hit,'' said rinn, adding the fate of another sister ship, the uss stark, ``is not lost on us.'' the stark lost 37 of its crew when hit by an iraqi exocet missile last may 17. held, changes to conform grafs 1-7. pick up 8th graf pvs, in catholic west belfast...</note>
a protestant gunman who attacked a funeral for ira guerrillas last week was charged tuesday with murder in the killings of six roman catholics, including three who died in the cemetery onslaught
michael stone, 33, was taken to court under heavy guard and police testimony said stone told officers his ``military operation'' was in retaliation for attacks by the outlawed irish republican army
police quoted stone as telling interrogators, ``i alone carried out this military operation as a retaliatory strike against provisional sinn fein, the ira, in response to the slaughter of innocents at la mon, darkley, brighton and enniskillen,'' referring to some ira attacks in the last decade
he stood silently in the dock through the 10-minute hearing while a police officer also testified that stone told detectives: ``i would state i am a dedicated free-lance loyalist (protestant) paramilitary. no surrender.''
stone was charged with killing three people march 16 at a funeral in milltown for three ira members shot by british security forces in gibraltar. an alleged accomplice is being held by police. he has not been identified
stone also is accused of killing three other catholics shot in sniper attacks between november 1984 and may 1987. the victims were a milkman, a bread delivery man and a carpenter, none with known ira links
an outlawed protestant guerrilla group, the ulster freedom fighters, claimed responsibility for each of those murders
in catholic west belfast, where british authorities ordered a ``massive murder investigation'' after the killing of two british soldiers during another ira funeral on saturday, police erected road blocks at main roads into the ghetto
british soldiers, rifles in hand, patrolled the streets
police sources say up to 30 suspects have been identified from an army video and tv footage of saturday's rampage
a funeral mob dragged the soldiers from their unmarked car, stripped and beat them. they were shot out of sight of the cameras in a soccer stadium
in london, prime minister margaret thatcher attacked britain's two television networks, the british broadcasting corp. and independent television news, for refusing to give police their unscreened film of the horrifying scenes. the networks said handing over the film would endanger the lives of their crews
either one is on the side of justice in this matter or on the side of terrorism,'' mrs. thatcher said in the house of commons as her rank-and-file supporters clamored for the government to seek a court order to force the networks to yield their film
government sources said lawyers were considering legal moves
the two soldiers, whom the army has acknowledged should not have been in the area, were attacked after they drove up to the funeral cortege
some of the tense crowd apparently suspected another protestant assault following the gun and grenade attack at milltown catholic cemetery
