foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov said the four were among 13 soviet military advisers captured in ethiopia last week by forces fighting the leftist government to establish an independent eritrean state
gerasimov told reporters at a news briefing that the eritrean people's liberation front recently ``has intensified combat operations.''
he said nine of the soviets captured returned to their command posts, three were identified by their captors as prisoners of war and one remained missing
ethiopia has strong political ties to the soviet union
gerasimov had no details of the incident or the conditions in which the soviets are being held
eritrea, a former italian colony on the red sea, was administered by britain from world war ii until 1952 when it was federated with ethiopia under a u.n. resolution. ethiopia incorporated it as a province in 1962, touching off a rebellion for independence
some eritrean groups have signed an agreement to unite, but not the eritrean popular liberation front, which is composed mainly of urban-born christians
according to the international institute for strategic studies military balance 1987-88 edition, there are an estimated 1,400 soviet technicians and advisers in ethiopia. an estimated 2,500 cuban combat troops also are in ethiopia supporting the addis ababa government
