legislators voted tuesday to keep the presidential system of federal government rather than switch to the parliamentary structure with a prime minister. president jose sarney called the action ``an important victory.''
sarney said the 344-212 vote by the lawmakers rewriting the constitution was ``better for the country. congress understood that.''
later tuesday, legislators approved a five-year term for presidents, rejecting by 305-223 a proposal to set the term at four years
the present presidential term is for six years, and sarney was installed in office in 1985
sarney had opposed a change to the parliamentary system, saying it would bring further economic and social chaos
opponents argued that a parliamentary structure was an option for the nation that emerged in 1985 from 21 years of military rule
presidentialism doesn't exist and doesn't work anywhere but the united states,'' said sen. affonso arinos of the liberal front party. ``military, authoritarian and dictatorial regimes emerged mostly because of presidentialism in brazil.''
leftist legislators opposed to sarney backed the presidential system. but they also demanded direct presidential elections this year with sarney stepping down in march 1989. sarney said he would leave office in 1990
we didn't want a queen of england, we want elections, direct elections this year,'' said rep. jose genoino of the leftist workers' party
the lawmakers have been meeting since february 1986 to rewrite the constitution
sarney, 57, was elected vice president in a 1985 electoral college election organized by the outgoing military regime. but president-elect tancredo neves died before inauguration in march 1985 and sarney took power as the nation's first civilian president since a 1964 military coup
brazilians have not voted directly for the presidency since 1960
gerhard claas, general secretary of the baptist world alliance, has died from injuries sustained in a traffic accident near lodi, calif., the alliance announced tuesday
claas, 59, was the chief administrative officer of the alliance, an international baptist organization which has a membership of more than 35 million worldwide. the organization conducts teaching, development and disaster relief efforts in third world nations
claas was traveling in california to a series of fund-raising meetings when the car in which he was riding collided monday with a truck on a rural road in san joaquin county near lodi, 80 miles northeast of san francisco
he died later in the day. two other people, the rev. mervyn betts, 74, and his wife nora, 67, of san francisco, also were injured, sheriff's deputies said
claas was a citizen of west germany, where he had served in a number of pastoral and administrative posts
claas is survived by his wife, the formed irmgard saffran, of mclean, va., and three children: regina, gabriele claas gloeckner, and martin, who live in west germany. papers</head>
a judge ruled tuesday that harvard university was entitled to papers of the late playwright tennessee williams after harvard attorneys promised that earnings from any publication would benefit his sister
williams, the author of plays including ``a streetcar named desire'' and ``cat on a hot tin roof,'' died in 1983 at age 71
the hearing, one of the final steps in distribution of the williams estate, came after harvard objected to a plan by southeast bank in miami, which holds the papers as executor of the estate, to give the manuscripts ``in trust'' to harvard
the trustees for the 78-year-old sister, rose williams, wanted the papers given ``in trust'' so the actual manuscripts could be sold if she needed additional money for medical and living expenses
she has been institutionalized for 53 years in ossining, n.y., having undergone a lobotomy to relieve an unstable mental condition. many of williams' plays are said to reflect the special tenderness and concern he felt for his sister and others who are lonely or mentally disabled
the university held that it had the right to clear physical possession of the documents and monroe county circuit judge helio gomez agreed, saying he found no limitation in williams' will on giving the papers to the school
harvard attorney frank connors assured miss williams' trustees that if anything had commercial value, she would have the benefit
attorney jim hendrick, who represents miss williams' trustees, told the judge that contents of some of the papers ``may be scandalous, and may make reference to persons still living
they may not be appropriate to make public at this time,'' hendrick said
the papers, reportedly appraised at $175,000, include sealed envelopes said to contain manuscripts such as the one that later evolved into ``the rose tattoo,'' and the first draft of ``sweet bird of youth'' as well as written notes and notebooks of various kinds, hendrick said
they include various plays and manuscripts, including some that have not been published, he said
the estate was valued in the millions and has been distributed gradually since his death, but hendrick declined to place a value on the overall estate
hendrick said the question about the papers was the last contested portion of the will of which he was aware. he predicted that legal procedures surrounding distribution of the estate should be concluded in the next month
u.s. and honduran troops will hold joint maneuvers now that nicaragua has withdrawn its soldiers from the honduran border and halted fighting for truce talks with the contra rebels
nicaragua announced monday its troops had withdrawn from the border, and the honduran military reported sandinista soldiers had retreated
col. manuel suarez benevides, the honduran armed forces spokesman, said monday the 3,200 u.s. troops that rushed to honduras after a reported incursion by 2,000 sandinista troops won't be needed much longer. ``it'll be a very short time. we're talking days only,'' he said in an interview
the u.s. troops were to begin a new set of joint maneuvers with the honduran army today, according to a u.s. military spokesman. details of the exercises were not made public
strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega offered to resign before the may 1989 presidential election if opponents agree to talks with his regime, but the opposition and the united states rejected the offer
the general has to go immediately _ not eventually,'' said aurelio barria, head of the national civic crusade, an opposition umbrella group. ``there will be no dialogue with him.''
in washington, the state department also dismissed noriega's resignation offer as ``little more than ... a ploy'' to keep noriega's cronies in power and the general in control of the armed forces
noreiga should go, and the sooner the better for panama,'' said state department spokeswoman anita stockman
the supreme court is considering whether abused children should have the right to sue public officials for failing to protect them from their parents
but the justices have decided to avoid another children's rights issue: whether public school students enjoy any constitutional protection against paddling or other corporal punishment by teachers and administrators
the court announced monday that it will tackle the parental abuse issue in the case of a wisconsin boy, joshua deshaney, who suffered serious and permanent brain damage from beatings by his father
nearly a year after texaco inc. filed for bankruptcy protection, the nation's third-largest oil company faces an uncertain future clouded by corporate raiders, tax bills and its legal fight with pennzoil co
the final phase of texaco's historic bankruptcy case was expected to begin today in white plains, with the opening of court hearings that could lead to final approval of the company's reorganization plan
u.s. bankruptcy court judge howard schwartzberg was expected to announce the results of a shareholder vote on the plan, then hear final arguments by interested parties. if schwartzberg confirms the plan, texaco could emerge from bankruptcy protection by mid-april
texaco filed for chapter 11 protection from its creditors on april 12. it was the biggest u.s. company ever to do so. texaco claimed it was forced into the move by a requirement that it post a multibillion-dollar bond while appealing a $10.3 billion judgment held against it by pennzoil
the disclosure that a former federal prosecutor may have fabricated death threats against herself and a magistrate during an extradition case has shocked her former colleagues
on monday, u.s. attorney samuel a. alito jr. said that judy russell allegedly cut out words from newspapers to form threatening messages that she received in the mail during the case she was handling against two sikhs accused of terrorism in india
a search of her house turned up similar threatening messages in a travel bag and scissors apparently used to clip newspapers and magazines, alito said. news digest: washington _ civil rights; panama city, panama _ panama; sapoa, nicaragua _ nicaragua-talks; san salvador, el salvador _ salvador-assess; washington _ us-soviet; undated _ political rdp; washington _ high-tech candidate; phoenix, ariz. _ mecham; jerusalem _ israel. ^by the associated press</note>
higher postage rates, including a 25-cent charge for first-class letters, will take effect april 3, the postal service announced tuesday
the postal service has been managing the costs of operating a growing universal delivery system and moving a volume of mail that has nearly doubled'' to more than 160 billion pieces this year, said john l. griesemer, chairman of the postal service board of governors
the new rates reflect higher costs of delivering mail, griesemer said. ``to all our customers, we can only repeat our pledge of better service,'' he said
senior administration officials believe panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega will be forced from office shortly because of growing opposition to his rule in the panamanian defense forces
the officials, speaking only on condition they not be named, said the anti-noriega sentiment within the military has been accelerating over the past week and is probably the most important factor working against his survival as defense chief
they said noriega's efforts to overcome the crisis probably were not helped with his conditional offer monday night to resign before the may 1989 presidential elections
president reagan sought tuesday to revive his stalled effort to aid the nicaraguan contras and said congressional democrats will be to blame if the supply-starved rebels fade from existence
in an hour-long meeting on capitol hill, reagan appealed to republican house members to unite behind a new effort to push through congress some kind of help for the contras, whose last u.s. aid ran out feb. 29
rebel supporters said their chances of prevailing on the divisive issue were improved by last week's incursion into honduras by troops of nicaragua's leftist sandinista government, which was making some moderates nervous about leaving the rebels without aid
the nixon white house kept heavy pressure on federal reserve board chairman arthur burns to do its bidding but gently turned aside complaints from one fed critic, then-california governor ronald reagan, documents made public on tuesday show
among 400,000 pages of white house records released by the national archives is a sept. 17, 1973 letter from reagan to nixon complaining about the impact of a fed decision on california mortgage loans
the documents also included many internal white house memoranda suggesting that white house aides devoted considerable effort to encourage burns, appointed by nixon in 1970, to stimulate the economy prior to nixon's 1972 re-election campaign
little deandra anrig was flying her kite when it suddenly started to fly her, her parents say. it was just a short hop, but one the 8-year-old isn't likely to forget
a twin-engine plane caught the 200-pound nylon test line of deandra's kite and carried her about 100 feet _ over her daddy's head and almost into a tree, she said tuesday
she let go, but said she was still sore after two days' rest. the plane, meanwhile, is grounded because of damage apparently caused by getting tangled in the kite string
extracts of a tropical plant appeared to reduce levels of hepatitis virus and liver cancer rates in woodchucks, a hopeful sign for the world's 200 million human virus-carriers at risk for the cancer, a scientist said tuesday
the trends emerged in analysis of data on about 60 animals that had become infected with the woodchuck version of the hepatitis b virus, said baruch blumberg of the fox chase cancer center in philadelphia. woodchucks are used in hepatitis research because the virus they carry so closely resembles the human hepatitis b virus
blumberg stressed that the results are only suggestive, and a prelude to a formal study of the plant extract's effects
cornell university is cataloging books, personal papers, videotapes and periodicals with names like ``mom guess what!'' and ``fag rag,'' hoping its new gay archives will help bring the study of human sexuality out of the academic closet
the materials, comprising one of the nation's most extensive collections on homosexuality, are nearly all gifts from the mariposa education and research foundation, founded in 1979 by physiologist bruce voeller, who felt universities were neglecting human sexuality
the basic endowment for maintenance of the archives, $824,000, came from the estate of david goodstein, a cornell alumnus who became wealthy on wall street and later published the national gay magazine, ``the advocate,'' until his death in 1985
the shortage of good books in the soviet union is being assaulted in a two-front war, with 3,500 previously banned titles being published and a new law in the works that will allow a vanity press
soviets have complained for years that while state bookstores are overflowing with political reflections, moralistic fiction and the works of communist party officials, people are hard pressed to lay their hands on the best writing of soviet, russian and foreign authors
two newspapers referred to the ``book deficit'' on tuesday in announcing programs aimed at expanding the pool of quality literature available at bookshops or public libraries
cbs, once nicknamed ``the tiffany network,'' has found the glitter gone from its prime-time schedule this season and expects to finish last in the nielsen ratings for the first time in 35 years of record keeping
though cbs' regularly scheduled prime-time programs are getting better ratings than those of abc, special sports programs including the winter olympics and the super bowl carried abc ahead. the network also had the world series this season
in 35 years of a.c. nielsen co. television ratings, cbs has finished in first place 26 times. it was second the other nine seasons, including the past two won by nbc
because shows such as ``dynasty'' must tiptoe around sex talk, aaron spelling productions has set its new abc show ``heartbeat'' in a women's clinic, where it can be right out in the open, couched in the glow of healthy openness
oh, please, ``st. elsewhere,'' come back!
tonight's two-hour premiere features difficult childbirths, artificial insemination and numerous gynecological exams. to start off, there's an emergency birth that requires forceps and incisions
oh, honey, bring in the potato chips!
kate mulgrew plays hapless, overworked dr. joanne springsteen, who founded the clinic with dr. eve autry (laura johnson, who is married to harry hamlin of ``l.a. law''). ben masters plays dr. leo rosetti, a pediatrician and object of joanne's lust
ray baker is psychologist stan gorshalk, who counsels the hospital's patients in matters psycho-sexual. in tonight's episode, he confides to another doctor that he and his wife haven't had sex in nine weeks. and the cobbler's children have no shoes
the show wants to offer up-to-date health information, like tonight's debate over mastectomy vs. lumpectomy in cases of breast cancer. women's fears are unlikely to be assuaged by gorshalk's argument that patient wendy (kathleen wilhoite) should be encouraged to face the fact that she very well might die. that should have 'em flocking in for mammograms
meanwhile, a couple who can't conceive are advised by the leering ``fertility specialist'' (darrell larson) to go for artificial insemination. after the procedure _ yes, we get to be there _ the nurse practitioner (gail strickland) gently suggests orgasm aids in successful implantation, and leaves the woman in a darkened examination room alone
in between trying to hit the sheets with leo, joanne contends with a friend who's pursuing a career and can't be bothered with an ``incompetent cervix,'' meaning the baby will be born prematurely if she walks around too much. joanne saves the day by borrowing a newborn from the nursery to convince the expectant mom she should stay in bed at least until the baby can be safely delivered after the next commercial
meanwhile, eve confronts wendy's sexist family doctor, who thinks wendy ought to have a radical mastectomy instead of a lumpectomy. what good is a breast, anyway, says the doc? it's ``just a piece of fat.'' huffs glamorous eve in her spandex dress, ``so are some of your body parts. would you like to chop them off and replace them with silly putty?''
some bad taste seems unintentional. dr. cory banks (lynn whitfield) is in a crisis because her husband is off on a building job in mexico, causing her to remark, ``sometimes i wish that whole construction project would get swallowed up in an earthquake.''
with any luck, ``heartbeat'' will get swallowed up by bad ratings
it is with great relief that thursday finds ``the days and nights of molly dodd'' back for another spring run on nbc
fans of jay tarses' touching, offbeat half-hour comedy, which premiered last spring for a limited run, will be glad to know, as molly's mom reassures in voiceover at the beginning of the episode, that molly ``continues to bang her knees against the cruel furniture of life.''
in the first new show, ``here's why you shouldn't get too attached to your cat,'' molly gets a new job, working in a cluttered bookstore for a befuddled but engaging bookworm, moss goodman (david strathairn)
and her friend nina (maureen anderman) is burglarized. ``do you know what it's like to come home and find your apartment ransacked, underwear hanging out of the drawers?'' rages nina. ``yes,'' says molly, ``but i'm a bad example.''
enter molly's new love interest, detective nathaniel hawthorne (richard lawson). replies nina upon being introduced to him, ``hello. i'm policewoman elizabeth barrett browning.''
elsewhere in television:
m-a-s-h still no. 1 _ nielsen's latest computation of the 50 top-rated tv shows of all time has the 1983 final episode of ``m-a-s-h'' still no. 1 with its 60.2 rating and 77 share. the rating is a percentage of all homes with televisions. the share is a percentage of sets in use. the ``who shot j.r.?'' episode of ``dallas'' from 1980 is still second with a rating of 53.3. the only show from this season _ the numbers are computed through the first week of march _ is january's super bowl xxii, ranked 46th. . .
jake's journey _ ``monty python'' alumnus graham chapman is starring in a new comedy series he has co-written for cbs, ``jake's journey,'' loosely based on mark twain's ``a connecticut yankee in king arthur's court.'' hal ashby is directing. chris young co-stars as an american boy whose family moves to england where he finds a python-esque fantasy world. no air date yet
is the united states headed downhill, spending and taxing away its might and power?
the thesis has arisen again, popularized by, among other events, an academic's best-selling book describing the rise to dominance and eventual deterioration of mighty nations through the ages
several factors fit into the notion that assigns the latter role to the united states, including budget imbalances, big defense budgets, trade difficulties, slow growth and onerous taxes
hastening the demise, according to neat but perhaps not correct analyses, is the kontradief theory, named for a russian economist who many years ago claimed to have found a 50-year cycle of economic rise and fall
as viewed by the most gloomy of forecasters, the u.s. economy and much of the world's economy has entered a decline phase
the gloomy prospect seemed to fit a paul erdman scenario, judging at least by the covers of his books. he is, you might know, author of ``the crash of '79,'' ``the last days of america'' and ``the panic of '89.''
he laughed. no way, said the economist-author. while the country has troubles, he said, it is in the process of renewing itself, with lots of 30-year-olds with new ideas and energy now entering positions of power
forget it,'' he said of the decline thesis. ``we've got the resources. we're dynamic. and we've got an infusion of the best of other countries through immigration.''
why, he asked, should we listen to ``a dead russian economist who made his observations before airplanes flew and before the development of service economies?''
but oddly, in the midst of one of the longest economic expansions ever, the notion of a dynamic america is sometimes lost, buried under concern for the worst aggregation of economic problems since the great depression of the 1930s
but dynamic america exists in the concepts of many scholars, among them david birch, who won a wide following for his research on small business while teaching at massachusetts institute of technology
small business, says birch, represents renewal. it has become the ``big picture in america.''
such businesses are innovating, exporting and creating jobs, he reminded a meeting of national small business united, an organization of independent business people that had it origins during the 1930s
turbulence in the business community often gains attention, with takeovers and demises and problems at well-known companies. but underlying the surface turbulence, birch suggests, is a strata of economic stability and growth
we turn over about 8 to 10 percent of our corporations and about 8 to 10 percent of our jobs in this country every year,'' said birch, founder and president of cognetics inc., an economic research firm in cambridge, mass
it means, he continued, that ``we turn over half of the american economy every five years _ half of all the companies and half of all the jobs change every five years.''
new business, he pointed out, find niches, create products and eventually compete and force larger companies to innovate or die
after tracking about 12 million businesses for close to two decades, ``what we began to realize was that there was this huge changing of the guard taking place,'' he said
the dinosaurs were dropping like rocks, and a whole bunch of little manufacturing companies were taking their place,'' he added
the turbulence that accompanies the process is economic decay and a waning of power to some viewers. to others, it is seen as renewal
argentines may have fallen out with the english over the falkland islands, but the upper-crust still likes the way they talk
that is evident on the quaintly british campus of st. george's college in quilmes where argentine children are still being sent to learn english with the proper accent and prepare to go on to cambridge or oxford
for as much as $7,800 a year in tuition, the 330 boys and girls who attend the only british-style boarding school in argentina are assured as fine an education as if they lived in england, said headmaster graham sims
ninety instructors from britain teach children aged 3 through 18 the fundamentals as well as computer programming, chemistry, advanced mathematics and english literature
english at st. george's is the most common classroom language, although argentina's education ministry requires that bilingual schools teach some courses in spanish
the school operates on british discipline
we are very strict and that means the boys and girls are not allowed any physical contact in school. holding hands is out,'' sims said in an interview. ``we've all got to lead disciplined lives. if not we become pretty hopeless human beings.''
st. george's is in quilmes, a city of 100,000 people 12 miles south of buenos aires. once a popular residential area for the british who earlier this century built most of argentina's railways, it is most noted now for a brewery and the school
dotting the 62-acre campus are a chapel, rugby fields, gardens, two swimming pools, a horse-riding academy and dormitories where students are required to place their folded clothes and towels on racks in the bathrooms
the only inkling this is not britain is when schoolchildren break into spanish after class or when argentina's flag is raised each morning outside the administration building
it really is a little piece of britain in argentina,'' said ray mckay, counselor at the lincoln school in northern buenos aires, the only american school in argentina. ``the student body is almost all argentines from wealthy families who want their kids to speak english.''
lincoln has 550 students, most of them children of u.s. embassy personnel, diplomats and businessmen in argentina. its schedule follows the u.s. system, with summer vacation from june through august. the english-style and argentine schools have their vacation from january to march, the southern hemisphere summer
st. george's, founded in 1898, is considered one of the four top schools in argentina for learning english
we offer a 24-hour-a-day education experience,'' said peter stoyle, director of studies at st. george's. wakeup calls are at 6:30 a.m. and lights are out across campus by 10 p.m., which is the normal dining hour in argentina
student magdalena winter, 15, hopes someday to become a diplomat
most people here believe we're getting a very good education so we learn to put up with things that maybe we don't always like,'' she said
three other top british-style schools, st. andrew's, st. catherine's and northlands, are in the northern suburbs of buenos aires, but they do not offer boarding
st. andrew's is observing the 150th anniversary of its founding by scottish settlers. with 1,900 students, st. andrew's is the largest of the british-tradition schools and oldest of the bilingual schools in argentina
one of its headmasters, watson hutton, was credited with introducing soccer to argentina at the turn of the century
without him there'd be no (diego) maradona,'' said headmaster kevan prior, referring to the star of argentina's 1986 world cup champions
st. andrew's has been coed since 1980
we have a particular ethos, particular spirit, something the parents of argentine upper middle-class children choose,'' prior said
tuition is $1,600 to $2,400 a year
northlands school near st. andrew's is considered the top girls school in argentina. headmistress jehane taylor takes pains to separate her school from anything british
this is an argentine school with no funds from england that happens to teach english,'' she said
sensitivities over anything british comes from problems regarding the britain's falkland islands in the south atlantic, off argentina. the argentines have claimed them since 1833 and here they are called the malvinas. argentina invaded the falklands in april 1982 and were driven off by british forces three months later
during the falklands these british-style schools got lots of phone treats, some of them obscene,'' said mckay of the american school. ``some kids were pulled out by their parents and there were some classroom tiffs over the so-called imperialist british
so it's really kind of remarkable now that so many argentines send their kids to these schools. i suppose it's kind of the snob thing to do.''
st. catherine's school for girls, like st. george's, offers the international baccalaurete program for its 1,100 students. the program allows students to enter colleges in the united states at a second-year level or qualify for advanced study in england
a st. catherine's coordinator, marie philpotts, described the school as ``british to a certain extent.'' tuition ranges from $1,050 to $1,600 a year compared to $1,000 to $2,000 a year at nortlands
mrs. taylor, head of northlands, said the tradition of argentines sending their children to english-style schools goes back several generations
the school, founded by a british governess in 1920, gives 985 students ``an anglo-saxon point of view and a latin point of view,'' giving students ``different ways of looking at knowledge,'' mrs. taylor said
the ouster by southern baptist officials of a scholar for contending that god upholds his compact with judaism opens an old wound in christian-jewish relations
it also pointed to a lingering, but increasingly repudiated, attitude in some church quarters
historical church theories that god revoked his commitment to jews, replacing it with a pact with christianity, figured for centuries in anti-jewish prejudice and persecution
however, many protestant and roman catholic scholars have rejected that notion, as have some denominations
if god's covenant has been broken with the jews, it's reasonable that other covenantal relationships might also be broken,'' says the rev. george j. sheridan, who was removed from his post
therefore, we in the church would be an endangered species.''
however, sheridan contends that god doesn't go back on his promises, either to the mother religion, judaism, or to the offspring of it, christianity, and he cites romans 11:
remember, it is not you (christians) that support the root, but the root that supports you ... and so all israel will be saved ... for the gifts and call of god are irrevocable.''
sheridan, 46, of union city, n.j., was dismissed after 13 years of working with jews as regional director of the interfaith witness department of the southern baptist home mission board
my point is that the covenant with the jews was not abrogated,'' he said in an interview, maintaining that they are saved through god's mercy, just as are christians, but without accepting jesus
christians, unlike jews, needed jesus to draw them to the one, same god, sheridan said
a letter notified him he was relieved from his assignment jan. 31 because of his ``theological position relative to evangelizing the jewish people'' _ something he opposed as unnecessary
it also offends jews, implying their faith is useless
sheridan's ouster ``strikes me like the middle ages,'' commented rabbi leon klenicki, director of the interfaith department of the anti-defamation league of b'nai b'rith
in atlanta, the mission board's president, the rev. larry lewis, said sheridan's view wasn't acceptable. the board lately came under fundamentalist sway, as have most of the 14.6-million-member denomination's agencies
lewis said, ``the bible teaches there is no other way to salvation except through a personal faith in jesus christ.''
sheridan, with degrees from southern baptist theological seminary in louisville, ky., and princeton theological seminary in princeton, n.j., linked his ouster to the heresy of marcionism
that's what this thing borders on,'' he said. ``the marcion heresy was that the god in jewish scripture (the old testament) is different than the god of the gospels (new testament).''
marcion, a second-century preacher whose views were condemned by the church, rejected the old testament, which historic christianity accepts along with the new testament
i believe in jesus christ,'' sheridan said, ``that jesus christ is god, but for me to believe that the god of jesus christ is not the god of jews rooted in their scripture is the heresy of two different gods.''
sheridan said that after a tense meeting with officials last year, he wrote a letter at their request outlining his views, and his dismissal followed. in it, he said in part:
the scriptures provide a chronicle of how god has taken the initiative in concrete historical ways to save god's people..
in the bible the term `savior' properly is ascribed to god...in the christian gospel, god comes to the world in the person of a man, jesus...in the new testament, the title `savior' is applied sometimes to god and sometimes to jesus christ,'' emphasizing that he bears ``the authority of god.''
this established that jesus christ is the revelation of god who, as the hebrew scriptures teach, is the one and only `savior' of the people of god. to distinguish between the god revealed in the hebrew scriptures and the god revealed in jesus christ is, for christians, a heresy..
god saves his people, the entire bible asserts. this salvation is not brought brought about by the goodness of the people, but by the merciful initiative of god. jesus christ provides the way for the nations to be engrafted into the people of god..
i find in the entire christian bible no hint that god cancels out lovingkindness freely dispensed or promised. in fact, we find the gifts and the call of god are irrevocable
for this biblical reason...i believe that the jews of today, as ever, receive salvation through their having been chosen by god in covenant with abraham, moses and the prophets
the election of the church is prefigured in this election of israel, and if the election of one is subjection to cancellation, so, too, is the election of the other.''
how do you figure it _ three movies in a row with the same basic plot? last year it was dudley moore and kirk cameron changing brains in ``like father, like son.'' now we have judge reinhold pulling a switch with his young son, fred savage, in ``vice versa.'' soon to come: george burns trading identities with his college-age grandson, charlie schlatter, in ``18 again.''
such coincidence is unfortunate, since all three movies possess the capacity to entertain
vice versa,'' in fact, is a nifty comedy of the supernatural variety. it benefits from a clever script by dick clement and ian lafrenais (who also produced), lively direction by brian gilbert and the inspired teaming of reinhold and young savage as the misplaced father and son
the role reversal is caused by a golden skull stolen from a thai temple. in ``like father, like son,'' it was a laboratory potion; in ``18 again,'' an auto crash
reinhold is a chicago department store executive who is a less than adequate part-time parent. his 11-year-old son lives most of the time with his mother who is now remarried. during a brief visit, father and son touch the skull and become transformed
the fun begins, though both victims are distressed by their new identities. reinhold is more interested in rock music and his pet frog, but he reports to the office and tries to fake his way through matters that are as foreign to him as trigonometry
savage attends school, but he is bored by the childish doings and finishes his tests in a few minutes. he withers the school bullies and barks orders to his limo driver. he devises a radio transmitter so he can guide reinhold through an all-important sales meeting with the store chief (william prince)
much of the hilarity is played off reinhold's attempts to resist the advances of his sexy date, corinne bohrer, and to explain his bizarre behavior to his secretary, gloria gifford
reinhold (``beverly hills cop''), with his loony face and rubbery body, is perfect for this kind of tomfoolery. matching him all the way is fred savage (``the princess bride''), who draws big laughs by mouthing his adult dialogue. director gilbert and the writer-producers have devised a genuinely sweet-natured movie, with only a few swear words by savage to warrant the pg rating
from columbia pictures. running time: 98 minutes
motion picture association of america rating definitions:
g _ general audiences. all ages admitted
pg _ parental guidance suggested. some material may not be suitable for children
pg-13 _ special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. some material may be inappropriate for young children
r _ restricted. under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian
x _ no one under 17 admitted. some states may have higher age restrictions. arts and entertainment package.</note>
when richard lester (``a hard day's night,'' ``superman ii'') came out with ``petulia'' in 1968, it quickly became a cult favorite with its quirky portrayal of life and love among the rich at the end of a turbulent decade
the critically acclaimed warner bros. movie starring julie christie and george c. scott is among the videocassette releases for march from warner home video
also highlighting the video debuts this month for home viewing: the jane fonda-jason robards-dean jones 1966 romantic comedy, ``any wednesday'' ($59.95, vhs@beta, no rating), which has made the rounds on commercial tv sliced and diced; ``innerspace,'' the 1987 steven spielberg sci-fi presentation starring dennis quaid and martin short; the sally field and michael caine comedy, ``surrender'' ($89.95, vhs@beta, rated pg)
just in time for the easter holiday are three movie classics with religious themes: 1959's ``the nun's story'' ($59.95, vhs@beta, no rating), starring audrey hepburn; 1952's ``the miracle of our lady of fatima'' ($59.95, vhs@beta, no rating), starring frank silvera and angela clark; and 1979's ``jesus'' ($59.95, vhs@beta, rated g), starring british stage actor brian deacon in the title role. a spanish-dubbed vhs only version is available of ``jesus'' for $59.95
reviewed this week are ``innerspace'' and ``petulia.''
innerspace'' ($89.95, vhs@beta, rated pg)

innerspace'' is last summer's fantasy adventure offering from the steven spielberg factory. its one claim to distinction is the spirited comic presence of martin short
the movie, directed by joe dante, takes off from the notion _ first explored in ``the fantastic voyage'' 20 years ago _ that a man can be ``miniaturized'' and injected into the bloodstream of another
in this case, the shrinking man is a daring but drunken test pilot played by dennis quaid and the unwitting recipient is a walter mitty-like supermarket clerk played by short
the overly complicated plot involves rival scientists and enemy agents trying to steal the computer chips that make the ``miniaturization'' possible. since quaid's air supply is limited, short _ aided by a newspaper reporter played by meg ryan _ must race the clock to retrieve one of the chips needed for ``re-enlargement.''
some of the hijinks are clever, but the frenzied car chases grow tiresome. the special effects are good but occasionally graphic, especially one scene in which a villain is dissolved in a pit of gastric acid
short makes a believable and likable character out of jack putter, who starts the movie on the brink of a nervous breakdown but ends up a self-assured hero. quaid and miss ryan have less to work with, and several other capable actors are more or less wasted in minor parts, including kevin mccarthy, fiona lewis and henry gibson
innerspace'' is harmless enough for helping kids 8 and over while away a rainy afternoon. adults, however, may grow weary before the caper has run its course
_ by mike silverman, associated press writer
  

petulia'' ($59.95, vhs@beta, rated r)

what is dr. archie bollen doing in a high-tech motel with the rich, lovely and utterly weird petulia? darned if he knows
we're about to become lovers,'' she informs him as he tries to unhook the feathery jacket to her sparkling gown. they don't. not then, anyway
the scene in the first 30 minutes of richard lester's ``petulia'' introduces us to the title character played by julie christie who has just picked up the recently divorced bollen (george c. scott) at a san francisco charity ball while her husband (richard chamberlain) looks on
bollen declares petulia a ``kook,'' but she haunts him in more ways than one, ultimately showing up at his apartment with a stolen tuba and broken ribs and crawling into his life. but even bollen's love can't save petulia from herself and a violent marriage
using flashbacks and flashforwards, lester and cinematographer nicolas roeg, present a stark, sometimes funny, sometimes frightening portrait of love among the spoiled rich during the turbulent end of the 1960s. on the small, home screen in the 1980s, the movie holds up just fine with some richly textured images and closeups that show a beautiful christie, a young chamberlain as remembered from tv's ``dr. kildare'' days and a somewhat sexy scott
there are also a few cameo surprises, such as janis joplin with big brother and the holding company entertaining at the benefit. music by the grateful dead also permeates the flick
petulia,'' with its love triangle and battered wife themes easily plays today, and like ``the graduate'' gives a savage portrait of a time not forgotten
joseph cotten, arthur hill, shirley knight, kathleen widdoes and pippa scott fill out the cast
_ by dolores barclay, associated press writer
motion picture association of america rating definitions:
g _ general audiences. all ages admitted
pg _ parental guidance suggested. some material may not be suitable for children
pg-13 _ special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. some material may be inappropriate for young children
r _ restricted. under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian
x _ no one under 17 admitted. some states may have higher age restrictions

savage'' (rca) _ eurythmics

on ``savage,'' the eurythmics are misanthropic, caustic and a bit paranoid. they're strong on attitude but weak on delivery
the record emphasizes a big beat, mostly via programmed drums and bass lines that make for mechanical music. worst is the opening cut, ``beethoven (i love to listen to).'' add singer annie lennox's dry delivery, and the resulting sounds have both the pulse and personality of a locomotive
lost in the thundering shuffle are the lyrics by lennox and dave stewart, which positively snarl on paper. lennox spends much of the record telling us that love is cheap and men merit no respect. ``love is a temple, love is a shrine, buy some love at the five and dime,'' she sings on the best song, ``you have placed a chill in my heart.''
oddly, lennox and stewart ease up on the syncopation on the last two cuts of the record, which closes with the upbeat ``brand new day.'' after 11 songs filled with cynicism, it's hard to believe the optimistic message is sincere. but maybe it presages more subtlety and finesse on their next record

live _ the road'' (mca) _ the kinks

it's bad news when the best thing on an album titled ``live _ the road'' is a studio cut. but that's the case with the kinks' latest record
it opens with a new composition, ray davies' engaging, autobiographical ``the road.'' ``there's gas in my tank, and i've still got a ways to go,'' the veteran rocker sings. on the rest of the album, recorded in concert last summer, the kinks play with the verve of a driver intent on getting good mileage
there are stirring moments in the 50 minutes of music: ``come dancing,'' sparked by dave davies' fluid guitar work; the provocative ``art lover,'' which only ray davies could have written; and the rocking ``destroyer'' and ``around the dial.''
but ``it,'' the album's other new song, and ``cliches of the world'' are too long and too ambitious. the other performances are routine, with riffs and tempos that belong in a heavy metal cutout bin
live _ the road'' is not a bad set, and the kinks deserve credit for reprising some of their lesser-known material from the 1980s (at one point they tease the audience with a false start of ``lola''). but from such a well-respected band, it's a disappointment
george burns paced the darkened backstage of the caesars palace showroom, hummed softly and flicked ashes from his ever-present cigar
i'm just making sure i can still walk,'' he dead-panned to a couple sitting in the wings
moments later, as the orchestra struck up ``ain't misbehavin','' burns sauntered on stage to a standing ovation, a rarity for the opening of a las vegas show. he would receive two more before exiting an hour later _ a sign of the respect audiences hold for this man who was a vaudeville star in their grandparents' time
at 92, burns shows no signs of slowing down. he's a regular at the palace on the las vegas strip and at other caesars properties in lake tahoe, nev., and atlantic city, n.j. his pace would satisfy, and slow, most performers half his age
however, burns has just completed a new movie, ``18 again,'' which opens april 9. and he's working on a new book about the one true love of his life, gracie allen, his stage partner, confidante, best friend and wife for 38 years until her death in 1964. the book, ``gracie: a love story,'' is due out in october
irving fein, burns' longtime friend and manager for 14 years, says the book will be ``a loving, warm story about gracie allen that has never before been told
george will always have this special love for gracie,'' fein said during burns' recent appearance here. ``he goes to her grave (in los angeles) once a month. he talks to her, tells her everything he's doing. he'll say `i just got back from vegas. we did great.' or `i just finished a movie. it's about me and my grandson and how we switch places
he'll spend a lot of time just standing there talking to her, letting her know what's happening in his life. she's still a very special part of his life.''
burns gives his long-time mate the credit for his success
if it wasn't for gracie, i wouldn't be here,'' he said, puffing on a cigar in his dressing room before a recent caesars show. he crossed the room to a bar, poured a cup of coffee, then settled in a chair next to the piano
morty jacobs, his pianist of 18 years, began picking out tunes burns sang as a teen-ager three-quarters of a century ago
what key is that?'' burns inquired of jacobs. ``take it half a tone lower.''
we'll do some lovin', then you'll ask for more,'' burns sang, tapping shiny patent leather shoes on the dressing room floor
onstage, opening act susan anton was belting out a raucous version of ``old time rock and roll,'' a signal for burns to exit his dressing room. he walked briskly back and forth in the darkened area, stopping to talk to workers or softly humming some of the songs he would sing
miss anton dedicated her final song, ``forever young,'' to burns. he took a long drag on his cigar, then entered to the standing ovation
in 1981 i played god,'' he said, referring to the first of three movies in which he played the deity. ``i was a nervous wreck. we're both the same age, but we grew up in different neighborhoods
why shouldn't i play god? anything i do at my age is a miracle
i've written six books. that's pretty good for a guy who only read two.''
his formula for acting?
if the director wants me to cry, i think of my sex life
if the director wants me to laugh, i think of my sex life.''
about that sex life?
i'd go out with women my age, but there are no women my age.''
another put-down: ``there isn't anything i can't do now that i couldn't do when i was 18 _ which shows you how pathetic i was at 18.''
burns smokes 15 to 20 cigars and drinks several martinis a day
what do his doctors think of that?
they're all dead.''
burns began in show business at the age of 8, quitting school to form a group of child singers known as the peewee quartet. born nathan birnbaum to a poor family on new york's lower east side, he had only to look to his 11 brothers and sisters for his own ensemble
he bounced around the vaudeville circuit until he was 27. ``then people discovered i had a talent _ a big talent. i was married to her for 38 years
gracie didn't tell a joke, she explained it,'' burns recalled of nearly four decades as straight man for the zany comedian
burns admits he was devastated _ personally and professionally _ by miss allen's death in 1964. a decade later, in august 1974, burns underwent a triple heart bypass. at age 78, he was the oldest bypass patient in history at that time
four months after his surgery, burns' longtime friend, jack benny died. benny had been scheduled to star in the movie ``the sunshine boys.'' burns was tabbed to take his place, won an academy award for best supporting actor, and was on his way to his second time around
lee chul-soo draws stark pictures of exhausted factory workers and peasants clawing the earth with their hands because he sees beauty in their suffering
beauty lies in the ordinary lives and suffering of the common people,'' the artist says with a shy smile
lee is a leader of the growing ``minjung'' or grass-roots school of art that has evolved in south korea in recent years as a reaction to decades of authoritarian rule and the impact of industrialization
minjung artists, who have attracted a wide following among young korean artists, advocate using art to fight for democratic reform by depicting the hardships of poor workers, peasants and slum dwellers
minjung art aims to expose the social evils and injustices in society. it also participates in the movement of the masses,'' said lee, a quiet, gentle man who often smiles as he explains his ideas
the bold, realistic style of minjung art and its bleak portrayal of life are considered shocking in a society where artists generally concentrate on landscapes or happy rural scenes
minjung art is about the suffering of many koreans who work long hours for a very meager living and spend their lives in poverty, lee said. it also is about how industrialization has destroyed traditional rural values and made life bleak and polluted, he said
lee's bold woodcuts and portraits feature haggard men and women drained by unrelenting labor and bleak, hopeless lives. a man claws at the stony earth of his fields, a woman working at a sewing machine in a factory dreams of heaven, a begger huddles in front of a church
i want to instill a detailed, concrete sense of reality into my works,'' he said
many of lee's subjects have disproportionately large hands and feet that have become a trademark of his work. lee says he doesn't know why he makes feet and hands so large
some critics have denounced the new style as violent and crude political propaganda that is not art. ``skepticism over the quality of the works by minjung artists lingers on,'' said one critic
lee rejects charges that his work is crude propaganda. he defends it as a reaction to decades of oppressive rule and says his only goals are democracy and aiding the poor. ``you have to compare our works with the violent nature of the political powers that be,'' he said
but lee also rejects the idea that he is a political artist, saying his work is a repudiation of politics. ``politics oppresses humans,'' he said
lee says his works are inspired by the hope that a fair society based on greater equality and compassion can be built. he dreams of a kinder, gentle world and says showing how people suffer can help bring change
i'm not a radical,'' he said. ``i'm an optimist.''
minjung art is also anti-western because its followers say that western influence has eroded traditional korean values and brought industrialization and other dehumanizing influences
western influence has brought with it decadence,'' lee said
lee moved to the countryside two years ago because of concern that industrialization was destroying traditional rural values. his work often features a rural life he fears is slipping away
some of lee's works were recently displayed at a seoul gallery. a steady flow of visitors viewed the lines of stark woodcuts displayed on whitewashed walls in the grimy, basement gallery
lee admitted the show was a sign of political liberalization and of how artists are allowed freedom. the government of president roh tae-woo, which took office in february, has promised to end authoritarian rule and allow complete freedom of expression
lee makes a living as a book illustrator and spends much of his time working to develop minjung art. he says he wants to develop the quality of the art and establish it alongside other artistic schools
we are striving to give better forms and flesh to our ideas,'' he said
in the past decade, george thorogood has gone from playing hole-in-the-wall saloons to headlining stadiums. but the whiskey-voiced rocker figures his career holds a few more roadhouse bars before he hits the retirement home
i can't wait until i become a has-been _ a has-been that never was, actually,'' he said with a cackle. ``i can't wait till that happens, because i know i can make a living playing bars. and have a lot of fun _ a great time.''
which is, he says, what his band the destroyers are having now on their national tour _ although thorogood makes no bones about saying they'd rather play stubb's barbecue, a small texas blues bar, than madison square garden
we started out, and still are, a bar band,'' said thorogood, whose career has kept alive the sound of muddy waters, howlin' wolf and other blues legends. ``it's just that the bars are a little bigger these days.''
thorogood and company are to blame for that. since 1977, they've cranked out a series of successful albums and singles, starting with a remake of hank williams' ``who do you love?'' on their debut album and stretching to the current lp ``born to be bad.''
despite his success, thorogood has not catered to top 40 radio, studiously avoided studio tricks and stayed about as far from the mainstream as any contemporary band can
even if i tried, i'm not going to be able to get out of this style of playing,'' thorogood said during a manhattan stop in the tour. ``there might be a different hook here or there, but basically it's going to be your two-, three-chord rock or your slow, tough-guy blues
i don't want to change that, and i couldn't if i wanted o, because i have tried _ i have sat down and tried to play other styles of stuff, and it was a disaster.''
with that in mind, thorogood and band included some classic covers on the new album: elmore james' ``shake your money maker,'' chuck berry's ``you can't catch me'' and hank snow's ``i'm movin' on.''
thorogood also wrote several songs in the same vein for ``born to be bad'' _ songs which, he stressed, carry no deeper message than ``let's all have a good time.''
i figure, i'm not operating on anybody's skull here. it's not brain surgery, man,'' said thorogood. ``it's just two chords. and people are supposed to dance to it and laugh at it, and two hours later forget about it. that's what entertainment is.''
thorogood was introduced to the blues scene in his native delaware, an area he quickly admits was no roots-rock hotbed
i was so foolish staying in the philadelphia area, because it's not a blues area,'' he said. ``if i had my wits about me, i would have gone to san francisco or chicago, where people know this sound their whole lives.''
but no matter where he he grew up, thorogood believes it was inevitable he'd end up listening to muddy waters and chuck berry
i think the things you're supposed to hear in your life will come to you. you don't go finding them; they come to you,'' he said. ``so it just came to me a little later.''
once thorogood heard the music, he began taking it to audiences with the zeal of a bible belt preacher delivering the good word
the band is constantly on the road: in 1981, they went on a ``50-50 tour'' in which they played in all 50 states on 50 consecutive dates
and while they have moved up from bars to arenas, thorogood figures that sooner or later he'll be back on the roadhouse circuit playing for barroom crowds, enjoying his golden years with a cold beer and some hot licks
i always thought, wow, wouldn't it be great if i did `bad to the bone' and i was 60, and i had on a gut on me like (jackie) gleason, and i walked out there with a t-shirt that said something like, `sex machine.'''
scholars entering yale university's 3 million-volume sterling memorial library are discovering there's definitely more to a book than its cover
the library's ``eccentric books'' exhibit includes works containing a rotting tortilla encased in plastic, a miniature stand-up portrait of humphrey bogart and a three-dimensional illustration of sperm fertilizing an egg
these are more-than-a-book books,'' says gay walker, the library's arts of the book department curator who put together the exhibit
the more than 110 books in the exhibit have flaps, fold-outs, revolving wheels, unusual shapes, cutouts or objects such as a pair of 3-d glasses. although children's books are represented, most of the volumes are aimed toward adult readers
walker says the earliest known example of an eccentric book is johannes mueller's 1474 ``kalendar,'' also known as ``regiomontanus.'' the text contains two cutout, movable discs tied onto a diagram that shows the movements of the moon
the yale exhibit has a fascimile of the book printed in 1937 as well as several original copies of 16th-century books with revolving diagrams by petrus apianus, the royal astronomer for charles v
another early innovation was the flap, cutout paper pasted onto a book page that either added to an illustration or revealed one when lifted up
euclid's ``elements of geometry,'' translated into english by h. billingsley and printed in london in 1570, was the oldest example of a flapped book identified by walker. it contains several illustrations of geometrical figures that use flaps to illustrate the solid figure, she says
anatomy books also made early use of flaps revealing various layers of the body by as early as 1573, walker writes in a catalog of the exhibition. among them was george spratt's 1833 ``obstetric tables,'' which had several printings. fifteen of its lithographed plates contain a total of 50 flaps, with explicit illustrations
there are books with eccentricities in other fields besides the sciences. in the exhibit are children's books with all kinds of innovations, including one that folds out into a five-room miniature house, landscape books, humor books, art books and many more
pull-tabs depress a computer key in one book and cause a robot's pants to fall down in another. in ``the great movies live'' by maxim jakubowski and ron van der meer, paper versions of screen stars in famous scenes from flicks ranging from ``casablanca'' to ``king kong'' literally stand up from the pages
in ``100 million million poems'' by raymond queneau, 14 lines of poetry cut from 10 pages but still attached to the binding can be combined into almost limitless poetic possibilities
jonathon miller's and david pelham's ``the facts of life,'' published in 1984, uses tabs, wheels, flaps and moving and stationary pop-ups in its illustrations, including one in blue and gray showing the fertilization of a human egg
included in a category that walker labels artists' book, are wesleyan university artist and english professor joseph reed's two books made out of candy boxes. one is a whitman sampler box that contains a mostly visual essay on walt whitman
the other, the ``book of eights'' has the eight dwarfs, a new addition being stuffy; the eight deadly sins, the eighth being ``boringness''; and the eight wonders of the modern world, which include trump tower in new york and graceland, the late elvis presley's home in memphis, tenn
a 1977 volume of ``eye,'' a yale art magazine, contains the plastic-encased tortilla
eccentric books published today are especially popular in the children's fields, says walker. pop-up books, popular in the victorian age, have been revived by waldo h. hunt, a los angeles publisher, who manufactures them in colombia, she says
walker says the idea for the exhibition started when she was invited to give a talk on any subject she chose, which ended up being eccentric books
the librarian found that very little research had been done in the area. she devised the categories such as flap and pop-up to which she assigned the books
walker also designed the exhibit's catalog, which contains two pop-ups and a serrated edge. she produced the catalog on a home computer, had its cover printed professionally and bound the 61-page work by hand at night in her home
the exhibit is open through april 15
fiddler vassar clements has played country music, jazz, rock 'n' roll and classical for groups as diverse as the grateful dead and the boston pops
and for the past two decades, he's recorded in the top studios with his instrument. it's been a romance of sound separated only by the styles he performs
when the rhythm is good, i can play it,'' clements says
the 59-year-old artist has just released an album with the intriguing title ``new hillbilly jazz.'' the name signifies a sound as versatile as the man who plays it
it's heavy rhythm, solid, dynamic,'' he said in his soft southern voice that contrasts the exuberance of his playing. ``but it's not fidgety music. it's smooth, danceable.''
this marks his 20th year in nashville where he's added luster to the city's country style after relocating from kissimmee, fla
people ask me what kind of music i'm playing, and i say i don't know,'' he said. ``it's just happy, moving music.''
along the way, he played with rock veterans the grateful dead on their ``wake of the flood'' album and toured with them when they were known as old and in the way
it was a departure from the country music he grew up playing when he and his cousins formed a band
it was a challenge and i loved that,'' he recalled about his days with the dead. ``it's exciting to take a chance.''
he also played with the boston pops, joining his close friend john hartford when hartford was a guest artist in a pops concert
in addition, he recorded with the monkees. that was by coincidence. he was working on a recording session when someone asked him if he wanted to stay and play on another one
i didn't know until later it was the monkees,'' he said
he's had no problem adjusting to the various styles, even on short notice such as the monkees' session. ``you just go in and do it. after so many years, no tunes change much. i've never had a problem with that.''
clements taught himself to play at age 7 and has no formal training. the first song he learned was ``there's an old spinning wheel in the parlor.''
it took forever,'' he said
it was god's gift, something born in me,'' he said about his talent. ``i was too dumb to learn it any other way. i listened to the (grand ole) opry some. i'd pick it up one note at a time. i was young, with plenty of time and i didn't give up. you'd come home from school, do your lessons and that's it. no other distractions
i don't read music. i play what i hear.''
but he understands how helpful it is for youngsters to be grounded in classical music and formal training. ``it should help them,'' clements said
he was employed at the kennedy space center in florida for a year in the mid-1960s, working on plumbing. at various times, he also worked in a georgia paper mill, was a switchman for atlantic coast railroad, sold insurance and had a potato chip franchise
but music was always part of his life
i'd always play. square dances, anything,'' he said
all the performing carried him to nashville where one of his first breaks was being featured on the album ``will the circle be unbroken'' by the nitty gritty dirt band
he then became heavily in demand for recording sessions of all types. this year, he was nominated for a grammy award with french jazz violinist stephane grappelli for their ``together at last.''
it was a truly great time,'' he said about working with grappelli. ``it was a challenge, but it came easy. we felt alike on a lot of things.''
clements won't say that he's getting better at playing, but prefers to say that it just comes easier
if i quit improving, i'd have to quit. it would be work and there'd be no sense staying in a rut and not learning anything. i'd hate to play the same way all the time. it would become mechanical.''
clements, who owns three fiddles and still practices some, has no favorite song. ``when things go right, i enjoy playing all of them, anything that comes up.''
similarly, he doesn't mind if his instrument is called a fiddle or a violin
i say fiddle, but if someone says violin it doesn't matter.''
texaco inc.'s time under bankruptcy court protection may be drawing nearer a close as the last shareholder votes are counted on a proposed financial reorganization plan
at a hearing beginning today in white plains, n.y., u.s. bankruptcy court judge howard schwartzberg is expected to announce the result of that balloting and listen to final comments by parties to the case
the judge then must decide whether or not to confirm the plan, enabling texaco to step from under court protection under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code
texaco filed for protection from its creditors last april to avoid having to post a multibillion-dollar bond while appealing a $10.3 billion judgment held against it by pennzoil co
the federal government says it posted a $23.9 billion deficit in february after a $16.1 billion surplus the previous month
the treasury department said monday that for the first five months of the current budget year, the government has run up a deficit of $89.7 billion, 4.9 percent lower than the red ink incurred in the same period a year ago
investment in plant and equipment by u.s. business is likely to increase about 8.8 percent this year but only 0.5 percent in 1989, according to a new survey
manufacturers are likely to lead the way this year with a 12.5 percent increase in investment, but trail in 1989 with a 2.9 percent decrease, data resources inc. of lexington, mass., said in a survey released monday
general electric co. has launched a double-pronged attack in its bid for roper corp. by boosting its tender offer to $507 million and filing lawsuits challenging roper's agreement to merge with whirlpool corp
ge's latest bid, up $9 a share to $54 for roper's outstanding stock, surpasses the $50-a-share sweetened bid whirlpool made last week for the appliance and lawn equipment maker
roper said it is reviewing ge's new tender offer and plans to hold a board meeting this week to determine the company's position on the sweetened bid
an investment group that owns an 11 percent stake in kansas city southern industries inc. is offering $60 a share, or about $594 million, for the rest of the railroad concern's common stock
kansas city southern, which also has interests in financial services, said monday its board would consider the all-cash proposal soon
the company has nearly 11.1 million shares outstanding, and the investment group led by howard kaskel claims it controls about 1.2 million shares
r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. has cleared some hurdles in the path toward winning federated department stores inc. while its rival, campeau corp. reconsidered its strategy following a major court defeat
macy announced monday that the waiting period during which the federal government could ask for information about the possible antitrust implications of a macy-federated merger had expired with no further requests. a request would extend the waiting period automatically
meanwhile, campeau was trying to decide how to proceed following a federal judge's determination that federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense could stand
batus inc. is taking its campaign for farmers group inc. to the company's shareholders, soliciting proxies to support reconsideration of its bid for one of the nation's largest insurers
batus said monday the non-binding resolution will be introduced at farmers' annual stockholders' meeting may 20 at the company's los angeles headquarters
farmers' board earlier rejected a hostile takeover offer of $63 a share, or $4.4 billion, and called upon its shareholders to do the same
bank of new york co. says it is beginning a $1.08 billion tender offer for irving bank corp. after having received approval to make the bid from the securities and exchange commission
sec approval os the registration statement allows bank of new york to issue its prospectus, bank of new york spokesman owen brady said monday
irving spokesman david santos dismissed the development as ``pretty much a non-event.''
a federal judge has threatened to fine eastern airlines $10,000 per day for future breaches of a court order that has blocked the carrier from trying to sell its profitable east coast air shuttle
u.s. district judge john h. pratt also on monday ordered eastern to halt its efforts to gain federal permission to complete the proposed deal
pratt wrote that in attempting to sell its shuttle, eastern had engaged in ``deliberate and intentional conduct'' that violated a ruling the judge issued last summer. that july 2 order had forbidden the company from changing working conditions of 12,000 mechanics and other ground workers represented by one of the airline's unions
eligible stockholders in six financially troubled production credit associations in the omaha, neb., and spokane, wash., districts will receive par value cash or credit for their stock, the farm credit system assistance board says
eric p. thor, head of the board, said monday the compensation will go to those whose stock either was frozen or not retired at par when the associations went into liquidation
the supreme court has agreed, in a case brought by phone customers in minnesota, to consider making it easier for people to use a federal anti-racketeering law to sue businesses
the court also agreed monday to hear a reagan administration appeal aimed at allowing some creditors to collect more money from debtors who declare bankruptcy
the justices also agreed to study the case of a laid-off pennsylvania man in a matter that could decide an important issue for lawsuits alleging age bias in employment
stocks stumbled monday in the slowest trading volume this year. the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 20.23 to 2,067.14
bond prices slipped and interest rates edged up
the dollar fell against most major currencies
platinum, gold and silver futures prices advanced, oil prices were mixed, and soybean futures rose
roper corp., which resisted general electric co.'s previous moves to snatch it from whirlpool corp., says it will study ge's latest, sweetened $507 million buyout offer
the giant appliance maker's new offer for roper came on monday just hours after ge filed suit challenging roper's agreement to merge with whirlpool in a $470 million deal
ge on monday increased its tender offer for roper's outstanding shares by $9 to $54 a share, topping whirlpool's $50-a-share offer in a bidding war that, according to some analysts, may have run its course
the prices are pretty generous to what we on wall street would call the intrinsic value of roper,'' said cornelius sewell, an analyst with argus research corp
roper rose $2.50 a share to close at $55.50 in composite new york stock exchange trading, adding to friday's $5.75 a share runup
in a statement issued after the stock market closed, roper said it was reviewing ge's new tender offer and planned a board meeting later in the week to determine the company's position on the sweetened bid
whirlpool began the legal battle last week, suing ge on the grounds the fairfield, conn.-based conglomerate tried to ``sabotage'' a whirlpool-roper merger with a competing bid
ge said roper rebuffed a merger proposal last november, and contended the roper board authorized a $37.50-a-share merger with whirlpool after whirlpool threatened to mount a hostile takeover bid, according to delaware state court documents
ge, which on march 6 made its initial $45-a-share offer, alleged roper failed to ``test the price'' before agreeing to merge with whirlpool. ge also contended roper concealed ge's interest in the company when it advised shareholders to tender their stock to whirlpool
roper also gave benton harbor, mich.-based whirlpool a so-called ``lockup option'' to purchase 1.6 million newly issued shares for $37.50 each if their deal fell through, which would make any subsequent roper acquisition more expensive. ge is seeking to block the issue and transfer of those shares
in a separate suit filed in u.s. district court in delaware, ge claimed both whirlpool and roper failed to adequately disclose terms of their merger agreement under securities and exchange commission laws and neglected to mention ge's interest in roper
whirlpool alleged in its suit last week that a ge executive tried to persuade roper to break its contract with whirlpool. the suit said ge ``intentionally, maliciously and unjustifiedly engaged in a continuing course of conduct to sabotage'' the deal
part of whirlpool's lawsuit seeks $117 million in damages, or the difference between its $50-a-share offer and original offer
ge vowed to ``vigorously defend itself'' against the charges and is seeking to transfer the suit from u.s. district court in grand rapids, mich., to federal court in delaware
roper, headquartered in augusta, ga., last week endorsed whirlpool's sweetened bid. robert cook, roper's president and chief executive officer, said then that the company ``has a strong desire to see this combination successfully completed,'' although he had no further comment when contacted monday
david whitwam, whirlpool's president and chief executive, stated monday that his company remains committed to pursuing its attempts to block ge and acquire roper
analysts say a roper-whirlpool merger would move whirlpool ahead of ge as the nation's leading appliance maker. for ge, acquiring the appliance and lawn equipment maker would enhance its supplier relationship with sears, roebuck &amp; co. and give it a valuable share of the gas stove market
analysts estimate that roughly two-thirds of roper's sales come from its agreement to supply sears with its kitchen appliance and lawn equipment products
ge's bid stems from its decision last year to expand its market share by selling gas stoves. rather than manufacture the gas stoves, ge now purchases them from four companies, including roper, said ge spokesman jack batty
still smarting from a major courtroom defeat last week, campeau corp. says it is working on other options in its battle to acquire federated department stores inc
campeau got another legal setback on monday and faces further courtroom entanglements over its attempt to acquire federated, which has accepted a rival offer from r.h. macy &amp; co. inc
a federal judge on monday rebuffed campeau's proposal to extend its $6.18 billion tender offer so it would expire simultaneously with macy's offer, if he removed federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense
judge leonard sand, in a closed-door session, said the poison pill would remain in place at least until federated makes a final recommendation to its shareholders, said campeau spokeswoman nancy raeside
in a key ruling on friday, the judge had denied campeau's request to block the use of federated's poison pill, which campeau says will prevent it from completing any takeover of federated
the defense makes a takeover prohibitively expensive by allowing federated shareholders to buy more of the company's stock at a steep discount
margaret nicolaides, a campeau spokeswoman, said the toronto-based developer was ``definitely working on other options.'' she said she could not elaborate on what those options were
however, there were reports that campeau was considering sweetening its bid or proposing a friendly merger. neither tactic has met with success in the past during the company's months-long quest for federated
in another matter, judge sand scheduled a wednesday hearing over a macy complaint that campeau made false statements in full-page advertisements in thursday editions of the new york times and wall street journal
separately, macy announced that the waiting period during which the federal government could ask for information about the possible antitrust implications of a macy-federated merger had expired with no further requests. a request would extend the waiting period automatically
the retailer also confirmed it had agreed to sell 11 of federated's 14 abraham &amp; straus stores if it wins the takeover fight. the agreement, reached with new york state attorney general robert abrams over the weekend, calls for macy to divest new york-area a&amp;s stores because they are in direct competition with macy branches
in georgia, where macy stores would compete with federated's rich's chain, attorney general michael bowers said the state will not oppose a macy-federated combination. but analysts speculate that macy might sell the rich's stores anyway
macy is conducting a $6.3 billion tender offer for federated under an agreement with federated management
macy is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. macy would exchange shares in the merged company, macy's-federated inc., and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares. analysts have estimated the total value of the offer at $6.3 billion
federated stock rose 62{ cents to $66.87{ in new york stock exchange composite trading monday
campeau's bid is a two-step, all-cash package that would be worth $68 a share, or $6.18 billion. it is offering $75 each for 70.5 million federated shares, and proposes to acquire the remaining stock for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger
macy's offer expires at midnight est april 4. the campeau offer must remain open at least until midnight friday, pending a securities and exchange commission ruling on whether campeau must submit documents on its financing for the takeover. moving on general news wires.</note>
the union trying to prevent eastern airlines from selling its lucrative east coast air shuttle says it is happy with penalties a federal judge has levied on the carrier, but the company says it plans to appeal the sanctions
u.s. district judge john h. pratt on monday said he would fine eastern $10,000 per day if the airline commits any future violations of a court order that had blocked the shuttle deal
pratt also ordered eastern to halt all efforts to get government permission to go through with the sale. and he said the airline's top officials would have to write to all 32,000 eastern employees, informing them that the carrier had flouted an earlier court order and promising that no further violations would occur
he imposed most of the sanctions we asked for,'' edgar n. james, a lawyer for the international association of machinists and aerospace workers said. ``there weren't any surprises, but it's pretty strong.''
but company officials insisted their court fight was not over
eastern continues to believe strongly that we have not violated any court orders,'' the company said in a written statement read by spokeswoman karen ceremsak from the airline's headquarters in miami
john j. gallagher, eastern's attorney, said the airline would go to court today to appeal the penalty and the original finding of contempt
pratt found eastern in contempt on march 10 for violating an order he had issued july 2. that order had forbidden the company from changing working conditions of the 12,000 mechanics and other ground workers represented by the machinists
eastern, owned by texas air corp., announced feb. 5 that it would sell its shuttle to a newly created texas air subsidiary for $225 million. the shuttle flies between washington, new york and boston
frank lorenzo, chief executive of texas air and eastern, has argued that financially ailing eastern needed the cash. but union leaders have insisted the move was aimed at stripping labor of power at the carrier by transferring thousands of workers to another corporate entity within texas air
the machinists' union had asked pratt to force a court appearance by lorenzo to discuss the shuttle deal. but in his ruling monday, pratt said lorenzo could send another corporate representative
the union had also asked pratt to fine eastern $20,000 daily for future violations of the judge's orders. the judge instead ruled the airline would face $10,000-a-day fines for violations committed after april 5
pratt did not grant a union request that the airline restore the jobs of all eastern employees who quit because of the announcement that the shuttle would be sold
in 1986, texas air, also the corporate parent of continental airlines, took over eastern, a large carrier that lost $182 million last year
since that time, lorenzo has sought wage concessions from unions and has tried selling several of eastern's most profitable assets to other texas air subsidiaries that he also controls. unions representing eastern employees have waged well-publicized fights to thwart him. industries</head>
investor howard kaskel, who says his plans to boost shareholder values have been rebufffed repeatedly by kansas city southern industries inc., is moving to take over the company
an investment group led by kaskel said monday it was offering $60 cash a share, or about $594 million, for the 89 percent of the railroad concern's common stock that it does not already own
the new york investor, in a letter to the company's management, also indicated he would attempt to place his own slate of directors on the kansas city southern board if it rejected or failed to act on the buyout offer by april 4
kansas city southern, which also has interests in financial services, said its board would consider the all-cash proposal soon at a special meeting
the company has nearly 11.1 million shares outstanding, and the kaskel group claims it controls about 1.2 million shares
in new york stock exchange trading, kansas city southern jumped $8.75 a share to $55 on monday
kaskel outlined the merger proposal in a letter to landon h. rowland, president and chief executive of kansas city southern, and requested an opportunity to negotiate ``all aspects of the offer, including price.''
he said completing the proposal was subject to reaching a definitive agreement, approval by the requisite number of directors and stockholders and satisfaction of all regulatory requirements
kaskel said he had made various proposals to company management over the past eight months on ways to maximize shareholder values
unfortunately, you have rejected each of my suggestions,'' kaskel wrote
in addition, he said he found it ``dismaying'' that the board erected obstacles ``designed to entrench itself and to prevent stockholders from realizing a full return on their investment.''
among these steps, kaskel cited the recent issuance of about 1.4 million shares, or almost 15 percent of the company's then-outstanding common stock, to employee stock ownership plans at $49 a share
this could only have been motivated by the board's desire to place substantial voting power in its hands as a means of opposing'' proposals that may be brought before its shareholders, the letter read
kaskel also cited kansas city southern's continued efforts to acquire the southern pacific railroad despite southern pacific's ``binding agreement for its sale to the denver rio grande.''
other than rowland's announcement that the board of directors would consider the offer at a special meeting, kansas city southern indicated it had no further comment until the board had an opportunity to study the offer
kansas city southern owns the kansas city southern railroad, which operates on about 1,500 miles of track in missouri, arkansas, oklahoma, kansas, louisiana and texas
it also owns 87 percent of dst systems inc., a kansas city-based concern that provides data systems and record-keeping services for mutual funds, insurance companies and other financial services providers
the company also owns 80 percent of janus capital corp., a denver-based concern that provides investment advice and had about $915 million in funds under management at the end of february, according to kansas city southern's vice president and secretary, albert mauro
for the fiscal year ended dec. 31, kansas city southern reported a profit of $17.7 million, or $1.82 a share, on revenue of $507.6 million
the british investor pursuing a hostile takeover of koppers co. says he is willing to acquire only the company's core construction materials business _ which the company already has said it may sell as a defensive measure
brian c. beazer, who along with the investment firm shearson lehman hutton inc. has offered to acquire koppers for $56 a share, or $1.6 billion, made his offer in a letter to koppers chairman charles r. pullin on saturday
in the letter, the bidders raised their offer to $56 a share from the initial $45 a share bid rejected by koppers, which also manufactures chemicals
beazer, chairman of the british construction company beazer plc, said previously he would sell the chemicals business if he gained control of koppers. his new offer remains open until april 1
koppers has stated that under a defensive recapitalization plan it is contemplating, it might sell part or all of the construction materials business to third parties
selling the businesses to beazer might save the rest of koppers, but ``i don't know how bright a move that would be,'' said securities analyst gregory drahuschak of butcher &amp; singer in pittsburgh. ``it's the lion's share of the company's earnings and revenue.''
the construction materials and paving services businesses are on solid footing after five years of retrenchment at koppers, he said. the company reported 1987 earnings of $10.8 million on revenue of $1.5 billion
the real persistent grower for the corporation has been the construction materials business,'' said robert kanters, analyst for legg mason wood walker inc. in pittsburgh. ``the chemicals business, they feel, is able to do some sustainable growth, but it's been kind of a more volatile business in recent years.''
koppers stock rose $3.75 a share to $57.50 on monday on the new york stock exchange
beazer proposed meeting pullin as early as sunday, but no meeting was held and none has been planned, koppers spokesman robert o'gara said monday
o'gara declined further comment beyond sunday's announcement that management would study beazer's latest proposals
southland corp. is raising $320 million in financing for its recent leveraged buyout through a loan from its convenience store licensee in japan
principal and interest on the loan from seven-eleven japan co. ltd., will be repaid from future royalties the company owes southland for use of the 7-eleven name, southland said monday
of the loan proceeds, $300 million will be applied toward repayment of debt incurred in the recently completed $4.9 billion leveraged buy-out, which took the company private, officials said
what we're doing is borrowing against the value of future royalties so we can have cash in hand right now to repay more expensive debt that we incurred in the leveraged buy-out,'' said southland spokeswoman cecilia norwood
seven-eleven japan opened its first store in tokyo in 1974 and currently operates about 3,300 7-eleven stores in japan
the $320 million _ 41 billion yen _ reflects more than 10 years worth of future royalties, ms. norwood said
southland operates 8,000 7-eleven and other convenience units in the united states and canada, as well as southland food division's six food centers. area licenses and affiliates operate more than 4,100 7-eleven stores in 16 foreign countries
southland also owns half interest in citgo petroleum corp
citicorp international, ltd., arranged the financing in conjunction with diamond lease company, ltd., and tokyo leasing company, ltd., which acted as lead managers for a syndicate of japanese financial institutions, southland said
bank of america has signed a business cooperation agreement with the people's republic of china, and says it is the first u.s. bank to make such an arrangement
the deal was signed in hong kong with china trust and investment corporation for foreign economic relations and trade, or fotic, a government-owned agency supervising all of china's major trading enterprises, bank of america spokesman jim mitchell said monday
under the agreement, bank of america and fotic will cooperate in several types of business: joint ventures, barter trade, trade finance, leasing, foreign exchange and the raising and utilization of funds
bank of america senior vice president stephen hunt, the bank's hong kong area manager, signed the agreement with fotic's deputy general manager, wan wen-li
best western is trying to become best eastern as well
the phoenix-based hotel company says it is undertaking a global expansion that it hopes will extend its reach to japan, china and 10 other asian nations
best western international inc. already has affiliate lodging properties in 33 countries in north america, europe, the middle east and the south pacific
by april, a hong kong office will be opened by carlton hotels international of canada, which will act as recruiting agent for best western in 11 countries, including china. the other countries are the phillipines, taiwan, brunei, thailand, indonesia, malaysia, singapore, hong kong, macao and south korea
ron evans, best western chief executive officer, said the company conservatively plans to have links to at least 20 more hotels within three years through the venture with carlton and that company's overseas connections
carlton already is involved in joint venture projects with the government in china and its development arm is active throughout southeast asia
best western separately will seek out new member properties in japan
the efforts are part of a master plan to have best western operations in 50 countries by 1992, increasing its member properties from some 3,300 to about 4,200
the chain also will seek properties in south america, greece, turkey and some african countries
best western enters the relationship with carlton already having made an initial entry into the region by opening a best western garden hotel in singapore last year
evans said best western's properties in asia ``will reflect the local traditions and ambience, the local architecture.''
that's why foreign countries like best western,'' he said. ``we are not converting (foreignn properties) to a cookie-cutter image. they keep their cultural traditions. we are there only to enhance their bottom lines.''
