orders to u.s. factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods continued to fall sharply in february, the government reported today
the commerce department said orders for durable goods, items expected to last at least three years, totaled a seasonally adjusted $111.4 billion last month, a 1.8 percent decline which was identical to the drop in january
it was the first time since the spring of 1986 that durable goods orders had been down for two consecutive months
the back-to-back drops surprised analysts, who had been predicting that orders would turn up again in february following a january decline which was blamed on volatility in the aircraft sector
separately, the treasury department said monday the federal government ran a $23.9 billion budget deficit in february, following a rare surplus the previous month
the $16.1 billion january surplus occurred because that month's social security checks were mailed early and counted in the december spending figures
for the first five months of the current budget year, the government has run up a deficit of $89.7 billion, 4.9 percent lower than the deficit incurred in the same period a year ago, according to treasury calculations
on wall street, analysts blamed inflation fears and lingering post-crash anxiety for the broad decline in stock prices
the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell sharply at the opening and remaining lower throughout the session, closing down 20.23 points at 2,067.14. broader market indices also fell
on the bond market, analysts said prices slipped and interest rates edged up in light trading that reflected continued uncertainty about the outlook for inflation and the economy
the treasury's closely watched 30-year bond fell \ point, or about $2.50 for every $1,000 in face value, as its yield rose to 8.70 percent from 8.67 percent late friday
foreign exchange trading also was quiet, with the dollar responding to declines in stocks and bonds by dropping against all major currencies except the canadian dollar
oil futures prices rallied, with crude piercing the $17-a-barrel level before sliding back in late trading following a statement by saudi king fahd on prices and production
fahd suggested that cheating on production quotas and prices by some members of the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries encouraged further weakness in prices
that punctured the rally on the new york mercantile exchange, where contracts for april delivery of west texas intemediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, closed at $16.49 per barrel, down 9 cents from friday. the april contract had been up as much as 45 cents during the day. reference to january and february declines and include comment. picks up 7th graf pvs, the weakness last month. ^by martin crutsinger</note>
orders to u.s. factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods fell again sharply in february, the government said today in a report that surprised analysts who had been looking for a rebound
the commerce department said orders for durable goods, items expected to last three or more years, totaled a seasonally adjusted $111.4 billion last month, a 1.8 percent decline which was identical to the drop in january
it was the first time since the spring of 1986 that durable goods orders had been down for two consecutive months. the back-to-back declines were the largest since a 2.3 percent plunge last august
the two drops surprised analysts, who had been predicting that orders would turn up again in february following a january decline which was blamed on volatility in the aircraft sector
the weakness provides evidence that the economy slowed during the early part of 1988 as businesses cut back on orders in an effort to get control of bulging inventories
the economy is weak. it hasn't fully recovered from the stock market fallout,'' said michael evans, head of a washington forecasting firm
but evans, who earlier had been forecasting a recession, said he now believes the country will be able to muddle through without a downturn during this presidential election year
he said he was expecting overall economic growth, as measured by the gross national production, to average around 1.8 percent in the first three months of the year, down from gnp growth of 4.5 in the fourth quarter
the weakness last month was widespread, with only the transportation sector showing any strength. orders for cars, trucks and aircraft showed a 3.5 percent gain to $29.3 billion following a 9 percent drop in january
orders in the volatile defense category fell 7.9 percent to $7.8 billion. without this decline, total orders would have fallen a slightly smaller 1.3 percent
the key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a good indicator of industry investment plans, fell 5.9 percent last month. this sector is expected to provide much of the strength for the economy this year as businesses step up investment spending to meet growing export demand
orders for electrical machinery fell 7.3 percent while orders in the non-electrical machinery sector were down 8.8 percent, the biggest drop for any sector
orders for primary metals such as steel dropped 0.2 percent following a 14.4 percent plunge in january
shipments of durable goods dipped 0.1 percent in february to $108.8 billion as a large decline in machinery shipments was partially offset by an increase in transportation
a trades union congress committee belatedly voted tuesday to back a single-union deal at an electronic components plant that ford motor co. has scrapped
ford decided against opening the $73 million plant in dundee, scotland after it was unable to win a single-union agreement, and the automaker said tuesday that despite the committee's vote, its decision was irrevocable
ford had reached an agreement with the amalgamated engineering union to represent the expected 450 workers at the plant, but other unions representing workers at 21 ford plants in britain balked at the plan
ford's decision caused an uproar in britain, where unions have been squabbling among themselves about how best to counter the erosion of their power under conservative prime minister margaret thatcher
the unions are particularly divided about whether to accept single-union and no-strike deals, which have become more common in britain in recent years
on tuesday, members of the finance and general purposes committee of the trades union congress, britain's large umbrella labor organization, voted 11 to 10 to back the single-union deal
the decision goes to the tuc's general council on wednesday for ratification
gavin laird, general secretary of the engineering union, said he would fly to detroit to ask ford executives to reverse their decision after the ratification
but britain's and ford's biggest union, the transport and workers general union, held out against a single union agreement
ford blamed the failure of the unions to reach agreement for its decision to cancel the deal
in detroit tuesday, ford spokesman john emmert said the company still considered its decision as final
we certainly intended it to be irrevocable, and i don't have anything in mind which would suggest that it isn't,'' emmert said in a british broadcasting corp. television interview
stocks rose early today after stumbling in the previous session over inflation fears and lingering anxiety stemming from the crash five months ago
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 5.31 points to 2,072.45 by 10 a.m. on wall street
among broader market indicators, the new york stock exchange's composite index of all listed issues rose 0.33 to 151.80. the american stock exchange's market value index rose 0.28 to 298.46
gaining issues outnumbered losers by more than 5-to-3 on the nyse, with 605 up, 364 down and 477 unchanged. volume totaled 21.1 million shares after the first half hour
on monday the dow jones industrials dropped 20.23 to 2,067.14. losing issues outnumbered gainers by about 2-to-1 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,042 down, 502 up and 444 unchanged
big board volume totaled 128.83 million shares against 245.75 million shares the previous session. it was the lowest level since a 111.58 million-share day dec. 29. million, edits to conform; picks up 8th graf pvs: the non-public ...</note>
merv griffin today boosted his bid to acquire resorts international inc. to $295 million while also waging a court fight to help him win control of the hotel-casino company
griffin co., the entertainer-businessman's private investment company, said in a statement today that it decided to increase its initial bid of $225 million, or $35-a-share, after reviewing ``appraisals regarding the value of resorts.''
based on 6.43 million class a and class b shares outstanding, griffin's latest bid for both classes of stock is valued at about $46 a share
separately, griffin said monday it filed a $500 million federal lawsuit in new york against real estate developer donald trump and resorts' directors, claiming breach of fiduciary duty to shareholders, among other things
trump, who has voting control of resorts and is the company's chairman, sued griffin last week, accusing the entertainer of interfering with trump's contractual agreement to acquire complete control over resorts
since making its initial offer thursday, the griffin co. has indicated it may raise the price if justified by non-public information from resorts, a hotel-casino concern with operations in atlantic city, n.j. and the bahamas. griffin said trump made that information available late last week
trump, who is making his own $22-per-share bid for the resorts stock he doesn't already own, said he won't boost his offer and has maintained that he will not sell his shares to griffin
resorts' board said it decided not to pursue griffin's initial bid because, in light of trump's rejection, the issue was moot
griffin said in a statement today that he would not approve any deal between resorts and trump ``unless class a shareholders receive a premium over my prior $35-a-share offer.''
the non-public documents were contained in a securities and exchange commission filing trump made on friday to supplement his tender offer for resorts
trump's tender offer, which had been scheduled to expire monday, was extended until 12:01 a.m. est on april 1
griffin's president, michael nigris, said the documents included a $1.3 billion appraisal of resorts' properties, including a when-completed value for its luxurious but troubled taj mahal hotel-casino in atlantic city
the appraiser further said it was prepared to support a bank mortgage loan of $550 million guaranteed by resorts, nigris said
based on those numbers, we may be able to sweeten our $225 million bid,'' nigris said monday
the $550 million mortgage is the amount trump has said will be needed to complete the taj mahal. when resorts began work on the project in 1984, it estimated the total price at $535 million. that figure has since soared to $938.5 million based on trump's estimates
trump became involved with resorts last year when the company ran into financial difficulties with the proposed 42-floor, 1,250-room taj mahal. he bought up most of resorts' class b common stock, which carries 100 votes per share, thus giving him 88 percent voting control
he also pledged to help arrange financing for the costly taj mahal project and, in exchange, was granted a five-year operating contract for resorts properties valued at about $100 million
resorts has 752,000 class b shares. it has 5.7 million class a shares that carry one vote each. resorts</head> increasing bid, picks up 4th graf pvs: both contestants ...</note>
in this corner: affable, courtly and somewhat portly mervyn edward griffin, the singer and talk show host who in recent years has emerged as a wily and successful businessman
and in the far corner: brash new york real estate developer donald j. trump, best known for building designer-label skyscrapers, owning casinos and having more than a modest dose of braggadocio
late last week, griffin and trump squared off over control of resorts international inc., the new jersey-based hotel-casino concern that trump has been offering to acquire for $22 per share, or about to acquire. griffin last week offered $35 per share, or $225 million for the atlantic city-based company, which also has operations in the bahamas
the battle escalated today when griffin increased his bid to $295 million, which values both class a and class b resorts shares at about $46 each
both contestants among america's wealthiest men. trump is listed by forbes magazine as worth at least $850 million, and personally claims $3 billion in wealth. forbes lists griffin as worth $300 million
for 23 years, griffin served as host of the popular ``merv griffin show,'' one of tv's longest-running series, winning 10 emmy awards in the process
in 1986, he sold privately-held merv griffin enterprises _ producer of the ``merv griffin show'' and two of his other successful creations, ``wheel of fortune'' and ``jeopardy'' _ to coca-cola co. for a reported $250 million. but he remains chairman of the company, and there is speculation he may take over as host of ``wheel of fortune'' when host pat sajak leaves to do his own show
unlike many entertainers who squander their money through bad investments and mismanagement, the 63-year-old griffin has earned a reputation in hollywood as a shrewd businessman
he has parlayed his entertainment fortune into a business empire that includes radio stations, a major closed-circuit television operation widely used at racetracks, and extensive real estate holdings in beverly hills and northern california
griffin, whose hobbies are music, tennis and good food, lives stylishly, but not ostentatiously, in a 10,000-square-foot beverly hills mansion near the homes of mca inc. chairman lew wasserman and investor marvin davis
by contrast, the 42-year-old trump, who in a decade transformed himself from a local landlord into a national real estate mogul, has worked hard to make his name synonymous with ostentation
he routinely travels in one of his fleet of five helicopters. when william bricker was ousted as chief executive of dallas-based diamond shamrock corp. amid criticism over his imperial lifestyle, trump purchased his luxurious boeing 727 private jet
his primary home is a $10 million triplex penthouse atop his glitzy trump tower in midtown manhattan. for relaxation, he retreats to his 118-room mansion in west palm beach, fla., or his 15-bedroom georgian manor in greenwich, conn
i can't afford for things not to be the best,'' trump has said, contending the glamour attached to his name _ and the buildings that bear his name _ allows him to attract prices of $1,700 per square foot for some of his new york condos
with a massive war chest to spend, trump was attracted by the lure of profits in takeover speculation. in the past year, he bought stakes in allegis corp., holiday corp. and bally mfg. co., and raked in about $122 million in profits when he later sold the stock to the company or rival suitors
earlier this year, trump said he was considering buying up to 24.9 percent of entertainment conglomerate mca, the parent of universal studios which is frequently mentioned as a takeover target. but nothing has come of it
likewise, nothing has come of his indications in january that he might buy up to 15 percent of federated department stores inc. _ which later became the takeover target of campeau corp
but when griffin decided to battle trump for resorts, the fight generally was expected to be short and victorious for trump
griffin is offering more money, but trump holds 88 percent of resorts' voting power through his ownership of nearly all of its class b common stock, which carries 100 votes per share
trump has insisted he will oppose griffin's proposal, and for that reason resorts' board decided it was moot to pursue the issue with the entertainer
but griffin has persisted. on monday, he slapped trump and resorts' directors with a $500 million lawsuit, accusing them, among other things, of breach of fiduciary duty
that action came after trump on friday filed a $250 million suit against griffin and his allies, claiming fraud, stock market manipulation and interference with trump's contractual arrangements with resorts
meanwhile, some holders of resorts' 5.7 million class a shares who had earlier indicated they would support trump's $22-per-share offer now are having second thoughts, their lawyers say. securities</head>
a unanimous supreme court today ruled that states are barred from regulating the way interstate natural gas companies issue securities to finance their operations
the court, ruling in a dispute between the michigan public service commission and a detroit-based pipeline, said the federal energy regulatory commission has sole authority to regulate such financing
justice harry a. blackmun, writing for the court, said the state authority sought by the michigan agency is pre-empted by the federal natural gas act of 1938
a federal appeals court previously had ruled against the michigan authorities
michigan law required pipeline companies to get advance approval from the state public service commission before issuing securities
the law was passed to assure that the securities were being issued for a legal purpose _ one related to the more efficient delivery of natural gas
the regulatory law was challenged in 1984 by american natural resources, which operates a pipeline system carrying natural gas to distribution customers in michigan, illinois, indiana, iowa, kansas, missouri, ohio, tennessee and wisconsin
according to court documents, the anr has plans to issue $150 million in securities to help finance projects costing about $560 million
