stocks turned mixed today, strengthened by higher bond prices and takeover-related buying, but restrained by investor reluctance to participate in a market still suffering post-crash uncertainty
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.16 points to 2,068.30 by 11 a.m. on wall street
among broader market indicators, the new york stock exchange's composite index of all listed issues rose 0.10 to 151.57. the american stock exchange's market value index rose 0.20 to 298.38
gaining issues barely outnumbered losers on the nyse, with 613 up, 558 down and 527 unchanged. volume totaled 45.5 million shares after 90 minutes
rising prices in the bond market injected some optimism on wall street because they dampened anxiety over inflation and higher interest rates. bonds were buoyed by lower oil prices and a government report that showed a surprising drop in factory orders for durable goods in february
some stocks also were boosted by rumored and actual takeovers, reflecting a stunning increase in merger activity over the past several weeks
nevertheless, stockbrokers said the relatively low volume of trading and the lack of any significant economic signals showed that many investors remain reluctant to re-enter the market in the aftermath of the october crash
people still are wounded,'' said philip c. puccio, manager of institutional trading at dillon read &amp; co. ``those wounds have not scarred over yet. there's fear we could be looking at another downdraft.''
among the most active issues, lucky stores shot up 14\ to 46{ after rival chain american stores announced a $45-a-share tender offer for the company. kansas city southern, target of a $60-a-share takeover attempt by a new york investor group, advanced 2~ to 57~
on monday the dow jones industrials dropped 20.23 to 2,067.14. losing issues outnumbered gainers by about 2-to-1 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,042 down, 502 up and 444 unchanged
big board volume totaled 128.83 million shares against 245.75 million shares the previous session. it was the lowest level since a 111.58 million-share day dec. 29
a.h. robins co. says it will submit another amended reorganization plan as the result of a court hearing on the adequacy of the company's disclosure statement
u.s. district judge robert r. merhige jr. and u.s. bankruptcy judge blackwell n. shelley conducted the hearing monday, listening to a series of objections to the disclosure statement
the document is the basis by which women with dalkon shield injury claims and other creditors of robins will decide how to vote on the company's reorganization plan
robins spokesman roscoe e. puckett jr. said monday evening that as a result of the hearing, the company ``will submit a sixth amended and restated plan of reorganization incorporating certain changes,'' mostly in the wording of the statement. the new plan will be filed in bankruptcy court by march 28, he said
merhige set an april 25 deadline for mailing the plan of reorganization to dalkon shield claimants and the company's other creditors for a vote. the votes must be received by july 11 and a confirmation hearing will be july 18, puckett said
merhige also said he hoped to choose by april 11 the five trustees who will administer the nearly $2.5 billion compensation fund for dalkon shield victims
the u.s. supreme court, in a related action monday, let stand a ruling against a $15 million emergency fund to help women who became infertile from using the intrauterine device, which robins sold in the early 1970s. the supreme court also refused to review a ruling that placed on hold several lawsuits against the insurer of the iud
robins has been in chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings since august 1985. the richmond-based maker of pharmaceuticals sought court protection from creditors as lawsuits mounted against the birth control device
joseph f. mcdowell iii, a manchester, n.h., attorney for 35 users of the iud, told merhige and shelley the disclosure statement should not go out because it appeared to give a discharge from liability to not only robins but to its insurer, corporate directors and members of the robins' family
attorneys for robins and the aetna casualty &amp; surety co. that insured the dalkon shield said claimants voting to ratify the reorganization plan are not prevented from subsequently going to court. mcdowell's objection was overruled
an attorney for the internal revenue service challenged an arrangement for robins to repay the federal tax agency's priority claim over a six-year period
we're being asked to make a $62 million unsecured loan at prime interest,'' said stuart gibson, an irs tax lawyer
merhige, however, overruled the objection. ``it's your own fault,'' the judge told gibson. ``i asked you to settle it ... and you couldn't do it.''
in washington, the supreme court upheld the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals' decision to reject the $15 million emergency fund, which merhige had approved as a means of helping women still of child-bearing age to regain fertility through special surgery
the emergency fund was challenged by robins' stockholders as giving preferential treatment to a select group of claims while the final reorganization was pending
the high court's decision not to review the stay of lawsuits against aetna upheld merhige and the 4th circuit. the appeals court said the suits brought by women in kansas and new hampshire inevitably would pull in robins and thus would detract from the ongoing bankruptcy proceedings
ford motor co. said it will begin exporting its lincoln continental and mercury sable cars this spring to south korea, where they will sell for about three times their u.s. prices
south korea dropped a ban on car imports last year, but tariffs, taxes and fees remain in place
ford said monday that the continentals and sables will sell in south korea for about $42,000 and $75,000, respectively. in the united states, sables sell for about $14,000 to $16,000 while continentals fetch between $25,000 and $30,000 per car
general motors corp. also has begun a small-scale program to ship luxury cars to south korea. gm said its buicks and cadillacs also will sell for about three times their u.s. prices
grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly lower today on the chicago board of trade
analysts said soybean futures were pressured by accelerated overnight selling by farmers, while corn prices were hit by news that vermont sen. patrick leahy is moving ahead with legislation that would ultimately put more corn on the market
wheat futures were higher, after a decline on monday
