the supreme court today rejected the internal revenue service's attempt to impose stiffer taxes when individuals or business partnerships form corporations to obtain financing
by an 8-0 vote, the court said real estate developers in kentucky should not be subjected to a heavier tax burden because they formed corporations for the sole purpose of borrowing money
jesse c. bollinger, either individually or in partnership with others, developed eight apartment complexes in the lexington, ky., area beginning in 1968
to obtain construction-financing loans, bollinger formed corporations to borrow the money at 8 percent interest. kentucky's usury law at the time limited the interest non-corporate borrowers could be charged to 7 percent, and lenders were not willing to finance bollinger's projects at that rate
when bollinger and his partners sought to claim business losses connected with the apartment projects on their individual federal income taxes, the irs disallowed it
the tax agency said the losses must be attributed to the corporations, deemed to be the true owners of the apartment complexes. that designation worked to the tax disadvantage of bollinger and his partners
a federal appeals court ruled against the irs, and today's decision upheld that ruling
writing for the court, justice antonin scalia said the corporations had been formed for a legitimate, non-manipulative purpose
it seems to us that ... tax-avoiding manipulation (is) adequately avoided when ... the corporation is acting as agent for its shareholders with respect to a particular asset (the apartment complexes) is set forth in a written agreement at the time the asset is acquired,'' scalia said
he also noted that the corporations at issue in this case functioned ``as agent and not principal with respect to the asset for all purposes, and the corporation is held out as the agent and not principal in all dealings with third parties relating to the asset.''
the case is commissioner, irs vs. bollinger, 86-1672. offer</head>
italian investor carlo de benedetti has increased his holdings in societe generale de belgique sa by 3.53 percent, but it was not known if his alliance held a majority stake in belgium's largest holding company, officials said tuesday
an official at de benedetti's french investment company cerus sa, who asked not to be named, did not know whether the public offer gave de benedetti and his allies control of the company
this alliance claimed to control 47.01 percent of societe generale's shares before tuesday. the newly purchased shares would apparently raise this to 50.54 percent. but the cerus official said the 47.01 percent might have included some shares from the public offer
on march 10, a franco-belgian alliance opposing de benedetti claimed to control 50.7 percent of societe generale
tuesday's announcement was the latest twist in one of europe's biggest and most complex takeover battles. it failed to provide definite clues about the outcome, more than two months after de benedetti first announced his bid for 166-year-old societe generale
on march 10, de benedetti called for shareholders meeting, which should make it clear which side has a majority. the meeting is set for april 14
meanwhile, a court case was still pending on a societe generale capital increase to fend off de benedetti. the ruling in that case might still dramatically change the stakes each side claims to hold
cerus, the investment firm through which de benedetti was vying for control of societe generale, said tuesday it had obtained 1.087 million additional shares, or 3.53 percent of the company's total share capital, including warrants
cerus launched a public offer for the extra shares on feb. 15. the bid was to have expired march 4 but has since been extended
the offer was designed to acquire 2.1 million shares, or about 7 percent of the share capital of societe generale
cerus offered 8,000 francs, or $228, for ordinary shares in the last stage of its public offer
reacting to tuesday's announcement, the management of societe generale, which opposes de benedetti, said there were no defections from the franco-belgian alliance to cerus' camp
de benedetti wants to turn societe generale into the platform of a pan-european holding company while the franco-belgian group wants to keep the company firmly entrenched in the belgian economic fabric
on tuesday, societe generale announced its net profit in 1987 fell 22.1 percent to stand at 4.138 billion francs. societe generale has a stake in over 1,200 companies world-wide and the government has stressed the company is vital for its investment strategy, technological development and its relations with its former colony zaire
the de benedetti group consists of cerus, the u.s. investment bank shearson lehman hutton inc., the swiss bank companie de banque et d'investissements and the food giant nestle sa, two belgian partners and several smaller allies
the franco-belgian alliance is anchored around the french investment firm companie financiere de suez and belgium's biggest insurer, groupe ag sa and includes several other partners
a federal jury has awarded a record $7.95 million to the estate of an ibm executive and his wife killed in a delta air lines crash outside dallas, including more than $6 million for his lost potential earnings at the computer company
the jury at u.s. district court in manhattan deliberated just five hours before returning its verdict at 8:30 p.m. monday in the suit by the estate of philip d. estridge, 47, of new canaan, conn., and his wife mary ann
estridge, who received much of the credit for moving ibm into the personal computer market, and his wife were among 137 people killed when the lockheed l-1011 crashed on approach at dallas-fort worth international airport on aug. 2, 1985
i thought it would have been more, and it should have been more,'' said attorney lee kreindler, who had asked for $25 million for estridge and $5 million for his wife. ``i was a little disappointed with the numbers.''
but evelyn eubanks, one of three daughters who filed the suit, said they were happy with the judgment and the end of the case
we don't think anything could have happened any better and we're definitely relieved it's over,'' she said. ``it doesn't make it better, but it helps us to live with it.''
kreindler said the sum awarded monday was a record for compensatory damages in a wrongful-death suit. the breakdown was $6.25 million for estridge's loss of earnings, $750,000 for loss of enjoyment of life and $100,000 for mental anguish
for mrs. estridge, the jury awarded $750,000 for loss of enjoyment of life and $100,000 for mental anguish
shortly before estridge died, the jacksonville, fla., native was named overseer of ibm's worldwide manufacturing operations, based in new york, at a salary of $240,000 yearly
although the trial was held in new york city, the award was reached under the law of estridge's new home state of connecticut to allow for the salary projection figures, kreindler said
delta lawyer john sabetta declined to comment on the award, but told judge john e. sprizzo he would appeal. delta spokesman bill berry referred all calls to the company's insurance carrier, u.s. aviation underwriters, and had no comment
the estridge verdict came on the same day of opening arguments in another suit stemming from the fatal crash
a wrongful-death suit on behalf of julie ann zarnt of boca raton, fla., opened monday with a 12-minute videotape highlighting her 15 years of life
the first half of the tape was made from silent home movies. it showed her as a newborn first coming home and as a toddler celebrating birthdays and christmas
in the stock market, the names, numbers and skills of the players change but the game remains about the same no matter how many times we are told that ``it's a whole new ball game.''
never was that advice more freely offered, more uncritically accepted and more avariciously followed than in the stock market of 1987, which crashed to reality on oct. 19
it is, by popular agreement, the big lesson emerging bit by bit as the event recedes into history, and as once giddy and greedy minds resume more sober interpretations of the economy
the various studies under way or completed seem to emphasize such factors as ``portfolio insurance'' and futures trading and other technical factors that arose over the past decade and seemingly changed the market's makeup
no doubt, such factors could have contributed, but it is now patently clear they couldn't have done so without the presence of the same old psychological undercurrent that boosted stock prices beyond reason
the omens were there to absorb or ignore:
shares sold at 22 times earnings, vs. a long-time norm under 15. they were priced at 2{ to 3 times a company's liquidation value, a full point above the long-term norm. dividend yields were half what they should have been
critics with a classic education in the ways of the stock market pointed to these lessons, and more, and were scorned as old-fashioned. who were they to argue with sophisticated electronic computations? do computers lie?
the oldtimers' admonitions have left an eerie echo, a painful one, somewhat akin to parental warnings that were ignored because, every child knows, parents issue warnings to children because that's what parents are supposed to do
looking back, some of the market's smartest investors, including big-name portfolio managers for mutual funds, insurers and the like, wonder how they got drawn into a market they knew was headed for a fall
they knew, but apparently couldn't resist the temptation of what they thought was easy money, just as others before them fell because they were governed by emotions peculiar to the human species
it is still a debate with some of them as they review the crash. they knew the old rules still applied. they knew the market was destined to correct its imbalance _ that is, fall. they knew the rules of the game hadn't changed
but, they ask, was it reason or emotion that governed their decision to jump in? was it unreasonable to assume that a market propelled ever higher, no matter how irrationally, offered an opportunity to make a quick buck?
was it reasonable or foolish to ignore the stories of quick profits by your brother-in-law and not be tempted to do the same? or, for a fund manager, was it foolhardy or sensible to try keeping pace with dice-throwing competitors?
you can blame the crash on new trading techniques, the acceleration of trading activity by means of computers, and the instantaneous communications that seem to exaggerate advances and declines
something might be done eventually to mute the adverse effects of these factors, but judging from the evidence of last fall there is little that can be done with the players themselves
the names and numbers change, and some of the techniques, too, but the game will always be played by human beings, and they can be expected to act no differently
digital equipment corp. says it has signed the nation's biggest explosives company as a customer because it can give ``more bang for the buck'' than international business machines corp
digital said tuesday it sold atlas powder co. a vax 8700 for its dallas headquarters and three microvax systems for production facilities in joplin, mo.; tamaqua, pa.; and frankfort, ky
the contract is for between $2 million and $3 million, including related data-storage devices, according to darwin wolfe, the company's director of information services
atlas, a subsidiary of dallas-based tyler corp., is switching from ibm
shareholders attending what could be firestone tire &amp; rubber co.'s last annual meeting tuesday voted to shorten the company's name but had little to say about bridgestone corp.'s bid for the tire maker
about 900 people attended the half-hour meeting, where shareholders voted to change the company's name to firestone, inc
shareholders asked only two questions about bridgestone's offer to pay $80 a share, or $2.6 billion, for firestone's outstanding shares. stockholders will meet again april 25 to vote on the tender offer
bridgestone's bid, which was accepted by firestone's board, exceeds a $1.86 billion offer from italian tire maker pirelli s.p.a
after the meeting, firestone chairman john j. nevin met briefly with reporters and discussed firestone's talks with bridgestone and pirelli. firestone and bridgestone had planned a 75 percent joint venture until pirelli made its unsolicited, $58-a-share bid for all of firestone's 32 million outstanding shares
nevin said he told both bridgestone and pirelli in negotiations that firestone was holding talks with a third firm that he declined to identify
nevin speculated that bridgestone was able to make its tender offer quickly because of its prior knowledge of firestone. bridgestone purchased a plant from firestone in 1983
i don't want to speculate on what bridgestone would have done under other circumstances. but i think all of the background that bridgestone had acquired in discussions with us earlier certainly made it much more possible for bridgestone to move quickly in a two-week period,'' said nevin
i think that had we announced in mid-february that the board of directors had decided to enter into a joint venture with pirelli rather than bridgestone, i think it was improbable that bridgestone then would have made an unsolicited tender offer ... this was by no means an unfriendly action on bridgestone's part,'' nevin said
he reiterated that he has no plans to buy back from bridgestone any of firestone's non-tire businesses, including its 1,500 mastercare car repair operations
opec president rilwanu lukman postponed indefinitely a scheduled news conference that was expected to have focused on stabilizing sagging oil prices, the guardian newspaper said
last week nigerian petroleum ministry officials said lukman would announce tuesday new measures to bring stability to the market
but the ministry said the news conference had been called off, according to the newspaper. no new date was given
lukman has accused the western news media of trying to destabilize the oil market to bring down prices, adding opec would not be driven into taking emergency measures to stop the fall of oil prices
he also has vowed the cartel would stand firm on its decision to produce 15.60 million barrels of oil a day. a barrel of oil is equivalent to 42 gallons
