there is no evidence g.d. searle and co. withheld information from the food and drug administration in winning approval for its copper-7 intrauterine contraceptive device, an fda spokeswoman said tuesday
fda officials met with searle representatives last week to discuss whether company documents recently unsealed in a minnesota court case challenging the iud were available to the government agency before it approved the device in 1974
the gist of our initial review is that we've had that information all along, and that we got it when we initially began reviewing'' searle's application for approval of the iud, said spokewoman susan cruzan
there's no evidence they didn't give us all the necessary inforatmion when we began our review,'' she said
the searle iud remains on the government approved list, but the company stopped selling it in 1986, citing growing costs from court suits
the company faces about 500 suits by women who claim that the copper-7 caused them to develop pelvic infections. the company has won 14 of the 17 suits that have gone to trial and maintains that the device was, and is, safe
the dollar finished mixed in dull trading tuesday as buyers focused their attention on other major currencies
