democrat richard gephardt charged tuesday that michael dukakis' support for tough trade legislation is just ``a political ploy'' that will end after the michigan caucuses are over
dukakis, the massachusetts governor, said his position on trade has been consistent, and his staff released quotations from last year indicating his support for major provisions of a senate trade bill
who is for a tough trade policy? who is going to be for a tough trade policy after michigan?'' gephardt asked in a telephone interview tuesday. ``the answer is, dick gephardt is and will be. mike dukakis hasn't been, isn't and won't be.''
when he is on the east and west coast, he wants to talk about free trade. when he's in michigan, he doesn't,'' gephardt said
gephardt's tough trade legislation, now in a conference committee on capitol hill, has been the capstone of the missouri congressman's platform
monday night, dukakis endorsed trade legislation sponsored by michigan sen. donald riegle, who in turn endorsed dukakis. gephardt quickly accused dukakis of having a ``battlefield conversion'' on trade, saying the riegle bill was the senate version of the gephardt legislation
dukakis and jesse jackson are tied for the lead in the polls on saturday's michigan caucuses, with gephardt a distant third. dukakis aides say that may be the reason for gephardt's attacks
on tuesday, gephardt stepped up the attack, questioning the sincerity of dukakis' support for such legislation
i think he remains against it. i think it is a political ploy,'' gephardt said. ``by what he has done, he is trying to have it both ways. ... now that he is in michigan and we are five days out from the caucuses, he wants to fool the people of michigan.''
dukakis said in michigan late monday that his position hasn't changed
he has been a strong opponent of the gephardt bill from the begining, but has always been an advocate of leveling the (trade) playing field,'' said dukakis spokesman leslie dach
dukakis' staff on tuesday pointed to quotes from the massachusetts governor last year in favor of the senate bill
on july 11, 1987, dukakis said, ``i think the trade bill which the senate approved yesterday says if there is a consistent pattern of unfair trade practices ... there i think we have to do something.''
i feel a lot better about the senate bill'' than the gephardt trade legislation, dukakis said on aug. 4, 1987
gephardt said dukakis ``has said in the past you don't need new legislation. ... he has been profoundly negative about everything i have said about trade.''
the congressman, too, provided quotes from dukakis last year _ quotes he said back up his charge of a flip-flop
the president today has all the authority he needs to do something about those unfair trade practices. we do not need more laws or more amendments,'' dukakis said at the aug. 8 debate at drake university, according to gephardt aides
in debates in dallas and atlanta, dukakis told gephardt, ``you want a law. dick, i want to act.''
and earlier this year in lansing, mich., gephardt aides said, dukakis said ``we do not need more legislation.''
the gephardt amemdment and the riegle bill do differ, but both try to strengthen potential retaliation against u.s. trading partners for unfair practices. in general, the riegle bill would target specific industries in foreign countries which engage in unfair practices. the gephardt amendment would trigger retaliation against another country for running a big surplus with this country in part through unfair practices
dukakis has always felt the president has had the authority to act. the riegle amendment ... gives the president a better way to get there, but he can pretty much get there on his own now,'' dukakis spokesman dach said
allis-chalmers corp., a once-mighty industrial giant that filed for bankruptcy reorganization last june, tuesday reported a net loss of $15.2 million, or $1.17 per share, for the fourth quarter of 1987
the loss, on sales of $109.3 million, compared with a loss of $5.8 million, or 52 cents per share, for the same period of 1986 when sales totaled $116.8 million
for the year, allis-chalmers reported a total loss of $29.3 million compared with a loss of $8.6 million in 1986. sales in 1987 declined to $410 million from $510.3 million in 1986
wendell f. bueche, chairman and chief executive officer, said the results reflected obligations from years before the company scaled down by selling off many of its businesses. once a major producer of farm machinery, the company later diversified into production of a wide range of other equipment
bueche said the cost of health care benefits for retired employees was disproportionate to the company's size, althoughthe company has implemented a strategy aimed at reducing that expense
economists stuck by their optimistic predictions for u.s. manufacturing on tuesday in spite of a government report that orders to american factories for ``big-ticket'' durable goods fell 1.8 percent in february
in other news, the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 0.99 point to 2,066.15; the dollar was mixed against other major currencies; and bond prices were little changed in light trading
the commerce department said orders for durable goods _ items expected to last three or more years _ totaled a seasonally adjusted $111.4 billion in february, following an identical 1.8 percent january decline
it was the first time since the spring of 1986 that durable goods orders have fallen for two consecutive months
economists maintained that manufacturing companies still were enjoying good business because the weaker dollar has boosted export demand
what we have is a two-month hesitation after some big increases,'' said allen sinai, chief economist of the boston co
still, analysts said the back-to-back declines showed businesses were cutting back on orders in the early part of 1988 in an effort to get control of bulging inventories. inventories swelled at the end of 1987 while consumer demand fell
cynthia latta, an economist with data resources inc., noted that while new orders fell in february, the total backlog of unfilled orders rose 0.7 percent to $397.1 billion, the 12th consecutive monthly increase
this backlog suggests that factories can keep humming along for a while even though new orders dropped,'' she said
fortune 44 co. of boulder is getting out of the fortune cookie business, saying the slow market for the cookies could spell problems for the company's future
company officials announced the decision on monday, citing continuing losses and sales which have not met expectations. fortune 44 believes the lack of sales are due to the limited market, the infrequent purchase cycle and intense competition in the low-price end of the fortune cookie market, officials said in a written statement
when's the last time you bought fortune cookies?'' said the company's controller, mary lou schwab. ``we're in the grocery store business where things have to turn. people buy fortune cookies but mostly for a special occasion.''
the company will service existing customers through may, she said
started in 1983, fortune 44 employs eight people and offers 20 different varieties of the cookies, including its wish biscuits and lucky chan lines
company officials said they have received inquiries from competitors interested in acquiring its lines and said fortune 44 is pursuing those inquiries. management also is seeking an acquisition or merger candidate and is having ongoing discussions with two companies, the statement said
the company is optimistic it can find a merger or acquisition that can benefit shareholders, officials said
fortune 44 reported assets totaling nearly $1.2 million last september; it has 110 shareholders
a department store chain's attempt to avoid paying taxes for merchandise catalogs received by its louisiana customers sparked skeptical questioning tuesday in the supreme court
andrew rinker jr., representing new orleans-based d.h. holmes co., seemed to be having little success in arguing that his client should not have to pay a louisiana ``use tax'' on the catalogs' value
rinker spent nearly 30 minutes responding to the justices' questions. by contrast, shreveport, la., lawyer robert g. pugh concluded his presentation for state tax officials in less than 10 minutes because he was asked so few questions
the court's decision is expected by july
rinker, from new orleans, contended that no tax should be assessed because the catalogs are published in other states and mailed directly to louisiana residents
the state imposes a tax on all tangible personal property bought or used within louisiana
when rinker argued that the department store chain actually had paid for a service _ delivery of the catalogs _ and not for goods, several justices seemed to disagree
holmes put this whole operation into creation,'' said chief justice william h. rehnquist
justice sandra day o'connor questioned whether delivery of the catalogs, even through the u.s. mail, is ``an activity that can be taxed.''
she later seemed to answer her own question in the affirmative: ``holmes caused the distribution in louisiana. it ordered it. it paid for it.''
when rinker contended that it is holmes' customers, not holmes, who use the catalogs, justice byron r. white responded, ``holmes is having that use provided.''
when justice thurgood marshall asked, ``could holmes have made a dollar in the state of louisiana without the catalogs?'' rinker said many of the customers who frequent holmes' 13 stores in louisiana did so long before catalogs were mailed out
those are pretty old people,'' white quipped
rinker acknowledged that the department store chain could be subjected to the louisiana tax if the catalogs are delivered to the state and distributed from there. but he said the current set-up precludes state tax liability
pugh argued that the real taxable activity undertaken by holmes is ``maintaing a market in louisiana for their sales.''
d.h. holmes co. also operates stores in mississippi, alabama and florida but 82 percent of its catalogs are mailed to louisiana residents
the state tax imposed on holmes is based on 82 percent of the catalogs' value, and the validity of applying the tax to the catalogs was upheld by state courts
the case is d.h. holmes co. vs. mcnamara, 87-267
csx corp. said tuesday it has agreed to sell its oil and natural gas exploration subsidiary to houston-based total minatome corp. for $612 million
the sale of csx oil &amp; gas corp. is expected to be completed in about 30 days, said csx chairman hays t. watkins in a joint announcement with minatome president jean-pierre donnet
the csx subsidiary's principal operations are located in the united states, mostly along the gulf coasts of texas and louisiana, and in the north sea
total minatome is involved in exploration and production in wyoming, oklahoma, the gulf coast and the gulf of mexico. it is a wholly-owned subsidiary of total compagnie francaise des petroles, which is based in france
the deal will allow total minatome a chance to expand its u.s. and north sea operations and is in keeping with csx's plan to concentrate on its primary transportation, pipeline, property and technology groups, donnet and watkins said
merrill lynch &amp; co. inc. and its futures trading subsidiary agreed to pay a $150,000 fine to settle administrative charges arising from alleged fraud committed by a financial consultant in the firm's dallas office, the commodity futures trading commission said tuesday
the consultant, charles dennis scott of arlington, texas, was charged by the agency with fraud resulting from illegally allocating trades in cotton futures contracts among his own and his customers' accounts
merrill lynch was charged with being liable for scott's conduct between december 1980 and august 1982, for failing to properly supervise him and for failing to keep proper records
the firm also was charged with hindering the cftc investigation in 1983-84 by failing to promptly provide documents. according to dennis klejna, cftc enforcement director, the delay amounted to 18 months
the firm, its subsidiary and scott all settled the charges without admitting or denying them and were ordered to refrain from future violations
scott agreed to pay a $40,000 fine and accepted a suspension of his registration for three weeks beginning on wednesday. he also agreed to a permanent ban on trading for his own account
klejna said he could not release information on how many customers were affected or the amount of the alleged fraud
michael geczi, a spokesman for merrill lynch, had no immediate response to the cftc announcement
sears, roebuck and co. said tuesday it has begun its $19-a-share tender offer for all outstanding common stock of western auto supply co
the tender offer expires april 18, unless extended
as previously reported, directors and management of western auto have agreed to sell to sears 52.3 percent of the outstanding shares upon completion of the tender offer
sears said the deal is expected to cost $250 million for the stock, plus $152 million in assumed debt. decker withdrawing bid; no pickup</note>
black &amp; decker corp. withdrew its $77-a-share bid for american standard inc. tuesday, halting the bidding war over the plumbing giant, and allowing a $2.45 billion leveraged buyout spearheaded by kelso &amp; co. to go forward
under the agreement reached tuesday, the towson-based tool manufacturer agreed not to purchase shares of american standard until kelso has had an opportunity to pursue its $78-a-share tender offer, according to a black &amp; decker announcement
under the agreement, kelso will pay black &amp; decker $25 million for withdrawing its bid, as soon as kelso begins purchasing stock under its tender offer or acquires at least 20 percent of american standard's shares in any other transaction
seventy-seven (dollars) was our top price,'' said barbara lucas, a black &amp; decker spokeswoman. ms. lucas said black &amp; decker had initially thought kelso's financing would not come through but it appeared kelso would be able to finance the deal
a spokeswoman for new york-based american standard said the company had no comment on the agreement
they (black &amp; decker) would still be making a deal at $77 if kelso-american standard wasn't able to pull it off,'' said analyst cornelius v. sewell of argus research corp. in new york
sewell said american standard's transportation products division, valued at about $600 million, is likely to be sold to pay off the debt incurred by kelso to purchase the company
american standard had resisted black &amp; decker's takeover overtures for months, including a sweetened $2.4 billion, or $77-a-share, offer made last week
instead, american standard agreed to a $78-a-share leveraged buyout spearheaded by the new york investment banking firm. last week american standard said its board would recommend kelso's $2.45 billion offer to shareholders
the agreement reached tuesday, including the $25 million payment, is conditioned on black &amp; decker not renewing its takeover bid for american standard
if kelso terminates its merger agreement with american standard or fails to purchase shares by may 2, black &amp; decker is free to pursue the acquisition of american standard, according to black &amp; decker
earlier tuesday, the new york stock exchange halted trading in black &amp; decker and american standard shares for three hours in anticipation of an announcement by black &amp; decker
nyse vice president richard torrenzano said at the time that black &amp; decker ``initiated a call'' to the exchange and ``shared with us information concerning the american standard bid which materially could affect the price of their stock.''
no announcement was forthcoming
both stocks began trading again at 1:43 p.m. est. after resumption, american standard rose 12.5 cents to $77 a share while black &amp; decker was unchanged at $20.125 a share. california, where most suits filed, other details, reax, moving list of plaintiffs lower. changes byline; also moved on general newswires</note>
eight states on tuesday filed suit accusing dozens of insurance companies of conspiring to create the liability insurance crisis, making coverage unavailable or too costly for many governments and businesses
the companies' actions were ``a major contributor to the insurance crisis that forced so many cities and businesses up against the wall,'' california attorney general john van de kamp said at a news conference
it was the public and the consumer who paid the price for this collusive exercise in corporate greed,'' he said
david ostwald, a vice president of the insurance services office, a 1,400-member rate and policy advisory organization named in the lawsuits, called the claims unfounded and denied the existence of a conspiracy
the lawsuits filed in u.s. district court here by seven states accuses major u.s. and british insurance firms, reinsurers and ostwald's trade group of using secret agreements and internal pressure several years ago in an effort to eliminate the most common type of general liability policy, that covering any damage that occurs during the policy term regardless of when the damage is discovered
reinsurers provide vital backup coverage for other insurers, van de kamp said
the attorneys general of california, new york, west virginia, wisconsin, minnesota, massachusetts and alabama filed similar suits in u.s. district court in san francisco, naming 32 insurance companies, underwriters and associations
van de kamp said arizona would sue in the same court wednesday. a separate lawsuit was filed in state court in austin, texas
these defendants have sucked the blood of our nation's economic well-being,'' texas attorney general jim mattox said at a news conference. texas filed suit in state court because the state ``has one of the toughest, best antitrust laws in the nation,'' he said
as a result of the conspiracy, california's suit said, property damage insurance for local governments, non-profit agencies such as child care centers, and various businesses suddenly became unavailable or prohibitively expensive
in california and elsewhere, local governments cut back or eliminated services, such as parks and police, because of insurance expenses, van de kamp said. many local government officials blamed rising damage awards in injury suits and joined the insurance industry in efforts to restrict the right to sue
the lawsuits claim the companies targeted for elimination coverage for spills and other types of pollution incidents and general liability for damage discovered after the life of a policy, known as ``occurrence'' coverage
the companies instead favored more limited policies, covering only losses that were suffered and claimed within the policy term, excluding damage that was discovered later, the suits said
the lawsuits said four major insurance companies _ hartford, allstate, cigna and aetna _ started a campaign in 1984 to curtail coverage that was generally available in the industry
according to the suits, the companies got major u.s. and british reinsurers, including underwriters at lloyd's of london, to threaten a boycott of any u.s. insurance company that provided the broader coverage
among other things, the plaintiffs seek to restructure the insurance services office by giving non-insurers a majority on its board and making public its data on insurance coverage losses
ostwald said from his office in new york city that pollution insurance and ``occurrence'' coverage remained available, with some restrictions
pollution coverage was changed in response to expansive court decisions, he said
it's simply incorrect to assert that an attempt was made to impose this policy on the marketplace,'' he said, referring to the alleged effort to scrap ``occurrence'' coverage
insurance rates increased mainly because of ``a demonstrable increase in claims losses and a drop in interest rates, slowing down (insurers') investment income,'' he said
steven perelman, a spokesman for aetna casualty and surety co., a defendant in texas and california, termed the action ``another political move by political officeholders who have consistently opposed any and all efforts to address the real problems of the nation's liability system.''
david willis, spokesman for the cigna property and casualty group, also named in both lawsuits, said, ``it's really an ingrained condition of how we operate in all our jurisdictions that we conform to whatever antitrust regulations exist. we do not violate laws.''
in addtion to iso, the suit in texas named eight companies that served on the iso executive committee: aetna, cigna, fireman's fund insurance co., hartford fire insurance co., liberty mutual insurance co., st. paul fire and marine insurance co., the travelers insurance co. and usf&amp;g corp
also named in texas were the reinsurance association of america and reinsurers merrett non-marine syndicate no. 799 and robin a.g. jackson. merrett is part of lloyd's of london, and jackson is its underwriter
in california, the defendants are: iso, hartford; allstate insurance co.; aetna; cigna; peter n. miller; robin a.g. jackson; merrett underwriting agencies mgt. ltd.; three quays underwriting ltd.; janson, green ltd.; edwards and payne management (u.a.) ltd.; c.j. warrilow-hine &amp; butcher ltd
also, j. brian hose &amp; others ltd.; harvey bowring ltd. _ murray lawrence &amp; partners; k.f. alder &amp; others (u.a.) ltd.; d.p. mann &amp; others (u.a.) ltd.; unionamerica insurance co. ltd.; cna re (u.k.) ltd.; terra nova insurance co. ltd.; excess insurance group ltd.; kemper reinsurance london ltd.; continental reinsurance co. (u.k.) ltd
also thomas a. greene &amp; co. inc.; ballantyne, mckean &amp; sullivan ltd.; r.k. carvill &amp; co. ltd.; general reinsurance corp.; constitutional reinsurance corp.; mercantile &amp; general reinsurance corp. of america; prudential reinsurance corp.; north american reinsurance corp.; winterthur swiss insurance co.; reinsurance association of america
